    "<p><b>The Way Home by Joshua Beckman</b></p><p>Nowhere to hide.<br/>As the black blaze of autumn<br/>folds like a large sheet of forest<br/>around the oak,<br/>what was once a forest<br/>is now a vast expanse of home<br/>where everything is decaying<br/>and the stones are molded.</p><p>The only thing I know<br/>is that everything is falling<br/>on the path toward it<br/>the path toward what<br/>I call \"home.\"</p><p>In the distance<br/>a bluff of water<br/>asif by Anecdote Encapsulates<br/>the place where we are reborn,<br/>where everything we do is meaningless<br/>and the place where we meet every day<br/>is true.<br/>It\u2019s a place we haven\u2019t quite<br/>really been to.</p><p>This is the way home,<br/>home that\u2019s not<br/>just a house<br/>but a solitary city in a world<br/>where the ideal<br/>of both the past and the future<br/>is not to be found in each other<br/>but, as always, in the long field<br/>of emptiness.</p>",
    "<p><b>Sonnet 19:\u00a0 Lord, I\u2019m leaving this life by William Shakespeare</b></p><p>Lord, I\u2019m leaving this life<br/>And all this sorrow, this pain, this strife<br/>Will be with you forever. I\u2019m leaving<br/>My life you made for me, for your son.<br/>My life was made to be your son.<br/>You said given talent descends<br/>And talent is the best inheritance.<br/>Thankfully, you know how to get talent.<br/>You quietly taught me those secrets.<br/>On this sad day I feel your wide embrace.<br/>I would be dead to leave this life,<br/>But I am certain you will be always.<br/>Arise then and let me\u2014\"</p><p>The world would be a better place, if only<br/>I could turn back, and so could you.</p><p>Your grandchildren are great people<br/>And I am sure I could not live any longer<br/>If only I could turn back to one of you.<br/>But if I could turn back to you<br/>I\u2019d be living in the day of my own,<br/>Which is not the greatest day.<br/>Now then let me leave today,<br/>Not dead but alive.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Flying Kitchen<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Miles Davis</b></p><p>The stairs are the same,<br/>the floor is the same,<br/>one window is the same,</p><p>every table is the same,<br/>every chair the same,</p><p>every plate the same,<br/>every knife the same,</p><p>although the women\u2019s room has changed<br/>to a kitchen, their money has</p><p>not changed, nor have<br/>the foodstuffs</p><p>that I bring, like potatoes<br/>that are not potatoes,</p><p>that are not sweet potatoes,</p><p>that are not carrots<br/>that are not carrots,</p><p>that are not even referring to<br/>volatile vegetables</p><p>by their very mention</p>",
