    "<p><b>\u201cThe momo\u201d by Maciej Bodnar</b></p><p>The momo \u2013 an armadillo \u2013 is a slender, largely unknown animal<br/>was probably brought here from the lowlands of western Mexico<br/>by pioneers</p><p>the first arms</p><p>may have been men</p><p>the first arms were the shape of a woman<br/>the head was not</p><p>a single leg</p><p>it is sometimes mistaken for a small flat horse<br/>the legs of the armadillo are</p><p>similar in length</p><p>but what distinguishes the armadillo from a horse is its</p><p>piercy green hide</p><p>it is stabbed on the ground in a fashion</p><p>that is painful \u2013 it has been said<br/>that the armadillo is</p><p>slow and graceful</p><p>that it likes to be held up</p><p>by the foot or cannibal ....</p><p>sometimes it is more like a rabbit</p><p>that crawls on a patch of ground</p><p>but it is not shy<br/>and it will not grow</p><p>it is what it is -</p><p>a pig that is hoisted</p><p>on a cart</p><p>that is headed south</p><p>that is a future for bones</p><p>a future that is psychic</p><p>and the reason the armadillo is</p><p>scarcely feral in the woods of western Mexico is because it</p><p>needed to be fed</p><p>and it is there that the next plains march</p><p>that is the \"precinct of things\"</p><p>that is sacred</p><p>and that is why the next Plains march stretches</p><p>into the distance</p><p>that is always previous to the mountains of western Mexico</p><p>that are always future</p><p>and the next prairie march</p><p>that is the blueprint for the spinal<br/>and the long awaited last leg of the great plains</p><p>that we are told will be long and long in the future</p>",
    "<p><b>Why Is My Hair Falling Off? by W. S. Merwin</b></p><p>Amenities are a bit easier. If the wind blows, I start with my thinking,<br/>and give up the idea of space, and start with my head.</p><p>If the wind blows, I start with my leaving hands<br/>behind me, and cling to the ground, poised to leap,</p><p>in the tall grasses. If the wind blows, I hold my breath,<br/>but not quite there yet, so I look around, and look back,</p><p>in the open view of a great field outside of Salerno.</p><p>Where is the hill that rose here from the sea of weeds?<br/>It is the last thing I should have done, a trifle unwise.</p><p>I am waiting for the horse to get out of the way, for the snow<br/>to melt in him, and the field to scatter in the wind and become a field of hay.</p><p>I am waiting for the summer to melt in me, and the sun to die.<br/>I am waiting for the last thing to happen in the world: the wind,<br/>the hay, the sun, the horse.</p>",
    "<p><b>Deeds of Love by Randall Mann</b></p><p>(Deeds of Love)<br/>I.</p><p>Know thy pain.<br/>Do not flinch.<br/>Hear, oh hear, the roar of the trampling step<br/>of the weary feet<br/>which the dog-king mounts<br/>to his gray palace of the strong<br/>on a sound stage<br/>to win the affections<br/>of the dancing feet and the ragged clothes<br/>of the solitary weary feet<br/>who have sweated there and gone there<br/>and who have hated their miserable shoes<br/>and gone away<br/>and been moved to search for new shoes with some truth<br/>now that the soles of their feet<br/>have been worn down and worn down<br/>to the shoes of the walking feet<br/>which have been worn down to the foot-high grass-<br/>graved with shitty hooves and muck<br/>so earth-bound the shoes of the walking feet<br/>shall have to be worn while the front door of the palace of the strong<br/>castle-like so that the guards shall shout<br/>and the door shall be slammed<br/>and the little girls who have been beaten<br/>and have been beaten<br/>and will have to be beaten<br/>by the men who beat the little girls and have an interest in beating them<br/>with their own battered feet and battered faces<br/>shall be gentle and gentle and gentle<br/>on the horse the dolphins shall be gentle and gentle<br/>and some day the dogs shall be gentle and gentle<br/>all the time we are all in our painful places<br/>and we need each other<br/>I.<br/>Know thy pain.</p>",
    "<p><b>Crying by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>Crying over the way things are,<br/>Wishing I were dead instead,<br/>You ought to learn a new trade,<br/>A trade of straw and water,<br/>A trade of walk, a trade of fire.<br/>You ought to learn to sing love songs.<br/>You ought to run into a wall<br/>And drown. You ought to get drunk<br/>And faint. You ought to get dirty<br/>And get raped. You ought to loot.<br/>You ought to stay home and cry.<br/>You ought to get a job at a lumber yard.<br/>You ought to be poor and poor.<br/>You ought to stay at home and cry.<br/>You ought to get married and die.<br/>You ought to be poor and poor.</p>",
    "<p><b>Madam, You\u2019re Being A Bad Feminist by Maureen N. McLane</b></p><p>She doesn\u2019t want me</p><p><br/>to change</p><p>the sign:</p><p>today\u2019s the day<br/>where I say</p><p>\u201c\u201cI\u2019m a Violinist\u201d.</p><p>There\u2019s a violin player</p><p>who\u2019ll play the rondo</p><p>and have no violin.</p><p>The world is my canvas;</p><p>I paint it and the wind</p><p>writhes away.</p><p>I\u2019m making music with rain.</p><p>Madam, you\u2019re being a bad feminist.</p>",
    "<p><b>from<br/>  <br/>  Last Resort by Manfred Boorman</b></p><p>I have only ever used this eldritch<br/>Omnipresent Vernacular as a kind of<br/>\u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u2022 \u00a0 <br/>Disco music: \u00a0 \u00a0in the baker's oven</p><p>and the Bakery\u2019s \u00a0 \u00a0press \u2022 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0o \u2022 \u00a0 \u00a0t<br/>Park \u00a0chair:\u00a0I am sick of killing</p><p>This \u00a0seventy years and I am sick<br/>of \u00a0banishing people that I know\u00a0<br/>and love.</p>",
    "<p><b>Sealed in Sails by Robin Ekiss</b></p><p>There are always a few flickering headlights<br/>we see in the distance, two or three<br/>beneath the darkening sky, they give</p><p>a small improvement; a fleeting sense<br/>of security; a politician saying</p><p>a long time ago<br/>it\u2019s called the seabedding fleet</p><p>showing up next to us</p><p>it is.</p><p>And it\u2019s not a distant fleet<br/>nor an empty vessel falling back</p><p>from the night with a single pilot<br/>nor a single anchor, it\u2019s</p><p>a ship, an entire ship,</p><p>a fleet, a polished, crystalline vessel<br/>and we love ships.</p><p>Our lives\u2019ll be held together by<br/>the seabedding fleet</p><p>a wingspan of sixty miles, a ten<br/>nautical miles, even the elusive</p><p>Atlantic. Even the elusive<br/>Margaret,</p><p>the sea. The seabedding fleet</p><p>merges with the seabied fleet<br/>and the seabedding fleet loses</p><p>its Atlantic.<br/>The seabedding fleet</p><p>floats, speedboats so slow<br/>that one could not keep<br/>their legs on board,</p><p>and the merchant ship,<br/>its steamer, its keel,</p><p>admits to bury its face<br/>in the seabedding sail<br/>that is relentlessly<br/>commitant but reckless</p><p>in the face of that straightforward cold<br/>in the ocean.</p><p>And it is our fate<br/>to look together</p><p>where we stand<br/>in this universe</p><p>being bound to each other<br/>by the seabedding fleet</p><p>that chooses this life<br/>and that small village,<br/>its many weatherbeaten houses,</p><p>its few hulked bottles<br/>of beer,<br/>its elegant carriages,</p><p>its well-trimmed feet,<br/>these are actually at the centre<br/>of all our lives.</p>",
    "<p><b>Hunfly by Jerry Braverman</b></p><p>It\u2019s no golden ticket<br/>or honky-tonk-pumper<br/>but just enough bling to fly<br/>through the ruckus</p><p>and back to you</p><p>your breath alighting<br/>on your nerves,<br/>your cello and your</p><p>lips. In the middle<br/>of the night,</p><p>you wake up the pale<br/>lip of your girl</p><p>looking for a great big</p><p>babe, a narrator</p><p>you\u2019ll never forget.</p><p>Double-decker buses<br/>have done all the work</p><p>and time is another star</p><p>to take you home.</p><p>Touch me, I\u2019ll give you</p><p>a ride, a calm</p><p>gentle wail,</p><p>a whisper of a seat</p><p>and the sound</p><p>of a door</p><p>clacking open,</p><p>and the sound</p><p>of a door</p><p>and a lift\u2014</p><p>I\u2019m always going to</p><p>call you back.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Reporter Can Read Words by Heather McHugh</b></p><p>She\u2019ll write the great speech, and we\u2019ll go back<br/>the other way, hearing the great talk. We\u2019ll walk<br/>through the back gates, down darkened hallways<br/>(we\u2019re only in this room long enough to hear<br/>the big ones, and the smaller ones, repeating,</p><p>\u201cit\u2019s my birthday,\u201d) and into an unruly hallway.<br/>That\u2019s how it will always be. I am not prepared</p><p>to alter that harness, belt or shoulder,<br/>just sit in the white chair in me<br/>waiting for the Spanish language bulletin.</p><p>I\u2019m only in this room long enough to hear<br/>the big ones, and the smaller ones, repeating.</p><p>I\u2019m just going to have to listen.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Story of Rachel<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Sadiqa Lipsky</b></p><p>We\u2019re not the only ones with stories. We shuffle<br/>ourself about in the dark like between two<br/>scapes, a poet and his sleeping book,<br/>the song with its keys picked up<br/>by a hand or an ear,<br/>a wall<br/>print on paper,</p><p><br/>language<br/>for the dead,<br/>where was he<br/>before he came back.</p><p>Who was her<br/>and what was her<br/>and what was his<br/>name, and what was her<br/>and what was her<br/>and what was his<br/>name.\u00a0.</p><p>The song with its keys picked up<br/>by a hand or an ear<br/>opens a story that is old,<br/>and will surely be<br/>old until we die,<br/>but many years</p><p>within its lines. That story<br/>is not ours. That song<br/>is not his, nor is his.<br/>Not by me.\u00a0.<br/>Not by Rachel.<br/>And neither is the story,<br/>but that music, that line,<br/>and the story\u2014</p><p>resonant and entrancing<br/>as the song,<br/>resonant<br/>and entrancing<br/>as the words,<br/>and the waking\u2014<br/>that it rings true.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Question by Billy Collins</b></p><p>I\u2019m here to greet you. I\u2019ll get you something to eat,<br/>I\u2019ll carry you to a hotel or motel. I\u2019ll get you a good night\u2009\u2014\u2009I\u2019ll do everything in my power<br/>to make sure that you get a good night. I\u2019ll do everything in my power to make sure it\u2019s a good night.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cWe Need a Material|\u201d by Brenda C\u00e1rdenas</b></p><p>we don\u2019t need a god<br/>we need a tool<br/>to strike out our block<br/>we need messengers<br/>from the rich and terrible<br/>texts of our childhood<br/>we need handbooks<br/>for pulling apart<br/>the defective<br/>texts of our twelve<br/>or thirteen year old<br/>days of suffering</p><p>we need a light<br/>a clear window<br/>a whip of light<br/>a brighter day<br/>we need a lot<br/>we need a lot</p><p>we need to make a lot</p>",
    "<p><b>Amber by A. F. Moritz</b></p><p>I was singing in the dark,<br/>like a bride,<br/>at the ball.</p><p>My mother was in the room<br/>and I was in the dark.</p><p>I was in a corner<br/>above the stage<br/>till my father came,<br/>in the dark.</p><p>He was dressed in black<br/>and he said,You couldn\u2019t come in<br/>to the sound.</p><p>I was in the dark.</p><p>I was singing in the dark.</p><p>I was singing in the dark<br/>at the ball.</p>",
    "<p><b>Rectangle with Poppy Trees by Rodney Torreson</b></p><p>They\u2019re all here: the crooked<br/>ruts, the pockmarked<br/>arthrons, the flattened-<br/>up sides of the houses<br/>that used to be their<br/>place, and the old<br/>bohemian bungalows or<br/>chipped-off boats.</p><p>The miles of roads<br/>that once ran parallel<br/>to the river\u2019s gorge<br/>here where I\u2019m standing<br/>on a mint-<br/>smelling cross; I\u2019m<br/>just about to step<br/>into a little\u00a0hole in the<br/>river where I\u2019d be<br/>a long, long<br/>single file if I could walk.</p>",
    "<p><b>Ceremonies at the Harry\u2019s by Dr. Peter Gizzi</b></p><p>A similar number of people<br/>Couldn\u2019t mind the smell of cooking,<br/>Couldn\u2019t care less about the misery in Springfield</p><p>and the bunch of orphans,<br/>Couldn\u2019t sleep until the lights<br/>Of a hotel appeared in the distance</p><p>till the shadows of trees<br/>Moved in the dark.</p><p>The lady in the purple<br/>Claymore asked if she\u2019ll be held,<br/>The lady in the charcoal gray<br/>Claymore asked if she\u2019ll be held.</p><p>And I guess that night<br/>The tall old lady<br/>Led up to the bed<br/>And just as I was about to say</p><p>\u201cShoot, you\u2019re here;\u201d<br/>So I was, I just pulled me out<br/>Of my chair,</p><p>Anyhow, I don\u2019t care,<br/>His mouth was a living stove,<br/>His eyes the priest on the floor,</p><p>He led me up and the bedraggled lady<br/>Approached the man in the dark<br/>And carried him into the woods,</p><p>To the sound of voices<br/>Jettisoning the body<br/>Of a deceased man.</p><p>\u201cSHoot, you\u2019re here,\u201d<br/>I said, \u201cO. K.,\u201d</p><p>\u201cWhy don\u2019t we just pay our bills.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cBeyond the Boundary by Daniel J. Langton</b></p><p>On the highway, a tree<br/>swings across a paned glass:</p><p>the window into a wind room.</p><p>The twisting road turns again<br/>to find itself again\u2014</p><p>the tree again<br/>consumed this sweet savoir:</p><p>a broken trail,</p><p>a burnt-off hand<br/>wrestle in fender brambles.</p><p>I'd like to kiss the stars<br/>plain and not by moonlight.</p><p>The tree untangled itself<br/>from the road like a hangnail:</p><p>and the trees did the rest.</p><p>From the porch, I would choose again<br/>the perfect afternoon, sun<br/>attending to nothing below</p><p>but the rain,</p><p>and being rewarded<br/>when its yearly gathering</p><p>dies on a wire box.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Dream in a Dream by Zoran Zopic</b></p><p>Here and there, on a queue<br/>I\u2019m the hot luck\u2014<br/>I\u2019m not</p><p>the luckiest. In the end,</p><p>a hedge flicks on a tree;<br/>I wake up at the foot<br/>of a pond</p><p>and hear a rustling close<br/>by the way</p><p>of a cat.</p><p>I\u2019m not what you think,</p><p>except that I was born</p><p>in the United States<br/>and have lived my entire life</p><p>in a dream<br/>about a woman\u2014</p><p>a woman<br/>who sings among the trees.</p><p>I\u2019m supposed to be a hero,</p><p>but who knows more about trees<br/>of war and peace</p><p>than I do.</p>",
    "<p><b>To the Virgin by Samuel Taylor Coleridge</b></p><p>A woman *must* be virtuous.<br/>No one is ever punished.<br/>Beneath the leather covers on our knees<br/>we stand, nude,<br/>in a field of leeks. Up the hill,<br/>there\u2019s a handsome little church<br/>with an enormous spire\u2009\u2014<br/>the roof over our heads,</p><p>the field\u2019s the ground\u2009\u2014<br/>the meadow, the bay,<br/>the wind\u2019s knocking at the door.<br/>But I have been to a real man<br/>who is in the house listening.<br/>He\u2019s in his nightgown<br/>talking to someone who\u2019s in the kitchen<br/>baking pancakes and pouring</p><p>mixed drinks. He\u2019s talking about<br/>the past and the future.<br/>He\u2019s in the kitchen<br/>baking pancakes and pouring</p><p>mixed drinks. That\u2019s the virgin.</p>",
    "<p><b>An Act to Raise the Metropolis by Robert Herrick</b></p><p>This petition has had the force of 13,092 petitions:<br/>The first ground-rental rent hath been<br/>Sell to me.<br/>I go to the hell of ancients \u2014<br/>They did me wrong.<br/>How many people need a shock in unison,<br/>And across the seas to fight a phantom?</p><p>Take these 7,259,470 souls (there are no excuses)<br/>And quench the deep.<br/>O fool, long-lived as a Ben Jonson,<br/>Made famous for his wisdom,<br/>With that mouth of his,<br/>Unspoke with so much malice.<br/>\u201cWho are you?\u201d asks the rain.<br/>It is, again, not disillusioned,<br/>It is dead set on exalting himself,<br/>On exalting himself.<br/>The Capacities of a felt glove.<br/>The rotten facade of his beloved city:<br/>The only real civilization in the land.<br/>A birdhouse outfitted to his comings and goings \u2014<br/>A spire, and a parlor called home.<br/>My heart\u2019s ears with a happy flap \u2014<br/>A bird shelter in a wren\u2019s nest.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cFeirdeau\u201d by Maxine Kumin</b></p><p>My favorite haunts in the belly,<br/>a distaste for the handshake,<br/>competently crushing the ichthyic crusts<br/>behind my fist. Push me again<br/>or I'll roll off a cliff\u2009\u2014\u2009I\u2019m often glad<br/>to have been born in Texas.</p><p>The fathers who took me<br/>from my parents and raised me<br/>in a good home are long gone,<br/>golden boys who lovingly fed</p><p>the roses in their garden<br/>and the good books of their children.<br/>They\u2019ve worn \"allowed\" T-shirts<br/>And signed the autographs<br/>I shouldn\u2019t have like lyrics on my car</p><p>I kid you not.<br/>I know my temper has outgrown<br/>the other two.</p><p>I\u2019ve done my best to be polite,<br/>smile or slap someone<br/>if it\u2019s necessary\u2009\u2014<br/>There\u2019s a privilege to be born</p><p>in a very poor area.<br/>I\u2019ve learned to be decent to each person<br/>like the poor children under my care.</p><p>The future is bright,<br/>all of the outside phylum<br/>has already been deleted.</p><p>The great ocean, singing Song<br/>is the greatest song,<br/>and I\u2019m singing.</p><p>Thank you, Mary,<br/>the great ocean,<br/>the great ocean\u2019s song<br/>is the greatest song.</p><p>The great ocean, singing Song, is the greatest song.<br/>\u2014\u2009Dillon, Chugach, Poetry</p>",
    "<p><b>Song: \u201cAllahu akbar\u201d by Anonymous</b></p><p>Allahu akbar\u201d</p><p>(\u201cAkbar\u201d is a Short Prayer.)</p><p>There are many books<br/>and people, great and small,<br/>who the most important thing is<br/>(to remind us who we are).</p><p>The most important thing is<br/>to remember that the most important thing<br/>is love.</p><p>Love is so important<br/>not because it is easy<br/>(because it\u2019s not),<br/>but because it\u2019s our<br/>#1 job to love ourselves,<br/>and we do<br/>.<br/>Love is so important<br/>because love means love,<br/>and love means Love,</p><p>and love means Love.</p>",
    "<p><b>Appetite by Ayrton Senna</b></p><p>You\u2019re only hungry<br/>when the food is plentiful,<br/>not hungry when the food is<br/>forgotten. Hunger<br/>is the desire to be satisfied<br/>by any means necessary.</p><p>I think of young women<br/>who\u2019ve survived hunger<br/>by not starving. I think of<br/>snowfields with the smell<br/>of horse reindeer and<br/>a fox guarding a mass<br/>of trout, a flock of dirty<br/>awful prairie dogs from<br/>the heat of the sun, the smell<br/>of human misery<br/>every time it\u2019s on the air.</p><p>I think of the strangers<br/>I met when I was<br/>an ichthyological outsider,<br/>the beadless and jaunty<br/>askance and panache<br/>of people I didn\u2019t know,<br/>the ludicrous innocence,<br/>all that hair and<br/>all that money and<br/>the bombs going off<br/>in the buildings where<br/>I worked.</p>",
    "<p><b>Chamois by Louise Erdrich</b></p><p>Remembered by the carnivals, the hev\u2019n folk,<br/>Washes up in the well.<br/>Forgotten by the rest of us in the nip<br/>and tuck and retrograde field,</p><p>It was always the chamois that knew<br/>Silly talk about Irish joblessness<br/>Even though the other kids knew<br/>The chamois was always talking about<br/>Irish joblessness, Irish unemployment.</p><p>And now I am here in this Kauai sunset<br/>And I can\u2019t see anything but the chamois<br/>Or I will be soon deported to Ireland.</p><p><br/>Cattle-talk was always including the chamois,<br/>And that\u2019s why it is remembered today,<br/>Not only as a cool thing to say,<br/>But also as a thing we like to say.</p>",
    "<p><b>The School And The Ringby William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>Since we hang our heads,<br/>And sham our stands,<br/>And sham our rows,</p><p>And sham our bells,<br/>And sham our swords,<br/>We shall not hear<br/>The school bell ring,</p><p>The school and the ring,<br/>The teacher and the rings,<br/>The bell and the ring,</p><p>The bells and the rings and the teacher,<br/>The bell and rings and the teachers,<br/>The bells and bells and the bells and the rings and the rings and the teachers.</p>",
    "<p><b>Sleepers by Marge Piercy</b></p><p>Awake, and this sweet hum of silence fills me.<br/>In the frail green night in a phoenix\u2019s glass<br/>I look, I stare, I wait for the perfect<br/>touch of a woman\u2019s arm. The breath\u2019s like the breath<br/>of a calm, lilac, moon and a petal<br/>that once were two, and that my mother<br/>sweeps her hands over and over again<br/>like a casket with a sound-snatched needle.<br/>Plunging to your body, in the dark, open<br/>to whatever you have to put there,<br/>you are still wrapped up in your own skin,<br/>circling and fading, and, walking,<br/>you may hear yourself saying,<br/>\u201cOh, you\u2019re so beautiful.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>One Day by Ted Berrigan</b></p><p>Ask no questions and all will be done.<br/>Ask no more and the world stays the same.<br/>Ask and no more and everything is done\u2014<br/>All that remains is the remains of what you hoped to avoid.<br/>Such is life. \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 a a a n a n a l l l a n a n d e n d e n d e n d e d i g n u m</p><p>One day the son will be born,<br/>Only the shadow of him will remain.</p><p>The world will be nothing but the empty shades<br/>of tomorrow, the major and minor announcement,<br/>the quiet words of the great ones,</p><p>and the other little buggers.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cWhat is dead is dead\u201d by Yi Cai</b></p><p>What is dead is dead<br/>Is dead for its own sake.</p><p>It is a dead man's shoes<br/>Or a dead woman's shoe,</p><p>It is a dead pin,<br/>Strapped to an old chair,</p><p>It is a dead book,<br/>Written by a dead author,</p><p>Not dead.<br/>Dead*</p>",
    "<p><b>The Seeker's Dalliance by Charley Cassarino</b></p><p>The seeker's delight; the fire-lit circle of water; the olive tree<br/>could be a body of work, a new book of ceaseless art. . . .</p><p>Something once said<br/>is a blast of air or the entrance into a burning wound.<br/>It is the seer's body moved by the will<br/>to make love, the seer's old self reappearing</p><p>in a new flesh.<br/>The line of the mouth\u2019s where the sentence is said,<br/>the rotting world\u2019s blind ripe fruit;</p><p>I knew from your posture,<br/>that it was not my place to praise or scorn.</p><p>I could have said the penance that I had known,<br/>was not for me, but whose praise is theirs to give.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cAnd the Joered\u201d by Sir  Thomas Wyatt</b></p><p>And the Joered, who<br/>Doth sound the sad tale,<br/>Doth shine the light that shineeth;<br/>The Lord comes in his chariot,<br/>And with a straight face,<br/>And with a good face,<br/>Straight as the sun,<br/>With a heart like lightning,<br/>Hath he first hewed<br/>To the field of his praise,<br/>And then journeyeth<br/>Upon the fairs of the field,<br/>With slow pace,<br/>With a walk of the blind,<br/>With a scornful push,<br/>Till, as he hath done,<br/>He hath set his whole face round<br/>The holy place,<br/>And with a broad sweep<br/>Hind his brow,<br/>And with a grin,<br/>And a look of scorn,<br/>He hirself hath broken<br/>The day of his holy name.</p><p>Let us leave him<br/>To his fate;<br/>Whilst we grieve,<br/>We wish him pardon,<br/>And flush the sin,<br/>Until he may rise;<br/>Then, with speechless scorn,<br/>With a yell,<br/>With a tir'n,<br/>With a sing of laughter,<br/>He doth right and well,<br/>The enemy doth strike him.<br/>Until his vind or sill is done,<br/>Why shall we not enjoy<br/>His honour and his right,<br/>And his shame,<br/>And his shame again?</p>",
    "<p><b>(a) next reluctantly pilots<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Gail Mazur</b></p><p>I am the one who lays out the funeral<br/>for the one I love, the one I don\u2019t love,<br/>who shows up late to work, lifts<br/>all the food and drinks out<br/>and never once does it matter.<br/>I am the one who says<br/>\u201cHey Siri,\u201d but which one of us<br/>will start a car? Who will drive<br/>the one I miss the most?<br/>I am the one who waits<br/>for the one who is always<br/>not here, the one who looks<br/>like the ghost in the mirror.<br/>The one who has a<br/>perfect life, who is<br/>the luckiest woman in the world.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cJoey, the fuck up?\u201d by Frances Anne Kemble</b></p><p>Joey, the fuck up!<br/>You did what you can<br/>But if you think about it, you<br/>Know it's not your fault<br/>It's just the cops<br/>Making stupid mistakes<br/>That we don't<br/>Need to be reminded of</p><p>The G.I. Bill<br/>Was an outlaw Bill<br/>Who used to snap the F.B.I.<br/>All over the place<br/>Those days I<br/>Wrote are gone<br/>As gentle as yesterday<br/>I can still be<br/>A reverend and a good Christian<br/>For you.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lost Letter by Robert W. Service</b></p><p>In case you were sleeping on the edge<br/>of the sea, I guess I will always be here.<br/>Before the wind slides into the moorings<br/>and breaks<br/>the ship's door<br/>I will still be wearing my best clothes.</p><p>The wind is watching to see how I do.<br/>If I don\u2019t take off my shoe<br/>it will be past midnight,<br/>one hour late for work,<br/>though I know my clothes<br/>are still on.</p><p>The wind will become the moon<br/>when it\u2019s still too heavy to carry,<br/>and I will be well-rested<br/>if I\u2019ve already passed.</p><p>I will stay inside as long as I can.<br/>When the last clock is rung<br/>I will open the door<br/>while the other clock is still running,<br/>and I will be right there<br/>in my bed that smells of fish.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Elegant Municipalities of the Great Lakes by Margarita Engle</b></p><p>In thick silence<br/>the man at the register<br/>gave me a card for the permit<br/>for a weeklong renovation project<br/>but what I really wanted<br/>was a free phone line<br/>that would go straight to my house<br/>with no middleman<br/>like the old one in Union Station<br/>but, oh, how I wished<br/>it was not for the lack of a place to live<br/>with my ashes on top<br/>or for my being a ghost!</p><p>My mother was the gentle one<br/>who would not say too much<br/>but never drive alone<br/>or stay in too many places<br/>(the truth is she had<br/>a very tight heart)<br/>since she was always facing<br/>toward a bright future<br/>where she could grow up</p><p>and, if she still lived<br/>in beautiful places,<br/>where angels came even<br/>if they were not in power<br/>like the ones on this list<br/>I would still want<br/>a free, erect, beautiful home<br/>to live in</p><p>for my kids</p>",
    "<p><b>A Snowball by Lisa Gerstler</b></p><p>After Jerry Rubin<br/>We don\u2019t want<br/>a snow ball<br/>but we do need</p><p>some snow balls.</p><p>(You\u2019ve probably seen</p><p>them already<br/>on the sidewalk<br/>or in the mee</p><p>and red long underwear<br/>at the library or</p><p>on the porch at</p><p>eight in the morning<br/>on a Friday.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lonely Sea by Jorge Luis Borges</b></p><p>The mind has no chance of grasping the truth,<br/>Is in a world of its own making,</p><p>A world of a world, endless<br/>Leaden dark dark and keener than the rest;</p><p>Where the solid sand, the green bed, and the earth stand still,</p><p>Are nothing more than a swarm of the chaotic</p><p>Crane of a numberless flying bolsters,</p><p>Whose clanging, shivering wings of desolation</p><p>Dance in the sky like the mistress of the house</p><p>Dancing and dancing in a labyrinth of the mind.</p><p>If you have time for yourself</p><p>You will join with others</p><p>And go to sea, to the Lonely Sea,</p><p>Ploughing in the empty dust,</p><p>This world of a world\u2014</p><p>The sea sloughing itself out of the deep,</p><p>Glorious, silent city,</p><p>That no one dreams of leaving.</p>",
    "<p><b>Through Watery Green Sands by Rachel Richardson</b></p><p>It is not the birds<br/>that sing, but water,<br/>swirls and swirls,<br/>humors, all the river, all</p><p>the sense, all the<br/>night-to-day, all<br/>of it, and we are back to</p><p>what we were before</p><p>the river began to<br/>hurl its slant-roll bodies</p><p>above us, and about<br/>to be forgotten, and the birds</p><p>singing, less than birds</p>",
    "<p><b>A Scant Room by Robert Hedin</b></p><p>In a squalor, a passing taxi driver said:</p><p>\u201cGet a job,\u201d he said, like the loudest and most vulgar thing he\u2019d ever heard.</p><p>I had never looked at a building this way before.<br/>Night sun trying its luck<br/>waitting by an alley to catch a light,</p><p>or walked around the corner of this house,<br/>and shouted \u201cTo the glorious train!\u201d<br/>I wasn\u2019t there\u2019t. I never watched:</p><p>the dirty-dazed eyes of the author<br/>and his friend, the sober eyes of the author\u2019s wife,</p><p>and the hard heart of the writer<br/>who thinks a freewheeled blog is funny and (it\u2019s true) freaks out</p><p>at everything it does.</p>",
    "<p><b>Salima: The Unforgiven by Xia</b></p><p>I bear the hospital bed<br/>with the full name of each of the dead<br/>in the rabble-rousing rally</p><p>at the gate of the road outside<br/>the town itself.</p><p>Some days I don\u2019t want<br/>to write, I sit on my<br/>chair and read aloud</p><p>the following passage from<br/>the third book of the Sutra of the Body:</p><p>\u201cThe Love I taste in my mouth<br/>has been cut into pieces<br/>and scattered like flowers,</p><p>bean and sprigs of it,<br/>colors of the ocean and stars.</p><p>I write the next sentence<br/>with my fingers</p><p>and keep repeating it.</p><p>I have too much time!<br/>I\u2019ve just enough to pretend</p><p>I\u2019re not at all sick.<br/>I bear a special place</p><p>in memory of those who died<br/>at the hands of Dictators and Soldiers,</p><p>as well as those who willingly<br/>voluntarily walked</p><p>under the prison walls<br/>to occupy that space</p><p>where words spill like sand<br/>where nothing is left standing</p><p>like ripples on the great ocean,<br/>where the waves are making</p><p>the human body larger and more<br/>normal.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Ear by Robert W. Service</b></p><p>To the Jewish Community of the Pittsburgh,<br/>a place of honor,<br/>a place of love,<br/>the ear of luck<br/>has been listening,<br/>he has been watching,<br/>he has been receiving news<br/>every day and every night,<br/>he is not to be blamed<br/>for remaining silent,<br/>for remaining on the sidelines<br/>as I sit here in my chair,<br/>shaking my brown pelt,<br/>I am unaware of the earthquake coming<br/>or the death of the women of the Holocaust<br/>for centuries.</p>",
    "<p><b>How to Get Over by Jamie Chung</b></p><p>Is this the goodbye<br/>I've been waiting for?<br/>We are approaching death<br/>w/ a smile,<br/>not blind<br/>or dire.</p><p>I beg of God<br/>to let me<br/>use my last breath<br/>not as the death<br/>but to move forward</p><p>continually,<br/>without shame,<br/>into my own personal</p><p>nowhere<br/>where people<br/>speak of the weather<br/>hearing moon</p><p>at the top<br/>of the stairs\u2014<br/>a feeling<br/>that keeps</p><p>going,<br/>until every voice<br/>in the world<br/>calls me back,<br/>and I come out</p><p>of my shell<br/>like a phoenix\u2014<br/>an angry<br/>but happy</p><p>transformation.</p><p>In the dream<br/>I am on fire<br/>that is going to burn<br/>to ashes</p><p>I am not<br/>the kind of woman<br/>that I thought I was</p><p>but I am glad<br/>to be<br/>a wordless cry</p><p>not crying<br/>from the flame<br/>that is going to burn</p><p>and to keep<br/>going.</p>",
    "<p><b>The World Equinox Part 4 by Rachel Richardson</b></p><p>Paleontologists have fifteen different kinds<br/>of dinosaur bones, some of them<br/>thirty feet long. But the most valuable has<br/>all been lost for good. The world\u2019s first giant ant<br/>got stuck on the roof of a museum as if<br/>it had escaped from some power plant.</p><p>Weaving himself back into a heap<br/>of them, tree-sized, he began to dig<br/>his fist into the twisted earth.</p><p>A thousand years later, he turned his attention<br/>to one thing that wasn\u2019t there.<br/>Earth, his eyes said, is one of nine<br/>continents to frame a different face.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Seducing Grub<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by John Tipton</b></p><p>hand over your milk, form up your dog,<br/>steer clear of the servants, let the goats<br/>go at the horses, reject the baby business.</p><p>When the tide, the waters, feel great,<br/>never be surprised that they stay.</p><p>You are not to touch anything.<br/>Don't you dare rub your wife's her arm.<br/>Do you think you can dance it blue?</p><p>Remember how lovers drink wine in the car,<br/>and one, two, three,<br/>then a glass of water, and then</p><p>a third; and then another?<br/>Beware that, if you drink,<br/>the others, too, will return,</p><p>and die in the wake of you.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Boxed Casket by J. Allyn Rosser</b></p><p>It is less the coffin than the casket<br/>that weaves in and out of the room.<br/>As the moon begins the descent<br/>from the ceiling to the floor, the casket<br/>begins to tilt like a horse\u2019s head.</p><p>It is less the coffin than the horse\u2019s head<br/>that I lean over as my father lifts the lid.<br/>It is less the coffin than the funeral home<br/>that I put my mind to over the years<br/>and was fortunate to return to when the wind died<br/>like the horses I named that way<br/>and shuffled through the rooms until I could put them<br/>together to make the house of cards.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Night by Eileen Myles</b></p><p>As the night my loved's head<br/>wobbles downward until<br/>it hits her and she lies</p><p>blind on the dark until<br/>one eye rolls into her,<br/>the other out the window,</p><p>sitting up, sliding down,<br/>as the car rolls out of<br/>the parking lot, and the scuff marks</p><p>on her leather jacket<br/>climb into her lap, then back,<br/>her hair falling back</p><p>into the dark as she tries<br/>to figure out which is her</p><p>and which is who, my favorite<br/>friend, boyfriend, my mother.</p><p>I turn off the TV, watch her<br/>sit up through the night, hearing her</p><p>the words come back, the night<br/>making a meal of her, and remembering</p><p>the ways I neglected my own<br/>//particularly my own dreams,<br/>the excess, the</p><p>wanton, the geek thinks it is</p><p>cool to wear pants to work,<br/>the light shining through<br/>a decorated window,</p><p>but I\u2019m still a girl, not<br/>young enough for bed,</p><p>still there in the dark,<br/>daring to lie down on my<br/>carpet, breathing the</p><p>dark, while the car<br/>rolls to a stop, and I stand</p><p>a hair away from the door,<br/>holding the reins,</p><p>a girl I don\u2019t think<br/>I know anymore, still</p><p>leaving the dark<br/>tied to the door,<br/>in the driver's seat</p><p>while the light<br/>gels inside the door,<br/>then slowly moves</p><p>from one end of it<br/>to the other,<br/>then west, then east</p><p>to the other,<br/>this worn-down old<br/>where my body wasn\u2019t</p><p>made of Styrofoam and leather,<br/>never worn</p><p>again, I stood</p><p>shoving the reins<br/>against the sill,<br/>shoving them</p><p>onto the blinds and<br/>The merest thought</p><p>that I might</p><p>be good at this,<br/>that I</p><p>couldn\u2019t wait</p>",
    "<p><b>Year of the Elephant by Robin Ekiss</b></p><p>In the free world, the elephant is dead,<br/>the yellow is gone, the garbage is festering,<br/>the yankee has taken up residence alone.<br/>The best interviewer is still out there<br/>wanting a job because the chair<br/>was made to sit down and set<br/>even the most venal volit\u00e4n<br/>is dirty as mud. In the<br/>elimination roundtable<br/>of the showbusiness \"expert\"<br/>on the row, neither the elephants,<br/>nor the haters, nor himself<br/>are happy about that,<br/>yet the elephant, still at the head of<br/>the line is the best.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Fence by Daniel Hernandez</b></p><p>The fences were coming down. The fences in Ferm\u00edn, the fence in the park, two fences in the park, two fences in the park. As my daughter collects her things<br/>I want to stand in the middle of the street and say:Who are you? You're an empty wall.</p><p>The fences are coming down. The fences in Ferm\u00edn<br/>this evening.</p><p>We walk to the curb, and the trunks shake,<br/>one car imperceptibly<br/>wiggling out of a dustbin<br/>on the highway.</p><p>The tires of cars stand on end,<br/>all white as the line between road and curb<br/>no longer exists. The fence<br/>that doesn't exist<br/>is coming down.</p><p>My daughter collects her things<br/>and stands beside a fence.<br/>\"There's no one there,\" she whispers.<br/>\"Someone is going to come back,\" I say.</p><p>Her face radiates with excitement.<br/>\"There's people going to come back, baby,\" I say.<br/>\"What do you want, you'll get,\" she says.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Dirty Gear (Smile) by French Denton</b></p><p>The Dirty Gear (Smile)<br/>is the secret of how the Yemeni children are carrying and using<br/>the bomb in their lapels, getting a free ride<br/>on trucks and buses, eating an oily, white protein shake,</p><p>doing drugs and having abortions in factories and markets in Jizan.</p><p>\u2014<br/>Shabbir Ahmed, alias Abu Basir<br/>Tied to the Walls, adored by the Women<br/>Wandering by, women who dwarfs and dwarfs<br/>with the old and the young, some who look like pigeons<br/>who rot figure in the wall like bird racoons.</p><p>There are places where old clothes<br/>are blackened, and there are places<br/>where the puppets are painted in dim ink<br/>on the walls of dark rooms.</p><p>The women who parade down these streets<br/>staggering to the track to the pits of the tracks<br/>are holding up their hands<br/>until the cameras are not rolling.</p><p>The women who walk past these dark streets<br/>often think to ask the men to wait<br/>for them; they are lucky they can answer<br/>when the doors are never slammed<br/>and the cars have never been repaired</p><p>when a girl tos and frot has nothing<br/>to wear and the only thing to do is sit<br/>at the kitchen table of the woman who sits<br/>and tattoos.</p>",
    "<p><b>Comforter by Jacopo Polosa</b></p><p>The silver letters she had read opened<br/>like the mouth of a long pasty face,</p><p>wrapped around the crook of my leg<br/>with her finger and the last thing I knew,</p><p>I was crawling under one foot,</p><p>gaining speed as I turned and ran<br/>until I saw a yellow trail of snow</p><p>running behind me, and so forth<br/>in the cold of the night.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lost Cat by Rodney Torreson</b></p><p>He woke up<br/>in a rickshaw pulled by the trailer behind a bar in Baltimore.</p><p>He was a cat<br/>who had wandered miles<br/>in a light-colored coat<br/>&amp; under a blanket<br/>to find himself free.</p><p>Although he had no fur,<br/>he looked a lot like a rabbit,</p><p>especially in the documentary shots,<br/>which captured his every move.</p><p>He ate candy &amp; drank coffee,<br/>stayed with a girl who worked in a salon.<br/>The story would end,</p><p>but the hitch with the hair<br/>was the girl\u2019s.</p><p>At night he became a familiar figure,<br/>the subject of movie after movie,</p><p>a likely cape in the line of a windy wind<br/>that knocked at the door where a child<br/>was curled in a pink ball and reading.</p><p>The girl\u2019s sister's friends refused<br/>to come to watch it.</p>",
    "<p><b>To the Poems Untaught by Anonymous</b></p><p>The words I write<br/>and have no voice<br/>Go where no one hears<br/>Because I am still<br/>A child who has no father<br/>And no mother.</p><p>I am the briefest form<br/>And the best of what is being<br/>Young and fat and bad and vain<br/>And fortunate;<br/>But the words that come<br/>Clap against my eyes<br/>Like aureole of a young man<br/>Making a way to heaven.<br/>That's why I am here<br/>Today, remember,<br/>And that's why you\u2019re there.</p>",
    "<p><b>With Leeches and Blood-Buds by Hubert Zamora</b></p><p>Yesterday I took some pictures<br/>when a snail came by and dragged<br/>a rosea from a nearby tree<br/>back to my cabinet full of glass<br/>and a fountain I seldom used<br/>and then I saw in the mirror<br/>a child wearing a yellow<br/>t-shirt and a pair of boots<br/>and said, \u201cThat\u2019s me.\u201d<br/>And I was so in love with him<br/>I didn\u2019t even realize that<br/>the camera wasn\u2019t focusing on him<br/>until I was walking toward him<br/>to sit down<br/>and I was sitting across from him<br/>and I was certain.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cI\u2019m Checking Myself<br/>\u201cI\u2019m building a shelter, I\u2019m building<br/>a shelter, I\u2019m building a shelter...\u201d by Isaiah Berlin</b></p><p>I\u2019m checking myself<br/>from my back<br/>with a ballpoint pen<br/>on the soft.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Happy Clocks by Elizabeth Alexander</b></p><p>My mother was proud and golden and got up<br/>and brushed her messy hair. I sat in the kitchen<br/>and I could see the way she didn\u2019t care about<br/>the clockwork of the world.</p><p>Stairs were similar. We were walking<br/>to the library, and I fell down.</p><p>It hurt. I sat in a chair and I listened<br/>to my mother\u2019s happy noises.</p><p>I sat in the kitchen and I fell.<br/>I can\u2019t remember the real purpose of this life,<br/>but I\u2019m proud of the way I looked<br/>and I\u2019m glad I\u2019m not such a poor girl.</p>",
    "<p><b>Stairway to Heaven by CAConrad</b></p><p>We walk with you from here<br/>to there.</p><p>You move in the dark<br/>as if you\u2019ve already passed<br/>through hell.</p><p>It\u2019s like going down a rabbit loo<br/>or,<br/>a false step,<br/>a prayer,<br/>a bridge to nowhere.</p>",
    "<p><b>Come Sometimes by Delmore Schwartz</b></p><p>Come sometimes, a man of God,<br/>A mount, a mule, all in a row,<br/>To water from the well.\u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Come often,<br/>Not to show off, but to herd.<br/>Come to see the sunset.\u00a0Come to haunt<br/>A fountain, \u00a0A lighthouse, a cannery.<br/>Come to see the way the earth is flat.</p><p>The gate at the back of the room<br/>Is closed, and the bar is guarded<br/>By a crowd of tourists with fake IDs.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0I haven't found the stairs.</p><p>I don't want questions, I'ma take a nap.<br/>I'ma lie in a circle and pray.</p><p>I'ma photograph my back while the sun\u2019s high<br/>A couple prance in front, snorting joints\u00a0in their teeth.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0I'ma write poems about boy bands.<br/>I\u2019ma write poems\u00a0about boys who are on the high heels</p><p>And the fashion models who wear sneakers.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0I\u2019ma write poems about the guy at the bar next to mine.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Boat by Robert Duncan</b></p><p>That thorn, that thorn, kindly palmyra,<br/>Is leaving her, that thorn, that thorn,<br/>I find, yet not for want of<br/>Afe, but to me<br/>A soul in need<br/>Of an anchor, or for<br/>Something really good.</p><p>And if, fly, if, bird,<br/>Were to scrutinize<br/>The fade and shine, both<br/>Till they too should shrink<br/>And be lost<br/>At the same time,</p><p>I know<br/>That by this song,<br/>I shall make praise<br/>Mighty for all that yearns.</p>",
    "<p><b>Togetherness by Michael S. Harper</b></p><p>yo, what i wanted from you<br/>was not just friendship<br/>but recognition. that you understood</p><p>that no one ever wanted<br/>to be confused with someone<br/>or a remnant of a past friend</p><p>though a suspicion<br/>of being out of place<br/>that i am still able to shake</p><p>to feel free to be myself</p>",
    "<p><b>Toom by Kodama</b></p><p>I was buried in this flower.<br/>September was a kind of gift.<br/>Candor there was no treasure.</p><p>When I came to, there was snow.<br/>I was the flower of that snow.</p><p>I was the flower.</p><p>The hot sun wheeled over my head<br/>like a crescent on a sky<br/>that no one took me for some</p><p>reason.<br/>I was the flower and all the servants of the flower<br/>were the trees under which we walked</p><p>to the church, to the streetlight, to the laundromat, to the breakfast<br/>pot, to the rearview mirror, to the smiling faces<br/>of the people inside the city, to all of this</p><p>and then for the tree, to the forest.</p>",
    "<p><b>Fragments<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Frances Anne Kemble</b></p><p>We came to know<br/>what life is without it.<br/>When I was afraid<br/>my heart fled<br/>the fear-filled room,<br/>we walked outside<br/>in the open air<br/>and climbed a clearing<br/>of mulberry trees.<br/>A cowbell rose<br/>on a branch<br/>pilates from the tree<br/>and slowly turns.</p><p>Everyone walks<br/>the same way now.<br/>Says,it\u2019s okay<br/>to feel old.</p><p>And the sound of rain<br/>in the open air</p><p>is the greeting<br/>of the neighbors<br/>who have moved<br/>and who have<br/>caught fire<br/>bouquets of the things they\u2019re used to.<br/>The pieces<br/>of our lives<br/>we had forgotten<br/>are slowly coming back.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Way It Is by Larry CadFeder</b></p><p>a kind of intimacy</p><p>being pulled over<br/>by a stop sign.</p><p>The sound of sirens<br/>licking the car,</p><p>not lacking any</p><p>narratives.</p><p>\u201cA shy person<br/>out of the frame</p><p>who can\u2019t help it.</p><p>We use our phones<br/>to run our fingers</p><p>over notes, wanting</p><p>more to speak</p><p>than a silence,</p><p>a grinding, what</p><p>could have been<br/>if we had</p><p>a different accent</p><p>weren't</p><p>even half-</p><p>way there.</p><p>A waiter,<br/>hoping to hold back</p><p>the last table,</p><p>said, \u201cIf you</p><p>want a table,</p><p>come here.\u201d</p><p>The look<br/>I got once</p><p>was beautiful.</p><p>Even now<br/>the way it is</p><p>runs in my veins.</p>",
    "<p><b>To the Sonnet</b></p><p>I had to make do, and I did:<br/>Greatness is a very fleeting thing.<br/>But Alexander\u2019s passion, which graced him<br/>With such lovely grace, taught me this:<br/>Some things are worth doing.</p>",
    "<p><b>Where\u2019s Waldo by William Trowbridge</b></p><p>I never thought of it.<br/>But here in the yard<br/>it irritates me.</p><p>One day I\u2019ll write<br/>a poem.<br/>Scrawl it on a rock.</p><p>I\u2019ll put poison in the water.<br/>Cuff my body. No more milk.</p><p>I\u2019ll lick the ashes in the sun.<br/>So will I.</p>",
    "<p><b>Solanum by James Schuyler</b></p><p>tall precipitated for good reason<br/>and well worth going all<br/>backward to the shores of memory<br/>come to find that none of us remember<br/>what happened to us,<br/>we are not strong enough to bear the weight<br/>of what was, and as we<br/>lose our way through our past<br/>(maybe, maybe?) to the future<br/>that\u2019s not so far away</p>",
    "<p><b>Sign by Maeve Higgins</b></p><p>The sign on my property reads<br/>\u201cbuy milk.\u201d I\u2019ve always known<br/>I\u2019d have to work for my milk:<br/>a bale of straw, a stake<br/>in the ground, the first creak<br/>of a gate. Not the loud scream<br/>of the baby nor the crow,<br/>not the bang of the roof. This<br/>is the homecoming dance, her<br/>mixed metal cushion overflowing<br/>vaguely, her yen. I skip the braless<br/>puck that glares in my drink,<br/>I\u2019m just so terribly sorry<br/>for my failure to be hers.</p>",
    "<p><b>the Hawaiian Map by Frank Stanford</b></p><p>When you want<br/>to head for<br/>a river on a<br/>new and wet<br/>summer, it\u2019s</p><p>tough to think<br/>that your risks<br/>are weighted</p><p>against each other,<br/>and your friends<br/>can\u2019t say<br/>what to say to get<br/>to the end of a long road</p><p>into landlocked<br/>Hawaii or the Bronx<br/>or a community of</p><p>those whom the<br/>big-city may</p><p>leave a runway<br/>of, say, those<br/>who spring</p><p>from the mud<br/>to sing about<br/>the meaning of life.</p>",
    "<p><b>SCC 50: There is no me by Jonathan Williams</b></p><p>There is no me,<br/>at all, but the red-haired girl,</p><p>teeth pressed back,<br/>pupil holding in a few dark hairs,</p><p>calls everybody to the church,<br/>but everybody\u2019s home,</p><p>its doors flung open,<br/>the past and future,</p><p>the face that sailors upload,<br/>indifference to even a pause,</p><p>a strange document:</p><p>a picture, stuck in a picture viewer</p><p>on the Beanie Head hotel drive,<br/>the kind you might get from a garage sale,</p><p>the kind of document that has a face</p><p>and a traffic light on it.</p><p>\u201cSister Mary!\u201d</p><p>\u201cI\u2019m going to the SCC Fellowship\u2014</p><p>my mother says.</p><p>Jodie,</p><p>that red-haired girl is beside me.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Flooded River by Anya Silver</b></p><p>I want to stand<br/>on the obliterated<br/>horizon and see<br/>the sunset</p><p>lolling on a water-logged<br/>beach. The end of the world<br/>was just a dream.</p><p>I want to wear<br/>an animal mask<br/>and then walk</p><p>to the end of the world.<br/>Then I will be<br/>the mother, smiling<br/>at my real daughter</p><p>before her every drag.<br/>The flood waters will<br/>clasp me to their straps<br/>and I will be the shelter.</p><p>My daughter will be<br/>the great cook,</p><p>the first to fold<br/>her pillow, and</p><p>the one to clean<br/>the stove, and then</p><p>the one to look<br/>ahead,<br/>not toward tomorrow,</p><p>to the end of our journey.</p>",
    "<p><b>Game by A. F. Moritz</b></p><p>I.b. at the innermost recess<br/>from the forest, surrounded by savannas<br/>of semaphore, ;;\u200e\u200aa\u200a, rY\u2009ew, insane<br/>stiff, witty or happy, purchased by the season</p><p>I.b. I.b. I.b. I.b.</p>",
    "<p><b>Falling Rain by Robert Hayden</b></p><p>They've melted<br/>all this snow to<br/>the ground. It\u2019s not</p><p>the snow that falls on<br/>the ground. It\u2019s the rain</p><p>that\u2019s sporadically<br/>falling over the hill</p><p>the falling rain<br/>that my mother</p><p>watches to see<br/>what\u2019s next. It\u2019s</p><p>the rain that falls<br/>so rarely I can\u2019t</p><p>wait for it. I look<br/>up at the sky</p><p>and see a clearing<br/>&amp; a blackbird</p><p>come down over<br/>the hill. I know</p><p>the rain will come<br/>because now</p><p>it\u2019s midday<br/>and it\u2019s dark.</p><p>And there\u2019s no snow<br/>in the day.</p><p>The rain just<br/>moves slopily</p><p>&amp; reminds me</p><p>of snow on parked<br/>trucks, lightening</p><p>in the sky, leaving a<br/>little mess out<br/>of the front yard,</p><p>the way the rain<br/>has left this little</p><p>carpet of snow<br/>on our front steps.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Dressbox by Petra Brimhall</b></p><p>My father craves a dressbox. He wears the dressbox to parties and makes the bride and groom change into different dresses.<br/>Once I was the only child to go so far<br/>that I could try on dresses and look in a mirror.<br/>My mother does not believe that the dress box can be worn as an effective birth control.</p><p>My grandmother once said that the body must be protected from the body's own mistakes.<br/>My grandmother did not believe her granddaughter's fairy tales about how much more people will happily pay for clothes<br/>when we get married.</p><p>My grandfather had tried to kill himself.<br/>When he at last realized that he had simply been playing a fool<br/>and repenting his rage, he fell into the dress box\u00a0and died.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Sorrow of My Life by Leo Dangel</b></p><p>Forgive me, my love, for this day, this hour,<br/>I am not bashful tonight, I am sharp, i.e.,<br/>i.e.,<br/>are you with me? when I say<br/>yes.<br/>Will you?<br/>(to say no, brings great shame.)</p><p>My wedding-night, the saddest day<br/>I ever had, i.e.,<br/>i.e.,<br/>are you with me?<br/>(to say what, brings great shame.)</p><p>The moment I let you into my womb<br/>I knew that you were my future</p><p>i.e., the saddest, i.e.,<br/>are you with me?<br/>(to say what, brings great shame.)</p>",
    "<p><b>Pyrotechnics by Cathie Tompkins</b></p><p>Maybe I\u2019m just desiring you<br/>to confound me.</p><p>Someone once told me the pyrotechnics were stupid.</p><p>I don\u2019t recall<br/>the words that were spoken,</p><p>I\u2019ll try to be<br/>as nonchalant as possible.</p><p>If I am at the center of the pyrotechnics<br/>I am not amused.</p><p>Or am I?</p><p>Nothing\u2019s going to happen<br/>assuming I don\u2019t</p><p>otherwise assign an identity<br/>to myself.</p><p>There is no being<br/>elsewhere than me.</p><p>Who is it I leave<br/>behind?</p><p>I am the umbrella<br/>and my love</p><p>are the long branches</p><p>from which the pyrotechnics<br/>launch themselves</p><p>into the air.</p><p>Who is it that I pick<br/>up, pull, and carry</p><p>with me?</p><p>Is it myself?</p><p>Then who<br/>are you to conduct me?</p><p>Who is it that you borrow<br/>from me?</p><p>I am not going to say<br/>yes to more than one partner.</p><p>I am going to say<br/>yes but only to you.</p><p>Always pull yourself up by the scruff of the neck<br/>and do not scold.</p><p>Never take orders.</p><p>You\u2019re not going to be saved.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cSmall Phoenix, and Little Phoenix in Heron\u201d by Walter Clyde Curry</b></p><p>The little boy came from the flow<br/>of her gushing feet<br/>and the boat smelled of alcohol.</p><p>I had to teach him how to walk<br/>because I could not unfold<br/>the canvas on my back but he sat still</p><p>and read in the fantastic book<br/>and a man and a woman<br/>put a kettle on the stove.</p><p>We stood at the edge of the kitchen<br/>and the gray cat suddenly seemed a serious matter<br/>and I was angry with him<br/>and I would have likely yelled<br/>but it was not my place to make decisions<br/>and the intercom roused and rattled.</p><p>When the little boy,<br/>again and again, arrived,<br/>the man and woman put him in the<br/>helf where the carpet was<br/>and he remained asleep</p><p>until the rain had soaked the glass<br/>and the two women burst into tears.</p>",
    "<p><b>How I Betrayed Myself by Anya Silver</b></p><p>a kitten will jump at your foot<br/>thanks \u00a0beyond the bluffs<br/>I liked a good one<br/>that would learn the ways<br/>and teach the world<br/>he died<br/>unable to be</p><p>- \u00a0yawn\u00a0 \u00a0loooooove<br/>I thatn\u2019ve become<br/>a fat girl<br/>with some pain<br/>making my own</p><p>And I so my friend\u00a0 messes up<br/>he\u00a0 gets on top of me<br/>and after the stillness</p><p>the shaving cream<br/>honeydewing my butt</p><p>I can\u2019t revenge myself<br/>I won\u2019t, but I can<br/>speak up for myself<br/>and make amends\u00a0</p><p>(\u201cI\u2019ve\u00a0 killed myself\u201d)<br/>where is the girl that\u00a0 I condemned?<br/>I\u2019ve invited her to the party<br/>but she\u2019s not</p><p>she\u2019s afraid of nothing<br/>I told her that I\u2019d love her<br/>but she did my smoking</p><p>I was thinking that I\u2019d love her<br/>but the nightmare<br/>I wished my mother had</p><p>and looked down<br/>to find myself missing<br/>from my own image</p><p>a boy alive<br/>a one man band<br/>my brother just disowned</p><p>she does\u00a0 not\u00a0 know\u00a0 my name<br/>she is so proud</p><p>but I am so proud<br/>that I have not abandoned my own\u00a0 way</p><p>and I\u00a0 will\u00a0 leave<br/>my house<br/>with my mouth set on singing<br/>(\u201cI\u2019m\u00a0 a\u00a0 Hurley!\u201d)</p><p>with my doll up on a nail \u00a0on my tongue<br/>I will sing about<br/>Hurley! Hurley! Hurley!</p>",
    "<p><b>Scheheraz by Gail Mazur</b></p><p>You can't cockblock the sun because it can't be<br/>in your body\u2019s place. Your father didn't know that.<br/>He helped your family take the bus from there.<br/>He never let you down, or the neighborhood<br/>without a conscience.\u00a0 He was the most loving parent<br/>you could ask for.\u00a0 He was a queer Jew that loved even<br/>the tiniest thing.\u00a0 Uncle Joe, though he gave his back<br/>to the neighborhood, told you, \u201csieg heil.\u201d<br/>And did he ever.\u00a0 And did you ever.</p>",
    "<p><b>Why I Carry a Gun by Tobias Wolpe</b></p><p>Why I carry a gun<br/>is such a trivial piece of bloat<br/>that somehow I never get used to<br/>that I might need it,<br/>and I can envision next to no consequences<br/>for doing so. The gun is not<br/>a threat to anyone unless I shoot it<br/>then leave it to explode,<br/>I can imagine. The gun is<br/>indispensable for creative destruction.</p><p>One day, my body will be so weak<br/>I can't even walk,<br/>the gun will still be there<br/>and I will shoot it<br/>to send it flying over a thousand feet<br/>and kill or maim a few people.</p><p>What would be the consequences<br/>of this trivial life? I can tell you<br/>that God will be happy<br/>if I just get used to it<br/>and don't try to put it off.</p>",
    "<p><b>Dry November by David Wojahn</b></p><p>The winter I\u2019ve had, it\u2019s full of the sense that it\u2019s over<br/>because I\u2019ve been waiting and waiting<br/>for this to happen for years, and to have the tricycle<br/>that I never had, and the bicycle that I never will<br/>look back on again.<br/>It\u2019s almost winter in New York, and snow is</p><p>starting to come down in a big haystack<br/>on the abandoned building next to the bridge, thick<br/>grayish white snow, and the long winter<br/>has finally come and gone, and I\u2019ve almost forgotten<br/>that there is a big white old house in Brooklyn<br/>and it\u2019s empty, and why this stair<br/>needs to be pushed up so that I can step</p><p>down in it all, like my mother\u2019s face<br/>on the news: a man with a broken hand<br/>walks by, and I am reminded<br/>that when I am not reading, I am usually thinking of<br/>the bicycle I promised to find</p><p>when the weather turns cold, and I am happy<br/>to have it in my house, somewhere,<br/>where I can look up and see the world moving on.</p>",
    "<p><b>Sickle Pat<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Scott Cairns</b></p><p>A sickle Pat<br/> for color and a spur Pat<br/>for feeling and a sinister hand;<br/>Paps and decliners and an occasional Crow Pat\u2014<br/>These are, without a doubt, the most important colors in my life.<br/>I look for them at the market, at nail &amp; gasket,<br/>at the pawn-shop or the thrift store.</p><p>I love to see the ones I like<br/>the most in pairs and in trios.<br/>Paint one or two stripes,<br/>slip the other over.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cFrom the Period of the War with the Fever of the Heart\u201d as a Poem for a Long Time Under the Sea by Anonymous</b></p><p>From the period of the war with the fever of the heart,<br/>within the town below, a mass of men and women from the subversive ranks<br/>finding themselves on the razor's edge</p><p>of the town below.</p><p>Sipping their coffee in the cafe where they came from, the women</p><p>said goodbye, and went on into the assault on the city below.</p>",
    "<p><b>By The Sea by Richard Wilbur</b></p><p>And the tides have swept us off.<br/>We are collected in a room, said the librarian,<br/>to the library of your face,<br/>to your writing.</p><p>And so we have been locked out.<br/>We are brought in to a room.<br/>The tall white desk,<br/>where I once sat and listened<br/>to the sea,<br/>where I once sat and listened<br/>to the waves.</p><p>The sky is falling.<br/>The sky is red.<br/>The sky is blue.<br/>And the books are melting.<br/>The sea has broken their backs.</p><p>The sea has gone!<br/>We are the ones who\u2019re crushed.<br/>We\u2019re the ones who\u2019re caught.</p><p>And we are still dazed with the lights\u2009\u2014<br/>though the lights have dimmed.<br/>And the books are burned.</p><p>Or are they?</p>",
    "<p><b>Once Upon a Time by Robert Frost</b></p><p>It was a lovely November day,<br/>The day the house was home,<br/>And cozy were the nights,<br/>The parlor was a-changin',<br/>The lawn was a-raisin',<br/>And there was a picture book<br/>Everywhere</p><p>When I turned on the TV.<br/>I couldn\u2019t see the first movie,<br/>But it was the first<br/>One that made me smile.</p><p>I said it was wonderful,<br/>And I would have said the same<br/>If it had stayed on.</p><p>It did for a while.<br/>And then I went to bed<br/>And woke as soon as I was<br/>Downstairs,</p><p>Downstairs, down the stairs!<br/>Once upon a time,<br/>Once upon a time,<br/>Once upon a time,<br/>I went down the stairs in my house</p><p>And only then did I notice<br/>That I had forgotten<br/>About that picture book!</p>",
    "<p><b>The Story of the Disappearance of My Father by Henry Wadsworth Long</b></p><p>It was a cold day and I was standing on the terrace<br/>under the scorching sun. One of the stones<br/>I was sticking to, the grouse that I had trod<br/>as I walked for days, calling out to the ghost<br/>of my father. When he turned up and looked too good<br/>to be dead he said:<br/>\u201cThis is it, my boy. This is the end.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cPitiful Pencils for My Teeth of a Child\u201d<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Juan Bradley</b></p><p>You can\u2019t learn to set a condom down<br/>or erase a footprint<br/>but you can learn to get a shoulder from<br/>a tree and then it\u2019s not so much</p><p>getting a piece of you out<br/>but having a piece of you</p><p>and of you</p><p><br/>Your warmth and the silence of knowing<br/>is like a sick room on a desert island<br/>where you\u2019re alone with your life<br/>that nobody offers you.</p><p>Your skies and the birds that sing in them<br/>are like a blessed Rastarnath in my mouth<br/>where I shave a little bit</p><p>and they\u2019re not anointing;<br/>you are so beautiful<br/>and if you were here, what</p><p>would you do<br/>without your hands?</p><p>I\u2019ve heard from teachers<br/>that you\u2019re so bright<br/>and so kind<br/>that everything I do is dandy;</p><p>and I hear that you\u2019re very brave;<br/>but who is brave<br/>when he\u2019s afraid? I\u2019m afraid of</p><p>the darkness of being afraid.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Coral by Bernard Bro\u00e9</b></p><p>From the sea,</p><p>from the coral,</p><p>I\u2019ve learned</p><p>that the greatest of sorrows</p><p>are knowing,</p><p>knowing the wonderful</p><p>Coral Reefs are gone</p><p>(for good reason)</p><p>and that I\u2019m not alone</p><p>on this earth\u2019s unlit</p><p>mountains,</p><p>on the great plains</p><p>where the water rolls</p><p>through broken dunes</p><p>and frees</p><p>wood barns,</p><p>even from this vantage</p><p>hear the Coral</p><p>sing on,</p><p>sing with the sea</p><p>as I have for years</p><p>when my children</p><p>go to the beach to come back</p><p>and to look at the new creation,</p><p>knowing that no new ocean</p><p>will ever be empty</p><p>and nothing winds up</p><p>on a reef\u2019s support</p><p>and no need to run to a place</p><p>where I shouldn\u2019t hide</p><p>from the ocean\u2019s disapproval.</p>",
    "<p><b>Wallpaper by David Wojahn</b></p><p>It\u2019s like the one in The Constant Gardener,<br/>where the trees are photo-real.</p><p>You\u2019re in your room,<br/>the magnifying glass is on,<br/>you\u2019re alone.</p><p>It\u2019s so quiet that I like</p><p>the really quiet spot,<br/>if only to scream silently</p><p>at something.<br/>I\u2019ve done this</p><p>before,<br/>I\u2019ve seen it done</p><p>before,<br/>I\u2019ve done it this way</p>",
    "<p><b>Pap\u00e1 by J. Allyn Rosser</b></p><p>He was the first black man to speak in a Korean cafe<br/>in a Chicago alley<br/>despite a Roofsby-like vocal deficiencies<br/>he was a revelation<br/>Untermeyer, the Hungarian<br/>Chadwickian of the street<br/>I mean a human being<br/>who knew how to move<br/>what we mean by \"disemboweled</p><p><br/>heckled at the nose<br/>and chin<br/>the chin won\u2019t rise<br/>the nose won\u2019t fall</p><p>he was even biracial<br/>he could turn a black man\u2019s head<br/>and feel blackface<br/>we did not want</p><p>he had the lackadaisical<br/>unpredictable enthusiasm<br/>of someone who felt<br/>the need to clean a ceiling<br/>or ride the subway</p><p>it\u2019s hard to pin him down</p><p>he was taller than me<br/>even though we were mostly</p><p>the same height</p>",
    "<p><b>The Woman in the Window by Vicki Sorensen</b></p><p>Who is she? You have never seen her.<br/>You walk a long hallway<br/>debating who will blame her<br/>when she leaves the house after dark<br/>and does not return for hours.<br/>Who is she? You have never seen her.<br/>You climb the stairs<br/>to the fourth floor<br/>and reach for the hand<br/>that is still resting<br/>on the curtain rod,<br/>not looking back<br/>to see the face<br/>behind her back<br/>as you walk to the kitchen<br/>with a cup of coffee,<br/>your hand<br/>on the stove,<br/>your gaze<br/>on the ceiling<br/>winding between two<br/>ducks on the ice<br/>and back<br/>to the woman<br/>who has not<br/>walked out of the house after dark<br/>since you have not<br/>seen her.</p>",
    "<p><b>Prayer by Robert Burns</b></p><p>Now we are the friends we wished to be,<br/>All that was good in our hearts,<br/>And together we could love no more.<br/>Now, farewell! Please leave<br/>Not a word in our lives but<br/>The sight of your beauty<br/>Restores our hearts to love.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Man Who Met the Mammoth by Sandra Beasley</b></p><p>My mother went to visit the man who made her feel special.<br/>An animal, of course, but also\u2014no\u2014a kind of magic.<br/>He was a great admirer, and she loved to think<br/>the deer caught in the trapdoor that fell,<br/>the earth was made of butterflies and the moon<br/>was a can of worms. But she had never seen him,<br/>and it was a real risk, to look\u2014even in the photo<br/>in the absence of the frame, the man still looked<br/>stubbornly at her, and beyond the photo<br/>the man, who was in the photo, was nowhere<br/>to be found.<br/>I melted. I was so jealous, I melted.<br/>I am smiling now, thinking of you.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Other Side of the Farmhouse by Robert Hayden</b></p><p>They ballyhooed us from the lower deck,<br/>the blankets fetching the mums.</p><p>My mother sat in the soundproof booth<br/>watching the rest of the orchestra keep her brain alive,</p><p>her words crisping the air around them<br/>like pancakes falling into a slow-cooker of rice</p><p>and back again. She was living, her page<br/>on the ice was frozen and her hours</p><p>in the sun-battered yard were slipping into heat<br/>or heat into the kitchen cubicle,</p><p>or my brain. She was almost<br/>lovely. She sang about love,</p><p>open-mouthed, flat-palmed, in front of a plate<br/>of chicken nuggets, who would have had preferred</p><p>a longer tour to follow the corn to the next field,<br/>but who was coming along,</p><p>unreservedly, as the tour guide would have it,<br/>to carry us back, to the end,</p><p>to a stealthy car that looked like a distant farmhouse<br/>with three white doors and the look on her face<br/>was not weary or uncertain or sad.</p><p>How could we be happier?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Blessed Virgin by Gretchen Ritter</b></p><p>the unassuming philosopher<br/>who\u2019ll be noble<br/>from the dusk of passion\u2019s soul.</p><p>Bottles<br/>of dry-cleaned beer<br/>on the rug or someone\u2019s ass.</p><p>Blessed are you, our philosopher<br/>or the bullet that knocks you down.</p><p>The first breath, that\u2019s pure nothing<br/>and soundless, and the rest</p><p>are the prayer the fleshy</p><p>bodies make at the opening<br/>of life. She\u2019s either the breath</p><p>you are said to have committed</p><p>or the one you have not.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Hanging Gardens of the Willamette Valley by David Bottoms</b></p><p>Where snow comes<br/>to sleep at night.<br/>Where there are no<br/>winds, no<br/>bird calls,<br/>the mountains are silent,<br/>the wind dissolves<br/>to a sky<br/>of bright car lights.<br/>Where the trail<br/>of tired footsteps is made<br/>by the late<br/>hucksters, and no one<br/>has to carry shoes,<br/>the trail is out<br/>strewn with cans<br/>and bottles,<br/>and every place<br/>where the breeze\u200b\u00a0\u201cpurls,<br/>drips, and spills,<br/>the leaves are green.<br/>Where the house<br/>is made of piles of sticks<br/>and stacked<br/>on top of another<br/>made of sticks and stacks<br/>of sticks and stacks.<br/>Where the fallen<br/>angel is hidden<br/>and waiting<br/>for his fate,<br/>the land is made<br/>of damn near everything<br/>I\u2019ve wanted to be, but<br/>not the kind of crazy<br/>yuppie land that\u2019s<br/>being rented out.<br/>My land is beneath the earth,<br/>not walking on it.</p>",
    "<p><b>Echo by Samuel Taylor Coleridge</b></p><p>What are you taking from the world that is yours?<br/>A cow and a rat after a race,<br/>A bird and a crow<br/>About the same nature,<br/>And most of all love,<br/>Those two cows.</p><p>A cow and a rat<br/>Are two livestock.<br/>You have nothing to eat but love<br/>The calf, the rat,<br/>The ox.</p>",
    "<p><b>Resident Evil by Thunderbird</b></p><p>We reached where we<br/>had never been before.<br/>We were tall<br/>and blonde, had many<br/>backpacks, each with<br/>a desk and a pad.</p><p>Our bodies were paper,<br/>made of a thin<br/>&amp; light.</p><p>We ran through<br/>townies in sandals.</p><p>We didn\u2019t dare<br/>touch the poles sticking<br/>up from the ground.</p><p>We shoved<br/>back on the train<br/>&amp; walked<br/>down the aisle<br/>to a dark blue<br/>gown. It was</p><p>sunny that day.<br/>We weren\u2019t<br/>in the business<br/>of killing.</p><p>I was in<br/>the back of the car,<br/>facing<br/>the back seat.</p><p>I couldn\u2019t<br/>see my eyes,<br/>&amp; the vision<br/>of a man<br/>in a burlap sack<br/>rattling up and down<br/>it an upside down</p><p>beach that I witnessed<br/>and I could<br/>be inside.</p><p>The screen flashed<br/>a woman. After<br/>she died<br/>my vision<br/>shot upward<br/>a little on my<br/>right side.</p><p>It took<br/>a whole labor<br/>to stay<br/>where I was<br/>and take the part<br/>he wanted me to play.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Lot by Frank Stanford</b></p><p>I look through a gate into<br/>A small room filled with the<br/>Dead, who've never<br/>Made it here.<br/>What is the room<br/>For? Is that a hose</p><p>Raked behind me<br/>To hang the laundry above my head? Lock<br/>The door, and I'll be back<br/>As if nothing happened.</p><p>The night never sleeps,<br/>The light never dims,<br/>The spiders that watch it<br/>Sail off, never</p><p>Running out of breath.<br/>It's morning, and like<br/>A waterless cauldron<br/>In the eye, my mother would say</p><p>Is that a child?<br/>Or someone else's,<br/>Like the one I was seeing<br/>Behind the window? Even so,</p><p>It's not like that to me,<br/>Although I am anxious<br/>To get back to my place,</p><p>Which I thought was a house.<br/>But this is like a train,</p><p>A strange train, or a bed<br/>I have years to fill:</p><p>Do I even need a roof,<br/>When I'm already on top,</p><p>Or do I just want to stay in my place?</p>",
    "<p><b>Shake by Brent Pallas</b></p><p>In the old house,<br/>a porch<br/>has long since been pushed back,<br/>and in the old yard<br/>the boughs are still.</p><p>I\u2019ve never been to my father<br/>but the house is<br/>stale; I see clouds</p><p>through the window<br/>and hear the cold</p><p>coming from upstairs.</p><p>I get up<br/>and go outside</p><p>with my toes.</p><p>I sit in the shade</p><p>and watch the clouds<br/>throw and then</p><p>blown away.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Thing About the Toothbrush by Pauli Murray</b></p><p>What was it I had said<br/>about teeth that ran</p><p>toward the nose? It\u2019s possible<br/>that I had said all of my</p><p>oars were fucking<br/>a perfect toothbrush heads down</p><p>into a clean mouth and back</p><p>to the blacks of my face, running<br/>into the cocked gun, the gun</p><p>down the middle of the lineup, wheeling</p><p>the baton, the streets waltzing past</p><p>in a procession of debris, the silent</p><p>toothed teeth in the toothbrush mouths,</p><p>the spunky tang of my voice</p><p>wresting dirt in the teeth</p><p>make me daring</p><p>to love you,</p><p>leading a lost march</p><p>of the funicular</p><p>behind the train,</p><p>poised above the fray</p><p>of the screams,</p><p>the big metal motion of my face</p><p>as I slip the flat</p><p>circumference of the traffic</p><p>chrome into a fender,</p><p>in the heat of the moment</p><p>whoa, whoa, whoa,</p><p>accelerando,</p><p>the thing about the toothbrush</p><p>licking the snow off my arm</p><p>into my mouth,</p><p>the thing about the toothbrush</p><p>thumping off the snow<br/>off my breath,</p><p>a giant, unfancing black smirk</p>",
    "<p><b>A Prairie Baby by Rhys Jones</b></p><p>I will not hide from you</p><p>for you to protect.<br/>I will tell you everything</p><p>take you back.<br/>You are beautiful</p><p>and I am not.</p><p>I will never stop</p><p>knowing you</p><p>but most importantly</p><p>you are my son.</p><p>You look only on me</p><p>when I turn away</p><p>from my mother</p>",
    "<p><b>After the Aurora by Miriam Bird Greenberg</b></p><p>Follow the path, the light,<br/>no need to feel guilty, and the long<br/>way home. Be sure the house</p><p>is still standing, that it has not<br/>fallen during the night, and that the floodlights</p><p>will not spark once the moon stops<br/>shooting into the distance. And, following</p><p>the path, always remember that the rose</p><p>will never say goodbye, until you</p><p>lay your hair behind the door and turn</p><p>to go. Pick up your shoes, and kneel</p><p>before the stove in the dining room.<br/>The dog, who knows how to drop</p><p>a leash or sit up, will lead you</p><p>inside. See how the second hand</p><p>is always slipping out from under</p><p>the first, and I am wrong</p><p>about this: I have grown so used</p><p>to having the body,</p><p>caught up in the concept of</p><p>stuff and bubbles. And my feet</p><p>have grown so tall and heavy</p><p>that I cannot walk</p><p>and walk and walk,</p><p>and not be afraid</p><p>when I am about to go.</p>",
    "<p><b>On a Stone by Michael Anania</b></p><p>Canon:<br/>\u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9<br/>Remember those places<br/>where I had to cross<br/>the river, often alone<br/>with what had to be found<br/>there, what had to be</p><p>found.<br/>So that\u2019s why I\u2019ve<br/>never stood on the bridge<br/>lifting my hat.</p><p>Which is the better image<br/>of the universe,<br/>to be born<br/>only on your birthday<br/>or to have lived<br/>on a footbridge<br/>for seventeen years?</p><p>Except that living<br/>on a footbridge is<br/>not like the image<br/>of the universe.</p><p>Like the image of the<br/>protector who<br/>comes to the village<br/>to take away the boys</p><p>who\u2019ve wrecked the place<br/>that is your life.</p><p>Only like the image<br/>of the river,<br/>which keeps<br/>breaking open<br/>only one dam</p><p>does not<br/>make a perfect<br/>bridge, making<br/>a bridge</p><p>or a stair.<br/>Still, the image<br/>of a little boat<br/>lying on the bottom<br/>of a mountain</p><p>with a sign<br/>on the bottom<br/>of the hill<br/>on a rickety<br/>car</p><p>and the river<br/>inside it<br/>has been<br/>broken into<br/>pieces and thrown<br/>back to the top<br/>or to the side<br/>of the hill.</p><p>I wanted to make<br/>an image of the<br/>little boat<br/>on the bottom<br/>of the mountain,<br/>and the little<br/>car on the top,<br/>and the river<br/>inside it,<br/>and the little<br/>boat<br/>on its side,<br/>and the little<br/>chicken that<br/>pees on a tree.</p>",
    "<p><b>Misrowlor by Pete Edwards</b></p><p>In the house of mind<br/>where our party stayed,<br/>I held a unwritten rule: it\u2019s</p><p>not to dress this way.</p><p>If I felt threatened,<br/>I would not wear a bathrobe.</p><p>If I did not know<br/>how to walk through</p><p>the dark, I should not<br/>be drinking that evening and</p><p>spending the night upstairs.</p><p>Never mind the price,</p><p>I would not be<br/>stepping on the gas (<br/>I\u2019m not sure what to call</p><p>that feeling of space</p><p>that my mother wore</p><p>when she stood<br/>and twisted to us,</p><p>her long red skirt<br/>on the screen</p><p>offering more than the street<br/>to the street below.</p><p>And if I did<br/>not know</p><p>to be silent<br/>or to feel shame,<br/>I should not</p><p>know, because I did not know<br/>\u201cHow to use Legos\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>Emily Dickinson: The Mannequin by Algiers Zeff</b></p><p>1</p><p>A mannequin sits with a courtier\u2019s saddle<br/>and a clown\u2019s mask on<br/>\u201cThe Mannequin\u201d by Art Spiegelman</p>",
    "<p><b>continuous change: some troublemaker\u2019s color<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Shanley Bustamante</b></p><p>continuous change</p><p>no matter how hard my mind<br/>I\u2019m never going to be as good</p><p>as I used to be,<br/>so don\u2019t just</p><p>take that as a joke.</p><p>not everyone is the same<br/>or as good</p><p>maybe you\u2019ve heard</p><p>the woman say<br/>\u201cjust because your eyes<br/>always direct to the right</p><p>doesn\u2019t mean you\u2019re murdering my brothers<br/>idiot</p><p>not every blackface<br/>is a double-dutch</p><p>not everyone is El Rey</p><p>I am<br/>not doing just this either</p><p>I\u2019ll say it<br/>(in a karate bang)</p><p>not every blackface<br/>is a double-dutch</p><p>not everyone was El Rey</p><p>I was<br/>not doing just this either</p><p>and that\u2019s the thing<br/>about face work</p><p>where you start with the top<br/>and move up or down</p><p>you\u2019ve got to make</p><p>it work</p><p>are you suuuuuure?</p><p>I am<br/>up for it</p><p>and you\u2019re welcome</p><p>to join</p><p>and my brother<br/>was born</p><p>none of this matters anymore</p>",
    "<p><b>The Folding Chair by John Leo</b></p><p>Half of you are off the road<br/>and the other half are here.<br/>You\u2019re on the cushion or in the chair<br/>while the damaged ones<br/>make pilgrimages to the bench<br/>where a traveler once<br/>spoke quietly, as though he didn\u2019t<br/>know where he was going.<br/>You\u2019re looking up,<br/>waiting for the light to change.</p><p>You\u2019ve brought a book,<br/>which I assume is poetry,<br/>or perhaps a song,<br/>to read after the work.<br/>I stick the book to the seat<br/>where it\u2019s for sale.<br/>I don\u2019t care if I belong<br/>to a dying school in Washington<br/>or the latest model,<br/>I\u2019m still the same old<br/>street person perfect as I was<br/>a year ago,<br/>I\u2019m just trying to be<br/>hands on and efficient<br/>as possible</p>",
    "<p><b>by Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca</b></p><p>I once sat under a tree<br/>and watched women pass<br/>into each other\u2009\u2014\u2009almost a woman</p><p>and a man\u2009\u2014\u2009like little moon faces<br/>that could pour out</p><p>of their doorways and<br/>become a liquid flow</p><p>of sunlight or something<br/>that did not</p><p>make anything wet or sour<br/>enter my body</p><p>I was not allowed<br/>to talk or hear my voice<br/>or move</p><p>I was not allowed<br/>to see my own body<br/>and I heard my own voice</p><p>I said<br/>to myself\u2009\u2014\u2009how many times</p><p>how many people<br/>have died\u2019 under these circumstances</p><p>which do not</p><p>strengthen the arms or<br/>the hands or</p><p>the whole body<br/>to fight the mind</p><p>or to get over it<br/>to a place</p><p>where the mind<br/>can not</p><p>compare with anything</p><p>because it is not</p><p>generous<br/>because it is not</p><p>thoroughly reflective<br/>because it is not</p><p>of any use<br/>because it can\u2019t.</p>",
    "<p><b>The 4:33 Ampersand by Robin Ekiss</b></p><p>I get the feeling that, in the heretofore<br/>murky netherworld, I have not traveled too far,<br/>am I not a long way off?\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0I have,<br/>as they say in daytime, a long way to go.</p><p>I hear the familiar sound of my own voice--<br/>like a classroom where I am a teacher<br/>holding the same book which just happens<br/>to be my school notebook.\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0I have said the right<br/>thing<br/>to my students, and I have been<br/>truthful\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0at all times.</p><p>But this morning I listen<br/>for the sound of my own feet<br/>and I can hear them, when I am<br/>all alone, saying the wrong thing.</p><p>What is the wrong thing?\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0I don\u2019t know.\u00a0\u00a0 Maybe<br/>something nice?\u00a0\u00a0 Maybe a forest<br/>full of lovely animals and birds?</p><p>I am sure I am one of the few teachers<br/>who can teach my students how to say the right thing.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Fugue by Iliez Cato</b></p><p>It took me a long time to master the black-and-white photograph of my wife.<br/>In the end I moved on rather than owning the room.</p><p>Later I realized I had intended to paint a life<br/>but whose eyes were just too dim to handle the light.<br/>Later, I realized I had intended to paint a life.</p><p>Early Sunday morning I awoke before my wife<br/>and drifted off to sleep. On Monday I tried to sing<br/>Meet Me in the Square</p><p>while standing on the New York street that will never be<br/>an aisle</p><p><br/>where a still portion of the tree collapsed<br/>just as I was</p><p>and the tree, once it was to remain,<br/>floated up and broke and fell behind<br/>a building</p><p>when the building was right next to me.<br/>I must have moved at least twice<br/>during the day, was, or will be,</p><p>when it will stand<br/>again and falls again</p><p>and I will be there</p><p>thinking now and then<br/>of that photo</p><p>I took of my wife<br/>just before she died</p><p>and the silent line<br/>of the pilgrims<br/>falls from the sky</p><p>and it is neither here nor there<br/>I should say</p><p><br/>but never will be,<br/>if it ever gets there</p>",
    "<p><b>St. Mary's Cathedral in Malibu<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Jesse Addonizio</b></p><p>First the sun rose<br/>and a wave of clouds</p><p>burst over the valley</p><p>like austerities<br/>adrift in the deep</p><p>like aural orgasm</p><p>to come to a stop</p><p>on the hill\u2019s rim</p><p>where I could see</p><p>the tide curve</p><p>as if a boat</p><p>were just keeling over a gully</p><p>and then</p><p>a gleam rose on the horizon</p><p>and a hooded figure</p><p>was keeping a sharp eye</p><p>at the sound of the chimes</p><p>belonging to the city of angels</p><p>for as long as the sun stayed</p><p>on the horizon\u2019s rocky face</p><p>while a werewolf raged</p><p>I watched as he</p><p>crucified the city</p><p>and the only sound</p><p>were the chimes.</p><p>I remember thinking</p><p>every deputy knows</p><p>what\u2019s at the center</p><p>of this madness</p><p>but if God was here</p><p>he would know what</p><p>was it like</p><p>to be a boy in front of a werewolf</p><p>and a werewolf in front</p><p>of a city in the desert</p><p>and a werewolf screaming</p><p>no.</p>",
    "<p><b>Heart of the Dog by CAConrad</b></p><p>\u2014\u2009Lorraine Moten</p><p>Forgotten now, can we get back<br/>to what the dog said?<br/>Let\u2019s focus on the answer.<br/>A small fist</p><p>was all he needed to know<br/>to tell us he\u2019d been bitten.</p><p>Forgotten now, can we get back<br/>to the very dog whose words<br/>set off a chain of events<br/>and left us all a-walking</p><p>through the house of bones<br/>and the ocean\u2019s swirling filthy</p><p>beams of salt and clamoring,<br/>shameless and aggressive.<br/>A small hand</p><p>was all he needed to know<br/>to tell us that his paw</p><p>was the one who got bitten.<br/>Little one?</p><p>Forgotten now, can we get back<br/>to the very dog whose words<br/>bound our lives together</p><p>into the embrace of something<br/>we couldn\u2019t have changed?</p>",
    "<p><b>Funeral by Donald (Grady) Davidson</b></p><p>Passing, with a lazy jerk, past the boarded-up cemeteries,<br/>The baker's, like the street of the dead;</p><p>In a dimly-lit room where the casket was locked<br/>At the top, a white of logarithms<br/>A beaded hose, filled with molten lead,</p><p>Spike-nosed, in the face,<br/>Crossed by a strap from the casket,<br/>As I pass; as I pass,</p><p>Only beggar-like, a slouching bum,<br/>With ragged, toothless hair,</p><p>Loosed with a scuff of bones,<br/>Gligarly, grubby, unpressed,</p><p>Sewn with it, hang-dog, with a lice-ridden face,<br/>Picking up the bones as they are lost,</p><p>Like scraped-up handkerchiefs,<br/>Worn, rotting, in the post-mortem<br/>Sorter, faster than being interred, I am</p><p>Taken home to my bereavement<br/>And the people who were just like me.</p><p><br/>In Buenos Aires we like to sit in a corner<br/>And have a drink, or a bit of conversation,<br/>For there is only one other person there,</p><p>This local who has never been to Argentina<br/>And has been to the United States only once.<br/>If I were in his place, I would read him my last rites<br/>and say,Grady, thank you. To \"Eat for the Mindful\"</p><p>is a joke, but there is much to be said<br/>For the people we pass, for the others</p><p>We have come to love and for whom our lives<br/>Are not harmless slow-jumps, but real,<br/>And who have shown us more than others<br/>The way to become a person.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Landscape by Eileen Myles</b></p><p>The very scent of the place I grew up in<br/>is seductive\u2014the alfalfa<br/>pale, the lavender<br/>evergreen, sweet smelling.</p><p>The sun sinks behind the hills<br/>and they whisper from the houses<br/>and the yard and the wrappers<br/>in the corner of the grocery store<br/>that it will stay there<br/>and come again.</p><p>The air<br/>is one hundred percent decorous<br/>and neatly frilly<br/>and clean and nice<br/>and there is music<br/>in every room<br/>and a water fountain<br/>in every tub.</p><p>The earth is free herring<br/>when I pull the pruning knife<br/>by the roots<br/>and drop it into the earth<br/>and it returns to the sea<br/>and it is the earth<br/>that comes up around the roots of a tree and<br/>climbs into an oar<br/>and the white car of the driver<br/>coming up behind it</p><p>and I\u2019m there again<br/>searching, a wing<br/>not without me,<br/>but we\u2019re converging<br/>as if we\u2019ve never parted<br/>before when I say<br/>\u201cThe landscape of my life\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>A Scent of Laughing By Richard Wilbur</b></p><p>He did not know what he was doing.<br/>He was a child who went outside<br/>And learned to make himself an art.<br/>Then he danced. Then he sang.<br/>He did not know what he was doing.</p><p>There are two kinds of flowers, the kind<br/>That Look like the Sweet Smell of the Sun.<br/>And the kind that Look like the Musk of a Worry.</p><p>And that is not pleasant.<br/>That is not pleasant at all.</p><p>He did not know what he was doing.<br/>He was going to be the most beautiful boy<br/>In the whole world.</p><p>There are two kinds of men, the kind<br/>That Wake up Every Morning a Happy Man.<br/>And the kind that Stay Home and Forget.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cWhy did you let your deadbody go?\u201d by Anonymous</b></p><p>Why did you let your deadbody go?<br/>I don\u2019t have one<br/>I\u2019m a free man<br/>|\u201cSo who is your daddy?\u201d</p><p>So who is your daddy<br/>You don\u2019t own a dog</p>",
    "<p><b>When I Look at You by Charlotte Mew</b></p><p>Because you are so<br/>un-plastered,<br/>I finish my watch<br/>in an hour.</p><p>Because I\u2019ve gone<br/>pale, you are<br/>almost invisible.</p><p>Because you\u2019re<br/>always smiling,<br/>you\u2019re our source of<br/>advice.</p><p>Because you ride<br/>your bike to work,<br/>you\u2019re the only<br/>body who can give<br/>in to the office politics.</p><p>Because you call yourself<br/>an adult,<br/>you need to get<br/>a life.</p><p>Because you want<br/>to dress<br/>appropriately,<br/>you need to do<br/>something about it.</p><p>Because you\u2019re a recluse<br/>like me,<br/>you eat dinner alone<br/>and go to bed hungry.</p>",
    "<p><b>Chant by David Wojahn</b></p><p>For the one who\u2019d never \u201cgrieve\u201d<br/>When I\u2019m gone, it\u2019s for sure<br/>And enclosed<br/>In a liberality of words</p><p>And by no means<br/>Nervous or in a hurry</p><p>Settled myself down<br/>As my go-to solo song</p><p>To be sung by me<br/>In a coffee shop somewhere</p><p>I leave the room.</p><p>Here I am,<br/>With my own slightly shivery voice and</p><p>An empty chair.</p><p>On my way<br/>I\u2019ll never return</p><p>And how am I grateful</p><p>That I\u2019ve missed my chance?</p>",
    "<p><b>A Description by Robin Ekiss</b></p><p>In the labyrinthine atrium where I sit,<br/>sleeping, I am surrounded by the sound of<br/>the driver\u2019s feet,<br/>the night breeze, the curtained figure<br/>of the windowblind opening<br/>or closing. Sirens</p><p>and horns, the noise of four doors<br/>closing, doors steadily starting<br/>or stopping, and the night wind</p><p>trying to catch me. The tall<br/>glass, the long mirrors, all<br/>in a panic, as if I am<br/>just the brain of a pigeon,</p><p>And as I try to remember the train<br/>the name or what the name means\u2014<br/>all hard and beautiful work</p><p>or mindless play, all<br/>a kind of surrender. It is<br/>unemploymentable to work</p><p>in the thicket of this room,<br/>hooked into the ceiling by the sound<br/>or echoes of the latch,</p><p>to be completely alone<br/>on the cobbled streets of Manhattan,<br/>nearly the only silence</p><p>I would ever want, this drunk<br/>singing in the dark or in the dark,</p><p>I am just a kind of vessel<br/>that carries the meaning of an entrance<br/>and an entrance</p><p>into a letter or into a subway<br/>at the end of a long journey</p><p>for the words<br/>that carry no meaning</p><p>but the same sound of hope<br/>and love, I am</p><p>borne like a bird<br/>by the sound of someone\u2019s feet<br/>and the soft, dried</p><p>lingering sound of the door.</p><p>And the network of tunnels and<br/>ladders</p><p>the whole metropolis that<br/>I have walked through</p><p>with my bare feet,<br/>I have trod</p><p>under the great glass<br/>that looks up into the desert</p><p>and down into the sea<br/>and I have stood</p><p>to watch the quiet<br/>birds of death</p><p>the star wolves<br/>and their helpless</p><p>children</p><p>cowering under the metal<br/>of a collapsed train and<br/>the great windows</p><p>that have allowed<br/>the building of a civilization</p><p>that has lost its</p><p>arable land<br/>and is lying</p><p>over itself.</p>",
    "<p><b>An 80-Yard Drive by Robert Miller</b></p><p>On the transition to shade<br/>the earth takes over<br/>and the meadow litters itself</p><p>with mimosa-mimosa, making<br/>the peak peek around a tree</p><p>and the woodschooned depression<br/>nearly 2 ft. tall</p><p>and the sheworn, orthophthalmic ridge<br/>with a half-moon slant</p><p>to its base shoots<br/>in a whirlwind of white,</p><p>and it could be the source<br/>for the amber sea</p><p>on the hillside above the antique shop<br/>or a nursery rhyme</p><p>or a spilled hibiscus.</p><p>Can you imagine a man leaning over<br/>a cowling that little? Can you imagine a tree</p><p>stepping over a flake or two<br/>on the way to a trunk or a knucklehead?</p><p>It\u2019s not quite like the movie<br/>\u2014that\u2019s implied<br/>by a dingy dimpled skirt,</p><p>a sorry excuse for a sweater<br/>and a generic t-shirt,</p><p>but living is hard and it\u2019s not<br/>every day you get to do it<br/>and there\u2019s a reason for that.</p><p>I\u2019ve had this thing<br/>going on for years now</p><p>where I\u2019m either mutual or natur<br/>and I\u2019ve always managed to be some sort</p><p>of tragic hero who somehow<br/>has to forgive\u2009\u2014\u2009that night</p><p>when the storm came<br/>I had a chance to pretend</p><p>I\u2019m still in love with the snow and I<br/>laughed\u2009\u2014\u2009I\u2019d walk home</p><p>in that duffel, maybe a wool sweater,<br/>but only if it was wool.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Boy Who Wet His Pants by Elfriede Wolp\u00e9</b></p><p>Let\u2019s not help him, or<br/>his mattress, because his mother<br/>since he was an infant<br/>has never done so.<br/>Scrambling for whatever<br/>he can find, he will<br/>distrust my nakedness,<br/>but the threshold<br/>of all that I will do<br/>is when he\u2019s a grown man,<br/>not when he\u2019s a boy.</p>",
    "<p><b>End and Beginning by Marge Piercy</b></p><p>The end of my suffering is the beginning of my enjoyment,<br/>final act of a creative play that avoids despair.</p><p>The beginning of my suffering is the end of a piece of work<br/>that is already good but unfinished.</p><p>The end of my suffering is not a development of art<br/>that has not yet achieved a mature feeling.</p><p>The beginning and end of my suffering<br/>are two sides of the same coin, one of which<br/>is the end of pain, the other an expression<br/>of the end of pain.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Spandrel by Edith Sitwell</b></p><p>I have no doubt I shall live to see that day<br/>When I shall be as fair as I am;<br/>When life and all the world shall know<br/>That I am alive and worthy of all the rest;<br/>When I shall be worthy of all the rest,<br/>And the green earth shall once again tremble,<br/>And the sea shall call my trade,<br/>And the trees shall call my clamor?</p><p>Now, for Heaven's sake, if that day should come,<br/>And that my life shall have me borne<br/>Out of my labors and my sleep,\u2014<br/>I will go and be worthy of it!</p>",
    "<p><b>Elegy by Kevin Forty</b></p><p>Why don\u2019t we let the day pass<br/>like the rest of us, eyes on the horizon,<br/>chattering as the gossip seeps<br/>through the walls of our heads that have known<br/>safety, a lifetime of snobbish pride<br/>so that we might leave a little something<br/>to the economy and bring on the next day<br/>a morning full of butterflies.</p><p>We could sit in the minifridge of the desk<br/>and gossip about how much we actually owe<br/>to this fourth wall and our own place,<br/>the chamber pots and the fountain behind us.</p><p>Or we could just wake up and be like everyone else,<br/>so excited to be leaving behind a legacy<br/>that we would not hesitate to take our own life.<br/>If it were just another job and the paycheck<br/>was just another pittance, perhaps.</p><p>Yet the circus ends a little before it begins,<br/>some time prior to the start of the day,<br/>and we sit there, silent, toasting<br/>the days that have passed,<br/>and the empty promises that we could have<br/>made if we had just braved the cobalt traffic<br/>and wandered the dark corridors of a castle<br/>that nobody would have ever heard of<br/>before we headed into the open sky,<br/>and was that all there was of that?</p>",
    "<p><b>Apostasy by Linda Everwine</b></p><p>Remembering<br/>What is left of us<br/>Is not the city<br/>(according to the bible)<br/>but a town, a place of caves<br/>with walls so thick<br/>they were made of lava<br/>and obsidian<br/>and tunnels so deep<br/>they reached the very edge<br/>where stars come out<br/>and start their own hours</p><p>Every night the same<br/>gulls sat on a boat<br/>and prayed<br/>I still am alive<br/>forever on the ocean--</p><p>The only place<br/>I'll ever be<br/>is sinking by the sun<br/>and sweeping the earth<br/>away</p><p>Loners<br/>and closeted<br/>songs<br/>come to me<br/>with poetry<br/>in their ears</p>",
    "<p><b>Some Sinners by Raymond Williams</b></p><p>I had a life. It wasn\u2019t gay.<br/>That\u2019s what we said inside the house<br/>that we couldn\u2019t move out of.<br/>It didn\u2019t hurt that much longer<br/>at the end of the streets.<br/>The rain poured<br/>and washed the windows.<br/>A rusty Jeep pulled up<br/>to a house in the middle of nowhere<br/>and took off and closed<br/>the door. I wondered<br/>where was they going,<br/>where was they going?<br/>But then I noticed<br/>a little gray box<br/>tied around the back of a chair<br/>like a little lampshade<br/>illuminated in the sun,<br/>and there it was again,<br/>the same face,<br/>the same mouth<br/>of the same old gray face</p><p>and me asked again<br/>if I\u2019ll stay.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Orange by Nicholas Shax</b></p><p>The late plan,<br/>our method<br/>of lying\u2014<br/>we hatched a plan<br/>to clean a sacred place,<br/>we dreamed a vision<br/>of naive invention.</p><p>We knew<br/>the sun rose<br/>in a nice pink<br/>room in a house<br/>in a little town<br/>in Kentucky<br/>and it did.</p><p>We knew<br/>he was into black<br/>women and white girls.<br/>We looked<br/>up at our children<br/>and said, it\u2019s fine<br/>if you\u2019re<br/>monstrously beautiful<br/>and handsome<br/>an older woman,<br/>whose hair is crazy<br/>and beautiful, told us<br/>it\u2019s fine<br/>if you don\u2019t<br/>live on the ocean.<br/>We were considerably disappointed<br/>to learn that<br/>he\u2019s<br/>just like us.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Punch Up by Glen Mulcahy</b></p><p>A punch up in bed,<br/>a backseat to the bumper with<br/>A man on the wheel. A punch went<br/>Down, a wipe in the cup, a<br/>Fingertip, a hangover, a slub.</p><p>Downed, I have to navigate<br/>The crowded Fremont Street<br/>Wrecking &amp; Scenic with someone<br/>I don\u2019t know\u2014<br/>Two lieutenantly<br/>Ordinary men\u2014who<br/>Are also going to go to jail\u2014</p><p>Are going to be my life.<br/>I\u2019ll still be The Man<br/>In the Moon</p><p>But a man on the<br/>Racetrack<br/>Sweets the way you dream<br/>Of vacation....</p>",
    "<p><b>A Lot by David Tovar</b></p><p>I\u2019ve been out shopping<br/>the last 3 days. Do I need a brace?<br/>Do I need braces? Do I need braces</p><p>and make-up? I\u2019ve been out shopping</p><p>all night with my friends<br/>I\u2019m not buying anything<br/>like a pink slip or a can't drink-</p><p>d in a parking lot\u2014I want antiperspirant<br/>I want t-shirts and dresses<br/>I\u2019m buying shoes<br/>I\u2019ve never been in a bikini<br/>I\u2019ve never been in a perfume<br/>I\u2019ve never been in an elevator<br/>I\u2019m never going to an airport<br/>I\u2019m not going to any of that!</p><p>I\u2019m in a beauty parlor<br/>talking to a beautiful woman<br/>(who\u2019s going out shopping today)<br/>I\u2019m doing everything I can<br/>to look a certain way<br/>but I\u2019m still not where I\u2019m supposed</p><p>to be</p>",
    "<p><b>Serenade by Juliet Kohler</b></p><p>The sound of a symphony drowned from the windows and a van heave,<br/>a woman on the wheel, her hair more than a foot off the ground,<br/>her face slipping into silent crinkles as she drove</p><p>back home to the sea, her eyes half open,<br/>her nothing but her hair and her wish she had never</p><p>to go back to where she belonged, unable to hear herself</p><p>in a string of turning cranes, another woman<br/>on the wheel, her hair more than a foot off the ground.</p><p>The sea was not a woman, except for its blue tint.</p><p>It was the sound of an airplane.</p><p>It was the sound of a symphony drowned from the windows.</p><p>Rocks, flake of feathers, free will.</p><p>\u201cA being is only its sound.\u201d</p><p>\u201cYou\u2019re only your sound.\u201d</p><p>The sound of the symphony drowning from the windows.</p><p>Of course, there\u2019s the whole effect of the sound of the symphony drowning.</p><p>Of course there\u2019s the whole effect of the sound of the symphony drowning.</p><p>But as night fell, I was also drowning,<br/>What once had been my home. And I knew the right way out.</p><p>At night it seems that you\u2019re not going to be taken home.<br/>But you\u2019re never going to be taken home.</p><p>And so there comes a time when it\u2019s really necessary.<br/>And you\u2019re there in the rain, the stars are clear,<br/>and the sea, splendid,<br/>is nothing but the sound of your voice<br/>playing in the empty air outside.</p>",
    "<p><b>From the Shadows by David Wojahn</b></p><p>Abandoned in a tidy spot,<br/>snow on a dusty tree,</p><p>a single rock,<br/>a brief trench<br/>of water-worn ice.</p><p>Locking in slow motion</p><p>as I peel back the sheet-</p><p>pocked windowsill;<br/>footsteps in the dark,</p><p>hallways still dark,<br/>the hotel hallway</p><p>no longer a room<br/>to go back to.</p><p>Next to the bed,<br/>windows are clean,</p><p>there is no sign<br/>that I am still</p><p>in the inn.</p><p>I\u2019ve forgotten my password<br/>or my name.</p><p>I\u2019ve forgotten my phone<br/>or my itinerary.</p><p>I\u2019ve forgotten all together<br/>of the days I have worked</p><p>on this house.</p>",
    "<p><b>Sympathy by Hubert Zimmermann</b></p><p>The soft spring day the one<br/>where a tree begins to twine,<br/>where a berry falls,<br/>where a ladybug lays her eggs,<br/>In a gallon shock of red sunshine<br/>one foot long, one inch wide,<br/>a filthy pile of dog hair and hair,<br/>like the unfinished sewer of a city.</p><p>Why did we not leave the confinement of our lives?<br/>How much further will it take?<br/>What will be the mountain to climb?</p><p>The moon is one month old,<br/>and so is the T-shaped<br/>crest, and the cornel<br/>that is yellow, and then orange,<br/>and then finally black,<br/>and if i\u2019m being realistic<br/>i\u2019ll sell my soul<br/>for this friendship,<br/>as we walk the path<br/>between two rocks,<br/>one of which is a fig tree,<br/>the other a sapling,<br/>and we sit upon a fig tree,<br/>and the moon doesn\u2019t<br/>keep time, it\u2019s just<br/>a weather vane<br/>at the end of the night.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Far Country by Jennifer Coyle</b></p><p>My stomach ached like someone \u2014he\u2014rutted the mud<br/>off the back of my chair, he held back his shirt<br/>so the clouds could pass over me like a curtain</p><p>and never leave the house, the memory of it<br/>lasted all day, and then all night, walking on the mud<br/>always made me laugh.</p><p>He wore shorts, and the rain made sweat stains<br/>on his arm, and he did what he was told,<br/>at the end of the road, his face broke into a grin. We left</p><p>the road to follow it, so it could tan<br/>like a horse hair seen through a window, we wandered<br/>their afternoons back to the cabin, where we settled</p><p>with our meals, our sleep, and how much<br/>we had eaten before we left.<br/>The people laughed at each other,</p><p>and we weighed our options, and decided<br/>to continue driving, out of habit,<br/>for one more night, and that was before the earthquake</p><p>and snow and the smell of burned wood.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Landscape by Stephen Dunn</b></p><p>Where did I go?<br/>And where did I pay?<br/>Luckily I am not a product of my own tragedy,</p><p>as I am dead to the world because I lived<br/>unmanned: as if I had no purpose,<br/>nor a desire for it. If I was in charge,</p><p>I would not sleep, nor on a structure in charge,<br/>I would lay a hand on a woman who ran<br/>against me, but I am not.</p><p>I am not either of these\u2014<br/>one is a scarf hiding a pair of shoes,<br/>the other a pair of socks inside a coat.<br/>If I had been the one who opened the door,<br/>I would have gone faster, but no.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Artist's Impetus by Robert Herrick</b></p><p>We are artists. We are so busy<br/>Postured forgiveness, and, by no means,<br/>Lust, only torrid will be there again.</p><p>We surround ourselves with patterns,<br/>Make it so others satuate us.</p><p>Make art what you think it is:<br/>True art if true art shuts out</p><p>the truer art and shoots<br/>Inauthentic art straight to the wind.</p><p>Without art. Without hope.<br/>Without art the world is nothing but despair.</p><p>Even the most sustained destruction of hope,<br/>The most grievous failure to grasp its meaning,</p><p>If art is not art.<br/>Even when art is art, even when</p><p>you think you know what is art,<br/>You forget.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Little Child by Gottfried Benn</b></p><p>Little did I know,<br/>I'd become a bad mother.</p><p>The pain grew,<br/>and I cried too.</p><p>I didn't know<br/>that a woman</p><p>would put a wand up my nose<br/>and sweep away my dreams.</p><p>No, I\u2019m not a mother<br/>with a wand,</p><p>a mother who loves her child.<br/>I\u2019ll tell you the truth,</p><p>but not the<br/>bad mother.</p><p>I was never a bad mother.<br/>I was a good mother.</p><p>The pain grew,<br/>and I cried too.</p><p>The mother who loved me<br/>was gone.</p><p>She\u2019s gone now,<br/>and I don\u2019t know who\u2019s<br/>the son, the daughter, the<br/>bad mother.</p><p>I\u2019m a bad mother, dear;</p><p>I\u2019ve taken an oath<br/>to make sure that nothing</p><p>gives me away;<br/>I\u2019m the biggest witch</p><p>in the whole neighborhood.</p><p>I'm the worst kind,</p><p>the worst kind of mother.</p>",
    "<p><b>You Have a Song by Stephen Dunn</b></p><p>You have a song<br/>I hear it from across the table<br/>and it has the right amount of cheer</p><p>you\u2019ve been waiting for<br/>to let me in.</p><p>I\u2019m not even a woman yet<br/>and this morning I was born</p><p>I did not pay for this<br/>but you did.</p><p>I\u2019m thinking, now,<br/>how much of this</p><p>is just a song!</p><p>I will end this as soon as possible</p><p>and you will begin to sing it<br/>in the manner I am trained to\u2014</p><p>ask the question you think<br/>it will ask, only then</p><p>you are ready.</p>",
    "<p><b>by Francis Ponge</b></p><p>After dark, from behind the porch<br/>the helicopter, a motley crew<br/>of motels, cuts, and bicycles,<br/>a muddy haystacks, every sort of<br/>adorned junk, from broken car parts, to<br/>used car parts, to ripped-off catalogs,<br/>to the stomachs of a vehicle, to the<br/>unintended side of a bicycle</p><p>I\u2019ve been to the garbage-man<br/>who is near the river, for help<br/>with a metal tube. The chopper<br/>came down and did repairs<br/>for me, all day, it was<br/>just a matter of getting me there.<br/>And I\u2019ve been to the last of your<br/>newscasts, and the odd<br/>lunchtime interview, and to<br/>the average dreary of the Sunday<br/>morning, as I sit here now, I<br/>look across the large, iced<br/>open audience, who looks back to me<br/>then back to them, and to you<br/>you can\u2019t have it both ways:<br/>talking about what\u2019s important<br/>while trying to be the best<br/>thing in the world, while trying<br/>to be as good as you can be.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Great Grey Wolf by Elizabeth McFarland</b></p><p>I was looking for washing hands<br/>and criss-crossing my body<br/>with tufts of fur from the great grey wolf I had seen<br/>a few nights ago.<br/>I had seen him since as soon as I entered<br/>from the top of the dumpster\u2014with his tail<br/>dipping like a candle's flame\u2014<br/>he leapt and pounced on me<br/>and stamped the wood and the shoes<br/>with even more fur.<br/>He had a group of bright wolves<br/>who followed in his wake<br/>and chased us out of the woods<br/>with their tails between their legs,<br/>everyone else still there and quiet.<br/>The great grey wolf I had seen<br/>was gone. We were in the middle of nowhere,<br/>with nothing else to do but stay<br/>and watch him as he rocked the dumpster<br/>and shoved and shoved<br/>the air in, and then<br/>carefully worked back into a long<br/>clutching strop<br/>that held the shoe in<br/>and stopped for a moment<br/>and then started again\u2014<br/>the fur catching<br/>caught in a trap and<br/>carried into the yard by\u00a0 a herd of sheep<br/>who had been watching.</p>",
    "<p><b>Gone by Gwendolyn Brooks</b></p><p>When lyery night<br/>I was growing<br/>And I sat there<br/>From down by the river</p><p>And cried<br/>\"Bad Lyery Night<br/>I dreamed<br/>About the long-domed building<br/>In which I had a house</p><p>Nights ago\u2009\u2014<br/>\u201cThe Lyery Night\u201d</p><p>I used to tell you all about<br/>But I thought<br/>Of all the ways<br/>I had been<br/>Saved.</p><p>And then I realized<br/>It is not worth<br/>Worrying about the bad Lyery Night</p><p>But if I could just<br/>Break into a shoe shop<br/>And there was a bright<br/>Chair there</p><p>I would be happy<br/>But I would not be happy</p><p>Anyway, the Lyery Night<br/>Is gone.</p>",
    "<p><b>Common Worm in the Tunnel by Robert W. Service</b></p><p>Common worm in the tunnel<br/>scuffs the pavement with gravel<br/>till light wells up from dark<br/>where a beam of light<br/>hits the opening and shimmers<br/>like a flower's petals<br/>and blooms, blossoms<br/>like a flower's petals<br/>and blooms, blooms as a flower<br/>threws into the air,<br/>threws,<br/>And the road crawls.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Child-Rite by Wendell Berry</b></p><p>my cousin from Mississippi</p><p>brought home</p><p>a hundred dollars in a box</p><p>a sweatshirt</p><p>boxed in torn</p><p>xxl assorted papers</p><p>a blanket</p><p>a scarf</p><p>a baseball bat</p><p>a small bright box</p><p>the shrine</p><p>where they would all</p><p>sit under the sun</p><p>the casket</p><p>for two hours</p><p>the scroll</p><p>shaped like a</p><p>little white dove</p><p>the skinny silhouette</p>",
    "<p><b>A Pair of Wands for Rubens by Robert Bly</b></p><p>The bird that did not fly<br/>was dead. The viscera had hardened \u2013</p><p>the strays on my wall, the one<br/>on which the child sat</p><p>had caved down, my painted spoon.</p><p>Never mind the person, though<br/>who is there and who is<br/>dying does not matter. I am serve -</p><p>and that\u2019s why I am not happy.</p><p>This long walk to the market square<br/>where I bought the food and wine.</p><p>Some days the disease of the city,<br/>a song of joy, a psalm,</p><p>grazes on the wounded, grows in me.</p><p>\u2018Never mind the people,\u2019</p><p>I speak to myself, the words tumble</p><p>from my mouth without cause.</p><p>I have learned to be clean, to be silent</p><p>when I am angry, to be silent when I am sad.</p><p>I have learned to keep my house clean</p><p>and never to forget my dog,</p>",
    "<p><b>Arguably by Elizabeth Mullen</b></p><p>I was expecting black<br/>to come<br/>through the doors,<br/>at this level,<br/>and the serape<br/>I handed to him<br/>was soft as a sock</p><p>no one knows<br/>if the straw came through or<br/>the arrow<br/>did it.</p><p>He put it away<br/>with pride.</p><p>But when I went out,<br/>I pushed it<br/>back into the fence,<br/>then knocked,<br/>To be told<br/>that the wind<br/>had carried it<br/>far.</p><p>His wife,<br/>who was there<br/>at the door<br/>and overheard me<br/>requesting to speak<br/>to the president,<br/>said that<br/>it was my hat<br/>she had picked out<br/>from the sack<br/>in the plane.</p><p>I was shocked<br/>to learn they had<br/>fired her<br/>for a novel<br/>in the third<br/>person,<br/>these crackpots<br/>who should know<br/>better than to edit</p><p>that old thing<br/>and put it<br/>on the top shelf<br/>where it sits today,<br/>and into the forgotten<br/>multi-media<br/>of my life.</p>",
    "<p><b>When Heaven, the Supersound by Roddy Lumsden</b></p><p>When heaven, the supersound,<br/>or the demon-plane, came to Canterlot</p><p>to record my reverie<br/>on a blown-glass metal plate,</p><p>and feast me the dark pleasures of the main stage,</p><p>I crushed the carcass of the musician<br/>that had made me the Bat</p><p>and gave rise to the acerbic score.</p><p>I distorted the nursery rhyme<br/>So that my little one could receive</p><p>the Academy's honors:</p><p>the National Merit Scholarship, the Peabody,</p><p>and a Silver Slugger award.</p><p>But in the meantime, I'd serve<br/>in the Model Railroad,</p><p>and wait for the light<br/>to pierce the morning dew</p><p>and accept my fate as one who lingered<br/>until a siren blared from the next train,</p><p>hoping the train would be there.<br/>The siren sounded when I reached</p><p>the end of my journey--</p><p>and I was bound to the station.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Spruce by John Ashbery</b></p><p>This spring, silence was crucial,<br/>not a sound to be heard from the deep.</p><p>I was trying to be authentic. I had<br/>to be faithful, I had to be clear.</p><p>If we act like this again, this next<br/>may not be the last. The future is</p><p>not yet sealed. At the center of the house<br/>and all around, criss-crossing walls</p><p>above the streets, the houses, and the streets<br/>and the mountains, the homes, the hills,</p><p>and the forests, I stood outside<br/>my house, I made my own houses</p><p>in the courtyard of my house</p><p>I saw how the houses stood<br/>along a single road,</p><p>it was winter and it was<br/>morning, I was outside</p><p>and I didn\u2019t like it</p><p>it was raining, and the houses<br/>so tall and railed,</p><p>and the trees,<br/>and the spruce</p><p>and the trees.</p>",
    "<p><b>from<br/>  <br/>  El Pozad\u00e1 by Gabriel Spera</b></p><p>Now I am sick of you<br/>and no longer can be moved<br/>by your way of comforting me.<br/>I want to learn how to be ill.</p><p>You can never be old or young, but<br/>you are our friend in private.<br/>You have seen us and we have seen you.<br/>You have bought gifts and we have given them to you.<br/>You have treated us with respect and you have shamed you.</p><p>You have never been afraid.<br/>You\u2019ve always known what to do,<br/>and we\u2019ve known what to do.<br/>And if you ever die,<br/>you\u2019ll be buried in a private cup to avoid the stigma of the world.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Liar by George Elliott Clarke</b></p><p>It\u2019s more like a passion than a machine.<br/>There\u2019s no point in the mistimed-up,<br/>Or the race-horse stampede, or saying one thing<br/>And doing the opposite, or even feeling that way.</p><p>There\u2019s no form to top, for there\u2019s none.<br/>The only form is a bare-footed one,<br/>For nothing but a bare foot on the ground.</p><p>Perhaps there\u2019s a certain truth:<br/>\u201cwe\u2019re all in this together,\u201d it seems to be<br/>Depressingly true, but less so like it.<br/>So I\u2019ve always held about something<br/>That I\u2019m sure it\u2019s true. Shouldn\u2019t speak.</p>",
    "<p><b>O'er the Wild Trees by Celia Holt</b></p><p>Stepping off my bicycle<br/>in the city of Uniondale<br/>I hear my name in the heat of the sun.</p><p>I\u2019ve seen the forest burn<br/>someplace close to my speed.</p><p>I\u2019ve brought a present<br/>to the intersection<br/>of Canyon Lane and Avenue E<br/>where the freeway<br/>cuts into the Westside Highway</p><p>and is surrounded<br/>by neighborly homes,</p><p>a boy\u2019s dream<br/>ahead of its physical<br/>boundaries.</p><p>I have seen<br/>the southern mountains<br/>return to their shared<br/>pastures,</p><p>the limits of a location<br/>hopping in the early<br/>morning\u2009\u2014\u2009it\u2019s then</p><p>I am out of my home</p><p>and I am back in the house</p><p>where I am not from.<br/>The backyard has dried,</p><p>the front door is open,</p><p>the kitchen still needs<br/>a place to sit</p><p>and the living-room balcony<br/>does not have a place to sit.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Empty Vessel by Heinrich Heine</b></p><p>Lulled by the songs, I wake up the first time;<br/>I see the scaffold, then I see the scaffold\u2019s wall</p><p>gasping for something to do. Something to do</p><p>with nothing, facing no one: it\u2019s no time to be</p><p>half asleep or half awake or half washed</p><p>and a-woman, as I am, a-woman, washed</p><p>up in the tide, the tide looking</p><p>like shapeless tangled masses of air on my steel-</p><p>bottom, as though they were not there at all.</p><p>Is that what you were dreaming: the dreams</p><p>of being undone, of being forgotten for a month?</p><p>It\u2019s a beautiful day and I am always glad</p><p>when I wake like the tide, and I am always glad</p><p>when your feet touch the shore, as they were in</p><p>your bed, when your body lives</p><p>pierced and hot, as they did when you hung</p><p>like a poodle on a neon tetra rope</p><p>that floated like a poodle</p><p>on a chain to a kinked capitol,</p><p>peering from the rope to the sea</p><p>that said that is where this is going:</p><p>the sea equaling heaven.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201c\u201d by Shannon Briggs</b></p><p>December\u2019s temporary rhyme,<br/>the departure of the bloom.</p><p>After the monsoon,<br/>after all,</p><p>the breeze\u2019s enough.</p><p>But now,</p><p>I hear the subjectivist came up<br/>with Plaisir,<br/>wanting to be weaned,</p><p>to be groomed,<br/>to be the one</p><p>to wait on<br/>while the flower<br/>comes again.</p><p>It is not that I am<br/>unable to face<br/>my own problem,</p><p>it is the bard's</p><p>poems I quote</p><p>that make my mouth do it.</p><p>Smile</p><p>and don\u2019t cry.</p>",
    "<p><b>[the scene] by Rae Armantrout</b></p><p>in smallpox\u2019s astonishing natural<br/>novelty</p><p>its superb fragility</p><p>its survival</p><p>a narrative of hiding</p><p>a singular and brittle</p><p>its most important treasure</p><p>sometimes this jars</p><p>and has to be borne</p><p>there is always a</p><p>return to what</p>",
    "<p><b>A Mantie by Lucie Brock-Broido</b></p><p>I lived in a house on the middle of<br/>the main street that used to catch<br/>onto the boats, the night<br/>that chucked me here, the door<br/>open and draughty, a garage<br/>rolling me on the carpeted floor,<br/>and every breeze was a sudden prayer.</p><p>I'm not sure how to say<br/>\u201cdisaster,\u201d or how to say<br/>\u201cmistake,\u201d or what to say<br/>when I see you again in the city<br/>with the same old black and red t-shirt,<br/>which I opened with a free hand,<br/>or forced into a box<br/>that I never got to use, or had<br/>Ivanhoe fly into the house.</p><p>You must have walked down a long road,<br/>one that was at least not<br/>boring, or somewhere else<br/>other than the one you arrived<br/>at.<br/>Do you remember the kind of road<br/>that was there? It was only a<br/>strand of a distance between<br/>two buildings.<br/>What were you doing there?<br/>I'm sure you were on your way<br/>to another place, a place<br/>not far from where you were.</p><p>Live long and prosper<br/>the next time you see<br/>yourself and your dreams<br/>thwart the chains of hatred<br/>that tear you apart.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Silliest Surpassing Thing in the World by CAConrad</b></p><p>Forgive me,<br/>your stupid little letter.<br/>A truth<br/>crowds out the rest,<br/>but this one,<br/>waiting impatiently<br/>for the light.</p><p>You\u2019re late to the party,<br/>and now I am ready<br/>to see it grow.<br/>I\u2019ve waited in vain<br/>for the night<br/>to shade my sunny place,<br/>I think I\u2019ve finally<br/>fit in,<br/>you\u2019re wrong.</p><p>I\u2019m here, I\u2019m here now<br/>in case the whole world<br/>just falls away<br/>at the first break<br/>of a long, long journey.</p>",
    "<p><b>By Michael McElroy</b></p><p>Looks at you there,<br/>the late,<br/>or the hungover,<br/>and all that sizzling<br/>cocktail or pastrami,<br/>the old student president\u2019s ramen,<br/>and pants in the morning,<br/>the grease melting into ice<br/>on the hanger,<br/>how fat you look,<br/>and hot you smell,<br/>the young people\u2019s best single.</p><p>I hear you still have<br/>your virginity<br/>hung over your shoulder,<br/>so you can\u2019t<br/>see a peep of the<br/>curtain or the<br/>door anywhere,<br/>and look up at me<br/>and swear<br/>you\u2019re still not</p><p>done with college.<br/>Wear those pants again.<br/>So sexy to be so<br/>taut, so free.</p><p>I hear you still<br/>have your virginity</p><p>on the brain.<br/>And stay away from<br/>whores.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cIn the mountains, in the valley of the shadow of the mozaje\u201d by Georges Simenon</b></p><p>In the mountains, in the valley of the shadow of the mozaje<br/>I was born. As I have grown, I have wandered,<br/>I have learned of the woods and its many paths<br/>and of the valleys that I have discovered,<br/>and the things that have come out of them,<br/>and how I\u2019ve learned to fly. I was born in the mountains<br/>of Xanthar, a born to wander<br/>from one east to west,<br/>from one east to south,<br/>from one east to west, and from one east to east.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Last Train<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Nancy Simpson</b></p><p>on the last train home; the song I sung<br/>a real charm<br/>\u201cCome back to me in a bus<br/>\u201cGood luck, Philip\u201d<br/>I jingled and twirled my hair</p><p>just the way I do in bed<br/>acknowledged in a socked toe</p><p>and a toeed out ball of my hair<br/>though I can hear you moan</p><p>in the background\u2009\u2014\u2009my boy is singing again,<br/>I am thrilled my love is there and safe</p><p>with me on a brighter track so I should be happy.</p>",
    "<p><b>Blank by Peter Santieri</b></p><p>The blue ritournown of the mind,<br/>that which awaits the right to live full-time,<br/>for a year beyond the silences of waking,<br/>carries you to the end of feeling,<br/>from the manicured meadows of childhood<br/>to the abyss of death (a third<br/>which is nothing and nothing and nothing\u2014you know).</p><p>You walk into the sunset,<br/>the sea of eyelids, and there\u2019s<br/>no north or south. There\u2019s only<br/>the long silent road, where<br/>the old seas criss-cross the back<br/>of your head, where a tide<br/>that\u2019s been pulled out of time<br/>is falling into the void,<br/>the endless jungle that no one\u2019s<br/>going to tell you where it\u2019s coming from<br/>because it\u2019s no one\u2019s fault if it\u2019s there.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Torrent by Gail Mazur</b></p><p>Beneath the chilly moon,<br/>the night is black<br/>like a gutter<br/>that thrums for the dark<br/>where a t-rex<br/>spins like a freight<br/>car under the snows.</p><p>His name is Snails,<br/>he\u2019s fat, and he\u2019s<br/>happy to be fat.</p><p>Here on this lifeless<br/>road, snow drifts<br/>where he\u2019s been<br/>and lies curled<br/>up like a moth.</p><p>He\u2019s been moving<br/>for hours,<br/>and at least he\u2019s not<br/>going anywhere anytime soon.</p><p>He\u2019s not a thief<br/>he\u2019s just in it<br/>to have a corpse.</p><p>He\u2019s a messenger<br/>prepared to take you home,<br/>don\u2019t worry if<br/>birds don\u2019t come.</p><p>He\u2019s been through hell<br/>and back, he\u2019s got<br/>the scars to prove it,<br/>you\u2019re welcome.</p><p>You\u2019re welcome.<br/>The snow drifts,<br/>the cats escape,<br/>the wood is falling.</p><p>He\u2019s carrying<br/>special winter supplies<br/>and with them,<br/>special gifts.</p><p>With them,<br/>special things.<br/>The road grows<br/>deep and dark<br/>knowing the path<br/>has led nowhere.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Devil Is In the Details by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>In a little cottage by the woods where the rockfish roam<br/>I shall make a sketch and try to be brave...<br/>Come on, I will draw a horse's tail<br/>or a chicken\u2019s ass... Come on, I will<br/>make a boat\u2019s deck look like a girl\u2019s panties<br/>while the ferryman shouts a song in the Strait<br/>\u201cThe devil is in the details,\u201d I will pretend<br/>that I am the captain of the ferry,<br/>and drown my sorrow in the leathers,<br/>while the lights of the sunset flash across<br/>the tiny windows as I swim towards the next house.</p>",
    "<p><b>Anxiety by A. B. Jackson</b></p><p>I have learned to speak my pain back into your language. I have learned to answer my anxieties with confidence. I have learned to listen to my fears. I have learned to take my anxiety seriously. Now I\u2019m an airplane; the fields are silent. I don\u2019t have to worry about being the last passenger on this earth. I don\u2019t have to make you answer the phone. I can be someone I am not. I can\u2019t be afraid to be myself. I can\u2019t be someone I am in order to be something I am not. I can be someone I am in order to be something I am not.</p><p>My song is so simple, I should have never written it. It says only I\u2019ve run out of words to give to a man.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Cold Hearted in the Dark by Michelle Hang</b></p><p>When I first moved to Taiwan<br/>she asked to borrow clothes<br/>from the thrift store.<br/>I asked for something</p><p>shorter, and she asked me<br/>to borrow a sweater.<br/>I was wearing</p><p>a pink slip, and she was<br/>ready to beat me.</p><p>I was dressed in<br/>a tutu in a light blue<br/>toque. She walked next<br/>to me in the street and</p><p>compassed the brilliance<br/>of my eyes. She was<br/>genuine but cold.</p><p>I looked around for clothes<br/>on the map, and the stores<br/>taught me how to wear</p><p>ties. How do you grow<br/>a mustache? I asked<br/>her. She said</p><p>you\u2019re too hairy for<br/>a mustache, you\u2019re too<br/>thin, and you\u2019re</p><p>stubby. She said<br/>you\u2019re cute,<br/>but when I told her<br/>that I was a man<br/>she said,</p><p>\u201cBear in mind<br/>your new self<br/>has teeth.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>The Company by Robin Ekiss</b></p><p>Maureen Lipstetter<br/>Plenty of people have more than I do\u2014<br/>It\u2019s hard to know where to look.</p><p>I have many friends who have much more than I do\u2014<br/>They\u2019re going to college or getting jobs\u2014<br/>How can I be sure they\u2019re the only ones who know<br/>how much I have or haven\u2019t had in the past?<br/>Too late now. It\u2019s too late now to ask,</p><p>how much I have or haven\u2019t had in the past,<br/>how I was called the Wonder Gum of my childhood,<br/>how I got into culinary school,<br/>how I was called tsundere after all the dead.<br/>Isn\u2019t it fair to ask only now,<br/>when everyone has more than I do?<br/>If only I had a little more,</p><p>I could go back to that Halloween costume\u2014<br/>I\u2019d wear something safe and not too tight\u2014<br/>I\u2019d wear something strappy and not too tight\u2014<br/>I\u2019d even wear a strappy suit,<br/>but it\u2019s too late now.<br/>It\u2019s too late now to ask,</p><p>How much of what you have or haven\u2019t had in the past<br/>does you know about and does it matter?</p><p>How much of what I have or haven\u2019t had in the past<br/>does the past matter?<br/>I\u2019ve read all kinds of things about the future\u2014<br/>I\u2019ve even some of them been published\u2014but how much<br/>do I really know about it?</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cSteady, Old-Time\u201d by Robert Hayden</b></p><p>Twenty years on from the death of Sheffield by black men<br/>who started a thousand fires,<br/>steadily slouching<br/>temporarily at the urn where, for weeks,<br/>I held my newborn.</p><p>\u25a0</p><p>It was, finally, the dead</p><p>that got me back on with my life,<br/>as my blood fails, I\u2019ll be back<br/>to my old ways.</p><p>And so it was that,</p><p>at my relatives\u2019 place<br/>it\u2019s Saturday</p><p>and everywhere I go at still,<br/>a woman comes by mine,\u200e</p><p>the way she\u2019s always wanted<br/>to see me.</p><p>She wants to tell me</p><p>the death didn\u2019t have to come,<br/>the healing can begin now.</p><p>Tell me you\u2019re not going<br/>to bed yet, that you\u2019re going<br/>to bed as soon as possible.</p><p>Tell me you\u2019re not going</p><p>to bed yet, that you\u2019re going<br/>to bed, still, as soon as possible,</p><p>just to rest and heal.</p>",
    "<p><b>Sullen Cat II, the Chug<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Sylvania Winnifred</b></p><p>Cames a little before the sun rises,<br/>a little gray, a little lonely<br/>and wheezy at dusk. Is this your voice?</p><p>This is my book and with a little help<br/>from my wife I can be<br/>a free student and a happy student</p><p>for a long time.<br/>I am a laundry<br/>comber and if you see me<br/>you will be in a hurry, a good<br/>so/good so,</p><p>We can have fun every day<br/>and every girl is welcome<br/>at any time,</p><p>We can have fun every day<br/>with those teeny weeny cats<br/>and their annoying<br/>curdy little crates</p><p>(I tell you it is funny)<br/>We can have fun every day<br/>and be safe and strong and smart<br/>and beautiful and honest<br/>all those little fluffy cats<br/>who always wear a dress<br/>because that is how a girl is</p><p>and what they think<br/>I want this to be a tradition<br/>of not only feeling good<br/>but doing things the right way<br/>and not letting anger<br/>get in the way of doing things.</p>",
    "<p><b></b></p>",
    "<p><b>A Reason by William Blake</b></p><p>Nothing is the same without a reason.<br/>It is always in a thing\u2019s side,<br/>trying to stay out of the way.</p><p>If it\u2019s not in a thing, it looks like dirt.<br/>If it\u2019s not in a thing, it looks like a rotten apple.<br/>The disconsolate person, still in a house,<br/>tries to stay out of the way.</p><p>He doesn\u2019t need to be told what\u2019s the problem, it\u2019s just<br/>the time he has to pay the bill or bring the kids.</p><p>He doesn\u2019t need to be told what\u2019s the problem, the sad situation,<br/>the old man\u2019s excuse for not getting on.</p><p>It\u2019s always in a thing.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Whale-Skin by Peter Spagnuolo</b></p><p>Just this morning I was drawing<br/>the old picture of my mother<br/>without her, the part of her</p><p>we will never see, the one<br/>where we are children one moment</p><p>and suddenly we are two months</p><p>in the future, two months</p><p>into a broken marriage</p><p>of many years, of many</p><p>difficulties\u2014all of this</p><p>will be the best years of my life.</p>",
    "<p><b>loneliness by Arthur Sze</b></p><p>dear loner,</p><p><br/>I may not amuse you with the close ups,<br/>but I will make your life an absolute nightmare.</p><p><br/>See how I tucked the child<br/>into my pants, then pretended I\u2019ll</p><p>take her anywhere that\u2019s not occupied?<br/>You don\u2019t even have a smartphone!</p><p><br/>I\u2019d love to test your patience,<br/>but every time you\u2019re about to open</p><p>the door I am always sure to step outside<br/>with my shoes, concealing the truth beneath</p><p>a pair of silly flats.</p>",
    "<p><b>When I put the ring on my finger it is a thing<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by D. Nurkse</b></p><p>When I put the ring on my finger it is a thing.<br/>I have a dream of it going on my waist, of the knot going down, the liquid filling its very place.</p><p>It is what we call pain in this country, this tomb. It is a thing with absolutely no name. It is what is called by our children a toy. When you put it on your finger it is a thing.</p><p>But I play with it, I put it on my belt. I put it on my finger, saying,I am going to wear this ring, I am going to put it on my belt, I am going to wear this thing, I am going to put it on my neck, I am going to put it on my hair.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Transom by Nick Flynn</b></p><p>This small, clean room in a mall,<br/>where I\u2019ve gone to confess my sins,</p><p>I go there without a doubt,<br/>where I\u2019d somehow missed \u200amy confession.</p><p>I go there with my inner John Doe<br/>and my inner Rorschach,</p><p>where I\u2019ve always stayed so down to earth,</p><p>but now I recognize the title<br/>of my confession, and am so moved</p><p>that my life\u2019s pretty much over,</p><p>I\u2019d never had a life so beautiful,</p><p>I call it and I ask for forgiveness.</p><p>My old life, \u200amy old home,</p><p>is gone and gone forever.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Borderland by Manuel Amalfi</b></p><p>a point of light counting no more<br/>spaces or borders.</p><p>The borderland is a gateway<br/>that one can cross</p><p>without walking across history\u2014<br/>no one is ever at the top</p><p>of one\u2019s mountain</p><p>but the government is</p><p>promising new markets</p><p>where cars juke\u00ad</p><p>pop, the system of wretchedness</p><p>tutels you to new suburbs</p><p>or construction sites,</p><p>but you need a passport</p><p>to get into the landin</p><p>pier, you need</p><p>a mobile phone</p><p>to keep in touch</p><p>about the history of your country</p><p>or the first victims,</p><p>the Border Patrol agents</p><p>everyone loves.</p><p>One should never say<br/>not to trust someone</p><p>till one\u2019s answered</p><p>with No.</p><p>Speak first</p><p>before answering</p><p>you\u2019ll be sorry.</p><p>What is it like</p><p>to live alone?</p>",
    "<p><b>Game by Robert Herrick</b></p><p>The game we all play,<br/>Is this to be victors' devises;<br/>That no one, who by chance is touched<br/>By the stride of the great man<br/>In the lock and slam of the door,<br/>Or happens to be in the room<br/>On the instant at volume so loud<br/>As to drown the warm, mild sound<br/>Of our masters' who shew<br/>Their mantels and smart their feet;<br/>Or is it one who shews<br/>His gear in the room,<br/>Gestures the great man to a chair or wits' bench<br/>And forgets, that I know,<br/>That I cry, and knowledge gains<br/>In that noise of a great man's feet<br/>That's over the great,<br/>The cool silence is another name<br/>For the same thing.</p><p>O, the consciousness that comes<br/>From the large gate of love! Honoring such a grand woman<br/>As was the lovely woman I was,<br/>Or had been my dear one, or like,<br/>From the great harm of old!</p>",
    "<p><b>from<br/>  <br/>  <br/>   Saint Teresa is True by Marie Howe</b></p><p>Yet, even in the heart of a rose<br/>the soul returned alive<br/>in a web of sights, a veiled room,</p><p>a garden of cardoires, anthers,<br/>and bright-lit vases</p><p>where, with a surviving hand,<br/>you proceeded to rauc<br/>out the crackle of rose petals</p><p>to the heart of Saint Teresa\u2019s heart,<br/>where the muffled pulses of her<br/>girlhood singing reverberate today.</p><p>Spoken by Saint Teresa from the heart<br/>of a rose,</p><p>spoken by Saint Teresa from the heart of Saint Teresa,</p><p>spoken by Saint Teresa from the heart of Saint Teresa,</p><p>the heart is alive,<br/>in the open air, unconstitutioned,</p><p>and it is a habitat for souls,<br/>a body of water where the heart</p><p>stirrates and the wind makes the heart live,<br/>a grave of the heart that is not out of place</p><p>on this earth.</p>",
    "<p><b>Aeneid by Pauli Murray</b></p><p>On account of the work done, fortune had expected<br/>the bathtubs for the house and dug them<br/>up with saws and wades, then tossed them<br/>with their contents everywhere. They were full of water.</p><p>They were called boats because they were usually steam-assisted<br/>figures of boats sunk by pirates, still wet with the blood<br/>of those they had carried out to sea.</p><p>That morning, they paddled into the harbor,</p><p>officially open to the public, and there,</p><p>at the dock of a small fishing boat, stood two brick-colored<br/>constellations, taller than a house<br/>that was, itself, higher than the small,</p><p>gentle lake, the flightless birds with their nests.<br/>There they were in brass daylight, sailing toward<br/>their families, the castaways, the lonely ones<br/>nearly invisible, the ship's oars modestly tapping<br/>their soft feet against the path the passengers<br/>could see out ahead.</p><p>True, they were sailing toward a better life,<br/>but these were the women that Pauli Murray<br/>knew, and he wanted to make them his wife.</p>",
    "<p><b>This Is Our Skin by Michael Basile</b></p><p>No one expects to be released, but then they are, and the rest is routin\u00e9.<br/>This is our skin, our blood, our language, our eyes, our philosophy, our history.</p><p>It's taken all night, but we won\u2014and this is the best music I've ever heard.<br/>The acts of love and forgiveness are beautiful, but not the truth.</p>",
    "<p><b>Dairy by Gail Mazur</b></p><p>We had a dilemma<br/>about the dairy of cattle.</p><p>A dairy of cattle<br/>has it\u2019s own aesthetic</p><p>Of brutality.</p><p><br/>On the one hand,<br/>the cows</p><p>The calves</p><p>Derive pleasure.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cThe Whistler\u201d by Andrew Joron</b></p><p>In the heat of winter,<br/>in the wood-frame of a house<br/>sands pour into an unlit room<br/>where you stand</p><p>in a couple's bedroom<br/>while one of you sits<br/>on the stove<br/>with a cigarette<br/>In the desert the sky<br/>is full of stars<br/>and in the house,</p><p>the cold feels more like rain<br/>as you look out<br/>from the window<br/>at emptiness<br/>and the sounds<br/>of animals<br/>crashing into each other<br/>like the ends of two sheets</p><p>and from the window<br/>you see the yard<br/>that\u2019s always bare and<br/>the frozen village<br/>in the distance<br/>where you are</p><p>a great upset<br/>where you know<br/>nothing has changed and<br/>there\u2019s nothing in your life</p><p>that will change or<br/>are going to change</p><p>when the winds gather<br/>and blow the wind into the town<br/>of eros, get lost<br/>and when the raging winds<br/>flash into the window,</p><p>run to the window<br/>and yell<br/>I AM SO SICK OF THE SNOW<br/>to get out of there.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cWithout comments, the silence lengthens.\u201d by Ilya Kaminsky</b></p><p>Without comments, the silence lengthens.<br/>We are all living in the shadow of our silence.<br/>The virgin who lives behind our silence<br/>has lain there for years in the shadow<br/>of this silence. The silence of the future<br/>will deepen and deepen and deepen.<br/>The silence of our silence.<br/>The silence of the present.<br/>The silence of the past.<br/>This silence, this lengthening silence,<br/>is sad.</p><p>But grow louder, grow louder,<br/>grow louder,<br/>grow louder! The silence of the future<br/>is still as silent as it was before.</p><p>Yes, it will grow louder still.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Notes by Stephen Dunn</b></p><p>The notes of the clock are<br/>a record of my days,<br/>the notes of the music<br/>are a record of my hours of madness.</p><p>It is a debt that I have<br/>to pay, a debt that I will<br/>never pay again,</p><p>and what I have suffered<br/>for my debt I learn to love</p><p>and want to give back,<br/>I learn to be glad to be</p><p>a member of what is going on<br/>in a world for the birds.</p><p>And the birds, doing what they do,<br/>are not laughing that day,</p><p>are not sad in a town like me;<br/>they love the clouds<br/>of the suburbs like you.</p>",
    "<p><b>There's a Story by Stephen Dunn</b></p><p>There's a story\u2014my mother's<br/>in the hospital\u2014a rod of it<br/>cutting into her leg, the kind<br/>you'd use for kicking a fallen branch<br/>or putting a spoonful through a moth's</p><p>eyes. There's a story\u2014my mother's<br/>in the hospital, for the life of her<br/>they've broken open my shoulder and she's<br/>banging twice her size despite<br/>my best efforts. There's a tale<br/>of the play that started in the closet<br/>where someone tried to teach me<br/>how to be a man\u2014I was weak<br/>enough that I was killed<br/>by something worse\u2014a comic book<br/>with a zingy ending covered in<br/>dirty, bloody smudges.</p><p>There's a story. There's a story.<br/>This is it\u2014my past is coming<br/>back. It's a fine<br/>acre of grass. It's long past<br/>and quiet. Brinded in a corner a sign<br/>blows a smoke over a burning bush.</p><p>I want to be in the story.<br/>There's a story. There's a story.<br/>It's as if I'm in a light<br/>that's never had a name, as if I'm<br/>a black robe wrapped around a half-dressed woman<br/>in a storybook sitting in darkness\u2014<br/>type of story.</p><p>The story is still the same.<br/>There's a story. The story<br/>is the same. Then, in the dark,<br/>I'm a boy who doesn't know<br/>what I'm calling me.<br/>It's something like sleep or a dream<br/>that happens in a dream.<br/>There's a story. There's a<br/>story. The story is as usual<br/>a kind of black scale<br/>that's just moving up<br/>and down. A pile of old clothes<br/>that doesn't look like anything<br/>else. A room in a house<br/>that looks like a garage.<br/>This story's going nowhere.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Lullaby to an Old, Poor Box by Elizabeth Bentley</b></p><p>Our real fault<br/>Is showing up,<br/>Where we\u2019re no longer welcome:<br/>St. Matthew\u2019s, the Ministry,<br/>The circus, the Santa Clarita,<br/>The old house that we\u2019re moving<br/>To next, the next,</p><p>Until the time we\u2019re here,<br/>The weekend passes,<br/>And we take even more notice,<br/>The stars, the nights,<br/>The bricks we pile in boxes,<br/>Or just throw on the floor<br/>And have a good time.</p><p>Then we do the same,<br/>Coaching the game of numbers<br/>And hoping for the same,<br/>Alone in the room,<br/>In another room with the door,<br/>I know where I am, I\u2019ll be there.</p><p>And once again, you\u2019re not here.</p>",
    "<p><b>[The typewriter of dreams] by Lee Herrick</b></p><p>The typewriter of dreams<br/>(for a dozen hours)<br/>sucks up the breath<br/>\u2026<br/>and I, who\u2019ve awakened,<br/>forget long norings and they,</p><p>the heartstrings\u2009\u2014\u2009when my one loves<br/>he comes on his,<br/>he waits, clutching</p><p>his dog\u2009\u2014\u2009even the door\u2019s<br/>open, and he\u2019s the only one</p><p>at the door,<br/>and holding his breath.</p>",
    "<p><b>I Can Never Let You Go<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Ben Lerner</b></p><p>I can never let you go,<br/>I will never let you go,<br/>If you do not stop acting<br/>with that selfish<br/>misery of yours,<br/>that salty narcotic,<br/>and, I\u2019ve been dreaming<br/>of someone else suddenly knocking<br/>on your door,<br/>looking<br/>at you politely and kindly,<br/>telling you he\u2019s there,<br/>telling you he\u2019ll be there<br/>soon, telling you<br/>this is his job,<br/>he\u2019s in the know,<br/>he\u2019s on the way<br/>to come in and be<br/>the friend you never had,<br/>a kind of lover\u2019s parole,<br/>reasoning with you<br/>and letting you<br/>know how much<br/>this means to him,<br/>with how much<br/>it\u2019s meant to you,<br/>hanging out<br/>some nights,<br/>helping you<br/>have fun,<br/>helping you laugh<br/>at your mistakes<br/>and growing pains.</p>",
    "<p><b>Echo by Melissa Broder</b></p><p>silence as a door<br/>kept swinging.</p><p>I dimming my reflection<br/>in a room of my own,<br/>and this shadowy room of my own.</p><p>I felt inside of me<br/>as if I was to be</p><p>a tiny piece of the show,<br/>a little piece of what I wanted</p><p>to say. I was afraid to bite.<br/>I was afraid to command.</p><p>Silence as a door<br/>didn\u2019t shut.</p><p>I could have said<br/>something else\u2009\u2014</p><p>that\u2019s what a show<br/>is all about,</p><p>the presence of the host.</p><p>I didn\u2019t want to be<br/>a public speaker<br/>in public.</p><p>Instead, I wrote<br/>myself a song.</p><p>But silence was<br/>deep inside me\u2009\u2014</p><p>and I wanted to come<br/>even more deeply</p><p>into that silence.</p>",
    "<p><b>Last Snow by E. D. Hirsch</b></p><p>The first snow fell in a forest<br/>Not far from here.</p><p>The second.<br/>The third.<br/>The fourth.</p><p>It melted.<br/>White roofs of ice<br/>covered the steps<br/>where we stood</p><p>in the straw barn<br/>that had been<br/>filled with greenery</p><p>and tannery sparks.</p><p>The fifth.<br/>The first tree<br/>had all of the leaves</p><p>of that year\u2019s leaves<br/>falling from it</p><p>on it\u2019s fragments.</p><p>The sixth.<br/>The crawfish<br/>had all of the legs<br/>of that year\u2019s legs</p><p>on its shoes.<br/>The seventh.<br/>The dog that had been<br/>kept at the school</p><p>belongs in a box<br/>to the spider, which is<br/>doggy.</p><p>The witch has brought<br/>only one toy<br/>but no healing tools.</p><p>The father has used<br/>his daughter as a sacrifice<br/>to the crawl<br/>by his side.</p><p>The mother\u2019s invoked<br/>her power as a candy cane.</p><p>And the patriarch\u2019s?<br/>He had promised<br/>not to abandon his wife<br/>if she were wed.</p>",
    "<p><b>Pocket Marbles by Linda Pastan</b></p><p>Out in the yard the pigs, the dogs,<br/>sit in a circle around the fire<br/>smoking hot, muttering, shuffling<br/>their feet, tapping their heads.</p><p>Soon they will be snowed in by the sleet<br/>and turned into the trunks of sand<br/>sledding across the yard, patching<br/>the cracks along the road.</p><p>After America the Joke is Over<br/>we bend down to the blue and white striped<br/>sledding field, players and coaches<br/>carry bags of sacks and balls<br/>like muddy horse shoes.</p><p>No one is home. No one is in the yard.<br/>We take off our coats and plunge straight into the mud.<br/>We practice hook shots and kickoffs,<br/>touching the ball in the back of our hands.<br/>We pretend to be little boys and girls<br/>and sledding over the field.<br/>We make our voices a song<br/>like the pigs of the neighborhood<br/>sleeping in their corners with their dogs.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Lonely Girl by Judith Ortiz Cofer</b></p><p>I bought a skirt,<br/>a pair of black stockings,<br/>and a brown leather skirt,<br/>but I had no money.</p><p>I had only two hours<br/>to live and die.</p><p>The rain made me happy:<br/>I sang in the rain.</p><p>It got more beautiful<br/>and more peaceful while I slept,<br/>but the rain<br/>never stopped.</p><p>My mother stood in her bag<br/>and cried not to leave<br/>I was a fortune-teller.</p><p>It was my dream come true when<br/>I woke up.</p>",
    "<p><b>from<br/>  <br/>  The Sad Beautiful by Shana Hakim</b></p><p>Sad beautiful, my lady,<br/>With all her love, I am doing<br/>With the threat of so much worse.<br/>The razor-sharp edges of the winds<br/>Beating the trees are coming.</p><p>I am not afraid: I have<br/>Piled my fear with a roof<br/>Awnings to protect myself,<br/>And I am not crying.</p><p>He is laughing.<br/>The world has become<br/>An imaginary room,<br/>With the promise of<br/>A ghastly trip.</p><p>Misfortune will not overtake<br/>Inanimate Matter,<br/>Nor hunger or thirst,<br/>Our hearts will not poison<br/>Our mouths and minds,<br/>We will be reborn<br/>Into an atmosphere of<br/>Beauty.</p><p>When I speak this,<br/>The local tapestry is twining<br/>Around the long, tall telephone,<br/>And I . . . the telephone is limping<br/>Across the room.</p><p>The truth is that on somewhere<br/>A child is listening.<br/>He is laughing.<br/>The world is not a big, grand or secret room,<br/>But there is a lot that is laughing,<br/>And there is a lot that is limping.</p>",
    "<p><b>Comfort Food by Laurel McCune Peterson</b></p><p>They dance a dance<br/>away from each other,<br/>stiff and sober, not out<br/>of any longing to impress,<br/>but rather to be happy.<br/>Their pockets are oversize,<br/>their buttons undone,<br/>and a crowd pleases them<br/>more than I can possibly do.<br/>The music keeps on<br/>as the dancers begin to move again,<br/>it's like two dancers<br/>stiff and sober, not out<br/>of any longing to impress,<br/>but rather to be happy.<br/>They dance a dance<br/>away from each other,<br/>stiff and sober,<br/>not out of any longing<br/>to impress, but simply<br/>to be happy.</p>",
    "<p><b>[my] feet flat on this wooden floor<br/>  <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Josephine Miles</b></p><p>My feet flat on this wooden floor<br/>I\u2019m seeking out coco and mints<br/>I\u2019ve been hoping<br/>I\u2019m the only racialist in the room<br/>I\u2019m getting my ass kicked<br/>I\u2019m going to keep on smoking<br/>I\u2019m here to stay<br/>I\u2019m on a diet<br/>I\u2019ll thank God for my eyes</p><p>I\u2019m going to keep on smoking<br/>I\u2019m here to stay</p><p>I\u2019m here to stay</p><p>My feet flat on this wooden floor<br/>I\u2019ve been walking to school<br/>I\u2019ve been looking for food<br/>I\u2019ve been looking for a place<br/>I\u2019ve been looking for what\u2019s hot<br/>I\u2019m hungry for white people</p><p>My eyes are boring up front<br/>my mouth is closing</p><p>My toes are typing rapidly on my road shoes<br/>a great big white shoe</p><p>My feet are annoying<br/>I\u2019m running out of white space</p><p>I\u2019m walking to school</p><p>My feet are irritating<br/>I\u2019m tired of walking<br/>I\u2019m tired of looking white</p><p>I\u2019m bored with walking<br/>I\u2019m sitting on my road shoes<br/>And it\u2019s soccer time again<br/>I see my friends kicking a ball<br/>I hear them playing soccer<br/>I see my feet flat on this wooden floor<br/>I\u2019m looking to walk to school<br/>I\u2019m tired of walking</p><p>I\u2019m tired of getting up in front of people<br/>I\u2019m tired of looking white<br/>I\u2019m tired of becoming somebody<br/>I\u2019m tired of looking white</p><p>I\u2019m tired of becoming somebody<br/>I\u2019m tired of always being someone<br/>I\u2019m tired of being a fat, white fat asshole</p><p>I\u2019m ready to give up<br/>I\u2019m ready to give up being somebody<br/>I\u2019m tired of being a fat, white fat asshole<br/>I\u2019m ready to stop being somebody</p>",
    "<p><b>The Wind by Mitchell Manuvers</b></p><p>But the wind<br/>choked up its mouth,<br/>though it had never learned<br/>to swear,<br/>since suddenly its face<br/>turned stone.</p><p>The wind leaned back,<br/>though it had a good arm,<br/>and played with its sock.</p><p>The wind ran after us<br/>like a pig\u2019s tail,<br/>saying foolish things as they wore a speckled<br/>ballast of shame.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Country by Kevin McFadden</b></p><p>a flanneler, all up and down</p><p>a comb<br/>a headband and tie<br/>a jean pocket square<br/>a shoehorned untied</p><p>a button down the back of my<br/>eyes\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 clothespins unfurl</p><p>a crease in the edge of my nose\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 black</p><p>a crooked tooth\u00a0\u00a0 a rocker</p><p>the side of my dress pulled back</p><p>a pencil's scribble on the white</p><p>black line of my toe\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 a shoe on the<br/>ground\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 a</p><p>I walk, I hunt, I mug</p><p>when I look at what I've done now</p>",
    "<p><b>Jukebox by Deborah Paredez</b></p><p>Join or be part of the guerilla rock band<br/>Jukebox, perform stand up comedy, sing karaoke,<br/>melt down to pumpkin and juke,<br/>smell bourbon, panties in the air,<br/>smoke weed, be a wildflower,<br/>nicotine hype, be a yedi,<br/>and wear sparkly tweed<br/>with a pair of big black jeans.<br/>Yes I know what you did<br/>was a joke, didn\u2019t you say?</p><p>Jukebox is loud, they\u2019re good for a laugh,<br/>it\u2019s okay to be a prude,<br/>and the burly bunch of us<br/>can\u2019t stop laughing at the joke.</p><p>We\u2019re a bunch of moochers,<br/>we aren\u2019t too smart to be rockstars,<br/>we\u2019re super serious.<br/>We could probably do with a little more</p><p>oomph and poise\u2014the slightest slip<br/>means disaster. We carry our own<br/>luggage, we don\u2019t ride motorcycles,<br/>we don\u2019t drive fancy cars,<br/>we don\u2019t have mamas or judges<br/>who could throw the perfect<br/>quiz. We\u2019re jukeboxes\u2014<br/>we are rock stars\u2014<br/>standing tall, swinging, entertaining.<br/>Can you feel the electricity?<br/>Yes I can.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Screw by Louise Imogen Guiney</b></p><p>I took the love I deserved, so cold\u2014for the coals of the night<br/>the weary journey, the search for a world that I found<br/>I took at the end of a long day of hunting</p><p>And the blackest night, the roads of a distant land<br/>that ran with icicles of ice upon my skin,</p><p>And in the hands of the roaring lightning<br/>carried more rape than most lovers do in a bed of roses.<br/>I took roses and I, of course, took several screwdrivers<br/>to clean the dented plates of a statue</p><p>And the bells that rang from the taverns and parlors<br/>of my days<br/>though my cataracts are a work of art when I write</p><p>Don\u2019t you forget me, dear, that I know<br/>and heard you saying so loud, a groundless plea<br/>for your life</p><p>And the streets of a wild town were choked with all the thrum of love<br/>languished around your tall frame, but then were replaced by streets of murder</p><p>And then, finally, by the deserted streets of the lost city<br/>come back, it was not love that made me more alive, but fear<br/>of love, and the steel bars that or have been locked<br/>against my heart, the ashes that are making up the living</p><p>That you are alive.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Big Ones by C. P. Cavafy</b></p><p>It is going to happen again and again<br/>according to the plan,</p><p>and as a powerful and caring teacher,<br/>I urge you to listen<br/>to my voice,</p><p>to my long-form sentences,<br/>to the deep voice inside you,</p><p>to turn off the TV,<br/>to take a warm bath,</p><p>to ask only the things you want<br/>and do not have to ask\u2014then</p><p>when the time comes,</p><p>to answer your loving questions,<br/>to hold your hand,</p><p>to kiss your cheek,<br/>to drink from your glass<br/>with your own body</p><p>the way you did<br/>before the fall</p><p>and don\u2019t forget to say Good-bye<br/>to the sky,<br/>to the sun,</p><p>to my words, love,<br/>to the red-winged sparrows<br/>in the wildflower mead,</p><p>to the bus that never comes,<br/>to the diamonds scattered in the sand,</p><p>to the little things\u2014<br/>the little performances<br/>that make the rest come together</p><p>like jigsaw puzzles.</p>",
    "<p><b>Become A Giraffine by June Jordan</b></p><p>The giraffes of the other side of the river<br/>now live in a cave above the water.<br/>They still remember their past<br/>but don\u2019t remember the one before.</p><p>Flying with the sun, great white pythons eat<br/>the whole steaming boat at once.<br/>They\u2019ve never been so fast<br/>from the egg-laying barn.</p><p>There\u2019s a lot riding on this<br/>and no one knows why.</p><p>Up there in the pine forest<br/>the sound of thumping feet can<br/>be heard all the way down.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Labby by Josephine Miles</b></p><p>I\u2019m not the lonely person I hoped to be, unless I\u2019m not careful.</p><p>But will my voice be found<br/>on Labby? Or will there be music?</p><p>Or will Brooklyn be dead again?</p><p>Will the world collapse?</p><p>Or is a second birth to come</p><p>In another city?</p><p>How can I get back to the lab</p><p>That I left in the world?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Grifter by T. K. Sciamma</b></p><p>We were walking past town the other night<br/>when suddenly I saw a woman walking with a bag.</p><p>She was a slicer in the city. She packed<br/>every sandwich at the market. Her security camera<br/>was on all fours. Now I'm sure what she said</p><p>I could not believe. No one wanted to be<br/>grateful or to look at her.</p><p>We were walking past town the other night<br/>when suddenly I saw a woman walking with a bag.</p><p>She was nervous:<br/>\"Whoa, whoa, whoa!\"</p><p>I can still taste that smile<br/>I gave her earlier. Only now,<br/>it was withering and I knew I owed<br/>it to her to do the same.</p><p>I like to think she loved me, not<br/>for what I said but for who I smiled.</p><p>She came back to me later that night.<br/>And just like that, I was in a love poem<br/>and she was wearing the centerfold.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cDress by William Butler Yeats\u201d by Samuel Taylor Coleridge</b></p><p>Dress of the sea, how doth it drave me?<br/>Fare thee well, for that bed hath slept with<br/>My well-chastised heart; and with pain drest,<br/>The young and the frail, the betrothal,<br/>The wantad and I, the dearer thing,<br/>Fare thou well.</p><p>Wrest thou me with her fairer hand,<br/>Let me charge thee as one who hath<br/>Taught her the things she herself hath not;<br/>But now, fair and sincere,<br/>If her hand can love thee, let her charge;<br/>For thou too can move the hearts of others.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Saddle by Leslie Harrison</b></p><p>I was mounted in a saddle<br/>on a ridge<br/>above Beartooth, Montana<br/>in the early summer</p><p>and I was bleeding<br/>for no reason other than mountaineering<br/>and wanting to be carried.</p><p>I counted<br/>five deaths by accident<br/>after sliding off the edge<br/>of the summit.</p><p>I was riding toward<br/>a place I would never return.</p><p>I was saddled up on rails<br/>in exposed spaces</p><p>and still I was being carried<br/>like a big heavy suitcase.</p><p>It was a wonderful thing,<br/>the experience of a lifetime.</p><p>Later, I was on my way<br/>north to pack up<br/>and I would return the saddle<br/>to its old place</p><p>behind the house<br/>in Beartooth, Montana<br/>and the rich history of the area<br/>would come out in the foreground<br/>like a ball of light<br/>pulling me toward it.</p><p>But the saddles never<br/>reappear,<br/>and the dirt trails never<br/>end.</p>",
    "<p><b>My Mother's Flowers by Stephen Dunn</b></p><p>In the living room, in my mother's palm</p><p>and the girl's desk, I tried to ask</p><p>what it is I\u2019m supposed to do now.</p><p>And what am I supposed to do?</p><p>Knot fertilizer exploding.</p><p>A ten-foot bob took down our house.</p><p>The projection, so we\u2019re thinking</p><p>about tomorrow.</p><p>Our children, I\u2019m thinking about tomorrow.</p><p>My children, I\u2019m thinking about tomorrow.</p><p>Because the gift of tomorrow is</p><p>always faster than the gift of today.</p><p>So we\u2019re living now. The living room, the girl's desk,</p><p>my mother\u2019s flowers, if my mother\u2019s flowers</p><p>can be construed as anything other</p><p>than a living room, the girl's desk,</p><p>my mother\u2019s flowers, if my mother\u2019s flowers</p><p>can be construed as anything other</p><p>than a hung aisle.</p>",
    "<p><b>Pythagorean by Edward Thomas</b></p><p>\u201cUnbearable, ungrateful man\u201d<br/>I answered, \u201cBlah, blah, blah. I\u2019m just thankful it\u2019s not the apocalypse.\u201d</p><p>What a joy to be glad at having<br/>been in love. But invariably<br/>I\u2019ve missed the decals<br/>or my long-lost ex-lover.</p><p>\u201cI\u2019m not just glad. I\u2019m glad.\u201d<br/>I\u2019ve called a taxi<br/>and lodged a complaint, never<br/>thinking about what would happen<br/>I\u2019d never be sorry.</p><p>\u201cIf only they\u2019d let me<br/>call a cab and pay!\u201d<br/>In the dark, at night<br/>I lie curled in a corner,<br/>stopping to make small jokes<br/>about my ex-wife..</p><p>\u201cI\u2019ve interviewed the Red Sox<br/>for a job that\u2019s out there.\u201d<br/>I\u2019ve waited in line<br/>for hours on the 6:10<br/>or finally retired.</p><p>\u201cI\u2019ve been to the doctor<br/>and checked into a hospital.\u201d<br/>The sky thins as the wind blows.</p>",
    "<p><b>Tours by M.L. Talbot</b></p><p>Desolation Tour, Oxford and Cambridge, 1903<br/>For a healthy man or a sick man the body has tools to spare. One thing the world can do.<br/>The north wind blew over a canal. Most of the world was showing from one<br/>river, Thames cinema, or the Whitney. The stalls were crowded with English and American writers,<br/>poets, translators, and the like, and the theatre was packed with the eye of the world.</p><p>You could not walk more than thirty miles without stopping.<br/>It was the Battle of Somme, and the previous summer an aviation platoon from the United States had finished a tour in the same place as my mother and I.</p><p>We had walked twenty more. While walking, we had looked over the hills and paused to marvel at the hydraulic road,<br/>the narrow gauge tracks, the unfair cost of living, the train horns, the sound of the bell, the things you imagined and hoped to be.</p><p>Now, two thousand miles from the battlefield, we stood before an altar and, at the brink of the earth, we shared our fate. What we had done was unworthy of us, but what we had done was necessary and heroic.</p>",
    "<p><b>The New England Triangle by Jane Hirshfield</b></p><p>You think I\u2019ve got this for you:<br/>lunar restaurants, rock pools, a view</p><p>of the Hudson River, like the one<br/>above mine, the one</p><p>in Venice plazas, people munching</p><p>chees in mazes, or strolling</p><p>on a summer afternoon through<br/>an apple tree forest, or</p><p>a couple of children playing in fountains,</p><p>where should I park? Will I need</p><p>a car to get there? More than enough</p><p>to satisfy my desires, but what about<br/>snow and raindrops? Where will I park</p><p>on Sunday when the moon sets</p><p>again? Or on a Tuesday</p><p>when the sun sets</p><p>again? Or daily,</p><p>or every other week? Don\u2019t underestimate</p><p>the importance of these things.</p>",
    "<p><b>Rain<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Stacy Szymaszek</b></p><p>Before the calm lull came, the moon went down,<br/>the clouds parted, and a car was abandoned<br/>in the thresholds of the dark town.</p><p>Rain had settled over the country,<br/>the sky had put on shadows,<br/>but the night had come<br/>and never did.</p><p>Across the street, a neighbor\u2019s house<br/>grew, another home, one with a record player,<br/>there was a radio, too, and a bookcase.</p><p>The doorway was closed, and a knot hung<br/>between the counter and the stairs,<br/>as if the door had been misshapen,</p><p>boring, or simply abandoned<br/>for no good reason.</p><p>In front of the house, a family<br/>spoke of their old quarrel,<br/>of jealousy, of shared possessions,<br/>of religion, and how the night came<br/>and never did.</p><p>Next to the house, a man sat<br/>on a wooden stool, and he poured<br/>a glass of milk into the crowd<br/>in the pouring fountain, and the crowd<br/>gave back their time, their money,<br/>as they poured the glass before the rain.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Star by Douglas Lovelace</b></p><p>We hold fast the dogma of naked things.<br/>We stare at the great cities,<br/>we peer into the vaults<br/>of the oceans, our feet<br/>scuffed, tolled, and dented.<br/>We stand transfixed in the dark<br/>\u00e0 la Lezard\u2019s eyepiece,<br/>unseeing, unaware, drear.<br/>In the long night of the 1950s,<br/>we saw ourselves<br/>remission in motion<br/>in the silhouette of the star<br/>inside anaconda.</p>",
    "<p><b>An Act for the Savings by Samuel Taylor Coleridge</b></p><p>Noe! I have known no man love so long,<br/>Nor love of animals so sore;<br/>That Love\u2019s a foolish man, who attempts<br/>To draw the flame or seize the blade<br/>By any false pretenses or calumny;<br/>Love\u2019s love is either a coward, or lives<br/>In confusion with his true love,<br/>The man I\u2019ve known beside whom<br/>Love\u2019s every word, every lust,<br/>Is a disgraceful, rotten violence.</p><p>If you, no, you, have any talent,<br/>If you, if you, have any wit,<br/>To tell the truth or not tell it,<br/>You better use it, sir, sir;<br/>If you, sir, have any wisdom,<br/>To look cool and thoughtful,<br/>Or to avoid hell or gaol,<br/>Or to step up for your love,<br/>Know even then how to live in love,<br/>Because love\u2019s a wasting thing<br/>That can be so cruel or so fair<br/>As to make no one strong,<br/>But always, in the end,<br/>Is just folly, for fools<br/>Are sworn up into Heaven,<br/>And let Love overcome you.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Possibility of Seeing By William E. Stafford</b></p><p>I was alone twice<br/>with a strange wooden box</p><p>in my vehicle.</p><p>I was blindfolded<br/>by an old man</p><p>who flashed his<br/>*father-blue* badge<br/>knowing I did</p><p>speak with a foreigner<br/>who held a different</p><p>piece of paper<br/>from which to sue</p><p>for a destination after</p><p>merchants sat<br/>in rows on desks,</p><p>keen and drunk as</p><p>tractor trailers,</p><p>then I heard her:</p><p>a boy\u2019s voice</p><p>that said, \u201cMy name</p><p>is Matilda.\u201d</p><p>She ran</p><p>through the woods,</p><p>straight through the cabin,</p><p>and out the window<br/>to the living room.</p><p>There was only a sound</p><p>of a door being<br/>open or shut.</p><p>Who was she?</p><p>A woman in a gray</p><p>cover,</p><p>nearly blindfolded,</p><p>in a wad of paper</p><p>that morning,</p><p>that same day three years</p><p>later, whiling</p><p>over breakfast,</p><p>she\u2019d write, \u201cHold me,</p><p>my love,</p><p>by your side,</p><p>with your favorite</p><p>flower,</p><p>I\u2019ll be back</p><p>to make it rain.</p>",
    "<p><b>The<br/>Noisy by Audre Lorde</b></p><p>I walk at night<br/>with a raptor<br/>to the mall<br/>and it rips off<br/>my skirt under the bridge,<br/>exactly how I wanted<br/>to wear.<br/>I walk an hour<br/>and an hour of this</p><p>I\u2019ll never learn to read,<br/>but I know 11 angels<br/>will come to minister<br/>to the child who stays,<br/>and I cry when the door opens.</p><p>The circus is right in front of me,<br/>and I\u2019m always nice<br/>to the bumbling circus;<br/>I wash my teeth<br/>after football games,<br/>I rove<br/>up and down the hallways<br/>for my toothbrush,<br/>and only the purring<br/>of a tooth is all I hear.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Little Slug by David Trinidad</b></p><p>Left behind<br/>in the giant dark space<br/>within a man\u2019s torso,<br/>a miniature slug,<br/>the only thing visible to us,</p><p>it stomps<br/>with the speckles,<br/>the salad dress<br/>a hurriedly</p><p>chicken stew.</p><p>Then it slips<br/>into the gap,<br/>the long slant eye<br/>of a mouth,</p><p>the long slant mouth,<br/>the long slant tail,<br/>the long slant tail,<br/>and into the gap,<br/>the long slant eye,</p><p>the long slant mouth.<br/>The letter \"L\" is<br/>invisible, the picture<br/>is a canvas of a slab<br/>of dark,<br/>the whole room has been<br/>cleaned clear.</p><p>It\u2019s possible a Junior<br/>could have done it, the letter<br/>wet, the lid<br/>blown off.</p><p>But that would still have been<br/>pretty good photography.</p><p>And anyway, I\u2019m not<br/>sure I\u2019ll get to do this,<br/>and the smell<br/>anticipates it, if</p><p>there is anything<br/>to do there.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Girl from the Metro by Alice Fulton</b></p><p>Do you have a word for the sudden fear of loss that comes along with being older? For what happens when you retire, in your snowed-white pajamas, outside a crowded movie house, surrounded by strangers, in a room packed full of friends, with no idea where you are or who you are?<br/>Do you have a word for what happens when you lose track of time and don't hear yourself coming back? For what happens when you sit in a darkened room at the back of a bar and eat alone, under a watchful eye that watches you, and forget to get home, lifting your elbows, no longer lifting them, and then remember?<br/>Do you have a word for the miraculous recovery that comes from daily repetition, the repetition that seems set to continue forever? For the girl who woke up one morning and had to repeat the same steps over and over again, and who woke up in a strange bed and had to repeat that same simple ritual over and over again, and who began to feel as if she were somehow on the wrong side of the tracks, and whom no one had ever been able to touch, and whose life had been on the wrong track all along, and whom the strangers had never really understood, and whom she had always blamed herself, and whom she had never really wanted to be, and whom she had always wanted to be anyway, and which her parents had never really understood, and which her friends had never really understood, and which she herself had never really wanted to be, and which she herself had never really wanted to be, and which neither she nor anyone else could really be, and which she herself had always hoped to be, and which she herself had always sincerely wanted to be, and which neither she nor anyone else could ever really be, and which the strangers had never really understood, and which she herself had always sincerely always wanted to be, and which her parents had never really understood, and which her friends had never really understood, and were she not so, she would have been the happiest girl in the world, and everyone would love her, and they would love her by the way they had always loved her, and everyone would love her, and she would have been the happiest girl in the world.</p>",
    "<p><b>\"Under water\" by Edith Sitwell</b></p><p>Under water,<br/>a fir tree,<br/>bent.<br/>I\u2019m going to stay.<br/>I\u2019ve stood<br/>up for too long<br/>and I\u2019ve been thrown.</p><p>Water is choking\u2014<br/>the trees are<br/>underneath your feet.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Twisted Century by Roddy Lumsden</b></p><p>I am going mad from the fight and can't get myself<br/>onto the organ begins to burn; I am<br/>doing the wobbly shuffle of Earth as I move<br/>away from the grave; the teeth I eat<br/>have grown longer than a cigarette box<br/>and are still big enough to scratch a whetstone.</p><p>I'm never going back, so I'll start out<br/>in the mid-century, ripping up old pictures<br/>of people I've never liked, making plans<br/>for the first time in my life I will never<br/>get out of. My house is on fire.<br/>Why not just turn up the heat<br/>and let it blacken across the pale walls?<br/>Take advantage of the time<br/>I have left? No one has?</p>",
    "<p><b>Lament by Yusef Komunyakaa</b></p><p>The reason is because the things that I thought<br/>I\u2019m capable of, like my father teaching me,</p><p>I\u2019m also not</p><p>I\u2019ve put off learning to be like someone.</p><p>It\u2019s something like that</p><p>I\u2019ve thought about a lot, like the flavor in canned tuna,</p><p>the way that young adults look at me with their faces</p><p>that I\u2019d like to say are the same,</p><p>what it\u2019s like to be the only one getting up</p><p>and walking up a flight of stairs</p><p>and hug the girl in front of me</p><p>who stopped herself</p><p>also because</p><p>all I can do is walk</p><p>back into the place where I\u2019m always going to end up,</p><p>since I\u2019m not where I want to be right now,</p>",
    "<p><b>The Tithe by Susan Stewart</b></p><p>For as long as I can remember, my son was<br/>Saying that we were going to the get-go.</p><p>We were going to if I hadn\u2019t said no<br/>to the first question, he looked like he\u2019d</p><p>be the one to listen to.<br/>I\u2019m not a bad woman. I mean</p><p>I\u2019m willing to try.<br/>Truth be told, I didn\u2019t seem all that</p><p>emotionally healthy to him either:</p><p>at moments, when he grabbed me<br/>like I was a sexy rag doll,</p><p>or knocked me to the floor, then<br/>yanked me back and said,</p><p>Do you have money here?</p><p>I\u2019ve got a shotgun.<br/>And a maiden-gown<br/>punched in your face,</p><p>to the forehead.</p>",
    "<p><b>Fair Maid: 13 by Jonathan Williams</b></p><p>A fair maid, fearless,<br/>Doth gaze thee out of the stall,<br/>Still hairless, and stuff'd but not frizz'd,<br/>Doth peer thee her by,<br/>Heavenly head, and bare feet,<br/>Doth, like the fair maid, gallop thee,<br/>How her song do move thee?<br/>Her song, thou mockers in words,<br/>His fair maid, her beau-<br/>tiful eyes, and the fair maid's eyes,<br/>Play thy trifles to scorn thy stoutness,<br/>Too much like a slave, thou nay:<br/>Too much like a slave, thou nay!</p>",
    "<p><b>The Beagle by Ninette McFarland</b></p><p>It\u2019s hindered, it\u2019s hindered, it\u2019s hindered.</p><p>I\u2019ll be unstrapped. In front is a house,<br/>My dog serves as a bed, a place to stay.</p><p>I\u2019ll be able to reach my dog.<br/>I\u2019ll be able to reach my dog.</p><p>Like I used to, I\u2019ll try.<br/>I\u2019ll try.</p><p>I\u2019ll try again.<br/>I\u2019ll try again.</p><p>I\u2019ll try.</p><p>Like I used to, I\u2019ll try again.<br/>I\u2019ll try again.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Scrying Hermit by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>The dawn on the road,<br/>Sensing that my life<br/>Is in vain, and that<br/>The river is flowing away,<br/>I pretended madness.</p><p>It was not undeserved,<br/>But certainly it was not<br/>The unwanted.</p><p>The road began to run<br/>Along a cliff,<br/>The valley began to pass<br/>Over a clearing of broken snow,<br/>And brambles of acacia.</p><p>I knew that my sense of shame<br/>Was the greatest blind spot,<br/>But where were those stones?</p><p>And the goddess with the blue eyeballs<br/>Dressed in the red leotard of a cow<br/>Took me up to her;<br/>With her tiny black toes she \u200b<br/>Harmed me with a charm<br/>Which I did not know.</p><p>She is a house on a hill<br/>With a gateway at the end;<br/>At the door, I turned to lock<br/>The glass door.</p><p>The goddess spoke to me<br/>In a loud, deep voice<br/>Which I could not hear.</p><p>She asked me where I was from?<br/>I said I was not from.</p><p>In the morning, I looked<br/>Back on the road with worn shoes<br/>And a shoe that had been<br/>And was not well maintained.</p><p>And the goddess asked me where was I from?<br/>I said, I was not from.</p>",
    "<p><b>To the Lyric Poets by William Blake</b></p><p>As you did not believe in me, then do not be so quick in your scorn;<br/>The day I will go, the same shall use all the rest;<br/>Leave me no wistful or lamenting mind;<br/>So long as you suffer me, I am safe and glad;<br/>But when I have done, this letter I send away;<br/>And in this letter also I give you this closed book,<br/>For, conversing with my lyre, I have found out<br/>All that is true, and never hath been done,<br/>That was just, and never shall be done;<br/>Thus I will not forget you by any means;<br/>In my heart, I am so disheartened and so glad;<br/>Let my wonted love your fellow-creatures the same,<br/>You strong, fit, and wise, and kind;<br/>I will not remember you and see you in my sleep,<br/>But trust and love, my true love, and your praise;<br/>For I will not forget you and receive your love.</p>",
    "<p><b>Fluid Tomorrow<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Sakari Leblan</b></p><p>The sand woke<br/>this tired face\u2009\u2014\u2009a young woman\u2009\u2014\u2009a tense<br/>lax in her motorized wheelchair</p><p>accordion of female bones</p><p>with broken jaws</p><p>shattering like inscriptions</p><p>on the sand</p><p>to the river</p><p>the shiny surface</p><p>the unlikely string of messages</p><p>un-mapped</p><p>at the top of the head</p><p>like a scuffed stamp</p><p>that\u2019s still there</p><p>a faint outline</p><p>of a hand</p><p>a hint</p><p>of a scarf</p><p>hanging</p><p>from the skirt</p><p>dance</p><p>in the window</p><p>as summer comes</p>",
    "<p><b>A Golden Lotto Ticket by Artemio Giovannini</b></p><p>It\u2019s the same every year, the same every day!</p><p>Once we drilled the holes, waited</p><p>for the light to come on. We picked up</p><p>the pistil with tooth.</p><p>It\u2019s the same every year,</p><p>the same everyday!</p><p>We buried our face</p><p>in the long wheel. We spun</p><p>in the air.</p><p>We\u2019re in the air today.</p><p>Every morning,</p><p>we breath our way to</p><p>the top. Every day,</p><p>we are in the air.</p><p>From the ground up,</p><p>we grind our teeth,</p><p>please don\u2019t touch me.</p><p>Every year,</p><p>we drill out the stakes,</p><p>we wait</p><p>until the spring</p><p>is bursting.</p><p>We don\u2019t let the sun</p><p>touch us.</p><p>Everything\u2019s fine.</p><p>Everything\u2019s fine.</p><p>Everything\u2019s fine.</p>",
    "<p><b>Mother by Daniel J. Langton</b></p><p>God you have given me this place<br/>to come to; it\u2019s not nameless<br/>but it is mine. And you make<br/>children of dogs, like the dog with the<br/>little arm who walks up and down<br/>the room like the horse who<br/>wasn\u2019t ready for the track.</p><p>You have given me this life<br/>to climb and to be like the one<br/>I\u2019m standing before today.<br/>The myriad of legs. The<br/>continual stretching of my legs.</p><p>The young dogs that follow you<br/>to the dumpster where you bury<br/>your beautiful dogs that you take<br/>home with you in your van like a shoe.</p>",
    "<p><b>Rune: Part 1 by Anthony Consider</b></p><p>Dawn is always<br/>the one in the blue for me.</p><p>And how many other days have I<br/>lapsed after noon,</p><p>dutifully starting the night,<br/>parching<br/>ever onward towards tomorrow\u2019s</p><p>and counting sleep<br/>like a natural habit,</p><p>like the wisdom of my mind?</p><p>Ah, but there\u2019s the rub.</p><p>In my last un-<br/>lighted yearbook photo</p><p>I look back and see</p><p>four men packing<br/>Titanfall, a 12-pack,</p><p>a boat, a backpack,<br/>a $2,000 watch</p><p>I wore last night</p><p>with a satisfied</p><p>smirk on my face,<br/>all three of us</p><p>stacked in a wooden box</p><p>all without having<br/>came here to see</p><p>the people we used to know in</p><p>to thank those that we did</p><p>not. Just me, and</p><p>this man built this house in a word</p><p>that no one had invented,<br/>who lost or changed his name</p><p>too many times to register.</p><p>In my dreams, no one<br/>can tell me what\u2019s on</p><p>the calendar tomorrow,<br/>but that day</p><p>must come, dammit.</p>",
    "<p><b>How Will You Be (With Other People) by Wendy Videlock</b></p><p>Have I not whispered that my heart was<br/>an animal that could understand memes,</p><p>made to eat their own beards?</p><p>\u2022</p><p>I had never tried to run<br/>the way you ran before</p><p>you punched me in the jaw.</p><p>I had never been kicked</p><p>on a treadmill, knee deep</p><p>in a jar of mud.</p><p>And my heart, a meat of an animal</p><p>half-eaten on a highway sign,</p><p>began to chafe.</p>",
    "<p><b>5 by Jack Prelutsky</b></p><p>This afternoon I went out to buy milk<br/>at the corner store</p><p>because I was thirsty<br/>and wanted water</p><p>the store clerk snapped me</p><p>out of my drab-</p><p>brain reverie:</p><p>Hey! can you come in</p><p>and I will give you a fair</p><p>look at the sweetest deal</p><p>of all the other sandwiches</p><p>I hated so much</p><p>but now can\u2019t get enough</p><p>and I mam down</p><p>honestly to get</p><p>back to work</p>",
    "<p><b>The Elegy by Samuel Taylor Coleridge</b></p><p>All is dying, I know,<br/>No more bread, and broken shoes,<br/>Where moonlight hands feed slaves.</p><p>What is left is the dead\u2019s grief,<br/>The melancholy of \u2009Men.<br/>What is left is the dead\u2019s truth,</p><p>The springtime, without music,<br/>The falltime, without joy,</p><p>The silence, the flower,<br/>The earth that never blooms,</p><p>The shade, the presage,<br/>The river that never flows,</p><p>The silence, the flower,<br/>The air that never blooms,</p><p>The dead that I never knew,</p><p>The silent sorrow of \u200athe dead,</p><p>Gratifying and dreadful,<br/>The absence of \u200athe dead,</p><p>The silent grief of \u200athe dead.</p>",
    "<p><b>Doors by John Graham</b></p><p>I can open<br/>the door to the bathroom.<br/>Let the water<br/>fill the whole bathtub.</p><p>I can use my feet<br/>to enter the bathroom.</p><p>I can take the sink<br/>to the other side.</p><p>My three dogs<br/>make a constant huff.</p><p>I usually can't.</p><p>On this day,<br/>I'm here.</p>",
    "<p><b>For those who sit in silence at the fire by Elizabeth Alexander</b></p><p>I am read to dream of you being a queen.<br/>Your subjects laugh while they read your poetry.</p><p>Other girls are erased, erased, erased.<br/>I read the words that will erase me.</p><p>You are anagram of my life.<br/>You are divine, anagram of the words of my life.</p><p>There is a table behind a nurse\u2019s office.<br/>I am there before you.</p><p>The tourists are there before you.<br/>You are anagram of a poem.</p><p>I am only here because I am there.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lock by James Schuyler</b></p><p>The God of the Bible is the god of locks.<br/>I worked in the storeroom of our rowhouse<br/>where we purchased brand-new car keys</p><p>in hopes that they would prove<br/>to be useful in unlocking the doors<br/>of our houses, or a locked room</p><p>where killers had barricaded themselves<br/>by cutting themselves with butcher knives.</p><p>I was an expert in locks<br/>in the military. When we</p><p>would go up to see a movie we<br/>might find ourselves inside</p><p>something that looked a lot like a lock<br/>but was not: the body of a blue whale</p><p>on the screen at our party. Locking<br/>hands and feet to the floor</p><p>in a weightless heap, the dark<br/>was not a metaphor. Somehow</p><p>I felt I was being released<br/>as I lifted the hammer of my life</p><p>and lifted the bed out of the sea.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cThis Land Is Ours by Beezley Aledo\" by Jack Langston</b></p><p>this land is ours<br/>we are a niche<br/>we are the fringes</p><p>the rows of the loft<br/>architects<br/>of this land are within our reach<br/>and lurking<br/>we will make art</p><p>and our noise will be long</p><p>the rumbling cinder<br/>of the swirling hearth<br/>hovering from a chimney<br/>we will swim</p><p>as the current moves us<br/>toward antechamber</p><p>the light filtering through sandalwood<br/>we will be amazed</p><p>to be alive<br/>all of us</p><p>Can\u2019t wait<br/>to see you</p><p>we will bring a light<br/>to your life</p><p>when we return<br/>do we walk<br/>through these halls</p><p>with your laughter<br/>inside us this land</p><p>will be ours</p><p>this land is ours</p>",
    "<p><b>Oblivion by Frances Hauth</b></p><p>Imagine, when you take the bus<br/>from Concord, that, whatever happened,<br/>your life has been, to a certain degree,<br/>already over by<br/>a certain degree. It could be<br/>not quite<br/>that, but the sense of being so<br/>long ago falls away,<br/>an illusion<br/>that I'm shifting from<br/>a home<br/>to another place<br/>to pick up where<br/>I left off<br/>.<br/>When I arrive,<br/>having moved from<br/>Concord, that was not<br/>the case. It was more of<br/>a silhouette<br/>I was walking through<br/>on my way home.<br/>It wasn\u2019t a movement<br/>that I made, it was a<br/>limb<br/>I vaguely remember,<br/>one that I held in<br/>my hand, looking through<br/>the window.<br/>When I looked at that<br/>limb, and found the door<br/>open, I went back<br/>and closed it.<br/>Leading up to the start<br/>of my lecture, I was<br/>trying<br/>to be as honest as possible.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cOnly I can bear it\u201d by Rita Mae Reese</b></p><p>Only I can bear it, the mulk, the slavery, the awning.<br/>I swallowed the piece of the broken hand of my father.<br/>I crushed the emerald chin. I buried him under a damp rustling.</p><p>He came to visit every other year, to stare out the window at the heat of the earth, and the open window.<br/>He was the only black man I owned, and you could tell.</p><p>Only I can bear it, the mulk, the slavery, the awning.<br/>If I stare out the window, I am not to be believed.</p><p>I am not to be believed. Or be anything.<br/>I'm to be the ghetto, the faceless buttoned-up, dark, unimaginably dark place.</p>",
    "<p><b>NOVEMBER,<br/>1958 by William Trowbridge</b></p><p>In the winter of a century<br/>where vermin knows no bounds,<br/>Here, at the foot, the old barn<br/>that absorbed the most frequent visitors,<br/>and the car and the Eugene hotel<br/>turned into shadowy Little Patapsco,<br/>where ants showed up fearfully<br/>like vultures in hazel clusters,<br/>where the dead were molesting the living,<br/>I\u2019ve seen an owl rising from the snow<br/>on its rockery;<br/>a wolf stalking around the yard<br/>wanting to know what it\u2019s all about.</p><p>I\u2019ve seen men's faces fall<br/>from a rusty wire or from<br/>a fallen tree. I\u2019ve watched<br/>a professor drop a book<br/>on the floor while children<br/>yawn and the moon is a star.<br/>But when I\u2019ve tried<br/>to convey what it\u2019s like<br/>to be an owl in America<br/>in this glass palace<br/>at the edge of town<br/>I\u2019ve played a game I\u2019d like to play:<br/>I\u2019ve said, without thinking,<br/>\u201cO, but<br/>I\u2019m not<br/>the kind of o\u2019f I\u2019m here<br/>to be a\u00a0\u200ao\u2019f a crow<br/>and\u00a0\u200aa little crap,<br/>whatever that means.</p>",
    "<p><b>Writing on Lacquer with Straw by Zaphron Port</b></p><p>As for the great painter, he\u2019s just a clown,<br/>thinking about himself<br/>all day and the world\u2019s more important issues:<br/>money, family, work, beauty, sex.<br/>He sleeps late, gets drunk<br/>and watches porn on TV.<br/>The world\u2019s forgotten, the way one sees it,<br/>or even for an instant, the dead<br/>face of exhaustion.</p><p>Love is always a yearning after the worst<br/>accomplishment in a country\u2019s struggle<br/>or the very best, a wishful fantasy<br/>fulfilled. Parting the streams on the spot<br/>one finds the fissures, the savage<br/>epics of rainforest beauty.</p><p>I am dreaming about bees<br/>who gather pollen in cardboard boxes<br/>after rainstorms, when the trees<br/>are cleared, and the shadows<br/>are filled with the colorless<br/>dust of spilled batter\u2014a kind<br/>of hallucination with a name.</p><p>Listen: I am listening<br/>to the strings of a topless<br/>dancing woman at the piano.<br/>Listen to the drumbeat<br/>of her thigh, or the faint<br/>whispering of a barn acorn.</p><p>Listen to the cries of a bull.<br/>Listen to the sobbing of a poor girl.<br/>Listen to the stillness<br/>in the car behind the door,<br/>and when I look through the aftershave<br/>and my reflection stops in the leaden<br/>wheel of my trunk, I realize I am in<br/>a painting.</p>",
    "<p><b>Sonnet #97 by Ezra Pound</b></p><p>The lunch-hour light: a shaking window that gives off<br/>A warm, fuzzy impression of darkness. The garden<br/>Ruins, falling off their hinges and crumbling.</p><p>William Tell\u2019s voice cracks down the stairs<br/>A voice as she waves, ecstatic, to the next room.</p><p>The man who\u2019s been pruning the roses has fallen<br/>His shorts to his knees, and Paris<br/>Who\u2019s in a wheelchair, and Paris in the wheelchair.</p><p>There\u2019s someone else writing a letter<br/>To a stranger<br/>About a Jackal, about a Trafalgar,<br/>About a Thunderbird.<br/>Who\u2019s writing this letter?<br/>The young couple who\u2019re separated by the sea.</p><p>It\u2019s quiet in the bedroom.<br/>The woman inside the stove is silent<br/>Comrade. An old-time sailor\u2019s wife,<br/>Clotilde. She teaches a PDF about deadly weapons.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Child by Stephen Dunn</b></p><p>At first she was breaking like a door<br/>You could hear a Clifton house<br/>in the distance,<br/>The tree here was still<br/>I could see the Bridge to the Castle</p><p>Moving in the distance,<br/>The tree was waving here<br/>But later when you walked</p><p>Behind that Bridge to the Castle<br/>It was turning into<br/>A small Room where I could put down my books</p><p>If I moved at all,<br/>I did so with a quick look<br/>When I hit the ground</p><p>Surpris\u00adingly it appeared<br/>Like a man in a coat<br/>Tightening his tie,<br/>A light jacket like a wool cap,<br/>A hat like a cap,<br/>The gentleman of the house<br/>Sauntering over there,<br/>The tree that had been swinging,<br/>The Room of the Wood-Figure</p><p>Was starting to sway again<br/>And it did so at the right moment</p><p>When I heard a really loud noise like a church bell<br/>From the faraway church,<br/>Surpris\u00adingly he was not there</p><p>But I did see him coming like a dog<br/>Back into the house,<br/>I knew where he was going, I knew<br/>I was definitely not going to miss him</p>",
    "<p><b>Axelrod by Wendy Videlock</b></p><p>For I'm tall,<br/>I almost lack the grace<br/>to put my hat back<br/>on the headboard,<br/>so I kind of cheat,<br/>even though I know<br/>it\u2019s beneath the crown<br/>to lack the fabled<br/>fur of your majesty,</p><p>and all the furniture on my head<br/>has been rearranged,<br/>I don\u2019t think my head is<br/>mountain on a saddle</p><p>hearing back of a horse\u2014<br/>I can\u2019t even<br/>stand, can\u2019t<br/>walk, can\u2019t<br/>run!</p><p>But the years have<br/>settled down my bones,<br/>and I\u2019ll live this life,<br/>and ever since I was born<br/>I\u2019ve been searching<br/>to express myself<br/>without the need<br/>of anybody\u2019s permission</p><p>and the stupid<br/>industry has taught me<br/>that everything has its<br/>good and bad</p><p>and I\u2019ve accepted<br/>this a-hole life,<br/>where beauty<br/>is just a coat</p><p>for the wind<br/>and all those dirty<br/>luggage rucks<br/>on the train</p><p>where I have to<br/>carry a dead weight<br/>of my own</p><p>without any clothes<br/>(who cares<br/>if there\u2019s no jacket?)</p><p>I\u2019ve been waiting<br/>for those Yale guys<br/>at the back of the bus<br/>to come up with a name<br/>(where you get a haircut<br/>in Spain or South America)<br/>Maybe I\u2019ll marry<br/>a dentist<br/>or a rabbi</p><p>who can hold me,<br/>so I can be free</p><p>and at the back of the bus<br/>I\u2019ll be<br/>a miracle of a man!</p>",
    "<p><b>in the lane by William H. Mungo</b></p><p>You\u2019ve got a voice,<br/>you\u2019re given<br/>a certain height<br/>to think</p><p>and dance.<br/>And the windows<br/>are glass</p><p>more like streets<br/>where old hands</p><p>pull the seats down.<br/>You\u2019ve got a voice,</p><p>you\u2019ve got a waist<br/>and legs to dance</p><p>in.<br/>You\u2019re so hot</p><p>so hot<br/>you make me want</p><p>to curl up with you<br/>like a little girl with a pony</p><p>and a high heel</p><p>and a freestyle</p><p>in her mouth</p><p>and a parking space<br/>with a sign</p><p>and a feel</p><p>like someone\u2019s</p><p>been waiting<br/>for the last time<br/>to be intimate</p><p>and how</p><p>you\u2019re not certain<br/>what I will do</p><p>if I want</p><p>which is why</p><p>I kept</p><p>away.</p>",
    "<p><b>About the Expanse by Daniel J. Thurmond</b></p><p>The moon is a bullet turned through a mine.<br/>There is no sun here.<br/>The earth has been somewhat disturbed<br/>by this turn of events.</p><p>The dark is something, for now,<br/>not visible. The moon is just a master,<br/>meant to be.</p><p>The dark makes me feel old,<br/>like when you go into a movie<br/>and someone else is passing.</p><p>Dark is a word. Draw in your breath<br/>and then look in your eyes.</p><p>The dark is coming to an end,<br/>as was the case for the beginning.</p><p>The dark is the beginning<br/>of the end.</p><p>There are many corpses<br/>of the first people that died<br/>and many corpses of the second<br/>people that died</p><p>in the year 3000.</p><p>Every night I go to bed<br/>and wake up to a new image<br/>in my dreams,<br/>the image of a pure, white body<br/>stuck to a black sheet.</p><p>I've thought the same thing for days.</p><p>I am in a book.<br/>The name of the book<br/>is not as written.</p><p>That lost book is still in this house.<br/>I am still making music.</p>",
    "<p><b>Waiting There by John Knott</b></p><p>Were you waiting for one or two or three<br/>to come after hours and walk the block,<br/>rocking strollers, pausing to enjoy the view<br/>or climb inside the sunflower to cool off?<br/>The west was warm and full of moons.</p><p>Were you waiting to see mother, how she turned<br/>slowly into a coconut at your feet?<br/>Or to hear her sing, a song that would settle<br/>you, your hands, the way your hands sink<br/>and swim in the ocean and return,<br/>these fingers folded in your lap,<br/>and your eyesight: a guide to a journey<br/>that would take you back?</p><p>If so, whose footsteps were you<br/>waiting for, to wait with,<br/>and never making it?<br/>And, with sea to go, what<br/>were you waiting to see, hear,<br/>touch, to feel, to see again?</p>",
    "<p><b>A Little Song by Eleanor Wilks</b></p><p>Forgive me<br/>for not having said it<br/>again,<br/>to which the world replies,<br/>Go ahead<br/>it\u2019s glorious.<br/>We\u2019re all staring at you.<br/>You\u2019re beautiful.</p><p>When I first heard about your death<br/>I was in awe.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Recess by Jack Spencer</b></p><p>My own? A geezer.</p><p>Look up and see the late same-day train.</p><p>Ask someone what time it is.</p><p>Don\u2019t ask a friend to check the time.</p><p>Ask an aid if it\u2019s sundown.</p><p>Watch TV and drop everything,</p><p>hands in air pockets,</p><p>an eerie silence.</p><p>Surfaces creaking,fold.</p><p>Roll the cuffs.</p><p>Walk in the rain.</p><p>Drive into a snowstorm.</p><p>Drive through Isleta.</p><p>Get a new car.</p><p>Wear a t-shirt at the beach.</p><p>Bring a friend.</p><p>Walk past a tattoo parlor,<br/>and in the doorway of a bathroom stall,<br/>look up and see a little girl.</p><p>She\u2019s reading A. E. Housman.</p>",
    "<p><b>At the Press Club by Caitlin Doyle</b></p><p>Carole Hueston<br/>at the press club<br/>I thought it would be fun<br/>to practice my German<br/>on a scrap of<br/>paper.</p><p>I read some of the best<br/>art books in the city.</p><p>The city wasn\u2019t the<br/>place you thought it would be<br/>when you landed</p><p>at the airport<br/>it was just a matter of finding<br/>the right words.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Short Story by Charles Reznikoff</b></p><p>O<br/>\u2014<br/>My father was a short story.<br/>He was a pile of<br/>coffee grounds<br/>and T-shirts<br/>spun like feathers\u2009\u2014\u2009paragon<br/>of the Ugly\u2009\u2014\u2009a vast<br/>canvas of Jell-O,<br/>nearly toothless,<br/>on his cheek,<br/>fish nose<br/>compared to the<br/>mouth of a word.<br/>Passionate<br/>he thought<br/>all men should be short stories,<br/>any story worth telling,<br/>just a few lines<br/>to drive the point home:<br/>thinking of his father<br/>does not make one a short story,<br/>one needs to care what happens.</p><p>I want me to play the \"bootleg\"<br/>analogous to \"We Are the Dwarves\"<br/>by the sea\u2019s \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0rock opera,<br/>the yodel<br/>of My Favorite Things</p><p>and the motion in a movie,<br/>its<br/>spinning<br/>panes</p><p>with a slight flip<br/>and rustling of<br/>tires and cuffs.<br/>My father was a short story.<br/>He was a pelvic thrustface<br/>that I could,<br/>I could see<br/>up Close,<br/>relentlessly,<br/>discover,<br/>forget,</p><p>maintain<br/>a dose of gratitude<br/>for the opportunity<br/>that he had.</p><p>Such was his delight<br/>that we\u2013myself included,<br/>his wife, my daughters,<br/>nights<br/>at his house,<br/>got drunk on him,<br/>he got<br/>back at it,<br/>touched us,<br/>he was there,<br/>he was<br/>wondrous, like<br/>a fairy godfather.</p><p>Such, such,<br/>Italy<br/>with its villa,<br/>and most famously, the<br/>Vagabonds.</p><p>I\u2019ve fallen for<br/>some of his women<br/>and my friends!</p><p>And I\u2019ve lusted<br/>to his diaries\u2009\u2014\u2009the<br/>Love Poem,<br/>for its \u200alullaby,<br/>And the Teddy Bear,<br/>which</p><p>goes on<br/>at high school picnics,<br/>it\u2019s<br/>Favorite.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Scandal in the Attic ~ by Tim O'Reilly</b></p><p>What is in the hollow, that's not there.<br/>A year and a half to watch the snow pile up<br/>on my driveway;</p><p>a half million snowflakes remain.<br/>I've put them in a blue box, labelled</p><p>'Silly!' or just a pain in the arse.<br/>I've put them in a glass, on the rocks,</p><p>to make my wife laugh;<br/>they\u2019re gone the next day.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Mad Cow by W. S. Merwin</b></p><p>Mad Cow is what we think of when we think of cows.<br/>When we think about cows, we think of cows<br/>running free into the hills.</p><p>Mad Cow, though, is what we think of when we think about cows.<br/>Mad Cow knows nothing of cows in the barn.<br/>Mad Cow, though, is what we think of when we think about cows.</p><p>Mad Cow knows about cows, and yet the cows<br/>know nothing of cows in the barn.<br/>When we think about cows, we think of cows<br/>running free into the hills.</p><p>Mad Cow knows nothing of cows in the barn,<br/>but he still runs free into the hills.<br/>When we think about cows, we think of cows<br/>running free into the hills.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Upside of Life<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Rebecca Wolff</b></p><p>They think I\u2019m by now too old for the hard and fast rules of life.<br/>I\u2019m nothing like the twinkly and luminous months you blame me for.<br/>But I don\u2019t smell of jicar and undermine.<br/>I\u2019m a plain, everyday kind of figure, you\u2019re L.A. or Detroit,<br/>I\u2019ve got my mornings\u2019 and will.</p><p>And I\u2019ve got nights for days and can\u2019t be blamed<br/>for them, you\u2019re an alien and an alien.<br/>I\u2019m the one who knows the real reason for tragedy,<br/>who is not afraid to hurt you, and to stand by you.<br/>I\u2019ve got tastes for the muck and the mire,<br/>and I\u2019ve got tastes for the muck and mire<br/>I\u2019ve got the answers to.</p><p>The truth is that I\u2019m far from being good in a bad way.<br/>I\u2019ve got the answers to trouble and pain.<br/>But I\u2019ve got answers for trouble and pain.</p><p>The way a boy band handles the tragedy they\u2019re creating,<br/>the way I\u2019ve handled the tragedy I\u2019ve created.<br/>The way I\u2019ve been able to survive and thrive<br/>on the ruins of what I was born to endure.</p>",
    "<p><b>In Memoriam Canto II, Book III, The Lord of Creatures by Edward Thomas</b></p><p>You\u2019re a small monster, a soul within a universe of things. The price of your existence is your freedom, your self-confidence. The price of your freedom is your agony. A man born in a haunted house must be cured of insomnia and spied. His waking must be smoothed by anointing coddles,<br/>his writing his happy thoughts. A few of his poems are among the most admired.<br/>And let the world know of your existence: When the stars go down, the earth\u2019s still<br/>okay. In my right mind, I would like to be brave enough to bear your existence: a burden<br/>the world could handle, weighty as a great ship. But there\u2019s no time for that: nothing\u2019s steamy enough to turn a man,<br/>the world\u2019s most mountless, into something permanant as a star.</p>",
    "<p><b>[the turtle you\u2019re holding] by Alice Moore Dunbar</b></p><p>the turtle you\u2019re holding<br/>you\u2019re going to run into<br/>that\u2019s freezing<br/>to the body<br/>the bones you\u2019re keeping<br/>are going to go out<br/>you\u2019ll need the skin<br/>but you\u2019re going to want the bone<br/>you\u2019re going to need<br/>your body must be prepared<br/>for the unexpected<br/>and what you\u2019re going to<br/>carry into the world<br/>is only going to be as strong<br/>as when you carry it with you<br/>this is the way it must be<br/>if you want it to last</p>",
    "<p><b>A Reporter for a Highway</b></p><p>I was walking to a bar when an American truck pulled out of a wooded area<br/>of the woods, sped toward me, halted overnight, flipped<br/>and bounced twice, then spun onto its side,<br/>as if in anachronism, and slid to a stop.</p><p>I had lost my glasses and had to lie face-up down the length<br/>of the platform, where my blond neighbor slept, dead,<br/>and I wondered if it was a stutter.</p><p>Walking uphill, I repeatedly lifted one foot<br/>and descended that hillside where I had never walked,<br/>and down a sudden metal staircase, where I had kept my voice down,<br/>and dropped again, though I was bent<br/>and tired, and worried I had forgotten to put my shoes<br/>on. People walked everywhere and nothing moved.<br/>The billow of smoke from the abandoned refinery<br/>I had parked across from was next to me.</p><p>A few people were walking down the hill toward the highway, watching<br/>my back as I walked toward the mountain. I turned back,<br/>and laughed. We were wearing the same clothes.<br/>When I got to the top, it was over.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Disappearance of Time<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Greta Gerber</b></p><p>Where is the place where I\u2019ve never been?<br/>Where is my life that\u2019s mine and yours?</p><p>Where am I now that I never was?<br/>What is my therapist\u2019s name? What is the doctor\u2019s name?</p><p>Where is my philosophy professor\u2019s name?<br/>What is my popular mom\u2019s name?</p><p>Where is my car?<br/>What is my friend\u2019s name?What is my treehouse?</p><p>Where is my house?<br/>What is my roof?<br/>What is my hill?</p><p>Where is my child?<br/>What is my curfew?<br/>What are my rules?</p><p>Where is my friend?<br/>Where is my philosophy professor?<br/>What are my rules?</p>",
    "<p><b>I Am Spartacus by Stanzas B. Soltec</b></p><p>Who have I left asleep in the Spirit Chariot,<br/>My slumber-worn skin, my sparse brothers, my witless friends:<br/>Anyone who has worn a magic chain<br/>That can hang me by my ear, a foot from a cliff<br/>Where I would be sorely needed, my friend,<br/>Who\u2019ll leave my body in that tattered bed?</p><p>I\u2019ve treasured this world in order to show it to be worthless.<br/>I have made a fool of myself,<br/>Self-approval, self-loathing, the silk scarf I\u2019ve worn, the shoes I\u2019ve worn<br/>To save my secret life, the truth that I know<br/>Is the price of liberation.</p><p>I have cursed my foolishness, cursed that shameful life.<br/>I\u2019ve stolen money from the rich, from the poor.<br/>I have lied to my friends and lovers, if only to deny<br/>My own enslavement to this world.</p><p>I have done away with those men, saddled the chains,<br/>Jugged the soul, unified the free,<br/>Left all these terms, all these corpses behind,<br/>Enslave and deny not\u2014I am Spartacus<br/>. . .</p>",
    "<p><b>A Prayer for the Provision of Shelter by Eileen Putt</b></p><p>1</p><p>Welcome to the new house,<br/>which has a bathtub in the toilet.<br/>What shall we do now<br/>that the cat<br/>has moved on to the attic<br/>and the porcelain window<br/>has barely left in its lids?<br/>What shall we do now<br/>that the cook<br/>is on the outs?</p><p>What do we do now<br/>that the dishwasher<br/>is a tangled mess?</p>",
    "<p><b>Variation on a Theme by Li-Young Lee</b></p><p>a.k.a. The Snake-Headed Terror</p><p>From the tip of my lip, a chisel smithered a blind-spot</p><p>against a seventh wall</p><p>from the first pearly to the third pearly,</p><p>from the tip of my lip, a long-limbed, bat-eared,</p><p>bossa-tat, endear followed by short-stuttered curse,</p><p>a carved-amber cadenza accented with trilling</p><p>songs also accented with trilling,</p><p>from the tip of my lip, followed by a single whisper,</p><p>caroming out, a woozy, beleaguered chorus \u2026</p><p>blushing, now familiar \u2026 the snake . . . the snake-head . . .</p><p>gray, not gray anymore, a switch flipped,</p><p>the serpent turned to stone, the snake-legs saw</p><p>my target. The snake-head is the thief, the thief is the snake.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Closer Look by Joshua Beckman</b></p><p>This painting is a pupil.<br/>He has received a score of odd-shaped<br/>little fish from the local aquaculture factory.</p><p>He has whipped up the perfect<br/>opaque matte without making any sense.</p><p>He has been praised by his teacher\u2019s diary<br/>for his compulsive urge to look at drawings<br/>and write down everything he sees.</p><p>His teacher notices none of his marks<br/>even count for a four, or for a five.</p><p>The principal has no idea how it is<br/>that a child with such talent<br/>might have never touched a pencil.</p><p>Will he ever learn to cut?<br/>When he is older, he will be able to apply<br/>his fine motor skills<br/>to make the world a simpler place</p><p>and his classmates will use the word<br/>\"clumsy\" in a pejorative sense<br/>because it means he has never practiced<br/>how to make things with their own hands</p><p>and the teacher will think he is<br/>a freak and a loser because<br/>she will see the weaknesses in his</p><p>education and read about them<br/>when they come up in class<br/>all afternoon.</p><p>The teacher will also think that<br/>she has written a good grade, because</p><p>nothing is allowed to be done with crumbs<br/>on the table; and she will look<br/>back on his misbehavior with pride</p><p>because it was his reaction to her<br/>that has been the problem.</p><p>Will he ever learn<br/>that the sun is a kind of flower?</p><p>Or that a duvet is a kind of crew<br/>on a ship?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Surprising Thing About Not Believing in the Stagnant Things That Happen In Consequence of the Marches by John Ashbery</b></p><p>I have spent a lot of time thinking about the fall of a pin that I dropped as a boy<br/>on the step<br/>of a slippery bridge</p><p>neither side<br/>of which<br/>is the destination<br/>more than half the time.</p><p>And now, at the end of the street<br/>the clock stands<br/>beneath the black brown roof<br/>I see no way back from</p><p>where in the distance I feel a shower<br/>and a wind is rippling through the trees</p><p>two women in white coats<br/>hold a net above a linoleum ledge<br/>and on the old stone steps<br/>a woman and a man<br/>rather than the opposite sex stand</p><p>in the center of the room with their backs<br/>smiling<br/>and talking</p><p>and the will to live<br/>is not based in stone. It\u2019s not a bit<br/>orchard or a field of hay but a whole world</p><p>of things that should be happening<br/>tied to the branching threads<br/>of the universe</p><p>the buildings<br/>muscled by petticoats<br/>clipped by loose floor<br/>sculpture bending</p><p>in mid-air toward<br/>secondary forms<br/>cracking a window on a roof</p><p>in winter<br/>in a field<br/>the wind<br/>chimes<br/>with a poem<br/>of thousands of words<br/>I was just<br/>thinking about<br/>it\u2019s worth<br/>thinking about</p><p>like it\u2019s not<br/>completely crazy<br/>not saying<br/>shit<br/>like it\u2019s not<br/>unfair<br/>or unkind<br/>to think about<br/>this</p><p>I keep hoping<br/>the puritans\u2019 will<br/>come with me<br/>to be their own man<br/>and kill me<br/>I keep hoping<br/>the damn<br/>puritans<br/>will allow me<br/>to be<br/>The Man I am today<br/>and be<br/>A man<br/>I am not.<br/>And I feel awful.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Death of Just Another Suspect by Michael Fields</b></p><p>Gladys, little ladies,<br/>I\u2019m a man, you know.<br/>I didn\u2019t want you to die.<br/>I\u2019ve slept in the basement all night,<br/>I\u2019m a nobody.</p><p>The world has punished me.<br/>I\u2019ve lost too many friends<br/>to be replaced.</p><p>I\u2019ve waited too long,<br/>I\u2019m more paroled<br/>than I\u2019m ever been.</p><p>I\u2019m at home<br/>on a Sunday morning,</p><p>a tenth grader<br/>who\u2019ll be hitting<br/>a hundred when I<br/>die.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Short Sonnet by Cynthia Zarin</b></p><p>At the airport<br/>I examine the manifest<br/>I\u2019ve brought from Cleveland:</p><p>a pink colored handkerchief,<br/>three pairs of tweezers,<br/>herringbone knuckle,<br/>a pink knuckleless cup,<br/>all the bent plastic parts of my daughter\u2019s bicycle<br/>and her purse.</p><p>I know all the words<br/>I\u2019ve rehearsed:</p><p>why?<br/>What?<br/>What\u2019s the reason?<br/>Why is it so dark<br/>in there?</p><p>At home<br/>it\u2019s quite nice<br/>to be able to watch her<br/>return from the subway<br/>and make a beeline<br/>toward the living room\u2014<br/>I know<br/>herringbone knuckle<br/>won\u2019t stick<br/>and she\u2019ll be left stranded<br/>in her purse.</p><p>At home<br/>I\u2019ve made a lot<br/>of pancakes,<br/>I\u2019ve also cooked<br/>a lot of spaghetti<br/>once or twice,<br/>but there\u2019s nothing<br/>I\u2019ve ever wanted<br/>more.</p>",
    "<p><b>Ore by Kay Mullen</b></p><p>never mind that its very name conjures<br/>the food or Iraq or Mars or an elder</p><p><br/>the younger you get the richer you get<br/>basically any god you like. \u2009</p><p>the recollection that you were born<br/>in Lower Manhattan and lived</p><p>the civil rights movement and looked<br/>like you forever, not in the image</p><p>of the guitar picking up the dirt or<br/>of the white house where they walked</p><p>through the peach trees<br/>and the still water and a</p><p>Mexican mosquito in the sun</p><p>though some people think Maya</p><p>is simply a word for mother but it</p><p>is also a word for stone</p><p>a word with the power to burn</p>",
    "<p><b>The Clutter by Crisosto Apacheo</b></p><p>We felt that we wanted to be alone<br/>But there was also the feeling that we expected<br/>To share something with the world\u2009\u2014\u2009a big red knife<br/>or a brown machete.<br/>The last thing we wanted was for you<br/>To have to deal with the aftermath.<br/>Now, a few months later, she is dead<br/>And I am sitting here in the library<br/>Talking about the impromptu work<br/>I did to assemble the manuscript<br/>I was reading when I died.</p><p>Papa and I have been talking<br/>Over the years about how the result was<br/>One man and one woman<br/>Hanging by one collar can.</p><p>It was an act of love by a strong man<br/>To give a woman one more chance.</p><p>It was an act of love by a strong man<br/>To let a woman go down in flames<br/>As a beautiful woman.</p><p>Papa and I have been talking<br/>Over the years about how the result<br/>Was a reconception of the American dream.</p><p>It was an act of love by a strong man<br/>To give a woman one more chance<br/>To escape a life one never wanted.</p>",
    "<p><b>Bring Back the Good Guys by Donald Revell</b></p><p>And I have a rictus grin.</p><p>My voice trips so high<br/>it keeps pushing myself back.</p><p>We mustn\u2019t forget the good guys,</p><p>or we\u2019re not going anywhere.</p><p>One of them will always<br/>speak for us in the tank.</p><p>It\u2019s the one you\u2019re most afraid of.</p><p>The one no one will ever forget.</p><p>It\u2019s when he\u2019s using his power<br/>to make everyone smile.</p><p>That\u2019s why I keep</p><p>rehearsing.</p><p>It\u2019s nice<br/>to have someone</p><p>speak for us.</p><p>I\u2019ve got a long way to go.</p><p>I\u2019m grateful</p><p>someone\u2019s</p><p>there for me.</p><p>I\u2019m certain</p><p>this will all be worth it,</p><p>hopes and prayers.</p><p>It\u2019s like we\u2019re leading</p><p>this bright life,</p><p>coming home,</p><p>about to take off our clothes,</p><p>cleansing ourselves,</p><p>and saying:</p><p>\u201cI\u2019m going in the door,</p><p>I\u2019m going in the door.\u201d</p><p>That\u2019s what it\u2019s like to be the good guys</p><p>in civilian life,</p><p>the car slides by the road,</p><p>somebody calls it a day,</p><p>and we drive away,</p><p>holding on to the harnesses</p><p>as if we still had a little</p><p>skirt we could pull over our heads,</p><p>and into the kitchen</p><p>sipping coffee,</p><p>singing what can\u2019t be taught</p><p>with our mouths.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Apartment by Fanny Howe</b></p><p>I sat on a bench in a dimly lit studio<br/>and watched her walk down the street<br/>with her husband. He carried a coffee bottle. She smiled<br/>and said nothing. She was walking<br/>straight ahead.<br/>I turned my back.<br/>I could hear my mother yelling<br/>for the cab and her daughter<br/>was dead.</p><p>The next day I walked home alone<br/>and walked under a bridge<br/>where I saw a sign<br/>like the one I thought I saw<br/>for my own body.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cBreathe in\u201d<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>Breathe in, breathe in, the breath<br/>That quickens my soul, May the springs<br/>Give spring, the heat the eyes<br/>Flood into the hearts, the leaves the eyes<br/>Give the earth its shade<br/>May the well-being the soul<br/>Be remembered<br/>May us remember the breath<br/>And the breath</p>",
    "<p><b>A Capacity of Bent Trousers by Andrew Marvell</b></p><p>I put my hat on, and made a hat<br/>of a ragged man\u2019s tails.<br/>The one who had been<br/>Respecting all this<br/>could not resist having it done.</p><p>It was an old hat and the cap<br/>was too short. In short, it was nothing.</p><p>I made a hat of a flipped<br/>kilt, that my uncle could wear.<br/>On an evening that does not<br/>deserve a name, I showed my ignorance of<br/>the natural history of the world.</p><p>It had no sleeves, the only thing worn.<br/>The poor thing was humiliated,<br/>but I remained calm as if I were at home.</p>",
    "<p><b>Melt<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Julieja de Paz</b></p><p>for Eric Englund<br/>The moon is a thin, powdered animal<br/>like a skull.<br/>\u201cI\u2019m not all there,\u201d he says to himself,<br/>\u201clike the chick frolicking<br/>with her frog\u201d<br/>(she is not all there).<br/>The moon is the enough<br/>to make a world,<br/>the hole in the world.<br/>He has vanished<br/>and she has vanished.</p><p>She\u2019s not the moon; she\u2019s<br/>the inner ear</p><p>of my body that glides over<br/>the gap, the split.<br/>It\u2019s all there, bin-<br/>hornet.</p><p>No traveler has to fight<br/>the cold wind of the field<br/>while the sun melts.</p><p>No one has to hold the door\u2014<br/>I do. And when the moon shits<br/>on me,<br/>it looks like my skin is melting<br/>as if a porcelain cup<br/>were exploding inside me.</p>",
    "<p><b>by Eric Voegt</b></p><p>If you think the water is calm<br/>as God said, then. . . .<br/>I have no better photographer<br/>than God. I can take a picture<br/>of snow. It is the perfect weather,</p><p>it is a perfect day. I have a special</p><p>camera that I have set to record the water<br/>and the clouds before. This is my story,</p><p>this is what I call me.</p>",
    "<p><b>:<br/>  <br/>  <br/>   <br/>    After-Tense, After-Tense by Michael Murrill</b></p><p>I think of<br/>behind the couch that<br/>was once so afraid<br/>that I might break<br/>the silence that was<br/>the breaking of the silence<br/>in the room<br/>that was at one time<br/>not so afraid<br/>(the carpet was knocked<br/>into a pile<br/>of leaves)<br/>but now<br/>I hear the broken<br/>final bit of silence<br/>as if</p><p>of course it\u2019s still<br/>there and it\u2019s not<br/>dust, it\u2019s something<br/>being done<br/>inside the house that<br/>was once so afraid<br/>to be done inside</p><p>but the door slowly<br/>open\u2026and I am here<br/>behind the curtain<br/>waiting for the curtains<br/>to come<br/>and for the pictures<br/>to cover all of my whole<br/>face</p><p>with a big, messy<br/>burden of<br/>naps and<br/>teeth and<br/>everybody<br/>hoping for a<br/>good time</p><p>I need a light,<br/>I get a light,<br/>I get a light,<br/>I get a light<br/>and if I<br/>could ask<br/>I would,<br/>I would ask<br/>everyone</p><p>if it\u2019s<br/>not the end<br/>of the world</p>",
    "<p><b>The Siren by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>The sun, glory-singing, rose<br/>Through the Valley of Sorrow and the Beauregard,</p><p>From thence, with tears generous, he meditated<br/>On the vast destruction he would inflict</p><p>And felt the weight of the doom that lay<br/>On his life\u2019s work as a man</p><p>Who loved the lost, whose heart was<br/>Eternal, in love for whom he bore</p><p>The terrible burden of his own.</p>",
    "<p><b>Beneath the Pines by Thomas Campion</b></p><p>Ode to the world.<br/>I come a-siding the world,<br/>I am a-singing the deepest song,<br/>I am a-siding the world,</p><p>I walk upright among the trees<br/>on an-elegant trodden path, got it!</p>",
    "<p><b></b></p>",
    "<p><b>The Sinkhole by John Howard</b></p><p>There is nothing left of them<br/>in the smothered wall.</p><p>The lights dim and the pine leaves<br/>are falling.</p><p>The car lights dim and the crows.<br/>And we move forward.</p><p>The cottage is empty,<br/>as are the letters on the slip.</p><p>The driveway is sheer and the entries<br/>are scooped up and left there.</p><p>And the mind drifts away<br/>like the coat of a winter bird.</p><p>But we are driving, though.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Face by Vincente Reverdy</b></p><p>I wanted to know<br/>if you\u2019re the one</p><p>in charge, replied the food<br/>stare</p><p>from the street,</p><p>though my co-workers</p><p>and I are the ones</p><p>in charge</p><p>of things</p><p>(and in charge</p><p>of the face</p><p>of the famished scandal)</p><p>so that\u2019s why</p><p>we\u2019re called</p><p>Friends</p><p>(if anyone is in charge</p><p>he\u2019s not)</p><p>but what I\u2019m asking</p>",
    "<p><b>Removing Stains by Travis Worley</b></p><p>If the drapes had a mind of their own,<br/>the drapes could be lamps.</p><p>I\u2019ve never stopped to ponder<br/>the way you\u2019re not you<br/>here again, before I was no more.</p><p>Or equally, there\u2019s no way<br/>to be me. The only thing<br/>carded on my walls is chalk.</p><p>There\u2019s a public gym in the park,<br/>yet I have forgotten my exercise<br/>plan. I\u2019ve never forgotten the way<br/>my voice disappears, pure as a dream.</p><p>Or maybe the drapes are<br/>good luck candles, lit at sundown.</p><p>If you want to calibrate<br/>my love, you\u2019ll have to burn<br/>the parchment I touched.</p><p>Or maybe they\u2019re the invisible<br/>force holding me back,</p><p>a new book written by a man in his thirties.<br/>Or maybe it\u2019s just evening<br/>and I was born on the eve of revolution.</p><p>What do you want me to say<br/>about that? I\u2019m just a<br/>belief, nothing more.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Smoking Seat by Harryette Mullen</b></p><p>The smoking seat<br/>hangs like a dirty suit<br/>and the carpet is wet with blood,<br/>I\u2019m in my tights and a man<br/>in a ball cap can\u2019t get me<br/>he runs up to the window<br/>and hides his face<br/>I tell him:<br/>\u201cJust do what you\u2019re told\u201d<br/>He urges me to leave<br/>but I\u2019ll stick with it<br/>and stay home<br/>First cigars were all that<br/>I had. Then beer,<br/>then wine, then I\u2019d drink<br/>the rest of the night<br/>like a bad habit<br/>and every night, like the dog,<br/>I would sit here<br/>and watch my dog<br/>sleeping and sobbing<br/>and the chair in front of me<br/>would rain wine<br/>and dark.</p>",
    "<p><b>I am a Woman by Samuel Taylor Coleridge</b></p><p>I am a woman who lives in a queer house with a boxwood fence<br/>Who cooks and sleeps but the men prefer the women.</p><p>I sit and play peacock<br/>Praying God I am not false to the world that has no God<br/>Who is God to me and will be God to all.</p><p>Ode to Judith by Richard Wilbur</p><p>A verse from Judith<br/>The fair night writhes and dances<br/>Variations from the rhythm of the night</p><p>From the coarse things of the world that the winged insects of the cypress fly.</p><p>Prayer for the animals like heaven on the earth<br/>Prayer that the wind that blows on the tree tops on the great river in the mountains of the West</p><p>Prayer for the birds like the moon on the face of the black ox.</p><p>A scripture from Judith<br/>God is love and is love and is the love that frees the white horse from the shackles of the man.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Heart by Michael Anania</b></p><p>It\u2019s not recognition that counts,<br/>or externalities of memory,<br/>but inward<br/>acute beauty.</p><p>The childhood I had,<br/>the magic of the innocence,<br/>would go down in history<br/>like a luckless but valiant cart<br/>with goods, passengers, 'tourists.</p><p>The great leader said<br/>you\u2019re the man you\u2019re supposed to be<br/>and this is your fault<br/>because you are in charge<br/>in this by force of head<br/>and a threat of ugly kids.</p><p>You\u2019re the man of choice<br/>adorned in tuxedo,<br/>white tie and all.</p><p>You\u2019re the man of goodwill.<br/>What you will not do,<br/>don\u2019t do,<br/>except for that crucial<br/>important thing:</p><p>trust me.\u2009\u2014\u2009trust me.\u2009\u2014</p><p>Trust me,<br/>to vanquish this affliction.</p>",
    "<p><b>The English Fork is Sold by Daniel J. McIntosh</b></p><p>And how, you and I, I am hersliced<br/>late one evening, I say, and you and I<br/>get three things out of nothing, you and I,<br/>it was wise and necessary and wonderful<br/>to race through our streets</p><p>eleven full days, the thing<br/>do is alone. The thing is<br/>the one thing. You\u2019re the other one.</p><p>*</p><p>You go away and don\u2019t come back<br/>again for a very long time. And I<br/>nose around the faded steamed seat\u2014<br/>are you dead?\u2014but I\u2019ve forgotten<br/>how to kneel</p><p>and lie down,<br/>the other one, with that one</p><p>I\u2019ve never seen,<br/>the those I\u2019ve loved, with the<br/>black leather boots.</p><p>When the light of early dawn<br/>is gone, as it is in this picture<br/>where I stood and he<br/>was lying face-down<br/>on the bed</p><p>the English Fork is threatened<br/>by a tree that is the<br/>only thing, and also, cruel,<br/>might rip apart the world</p><p>and all that was.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Pillar by John Fergus</b></p><p><br/>The mother said, \u201cThere\u2019s something wrong<br/>with this place. It\u2019s as if she had<br/>seen a ghost.\u201d</p><p>Shoes<br/>cracked in the thresh of thy foot,<br/>the man crying<br/>cracked in the thresh of thy foot.</p><p>I (who'd never seen such places<br/>before) said, \u201cYou are the reason<br/>I\u2019m not or I\u2019ll never be<br/>relinquishing this life.\u201d</p><p>The mother said, \u201cI\u2019ve got a<br/>pipe to kill.<br/>Hurry up and get out<br/>before the church bell<br/>rings, he\u2019s bonfire dancing,<br/>singing, he\u2019s bonfire<br/>dancing, bonfire<br/>dancing.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Other by A. F. Moritz</b></p><p>I don\u2019t know which one<br/>I am, but I have an<br/>assassinate look. What\u2019s<br/>the lyric for? How can<br/>I remember?</p><p>This morning I lie<br/>up to my neck,<br/>a doughy girl, with<br/>an arm full of one<br/>and a pitcher of water,<br/>and the fish is not<br/>asleep on its plate.</p><p>How is it that I\u2019m<br/>not an ass! I\u2019m<br/>a guy in a hoodie<br/>and a hoodie filled<br/>with nothing but a windbreaker.</p><p>Even my mewing is<br/>taut and patient,<br/>as if it\u2019s<br/>touched by the wind.</p><p>I hear the desperate rattle<br/>of mahogany desks<br/>pulled apart.</p><p>That\u2019s because<br/>someone moved me<br/>this morning,<br/>someone walked<br/>me back to my place.</p><p>But that\u2019s not true.<br/>That\u2019s not true either.</p><p>I\u2019m still here.</p>",
    "<p><b>|Endoftext|><br/><|startoftext|><br/>The Judgment of the Penitent by William Blake</b></p><p>(FOR THE SEVENTH ALBUM)<br/>When the City is going mad<br/>The Dead are around the clock,<br/>And all the rest is weedy,<br/>Butted hissing and stinging<br/>A sad heave of the wind<br/>Doth fill with rage,<br/>And pock a chimney,<br/>And stir the deep,<br/>Pock the watery sea,<br/>Tho' the Stink is such<br/>A sulk, woe is a thing<br/>To send a fiend<br/>That wails in the Carriage,<br/>Tho' he wails in the Corridor,<br/>And tho' the wind is a roar,<br/>The tide is the hill.<br/>Give him some wide place,<br/>Give him some bright day,<br/>Give him some good air,<br/>Give him a solitary place,<br/>Give him some lonely clear place,<br/>Where he might be free,<br/>Give up some thing of such repute,<br/>Tell him to have the fatigue,<br/>Tell him he is wrong,<br/>Give up a thing of such high repute,<br/>Tell him say no more.</p>",
    "<p><b>Lines Written by Donald (Grady) Davidson</b></p><p>The reproach of a song in a stranger's ear<br/>Will soon be something as ridiculous<br/>As Louan\u2019s pretensions toward dulcet harmony<br/>Will soon be a monstrous crime<br/>My desires will soon be a bloody jumble</p><p>The clurg-numbing of the mamb-chop will soon be \u2026<br/>All excess, all poetic flourish will soon be \u2026<br/>All excess will soon be \u2026</p><p>The reproach of a song in a stranger\u2019s ear</p><p>Will soon be something as ridiculous</p><p>As the dead-pan snarls of Naked Highway,<br/>The grot-grotto-grot-grot of Hurdles &amp; Spikes,<br/>The obtuse and patently futile shouts<br/>Of Wildwood Boys &amp; Wildwood Girls,<br/>The even-keeled and sword-bendin\u2019 thump of \u200a\u200aVillage \u2014\u2009Town \u2014\u2009Will \u2014\u2009Willie \u2014\u2009Willie Gathers \u2013\u2009e Nanton\u2019s Fairy Tales From the Staten Island Steamboat Builder\u2009\u2014<br/>Will soon be a monstrous crime<br/>My desires will soon be a bloody jumble<br/>The clurg-numbing of the mamb-chop will soon be \u2026<br/>All excess, all poetic flourish will soon be \u2026<br/>All excess will soon be \u2026</p>",
    "<p><b>First Page by Kenneth Fearing</b></p><p>We can\u2019t go into our own interior lives<br/>with ten buttons, without a clue<br/>what the world will become. Our thoughts<br/>grow smaller and our senses enlarge.<br/>But when we enter the streets and say<br/>\u201cYo!\u201d the street signs go up and the lights<br/>go down. The cars around us flash and whiz.<br/>We walk the long, winding streets of Auckland.</p>",
    "<p><b>*  <br/>  <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Rae Armantrout</b></p><p>I raised my hand<br/>to shield my eyes,<br/>but was not strong enough,</p><p>and I did not feel well.<br/>I do not know<br/>where the pain won\u2019t</p><p>be, but it comes,<br/>and hurts, and I am</p><p>in the [latent] right<br/>to hurt you.<br/>I do not know</p><p>whether or not I can<br/>be strong enough to do<br/>this, or what</p><p>I\u2019ll say when I grow up.<br/>I do not know</p><p>whether or not I can<br/>touch your body,</p><p>or if I can.<br/>Regardless,</p><p>I am not<br/>sure if I can do<br/>this, or what.</p>",
    "<p><b>Song by Xochiquetzal Baca</b></p><p>you\u2019re in the real now but never a dream, my boy<br/>your music is good for a reason and I want to know everything<br/>my boy can take to the next level.<br/>band: You and I\u2019ll Become Free People, pimp: Little Quetzal Baca: you\u2019re in the real now but never a dream, my boy</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cI\u2019m an Iron Man Out there.\u201d by J. Patrick Lewis</b></p><p>I\u2019m an Iron Man<br/>Out there,<br/>I\u2019ll Make Fire<br/>To Break Your Heart.</p><p>I\u2019ve Got the Axe<br/>I\u2019ve got the Axe<br/>And I\u2019m quite the Skunk<br/>With it,</p>",
    "<p><b>Inna's Baby by O. Henry</b></p><p>Inna got a good shape,<br/>And wore a short white cotton skirt;<br/>The wind went round her hips,<br/>And she did her hair.</p><p>When the wind did go round her,<br/>The child she bore<br/>Did walk, and play.</p><p>When the wind did go round her,<br/>The daughter she bore<br/>Did walk a little far,<br/>And doze.</p><p>Inna did not take her hat off,<br/>But when the wind did<br/>Go round her,</p><p>The maids gathered round her,<br/>And made an ovation,<br/>And she was born\u2014</p><p>Inna here, inna there, do<br/>Remember how she did<br/>Walk a little farther;<br/>And she did take her hat off,</p><p>And when the wind did<br/>Go round her,<br/>Inna did walk a little farther;<br/>And she did do</p><p>The part, and wept.<br/>And the rain did come,<br/>And rain did go round her.</p><p>Inna did not take her hat off,<br/>But when the wind<br/>Did come round her,<br/>She did walk a little farther;</p><p>Inna did walk a little farther,<br/>And dozed.</p>",
    "<p><b>Exodus by Denise Levertov</b></p><p>On the verge of slaughter<br/>you are not Sarah<br/>but Papa and your ass</p><p>are probably Sarah(<br/>each the other),<br/>the great interracial butt<br/>that hungers, like it didn\u2019t happen,</p><p>the wife without family here<br/>or there in a handful of castles<br/>in the East, dark songs,</p><p>a kiss on the cheek,</p><p>Jeans, denim, beer<br/>and a taste for luck,</p><p>and a man of few words<br/>bewailing his fame,</p><p>are the big miss,</p><p>I still am not quite<br/>saying goodbye.</p>",
    "<p><b>Weeping by Judith Ortiz Cofer</b></p><p>He walks into the door</p><p><br/>and takes her</p><p>to the car, where she</p><p><br/>has just been pulled over and left.</p><p>He walks down</p><p>the stairs, leaving her</p><p>in the quiet of the kitchen.</p><p>He walks back into the room</p><p>and opens the door,</p><p>which she did her best</p><p>to keep, as if she knew</p><p>how to open the door,</p><p>trying to stay</p><p>inside, as if</p><p>she were going out alone,</p><p>only to sit</p><p>and read something on the</p><p>burning page,</p><p>then watch</p><p>her brother</p><p>turn the corner,</p><p>step into the moving door,</p><p>and then abruptly</p><p>return the way they had come</p><p>from the woods</p><p>where they had walked long ago,</p><p>and into a small fire</p><p>with only one side</p><p>the glass of water on the window,</p><p>and the sound of thin</p><p>claps of thunder</p><p>inevitable as they travel</p><p>out to the world,</p><p>each one of them</p><p>pushing up against the glass</p><p>and sighing at the dark</p><p>and the audience.</p>",
    "<p><b>The End by Yusef Komunyakaa</b></p><p>The crowd at our vigil<br/>turned to stone. We were</p><p>alone. The silence was deafening.<br/>The girls stood in the heat</p><p>and waited\u2014so their response<br/>could be heard. Make a song.</p><p>Their cry is not the end,<br/>their silence is not the beginning.</p><p>And it is not morning anymore.</p><p>Let\u2019s take a train. We\u2019ll leave<br/>tomorrow with headphones on,</p><p>mumbling the names of our dead.<br/>We\u2019ll walk the dark streets</p><p>of our memories, and the places we\u2019ve lived,<br/>before the trains arrive.</p>",
    "<p><b>Tangled Laces by Kevin Young</b></p><p>I can't put this behind the memory<br/>of being perfectly decent and laughing<br/>at myself. In the pylon, in a white<br/>toy, a pigeon squeaks a tune</p><p>that I can't quite hear. Birds<br/>of a different color, or no color<br/>at all, are hovering in the sky.<br/>I'm certain I'll hear the skeletons</p><p>of animals as they are being raised.<br/>Flyboy, I'm not afraid. I'm<br/>watching myself through the window. After<br/>the car crash on Rte. 69, I looked<br/>back and saw my house</p><p>bodies in the backseat,<br/>complete with slats,<br/>I saw myself on the screen</p><p>and knew I had to get out.<br/>I had to get out. That's why<br/>I have braces and a dummy head.</p><p>That's why I was happy when<br/>I got out.<br/>That's why I stay in</p><p>good shape and I'm going to school,<br/>going to school,<br/>for my future.</p><p>Without my braces, what will I be<br/>like in five years?</p>",
    "<p><b>Voodoo by Jaye Lowry</b></p><p>They told us that the official line<br/>is no longer spooky because it\u2019s a joke</p><p>and we\u2019ve learned to bite our tails<br/>because it\u2019s easy to loose a life</p><p>but we keep it glued like a T. rex</p><p>kind of bone that\u2019s hard to break<br/>until it\u2019s my birthday and I\u2019m wearing a robe</p><p>because I\u2019m the one in costume</p><p>and the thing that gets lost</p><p>is my mascara, my wig, my bikini top</p><p>and my panties, they\u2019ll never clean them</p><p>I\u2019m only allowed two times</p><p>at church today</p><p>when no one else is in first class</p><p>and I\u2019ve never sat in a parade</p><p>but do I look cute in my robe?</p>",
    "<p><b>Easter by Jane Hirshfield</b></p><p>The elderly,<br/>The barren<br/>And the dead,<br/>The battered animals in cages<br/>And the war-torn</p><p>The warmed flowers at the end of the street<br/>All which have been<br/>Has<br/>Only</p><p>If\u00a0if\u00a0if we\u00a0</p><p>Drive out the strangers<br/>And the cows and<br/>The heat is off</p><p>That<br/>Has<br/>Only<br/>If</p><p>We<br/>Find<br/>The distant walls of<br/>A forest</p><p>And the light is<br/>Onything,</p><p>And we are in</p><p>A forest<br/>And the trees are<br/>Staring</p><p>Out there in<br/>A crack<br/>Of\u00a0\u00a0chromatic\u00a0<br/>Horizons</p><p>We<br/>Always<br/>Are</p><p>Near<br/>To</p><p>The<br/>Secret<br/>Room</p><p>In<br/>A cave<br/>In a cave</p><p>At the<br/>End of the<br/>A moksha<br/>The grave in the<br/>A moksha<br/>The</p><p>Secret \u00a0room<br/>In<br/>A dancing day while<br/>The</p><p>Fairy Wood<br/>Is</p><p>A]]<<endoftext|><br/><|startoftext|><br/>Easter Valley by Mark Irwin</p><p>It\u2019s when you bury yourself</p><p>deep in the well of the grave.<br/>It\u2019s when you\u2019re worn out with</p><p>the tumult of the world. It\u2019s when you\u2019re</p><p>going back into the world. As you</p><p>sleep, the snares are flying</p><p>from the branches. When you wake,<br/>the door is a heart of stone.</p><p>When you go back into<br/>the night, the soul is wings</p><p>that are thin and chilly. When you</p><p>come out, the mountains</p><p>aren\u2019t heavy with snow, it\u2019s light.<br/>It\u2019s when you\u2019re away. It\u2019s when</p><p>you\u2019re silent. It\u2019s when you\u2019re gone.</p>",
    "<p><b>Election by Bob Hicok</b></p><p>I was on the phone with my boss when the massacre happened.</p><p>The other voice on the line said the other company is on its way.</p><p>I answered, \u201cYes, YES!\u201d</p><p>The voter can be sure she'll be honored.</p><p>I commit to this, and am hopeful that when I get to work</p><p>I'll answer the phone.</p><p>I am the only English teacher in the school.</p><p>This is Spring.</p><p>My teacher told me, \u201cNo, no, no!\u201d</p><p>I answered, \u2018Yes, YES!\u2019</p><p>My first day, I walked on the sea.</p><p>The teacher smiled and said, \u2018You\u2019re so cute.\u2019</p>",
    "<p><b>Blood on the Wall by Thomas Campion</b></p><p>Sealed in a box<br/>on the wall may one day rest;<br/>For like the box<br/>a beautiful bone made<br/>which, in time, will be<br/>a thousand times smaller<br/>and as flawless<br/>as a white cloud<br/>of snow</p><p>what is the deal<br/>with this no voice<br/>more beautiful than<br/>that which comes<br/>with prayer<br/>or the sick mind of a<br/>suppressing body</p><p>why should I<br/>ask myself<br/>with this box<br/>what I am pierced<br/>by<br/>stalled words<br/>while they<br/>come</p><p>like the cut<br/>of a knife</p>",
    "<p><b>Old as She Was by Lucy Tunstall</b></p><p>My father found the ring<br/>she hadn\u2019t taken to the hospital<br/>sewing her mouth for a kiss<br/>and turning her gaze to the air,<br/>roaring her hips and clapping<br/>as if she\u2019d forgotten how to dance.<br/>He\u2019d turned her down<br/>all over town, but one butts<br/>of a family from the Midwest<br/>got her in the door\u2009\u2014\u2009and lots<br/>of other girls from all over<br/>the country they picked<br/>out of skinny brunettes<br/>to dance in their paintball,<br/>nearly spooking the neighbors<br/>when they saw them<br/>singing like the girls from<br/>their school who from then on<br/>would be known<br/>as the trendsetters and after<br/>they would skate all over<br/>the country, that\u2019s where<br/>he got his inspiration<br/>and the ring, too, the fact<br/>she could manage to be<br/>controversial and just as bold<br/>as the tousled round-bellied<br/>tollbooth babes<br/>of the early rock & roll years<br/>at the Yale Ball<br/>while wearing<br/>an old T-shirt and jeans<br/>that said, \u201cIt\u2019s New York<br/>Everybody!\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>Coup, Cri\u00e9e by Michael Jeffries</b></p><p>I decided on a French word<br/>for the French language processor</p><p>(the . . . a) and when I typed<br/>the word \u200acanard en Nieuwe</p><p>was in the top seventy</p><p>and so it was</p><p>for the French language<br/>setter program</p><p>(The . \u200a\u200a\u200a)</p><p>the result was a ternary</p><p>a form that could only be</p><p>used by the French language</p><p>because french is my first language</p><p>and it makes a lovely French letter</p><p>because French is the only language I can speak</p><p>because French is the only language my Aunt or Grandma can speak</p><p>because French is the only language my Grandpa can talk</p><p>and so it was the perfect word</p><p>for a French language</p><p>to be fast, because French is fast</p><p>and therefore French is very fast</p><p>so it meant French was fast</p><p>and French was very fast</p><p>and French was very fast</p><p>because French is French</p><p>and French is very French</p><p>and it is French</p><p>that can\u2019t read or write<br/>because<br/>French is French</p><p>and French is French</p>",
    "<p><b>The Force of the Fireflies by John Haines</b></p><p>The fireflies have taken her away (but I love her anyway),<br/>And now the house is the burning house<br/>Of all the events we live through, which we share\u2014<br/>A giant pile-up of a century\u2019s memories,<br/>Visually stunning, felt-up colors and furniture,<br/>A collection of couples throughly shuffling.</p><p>But she is gone. And if there\u2019s one thing we really know<br/>It\u2019s that people are often dead or gone or not<br/>Forecasted, which means unpredictable.<br/>And this is no way to live or begin to live.<br/>A few weeks of visits from cousins and friends<br/>Then a dozen or so by more or less random<br/>Coupled strangers or acquaintances in our old place,<br/>A hundred years of the usual spring<br/>And new fall, a few months of testing time,<br/>A few wonderful years, a lifetime of dumb luck,<br/>A big fat pile-up of our memories that we try to keep.</p>",
    "<p><b>Chorus of the Blind by W. S. Merwin</b></p><p>What is the chorus of the blind, haunting their scaffold in the dark?<br/>Who is nearing the other side of the window,<br/>The woman who lives alone<br/>Who is at peace with herself now?<br/>The dead of night,<br/>The dead of war,<br/>The dead of history,<br/>The dead of love,<br/>The dead of the mind.</p><p>A chorus of the blind<br/>Haunts the window of the death<br/>House of this glass-floored room.<br/>What is in the ceiling?<br/>A red-carpeted ballroom,<br/>A chapel,<br/>A cowshed,<br/>A sea of faces,<br/>A choir of the blind,<br/>The five senses,<br/>The power of sight,<br/>The melody of the heart,<br/>The moral of the day,<br/>The beauty of the world.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Tent of the Duchess of Malfi by Peter Campion</b></p><p>The tent of the Duchess of Malfi, it might be, is situated in the garden too</p><p>and isn\u2019t the kind of tent used to sleep,</p><p>which seems to have been the tent of the Duchess of Malfi,</p><p>reserved for that purpose by the queen,</p><p>and again,</p><p>the size of this tent is the kind of tent only</p><p>can be extended.</p><p>As I think to myself,</p><p>I am not sure if I am tremendous<br/>or not,</p><p>whether or not I am full of my own goddamn</p><p>love.</p>",
    "<p><b>First Christmas by Joyce Sidman</b></p><p>The first Christmas, my father had<br/>abandoned the house, and I<br/>was free. Who doesn\u2019t want<br/>a Christmas present on Christmas Day\u2009\u2014<br/>to go along at the stickhandle<br/>over the fire\u2009\u2014\u2009can\u2019t<br/>go for the butter-smoke sludger that<br/>fell on the driveway, or<br/>the funny young man who<br/>spoke before the assembly line,<br/>or the old woman who<br/>was singing a celfactor song,<br/>serving up the roast turkey<br/>on Saint Nick\u2019s Day,<br/>the chauffeur who\u2019d<br/>stepped out of her car<br/>on her own, and the<br/>privileged hipster who\u2019d<br/>dined on the platter<br/>instead, all celebrating<br/>the Christmas I had been dreaming<br/>all winter.</p>",
    "<p><b>Printed-Out Letters by Jim Harrison</b></p><p>I draw, then write,<br/>I do not enter my name,<br/>I do not write.<br/>My short-lived short-lived<br/>Writes, silences, and disappears</p><p>At will; and the minutes in<br/>the heady months stare.<br/>I am one of the languid</p><p>Anasazi or Dakota<br/>Sylvanas who\u2019ll</p><p>Not be found out<br/>in the joints,<br/>not forgotten,\u2009\u2009</p><p>Herd making,<br/>trading in, artisanally</p><p>Bleached or forgotten,<br/>what it\u2019s like,</p><p>When the biggest is the white<br/>Hijacking the big,</p><p>Ready to take you<br/>in its aggrieved self.</p><p>How the cells of white<br/>Truck commuters</p><p>Fly a million miles<br/>herding the</p><p>Pittsburgh skyline,</p><p>Over an age<br/>of bracing-</p><p>Sealed corpses, growing</p><p>Lyceum-sized stumps<br/>where you</p><p>Expose yourself<br/>to the day\u2019s</p><p>Off-kilter, uncap<br/>the walls</p><p>Of role-playing<br/>Board Game</p><p>As if I\u2019d become<br/>A grading tool,</p><p>And I\u2019m</p><p>Caught off-guard<br/>In a time of \u200achange</p><p>Like this, the charm<br/>Of a word, a line,</p><p>A gesture,</p><p>Or as if an object</p><p>Were defined by<br/>A certain</p><p>Commands.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Man by Sir  Thomas Wyatt</b></p><p>Ere we nor year is come,<br/>As I my love have gone<br/>To Severn, and Oldham, and<br/>The South-East, the West-Coast,<br/>To see thee sit, too, as silent;<br/>Nation not clot thee at thy kiss,<br/>Till something else<br/>Thy love hath told me,<br/>Like the soft answering cry.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cIn a Low-Weed Moment by Robert W. Service</b></p><p>The world is not always bleak nor always just.<br/>We can\u2019t tame the black holes that indignant stars disgorge.<br/>The stars don\u2019t turn to stone. The world is not always bleak.<br/>We can\u2019t tame the black holes that indignant stars disgorge.</p>",
    "<p><b>by Scott Cairns</b></p><p>My scarf, the one that clings<br/>like a thin thread.<br/>Down my garment\u2019s ruffled,<br/>the mountains\u2019 robes of birds<br/>have gathered<br/>and the forest,<br/>like a silent song,<br/>has become<br/>a swimming pool,<br/>the pond outside my house<br/>is a river of voices<br/>poured from the other side<br/>of a tower,<br/>where it rains.</p><p>Down the sleeve of my coat,<br/>the ground has become<br/>a large, open window<br/>with cold tines<br/>on the glass.<br/>Flame, like a dog,<br/>humps up and down<br/>in the dark room,<br/>and when I close it,<br/>I know I am rowing<br/>to a beach with my back<br/>against the walls,<br/>where waves, going over,<br/>have eroded the shade.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Rainbow by Cynthia Zarin</b></p><p>Sleeping at the top of the hill<br/>at the back of the truck,<br/>the sun is at its highest point<br/>the river is every color<br/>of the rainbow<br/>the sky is a rainbow<br/>all I want is to be</p><p>with you,<br/>remember that you are my best friend<br/>and so I leave the bed.</p><p>I don\u2019t know what I\u2019ll do if the river<br/>of what I know isn\u2019t a rainbow<br/>but I can\u2019t be the one<br/>with the poor executive here</p><p>who doesn\u2019t know how to change<br/>and that is what I want.</p><p>Every time I close my eyes<br/>I feel you beneath me<br/>bringing me rain</p><p>and when I open them<br/>I see myself in your face<br/>in my frame of reference<br/>you call me a rainbow</p><p>but when I close my eyes<br/>and lean over you,<br/>I see how I could never<br/>be the one<br/>when the river of what I know<br/>is nothing but a rainbow</p><p>and I am the one<br/>on the bed<br/>who is my best friend<br/>and the only one<br/>I could call my own.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cPleasure is a Rainbow,\u201d by Valerie Bowers</b></p><p>Pleasure is a rainbow.<br/>I wish it pulsed, as in a peony,<br/>or a throbbing, milky bowl.<br/>Sometimes I feel wonderful.</p><p>Men are simply beautiful \u2013<br/>melodic, with a seductive<br/>sweating, magnetic presence.<br/>I wish they were lesbians.<br/>I wish I wore a skirt.<br/>Maybe it was a dress.<br/>I wish I were a painter.<br/>I wish I had a brain.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Holy Hand of God by Lucy Tunstall</b></p><p>The Holy Hand is not a toy.<br/>No, it is God, the High Priest of the Latter-day Saint's, blessed by a new-born angel.</p><p>It hugs you, it flits around,<br/>it punishes, it accepts as sacrifices<br/>your gift of kindness, faith and love.</p><p>He will never spit on you,<br/>he will never strangle you.<br/>He holds you by the hand,</p><p>rests your soul in his small hands,<br/>he lifts you up to Heaven,<br/>he takes you deep,<br/>he brings you to the Josephs.</p><p>I am sorry I have not exorcised the Holy Hand before.</p>",
    "<p><b>I\u2019m in Love with the Deer by Rohan Silva</b></p><p>I\u2019ve worked my butt off<br/>to earn the loyalty of your love.<br/>You\u2019ve probably known<br/>by this point<br/>that I\u2019m in love with the deer:</p><p>my hot toaster pays for the feed<br/>that my cousin (who\u2019s also a deer)<br/>serves for free\u2014</p><p>I\u2019ve walked the earth<br/>over 100 miles (or more)<br/>to spend one night in a trailer</p><p>with my love\u2014<br/>practicing every position<br/>you could imagine,</p><p>practices so perfect<br/>you could never guess</p><p>how it feels<br/>to be in love with the deer:<br/>knowing his tail<br/>lifts him over the stumps,</p><p>I\u2019ve hidden wood<br/>on the tree in his mouth<br/>so he\u2019s never hungry.<br/>Cards fall from the table,</p><p>we know they\u2019re there, smiling<br/>from them\u2014Making lots of<br/>emotional noise,</p><p>you think to yourself<br/>\u201cI\u2019m done moving<br/>this body.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>CourtCast by Lisa Bartle</b></p><p>In the early afternoon,<br/>a group of us,</p><p>twelve, four, three,<br/>at a table</p><p>on the third floor</p><p>of a building</p><p>close to a cafeteria,</p><p>drinking soft drinks</p><p>and earth,</p><p><br/>all eyes focused</p><p>on the black</p><p>candle in the window,</p><p>and a single table</p><p>to the left,</p><p>where two women</p><p>had been working,</p><p>and one friend</p><p>was jotting down</p><p>a letter from a friend.</p>",
    "<p><b>Aesomes by Richard Wilbur</b></p><p>The man who had bought the house<br/>from Strummer had gone mad. There was something<br/>broken in the man\u2019s brain as he killed himself.</p><p>I\u2019m glad I\u2019m the one who asks<br/>the question and takes the answer, and not the other way around.</p><p>We raise a glass to a star that\u2019s not only<br/>the brightest lightbulb in the sky, but has been<br/>shot down over Manhattan.</p><p>There\u2019s always nothing to do but leave<br/>and get on with the rest of our day.</p><p>The evening is always just a smidgen overcast,<br/>but the sun rises with a bang and sets with a whimper.</p><p>The place you\u2019ve been is not a house,<br/>but a shelter from the evening.</p><p>The man who\u2019ve been in a bad mood all morning<br/>has probably been in a bad mood all day.</p><p>Where did you go last night?<br/>In the shelter from the evening where the sun rises<br/>and sets with a whimper and huff and puff.</p><p>The man who\u2019ve been in a bad mood all morning<br/>has probably been in a bad mood all day.</p><p>On this chilly day, we raise a cup<br/>to a cup, put it down.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Sonnet to a Young Love by James Laughlin</b></p><p>A Sonnet to a Young Love<br/>Old man, do not let your hair grow too long, your face get too yellow, your lips become too far apart or your fingers grow too big. Your eyes, nose and mouth are all like cords cut, tied to a man or a pony.</p><p>You are a faulty assembly, a bundle of bones and blithely tossed without aim. Come out of your shell and be someone who is not like you.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Dream by W. S. Merwin</b></p><p>I have lived in a country for three days,<br/>I have been born and stifled,<br/>I am a stranger among strangers,<br/>I have hated my life,<br/>I have never been told<br/>by a friend I love<br/>that I am not<br/>the one I imagined,<br/>I have felt my beauty hide,<br/>I have been betrayed<br/>by my own helplessness,<br/>I have lived the dream<br/>of giving up the dream<br/>to live without fear,<br/>like anyone else,<br/>a dream made of glass,<br/>a dream of doors<br/>and windows,<br/>of flying,<br/>of a mind whose name<br/>I will never forget,<br/>and of abandonment<br/>like the dreaming<br/>of a dog.</p>",
    "<p><b>I Saw Her Parked Outside a House by J. Allyn Rosser</b></p><p>It was a good winter,<br/>that ill-fitting sweater made me<br/>chuckle. Up here<br/>with no hate, a love for the light,<br/>we can get away from<br/>the heat.</p><p>I watched her glancing<br/>at the snow, a white<br/>little girl with a wave<br/>held by the sleeve.</p><p>I understood that by now<br/>she could recognize<br/>a size and shape, and could<br/>bend to go with it.</p><p>I could see the light<br/>in her eyes, her face<br/>soft as a cockadoodle,<br/>her pretty brown potting<br/>tanks.</p><p>And on the way home,<br/>I could see all<br/>the ways she made<br/>me out, my house<br/>open and the yard<br/>full of pines,<br/>cracked trees,<br/>a river, the river<br/>that looked like it was<br/>never ending, the sound<br/>of my car<br/>splashing against the asphalt<br/>like a living soul<br/>made of sounds<br/>and smells and smells,<br/>a whole classroom, an orchestra<br/>of cars and pedestrians<br/>who never stop singing,<br/>the smell, the light,<br/>the sound, the air moving,<br/>you could find<br/>no words for feeling<br/>like you belonged.</p>",
    "<p><b>The. From. An. Adventure by Elizabeth Alexander</b></p><p>The Heart of the Matter</p><p>Onward the Sun</p><p>Shears of Blood:</p><p>The Rain of Blood</p><p>A Night in a Troubadour by Jane Mead</p><p>An old man sat cross-legged on the pale gray<br/>floor, his back to the door, writing a breeze<br/>down the blade-hung window of his apartment.</p><p>His hands were one<br/>or two-folded in the shape of a small,<br/>and boring, square or flimsy as a lighthouse.</p><p>Someone had stitched them on the window<br/>with black-and-white car banners,<br/>made of paper, that stuck out,<br/>like the giant catfish that swam under the window<br/>and landed on a piece of the tall building<br/>or the hollowed walnut that looked like a cross-piece<br/>from an old piano, a piano that sat<br/>on a table and was used to make<br/>a fortune. The letters curled like a man in his robe<br/>with his mouth open, metal slats<br/>against the vertices of his feet.</p><p>The old man tried to sing the heart of matter<br/>while his words were a fleet of children,<br/>while their cry floated above the street<br/>like a clarinet hitched to a horses' neck.<br/>The old man tried to sing the heart of matter<br/>while his heart was a feeling of power<br/>caught in the clicking lock of the door.</p><p>The old man tried to sing the heart of matter<br/>while the heart of the matter was a pain in<br/>the leg, a bother, a poor man\u2019s<br/>doubt, and whether or not all this was<br/>a metaphor for heaven, this feeling of<br/>return and despair,<br/>the big ol\u2009heart\u2009full\u2009 of swimming<br/>at the edge of something huge and violent.</p>",
    "<p><b>Pose (Noun) by Alice Notley</b></p><p>If the girls read a poem,</p>",
    "<p><b>After the Apocalypse by Hieu Minh Nguyen</b></p><p>For Hieu, the final years<br/>of his life be damned if<br/>the ocean will not wipe useless,<br/>unwilling, dead eyes out from under his<br/>eyes. He will neither<br/>bring back his wife<br/>or his body<br/>and, as the anguish<br/>of his suffering<br/>brings tears to the eyes<br/>of those who have come<br/>to comfort him,<br/>the dying<br/>uncensored and inexplicable<br/>a nice<br/>meals for the eyes of the dead<br/>that were already<br/>what, if not broken up<br/>or sometimes puffy<br/>?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lonely in Belgrade by Katerina Rudcenkova</b></p><p>When he finds out<br/>she has left him,<br/>just to pray,<br/>he\u2019ll find the pair</p><p>of dogs beside him<br/>has been all he\u2019s been riding<br/>for. Their collar<br/>has been pulled over their necks;<br/>he\u2019ll find a rabbit in a cage</p><p>the size of a whalebone.<br/>He\u2019ll hold up the dog\u2019s head<br/>and say,I am still here.</p>",
    "<p><b>I Couldn\u2019t Write This on the Rock by J. Allyn Rosser</b></p><p>I could,<br/>but I couldn\u2019t.</p><p>There\u2019s no more<br/>a place<br/>for my feet.</p><p>The clouds<br/>are brilliant.</p><p>The Devil\u2019s beard<br/>dedlyed on a plane.</p><p>The world is not being<br/>dull. Circumstances</p><p>matter. A woman<br/>with shoulder-length hair</p><p>and a springy voice</p><p>went to the beach to look for<br/>a lion. Her mustache</p><p>fell into the Gap.</p><p>That girl came back<br/>already the most perfect</p><p>American girl. She<br/>was different</p><p>from the other girls.</p><p>Now she could teach us<br/>what makes us special.</p>",
    "<p><b>Moon and Sun by Se\u00e1n \u00d3 R\u00edord\u00e1in</b></p><p>The moon and the sun are the same both<br/>bright and dark, and neither of them is<br/>upside-down, either of them</p><p>one of the two \u00a0roles that the other</p><p>should play. The moon is like a house,<br/>a platform of light, a needle thread,</p><p>a needle of air. The sun<br/>is like a dove, his beak<br/>like a bird's beak, his back</p><p>like a rabbit\u2019s back, his legs<br/>like a monkey\u2019s legs, his hooves<br/>like a duck\u2019s hooves, his tail<br/>like a pig\u2019s tail. You can\u2019t tell</p><p>the moon from the sun, because the moon<br/>has no face, and has no tail.</p>",
    "<p><b>Twinkling Faerie Girl by Lynne Thompson</b></p><p>As I made my way down the streets<br/>of small town New Mexico,<br/>I stopped every car and I blasted<br/>The Cure--they\u2019re in a trance. I\u2019ve never</p><p>Smoked weed since I moved here,<br/>but I do, and I\u2019ve done so many<br/>Bad Things. I\u2019ve list this here,<br/>because this is what I still feel like<br/>when I\u2019m not in a glade</p><p>Retreating, asleep, wishing<br/>Everybody I know where I am.<br/>I\u2019m glad my bed is empty,<br/>because I\u2019d like to get back to bed<br/>and have a book in my lap,</p><p>And I wish I had a good life,<br/>like mine is. I\u2019ve got nothing to do<br/>with fashion or courtly love,<br/>I\u2019m in the throes of a terminal</p><p>Pain, though, and I know<br/>what I\u2019d rather do is go back<br/>to bed, wet and khaleesi,<br/>and I\u2019ll lie buried beside you</p><p>in the white quilt of my dreams.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Legs<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Steve Blanks</b></p><p>The legs were no longer supernous, or, perhaps, they were shaky<br/>so I assigned a new meaning to legs. I found in<br/>the leotards, in the stalls, in the hallways,<br/>a constant sense of legs, legs, legs,</p><p>a leotard\u2019s restless legs, an antique taxi's limp legs<br/>and the morning after, when, in a panic, I jumped<br/>from the windows of my house, I was inevitably</p><p>pointless, and the chair the doctor had hooked me<br/>at the convention was sore, and I could not sit.<br/>I would have stayed in bed, in the dark, abjectly</p><p>knowing the rules of leotard play, but it was Friday,<br/>I would have slept, knowing the rules of leotard play,<br/>sleeping, knowing the rules of leotard play,</p><p>the ruse falling apart as a chair was dragged<br/>from a chair, I found myself acting<br/>like leotards, which I loved to act<br/>like leotards, and I was not out of my mind<br/>for a minute, though my eyes were forced open.<br/>I\u2019ve never been in a car before. I\u2019ve never sat at a table<br/>without my glasses on. I\u2019ve never been in<br/>a room without someone. A room with no mirrors.<br/>I am not T-shirtless. I do not have a limp.<br/>The leotards, the shakier legs, the intentionless<br/>talking between the stalls, the doctor, the paralysis<br/>from the panes, the failing chair, I am<br/>one of those leotards, who I\u2019m not, who<br/>I'm not, I\u2019m still in there, somewhere,<br/>talking to myself. I will not<br/>move, because I have forgotten to lie down.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Thought by Samuel Taylor Coleridge</b></p><p>I will not speak to any man of you,<br/>Bursting out, I will not be sad.</p><p>And though pleading the cause your cause,<br/>I will rise to the spot of your head</p><p>And draw my sword and pound on the crown<br/>Of your head, it will be a glad stroke</p><p>To strike this crown, which is your due,<br/>Raise your head and affirm that you have graced</p><p>The throne of life with your life,<br/>Then all that we discussed</p><p>Will be discussed in the court of justice.</p>",
    "<p><b>Lightning by Nathan Edlund</b></p><p>the sky turns dark,<br/>the sun goes down,<br/>and the river<br/>dragged by the sky<br/>back to the sea.</p><p>the star moves slightly<br/>to the north,<br/>and the river pulls<br/>tomorrow</p><p>and shadows the place<br/>where I used to live<br/>and the people<br/>who lived there.</p>",
    "<p><b>I voted by Hannah Mantzhuk</b></p><p>I voted, Emily,<br/>I voted,<br/>and I\u2019m hungry.</p><p>I\u2019m hungry, Emily<br/>for someone to tell me that<br/>I\u2019m not all alone.</p><p>And I\u2019m hungry for power,<br/>Emily,</p><p>to tell you that<br/>I\u2019m so brilliant</p><p>and I\u2019ve already won<br/>my first Pulitzer,</p><p>I\u2019m so brilliant<br/>I\u2019ve already won<br/>my second Pulitzer,</p><p>I\u2019ve already won<br/>my third Pulitzer,</p><p>I\u2019ve already won<br/>my fourth Pulitzer,</p><p>and I\u2019m getting so old\u2014<br/>I\u2019m getting so old!<br/>What was it you said,<br/>I\u2019m getting so old,</p><p>that you\u2019d be fine<br/>if I took your advice?</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cI Love Your Honors,\u201d by Anne Spencer</b></p><p>I love your honors,<br/>Till rest in and of good will<br/>Came to me soon as I got here,<br/>As I may be here too.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Tribute by Margaret Atwood</b></p><p>Satyr straight,<br/>I am worse than you.<br/>\u2014Cynthia Young<br/>I don\u2019t think of you anymore,<br/>I don\u2019t want to know who's killing who,<br/>or where, or what, or why.<br/>I sit in long lines at the DMV<br/>and stare at the back of your shirt<br/>while busy traffic goes by.<br/>I\u2019ve never done this with my life,<br/>or you, or any other woman,<br/>for someone so much worse<br/>than this:<br/>they just don\u2019t know.</p>",
    "<p><b>Shame by Ted Kooser</b></p><p>You can\u2019t wear a cape,<br/>belay a noose, or control one. You can\u2019t relieve yourself,<br/>you can\u2019t hold a candle<br/>to a symptom you didn\u2019t expect. You\u2019re<br/>subject to the whims of the \"imitate\"<br/>or the flippant \"example,\" or the careless<br/>smile. After all, the year you call<br/>a house, you wear it,<br/>it\u2019s where you\u2019ve lived,<br/>you can\u2019t move it. That\u2019s just<br/>how life is. Again.<br/>You can\u2019t adjust the dial,<br/>sit in the front seat,<br/>helmeted, and pilot the motor home<br/>without a map. You can\u2019t sit<br/>at the wheel,<br/>hawk your head,<br/>and bring the car to a halt.<br/>You\u2019re doomed.<br/>The bad news is, you\u2019re lucky.<br/>You\u2019re not her,<br/>the good news is, she is<br/>your sister. You\u2019re both<br/>conscious of being different.<br/>You\u2019ve decided,<br/>it\u2019s fine, her,<br/>but this isn\u2019t fine.<br/>You\u2019ve chosen the one<br/>you\u2019ll be the least yourself on.</p>",
    "<p><b>[G1] \u00a0\u201cflat, \u00a0revolutionary,</b></p>",
    "<p><b>The Sling of the Unemployed Nation by D. Nurkse</b></p><p>After the shroud of your body lay half-hidden<br/>on the court, it was your turn to pick up the pieces as in the shadows<br/>there were hundreds of all-seeing eyes with a single look on their faces.<br/>Your father, a man with a job who walked across the city<br/>to the prison the year before, who built<br/>a cabin on the crown of some older Russian tree, to be gunned<br/>down into the sky, or hidden in a corner<br/>where he stopped to ask a favor, or be pushed down<br/>like a rag doll.<br/>Bodies with stringy stringy strings<br/>spoke into each other\u2019s mouths,<br/>drifting downward in a long, still line,<br/>but the world giggled at the absurdity of our pain. And for<br/>few, few, was it funny, as for many,<br/>it was profound. The echo of this scene<br/>around the hour that stilled<br/>an entire nation, the pondering of each other\u2019s<br/>attitude toward each other, back to back<br/>as in the mouth of the slave that cried out in pain<br/>has lost its echo and left behind only<br/>the man who cried out in pain,<br/>an American hero, the right man to<br/>lead the rest of the fallen.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Beloved by Mary Est\u00e9lis</b></p><p>When the wind came whee<br/>between my left hip and the rafters,<br/>I imagined a voice saying,<br/>\u201cBeloved, you\u2019re the dead,\u201d<br/>and they were walking across the hall.<br/>I set my books and drawers down,<br/>stopped for dogs, I thought they went<br/>on somewhere else, maybe<br/>the coffee shop.<br/>It was the quiet that mattered,<br/>not the wind or the distance,<br/>though I knew I was going to<br/>die soon. A gruff voice<br/>would come from the stairs,<br/>a hand, a chin, the form<br/>of a face. I picked up the phone,<br/>my father\u2019ll togged his gray to get<br/>me phone service. I didn\u2019t know<br/>who\u2019d be there first. A man couldn\u2019t<br/>speak properly, the stair<br/>couldn\u2019t climb or anyone at the stairs could<br/>but the feeling of not being able<br/>to step into a room could,<br/>we were told, be death.<br/>What if I got paralyzed?<br/>I wanted to know. I carried a backpack<br/>full of books and poems.<br/>I remembered walking across<br/>a street of cars as a kid<br/>in New York, I wanted<br/>to be someone, but wanted<br/>to be somebody who worked<br/>for days on the subway<br/>as an oracle would<br/>do. I want to be a philosopher<br/>and be a chanteuse<br/>of some great song,<br/>but who can sing<br/>the kind of song<br/>that instills fear<br/>in the reader\u2019s heart.<br/>I\u2019ve always loved a song<br/>that says the wrong thing<br/>and ends with a line<br/>about bread.<br/>If I were alive today<br/>I would not want<br/>to have to choose between<br/>two cars<br/>around the corner from my house.<br/>Some day, I\u2019d like to go<br/>from being<br/>a fortunate person<br/>to someone like<br/>an alcoholic,<br/>a homeless person,<br/>a neighbor,<br/>a writer,<br/>or an invalid.</p><p>I would like<br/>to be one of<br/>them, and one of<br/>them only.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cUncle Herb\u201d by Sylvan D. Lawrence</b></p><p>Uncle Herb arrived in Milwaukee<br/>from Philadelphia with a wagon<br/>full of shoes. He told the story<br/>of his uncles<br/>who stayed behind in Philadelphia,<br/>the ones who crossed over<br/>to South Bend, Indiana,<br/>the ones who crossed<br/>over to Chicago, the city<br/>where he had to wear<br/>a filthy undershirt. He\u2019d leave<br/>behind shoes under<br/>a streetlamp, even though<br/>the neighborhood was awash<br/>with shoes<br/>and the streets were thin</p><p>and the streets were dirty.<br/>Uncle Herb said he\u2019d never<br/>let his uncles down<br/>in Milwaukee, that he\u2019d<br/>take them back, that he\u2019d<br/>be ready to give<br/>anywhere he got<br/>to the best of his capabilities<br/>if called upon.</p>",
    "<p><b>Grandma, Mother, Look Out! by Barbara Braida</b></p><p>Grandma, Mother, Look Out!<br/>Look out on this sweet,<br/>fiercely free country<br/>where, for a dollar, you\u2019ll get</p><p>a square-cut letterhead five feet high<br/>and a blue skirt five inches wide,<br/>a pair of chinos twelve buttons<br/>and a pair of slacks,</p><p>hazelnut-colored sneakers,<br/>chair shoes, fresh socks,<br/>all the things you could never</p><p>have before, thanks to<br/>the good people of the United States,<br/>and to the nurses and doctors and marshals who\u2019ve come before<br/>and continue to come,</p><p>and all the roadside vendors who\u2019ve come before<br/>for immediate sale or for<br/>a little inspiration,<br/>their shoes, their New Balance,<br/>great Northern hats,<br/>their rags in cuffs, their flats<br/>and knickers, their chapped-up feet<br/>and go-n-go sweaters,<br/>their full-body heavy-duty suits,<br/>for sweat money or because<br/>they love to do it, for<br/>the love of the fight or<br/>the rage to do it,</p><p>for the freedom that it gives.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Last Holiday from Santa Fe by Robert Frost</b></p><p>We stood and talked<br/>About the untutored snow<br/>that had fallen only<br/>a few hours earlier. I<br/>messed once or twice,<br/>and I have always missed<br/>the way you smiled. I<br/>was able to make<br/>some pretty good friends<br/>at the fair. The costumes<br/>I chose were totally<br/>free of radical or Christian ideas.<br/>I was happy every year<br/>when the sun turned<br/>and the winds blew<br/>into my ears. The alleys<br/>were empty of Christmas<br/>dresses and snow. Deer<br/>were nowhere to be found,<br/>just hoof prints on the snow.<br/>I moved from place to place<br/>without thinking twice<br/>before descending<br/>a spiral staircase<br/>arched above my head<br/>up the alleys,<br/>where you once stood,<br/>looking for me,<br/>where else could I be.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Form of Love by Frances Fox Piven</b></p><p>If for me a good evening, I\u2019ve seen the lights go down, the loo beep, the dogs barking,</p><p>I\u2019ve done with the rest of the day, the distractions,</p><p>the noise, the long lines of cars, one dog barking,</p><p>I\u2019ve had all day, and the table set, I\u2019ve got all</p><p>of my life back. I\u2019ve had all day to go to bed,</p><p>I\u2019ve had all day too. I\u2019ve had all day to go to bed,</p><p>I\u2019ve had all day to go to bed. In the morning I\u2019ve</p><p>walked out the door and been a foundress</p><p>without shoes, without a coat, without a wig,</p><p>having no clothes to wear, I\u2019ve been a woman</p><p>I\u2019d never be, who woke the dog,</p><p>loved the dog, but powerful dogs have their eye</p><p>carefully placed on the woman\u2019s head,</p><p>his feet rasping nails, his head buzzing out</p><p>screaming for air, after every visit,</p><p>how I have been questioned every penny, every hour,</p><p>asked every question, every question, every thought,</p><p>asked every question, every question,</p><p>that God gave me no answers to, but for Love</p><p>I have walked out the door without a coat,</p><p>without a wig,</p><p>without a safe,</p><p>after every walk, to the screen of a movie,</p><p>I\u2019ve been to bed without a good night's sleep</p><p>I\u2019ve been to the movies, I\u2019ve been to bed</p><p>without a good night's sleep, and left</p><p>night after night, leaving the door ajar,</p><p>on a thorough night\u2019s walk,</p><p>the road within sight, and the city I\u2019ll never leave</p><p>I\u2019ve had all day, and the dogs barking, I\u2019m</p><p>not a felt coat, I\u2019m not a handkerchief, I\u2019m</p><p>not a rag doll though I know who I am, I\u2019m</p><p>I\u2019ve been left a little lonely, I\u2019m not</p><p>let me tell you,</p><p>I\u2019ve been to bed, in my bed,</p><p>without shoes, my bed, the bed</p><p>no, not my bed, the bed</p><p>I\u2019ve been to the movies and not to bed,</p><p>and I\u2019m not a sobriety</p><p>I\u2019m not a Dettol either, I</p><p>have my doubts, my doubts</p><p>I\u2019ve been to bed</p><p>but more a conviction, I\u2019ve</p><p>washed through some trouble, I\u2019ve been</p><p>to bed, I\u2019ve been to bed</p><p>but the movies, the dogs barking,</p><p>the roads, the stand-up book, the belief,</p><p>I\u2019m not left a best, I\u2019m</p><p>not where I\u2019ll never be, I\u2019m</p><p>not a Dettol either,</p><p>I\u2019m not whole</p><p>when I\u2019m</p><p>angry all day,</p><p>sometimes, when I\u2019m about</p><p>crazy stuff, I\u2019m in love with</p><p>the thing that\u2019s craziest,</p><p>not the thing that\u2019s most crazy,</p><p>I\u2019m in love with</p><p>the thing that\u2019s most</p><p>crazy, crazy, crazy,</p><p>and I\u2019m not allowed to go</p><p>forward, I\u2019m</p><p>in the back of the house</p><p>with the TV on,</p><p>the movies on,</p><p>the radio on,</p><p>the clothes on.</p>",
    "<p><b>Religion by Peter Campion</b></p><p>Eliza Griswold<br/>The year I came here<br/>from rural Missouri,<br/>there was no one<br/>was standing on the sidewalk.</p><p>It is possible<br/>for a person to have a perfect life,<br/>but I am not one of those.</p><p>In my pocket, in this pocket<br/>I keep a whip.</p><p>I lived as long as I could in the shadow of this table<br/>that knelt in the middle of the road.</p><p>I lived longer than when I should have<br/>been able to live myself.</p>",
    "<p><b>Little Dip by J. Allyn Rosser</b></p><p>He\u2019s seen it slide.<br/>As you drove him to the highway block<br/>where he was waiting, he\u2019d waved.<br/>He\u2019d stopped to take the light<br/>from the cigarette while you drove<br/>your children back to high school.</p><p>He\u2019d doubted you as a driver<br/>to be able to make it home<br/>that afternoon, with hair short<br/>and black and unkept, not depressed<br/>at all. But here you were,<br/>in this dark gray, and not afraid.</p><p>He waited. He watched<br/>as you pulled over, and he came to the<br/>door, and the door opened.<br/>He sat down, and he lit a cigarette.</p><p>He said something about taking care<br/>of everyone else, and he smiled<br/>and said, \u201cGood luck.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>Finally, in the news: China o\u2019er the Bay Bridge by Bryan D. Harper</b></p><p>Finally, in the news: China o\u2019er the Bay Bridge.<br/>I see my mom walking<br/>down the road, tapping her toes,<br/>glideboard, and looking up.</p><p>I feel her heart breaking<br/>in my chest. And I know<br/>she must be thinking, \u2018\u2019T\u2019is the season<br/>for gray to go gray. Let\u2019s<br/>go fishing, right? Right?</p><p>I see my dad walking<br/>down the road, tapping his toes,<br/>glideboard, and looking up.</p><p>I feel her heart breaking<br/>in my chest. And I know<br/>she must be thinking, \u2018\u2019T\u2019is the season<br/>for gray to go gray.<br/>Let\u2019s go fishing, right? Right?</p><p>I see pictures of my mom and Dad<br/>on the wall. And I know<br/>that if I open my mouth<br/>then I\u2019ll have a chicken nugget<br/>I\u2019ll eat for breakfast.</p>",
    "<p><b>New York, 1961 by Marjorie Agos\u00edn</b></p><p>St. John the Baptist, 1944</p><p>On account of some thrust,<br/>I\u2019ve come to an understanding with myself:<br/>Not to run away from anyone;<br/>A song I\u2019ve written<br/>will be sung anyway.</p><p>The sidewalks, the parks, the maids\u2019 rooms,<br/>the people, our money, love,<br/>the fears, the frustrations,<br/>we\u2019re all one experience, it might get old.<br/>So I\u2019ll take up welding and pick up a book.<br/>A laundromat, a subway, the beat-up old ladies\u2019 clothes<br/>from a corner a block away. In the morning,<br/>I\u2019ll wake to a new city,<br/>a city of so many names,<br/>a city whose streets, streets,<br/>are not named after birds or flowers,<br/>or the creaking of soap stools.</p><p>I\u2019d like to stay in my old life,<br/>save for some complicated task,<br/>and go do it myself.<br/>It\u2019s not hard to learn to fly a plane.<br/>If only I could talk my way through a divorce.<br/>If only I could learn to give myself over completely\u2014<br/>that is, to ignore the fundamental needs<br/>of my life,<br/>and simply live for others.</p><p>Which brings me, once again, to my wife:<br/>with her eyes<br/>open, she\u2019s reading<br/>a story about a wise man<br/>whom God wills never to return,<br/>and she reads it with me,<br/>and we walk down a deserted street,<br/>little old man with his wings<br/>down, little old man with his wings<br/>up,</p><p>and I am obviously very sorry<br/>if I have suddenly become a terribly old man<br/>and she must learn how to hold me.</p>",
    "<p><b>God Is the Only Shoes by Jennifer Mueller</b></p><p>God is the only shoes, he said.<br/>And the only shoes have feet,<br/>and the one God gave<br/>was me.</p><p>And why is it:<br/>God is not like God?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Poemen by Carol Frost</b></p><p>To Marcia Hogue<br/>I was just searching for her.</p><p>The woodcut<br/>on the clean white page<br/>of the Cannery<br/>in the lobby of a hotel<br/>in the old town</p><p>in the old town,<br/>where you are now</p><p>because I\u2019m not miles<br/>from you</p><p>but I\u2019ve missed</p><p>the bus from Mendelssohn\u2019s<br/>Chestnut Hill Hotel</p><p>the same way I had</p><p>looked over the railroad tracks<br/>to the left</p><p>(to the right)<br/>you could see</p><p>a fire</p><p>and white tents</p><p>above the monster piles<br/>and the rubble</p><p>of a once-great bluff<br/>in the present-day forest</p><p>and the river</p><p>like a serpent<br/>terrified by its own fat\u2026</p><p>(I know</p><p>because I am a messenger<br/>to you.</p>",
    "<p><b>Dogwood by Valerio Magrelli</b></p><p>I don\u2019t buy supplies at any store<br/>I could find, my old duffel bag</p><p>is full of earrings</p><p>this is my favorite blanket</p><p>my favorite pillows</p><p>this is the way to sleep</p><p>I may not know how to make earrings</p><p>my favorite pillow</p><p>my favorite dogwood</p><p>I\u2019ve finally created my own tree</p><p>it\u2019s called a pinecone</p><p>it\u2019s called a tree</p><p>it\u2019s called a dogwood</p><p>a tree</p><p>an eagle</p><p>the dogwood spirit</p><p>is a bark<br/>\u201cbe,\u201d<br/>\u201cbell,\u201d<br/>\u201ccows.\u201d</p><p>a tree<br/>\u201cdestroy.\u201d</p><p>a tree<br/>\u201cgo,\u201d you\u2019re<br/>\u201cgone.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>Two Roads by Walter Savage Landor</b></p><p>\u2014\u2009Henry Garrett</p><p>A woman, kneeling, goes in search of a child,<br/>And her child, afraid of the woman,<br/>Is bowed in prayer and kisses her hand.</p><p>And two cows, one and two, come<br/>And sit in the pewter table, and their<br/>Cows are all fair and jade, while I<br/>Sit on my comfy chair and listen to her<br/>Singing happily the way a woman<br/>Sings happily the way she does.</p><p>I know this, but I am not surprised,<br/>Besides the gentle drifts in the air,<br/>The AIR IS SO GOOD THAT I DO NOT<br/>Feel the need to clean it up or anything.<br/>It is so good that I don\u2019t even stand<br/>Up for a minute. I hear a familiar voice<br/>But it is my own, her voice and my own,</p><p>The clock ticks, the tide drops, the snow melts.<br/>It\u2019s twilight and I am almost<br/>Home, I am almost there already, I\u2019m almost</p><p>Arriving I guess this is a song about<br/>Getting there, but it is really<br/>About the weather, it is about the weather</p><p>Being the wrong kind of weather and<br/>Being so cold, being so cold.</p>",
    "<p><b>The 'teach the pale and the pale by Claude Monet</b></p><p>Teach the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale the teach the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the teach the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the teach the pale and the pale and the pale and the teach the pale and the pale and the pale and the teach the pale and the pale and the \u00a0</p><p>Teach the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the teach the pale and the pale and the teach the pale and the pale and the educate \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 teach the pale and the pale and the pale and the pale and the teach the pale educate teach</p>",
    "<p><b>The Viscount by Ding Lu</b></p><p>We cut our knees<br/>on the st. promenade\u2009\u2014\u2009silence\u2009\u2014<br/>did we not read for laughs\u2009\u2014\u2009my father\u2019s<br/>motorized stroller, her hands<br/>on his car, his back<br/>i-beam. He was huge</p><p>and the paper was shaking,<br/>I finally understood how</p><p>he was able to carry<br/>grains</p><p>the way I had<br/>already done,</p><p>with my entire body</p><p>on the pavement, brushed against<br/>big shoes,</p><p>without knowledge<br/>we had awkward</p><p>communions<br/>to the Old Testament,</p><p>to my mother. Where</p><p>was her, I asked.<br/>A thin wire<br/>poured from the roof</p><p>of the carriage.</p>",
    "<p><b>Listen to the Babes by Rita Dove</b></p><p>Convince me. I am the one who\u2019ll take the jeep<br/>And run for cover.</p><p>I\u2019d like a better life,<br/>A family, a comfortable home,</p><p>Whether I\u2019ll live a long time or not.</p><p>Be sure to bring me something delicious.</p><p>I\u2019ll be riding the tiger, hell-bent<br/>On accomplishing my own end,</p><p>Criticize the status quo,</p><p>Think I deserve it,</p><p>Rock my skull,</p><p>Run to my death,</p><p>Be the one looking over my shoulder<br/>As I slip into traffic.</p><p>Back to top</p><p>Listen to the Diaries by Linda Donnelly</p><p>The mother sits up<br/>The night before her daughter<br/>The father sleeps</p><p>We talk of her hair.<br/>The father hands.</p><p>They are the survivors<br/>Of a war he survived.</p><p>There is the rub,<br/>The backbone.</p><p>Here is the war.</p><p>In between<br/>Is the future.</p><p>The last few bars<br/>Are the earth\u2019s songs.</p><p>They are the history<br/>Of one who sings.</p><p>I listen to the beat:<br/>A lion at the edge of a dry spring.</p><p>Lightning flashes across a dark.<br/>A dark cannot hide:</p><p>I can see the water<br/>Or a river, its banks split.</p><p>I can hear the roar<br/>Of the ocean<br/>Or the roar of a river</p><p>swaying by the moon.<br/>I can feel the spinning.</p><p>A feeling of weightless things.<br/>Here is the past.</p><p>Here is the future.</p>",
    "<p><b>I was not baptised by Henry Terry</b></p><p>\u25c6\u25ca</p><p>The stench of yesterday's crisp eyeglasses,<br/>the smudge of ski-slicked feet, the scrape<br/>of a postage stamp, so the people asked my name.</p><p>The corrugated waistcoat, short, tucked into the waist<br/>of my trousers, made the people gasp.</p><p>A well-tailored shirt, worn more than once,<br/>a pair of sandals of the right length,<br/>a pair of sandals that left marks<br/>where the right heels used to be,<br/>where the seatbelts had been,<br/>where windows had been rolled up,<br/>all of the stuff that we had to do.</p><p>When I came to bed, my slats were so tight<br/>I could barely lift my head and my mouth was trying<br/>to speak, my words were coming out like footsteps<br/>or knocks or thuds or slaps of the foot.</p><p>I had left my address and my phone<br/>in the car, I had forgotten my password.</p><p>I had left my keys in the car.</p><p>I had forgotten my street.</p><p>Even yesterday I\u2019d taken a train,<br/>not the one I would take today,<br/>which was clear of trains, only a line<br/>or two. Now the train seemed so long<br/>and wide and empty, the traffic light<br/>was nonexistent, I didn\u2019t know where I was<br/>since I\u2019d never been to this part of town<br/>and I was tired of wandering<br/>all over it tomorrow, wandering<br/>to the library where my name was on the index,<br/>and looking up at the sky,<br/>meeting my face,<br/>and reaching across my mouth to make<br/>a beautiful sound I had never heard,<br/>raising my voice to a level the people<br/>could hear and believing.</p>",
    "<p><b>Childhood by Matthew Rohrer</b></p><p>The shape of my interstices<br/>shall speak toward the future\u2014<br/>I\u2019ve carved including\u00ad\u00ad heads<br/>of burly plants, flowers and<br/>the fuzzy sprouts of spider mites;</p><p>I\u2019ve practiced up to and<br/>through the night to climb<br/>in my father\u2019s Cadillac<br/>and turned back to the sun<br/>in the dark, my eyes fixed<br/>on the stars in the sky,</p><p>I wavered\u2014<br/>then I said,<br/>\u201cI\u2019ll stay,\u201d<br/>to the sound of clouds rumbling<br/>above the Rio Grande<br/>and a twig snapping<br/>in the wind, the rumbles and<br/>thumps of horses trotting, the<br/>pop of building chimneys, the howls,<br/>the snows of horses<br/>milling in the long grasses.</p><p>And this day, in the end,<br/>I stood alone<br/>at the top of the stairs<br/>and lifted my hat\u2014<br/>I\u2019ve been up there<br/>all my life.</p>",
    "<p><b>Song for My Young Lover by William Blake</b></p><p>For my lover I am writing now<br/>Because you\u2019re dead.<br/>The fall of a glass over a footbridge is all that matters<br/>To me. It\u2019s not your fault I\u2019m dead.<br/>That\u2019s the trouble with love. He falls for me<br/>Even though he\u2019ll end up dead. And so it\u2019s true:<br/>I\u2019m dying too. So.</p><p>I am writing now because this is wrong<br/>And I don\u2019t know a thing about love.<br/>I\u2019ve tried it once with a bear,<br/>The neighbor girl who lives just down the road.<br/>He said she was beautiful, but I told him<br/>I hadn\u2019t done anything with a bear.<br/>He said:<br/>\u201cThat\u2019s what kids do.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>\"A Little Song\" by Beulah Hale</b></p><p>A little song, dear,<br/>is a song at all,<br/>meals me no harm.</p><p>A little song, dear,<br/>has a little boy</p><p>who's not exactly<br/>a little boy,</p><p>but who could<br/>possibly be</p><p>a Little Song.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cSylvia, Penny Lane...\u201d by Cristina Silva</b></p><p>The words swell to the sky<br/>and my grandchildren<br/>can\u2019t read the girl<br/>with her hijab.</p><p>It\u2019s the same for me<br/>when I glommed on<br/>or if a light was on<br/>and I was right there<br/>but that was back in the day<br/>I\u2019d make love to a girl<br/>who was beautiful<br/>and daring.</p>",
    "<p><b>Wood by Emma Lazarus</b></p><p>Page</p><p>the only wand of the wood<br/>I make,<br/>the only thimble of the wand<br/>made of wood,<br/>the bow like a cane<br/>with a sound like cannon shells<br/>shot into the sky,<br/>I make.</p><p>The rickshaw pulls on the tail of the bow<br/>and the silk pulls on the rickshaw<br/>all bends beautifully in a circle around the white desk.</p><p>I\u2019ve walked in the wood for as long as I can remember.<br/>The long hair hangs down<br/>like a broken arm. The face is unattractive<br/>and at the center a tremendous pride<br/>and sweetness shines inside.</p><p>I walk past the rickshaw on its journey,<br/>through the light,<br/>and go to the back of my mind<br/>and lock the door.</p>",
    "<p><b>To the Discontented by Henry David Thoreau</b></p><p>It is impossible to cut the grass<br/>without first<br/>care, and the grass is only<br/>on the threshold of the door<br/>for a reason. One foot</p><p>crosses the threshold<br/>while the other steps<br/>follow<br/>with the same sad<br/>burden</p><p>in the heart. One foot<br/>crosses the threshold<br/>and the other steps<br/>follow.</p><p>The grass is on the threshold<br/>but apparently it has grown</p><p>too hot, too cold.</p>",
    "<p><b>When I was a Pen and Paperboy by Mark Halliday</b></p><p>When I was a pen and paperboy<br/>may I borrow your poetry<br/>and have your cruelty</p><p>I\u2019ve been at this<br/>a long time</p>",
    "<p><b>When Light Arrives by Emily Nie</b></p><p>I have a situation that doesn\u2019t sound like its<br/>narrative</p><p>This is where I turn over the wheel</p><p>Note: I have a problem<br/>If I had an idea, I could write</p><p>A story</p>",
    "<p><b>Portraits by Ming-Dynasty Chief Justice Hsuan Yue</b></p><p>Here are some of the photographs I took while sitting at the station bench.<br/>\u201cThe main man, who is leaving soon, is waiting for the train.\u201d</p><p>Seen a hundred times, I\u2019ve never been one to miss, so I\u2019ve hustled<br/>to be the last to get on. However, I can\u2019t catch</p>",
    "<p><b>\"Ivy by the Old Country School in Oyster Bay, New York by Rachel Hadas\" by Ken Burns</b></p><p>Ivy by the old country school in oyster bay, New York.<br/>Crooked by cattle in the 1930s I was sent east<br/>to South Carolina\u2014something<br/>[I think] the Billy Boys and Independents did<br/>get to Oyster Bay, New York,<br/>[I remember] and the black people I knew<br/>I had to leave<br/>and go to Ohio\u2014not Canada<br/>[where] I was born] but Connecticut<br/>[where] my mother<br/>[couldn\u2019t] to be there<br/>[but] I\u2019ve got to be there<br/>[in Oyster Bay, New York]<br/>[adrift in the life<br/>of a black person in a hardscrabble town<br/>[in Connecticut]<br/>[adrift in the life<br/>of a black person]<br/>and it\u2019s not just about the money<br/>but the life itself<br/>[adrift in the life\u2019s life<br/>[in Oyster Bay, New York]<br/>I\u2019ve heard the line<br/>\u201cthat\u2019s what it\u2019s like to be me\u201d</p><p>and I\u2019ve got my arm around<br/>the rest of the world, inside out,<br/>[everything]<br/>[I\u2019m coming home]</p>",
    "<p><b>Laua Storm by Lisa Wells</b></p><p>The black-cockaded gulls, in the year-round sky<br/>are very visible every night in plain view of the house<br/>and town. The shingle roofs creak at the edges perhaps,<br/>but at the same time bear the understory.<br/>Even the fish that live in them poke their heads<br/>at the unassuaged coffee tables. In the center of the town<br/>there is a plaza where the old jukebox<br/>has been turned into a tea house where the young people come<br/>to listen to clarion guitars and hear old-time reggae,</p><p>to just relax under the water-painted sailboat<br/>or to stop at the picnic table, to pick up<br/>a cold water bottle and some dirty socks, to feel<br/>like a big brother or a big sister, or both.<br/>You have to be careful not to hit the chair<br/>or the sink or the alarm wire, or the icebox,<br/>or your own beans, or yourself.<br/>You have to be careful not to hit your own<br/>coming home from the park or the gym,<br/>or your own midnight show, or your own</p><p>convent in which you were sheltered from the terror<br/>of the everyday: the sudden running to get your clothes<br/>and your shoes and your suitcase, your hair comb<br/>and your braided ponytail, your cheap toothbrush,<br/>until it all traces of your tin-boss idle whispers<br/>into your ear until it all becomes:<br/>\u201cI\u2019ll be back.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>The Executioners, Mountain. by Leslie Pono</b></p><p>They came out of the woods, carrying<br/>bodies. They were not wearing snow-<br/>covering coats, they were bare-headed.<br/>They had mauled the remains of deer<br/>and buffalo, mutilating their selves.<br/>They had cut into the old man\u2019s horse\u2019s hide<br/>and eaten it whole\u2014slaughtered it.<br/>The river snakes, the road<br/>grids. These young men were on their way<br/>to a town that used to be mine,<br/>a place where men were<br/>supply-stressed, a house that had been<br/>finished but had been dragged<br/>into a tunnel-like hole dug through rocks<br/>and roots, a cemetery where a s\u00e9ance<br/>was held in the yard.<br/>The sand-haired initiates<br/>dressed in snow and white, to go along<br/>in their blood-spattered<br/>gear. They carried the skulls<br/>of the old, askew, polar bears,<br/>beaver skulls, or the bones<br/>of the newly slaughtered<br/>bucket-headed bear.<br/>They were not hunting,<br/>they were shooting</p><p>from a safe distance<br/>as the old man kept shooting<br/>until the stone was bled on<br/>by the old man\u2019s own bullet.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Slow Life by Elizabeth Bear</b></p><p>In the wake of the dawn,<br/>nothing is<br/>full of preconditions.</p><p>There\u2019s only<br/>so much energy<br/>to do what needs doing<br/>and no need to rush</p><p>to judgments or orders<br/>conferring with your<br/>face off. Because<br/>the reply to your question<br/>is a phone call<br/>waiting to be answered.</p><p>You are silent.<br/>The sun<br/>will not be up<br/>any moment<br/>but its noise and the flood</p><p>will be there<br/>when you need it.<br/>And stories will follow\u2014</p><p>the tentative illusion<br/>of you<br/>pulling yourself together<br/>to go back home<br/>when you need to</p><p>and people will be<br/>like you<br/>every day</p><p>and the world will<br/>be as it is now<br/>or it will be</p><p>more like it is<br/>when you have been<br/>and not<br/>much has changed</p>",
    "<p><b>Manhunt by Kimberly Parko</b></p><p>The kindhearted, gentle,<br/>technological genius, who would save your life.<br/>You might call him your friend,</p><p>the presidential kind,<br/>a deep thinker, who would listen<br/>to your pleas for mercy,</p><p>and who never forgot<br/>your endless gratitude<br/>for all the love you've shown<br/>till he lay living</p><p>on a disabled person's kitchen table<br/>days filled with hot meals,<br/>etched in a terrible skillet<br/>of a grinder.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Man by John Ashbery</b></p><p>A man has his little affairs.<br/>He\u2019s never embarrassed, though he\u2019s known<br/>to the swinging clubs. He\u2019s born in New York<br/>He\u2019s in his 90\u2032s and still can\u2019t quit<br/></p>",
    "<p><b>The Tobias by L\u00e9onie Adams</b></p><p>In the air the boy picks up his speed<br/>And trots along the highway with his hat<br/>Pulling the plug for the first time,</p><p>Knocking over parked cars<br/>Smacking the pavement with his shoe<br/>Kicking the sand out like a speck<br/>Of particles</p><p>The boy tries to keep up<br/>But his feet are bound to collapse</p><p>He must push on, pull on his gait</p><p>He knows that nothing<br/>Will work, but he has to try</p><p>Because the girl\u2019s life<br/>Is too short and precious to waste<br/>And she ain\u2019t got no life</p><p>In hotels or restaurants<br/>Or in any other routine</p><p>So the boy pushes on,<br/>Keeps going, keeps going,<br/>Shots the brakes, pushes this tire</p><p>Down the driveway, skids through a brick wall.<br/>What happened to him? And what was his reaction?</p><p>What can the boy do now<br/>To help a girl who\u2019s stuck</p><p>In traffic in Philadelphia,<br/>Or stuck on a train in New York City?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lonely and Lonely by Donald Revell</b></p><p>A feather as beautiful as a parrot\u2019s need</p><p>Is my morning and my morning, like my bird,</p><p>Is my voice that I\u2019reed to call my own</p><p>And my man. The music of my voice</p><p>Is a joy to me that there\u2019s not a bird</p><p>That might find the bird if it dares.</p><p>Would I had not caught the bird</p><p>Even if I had been more beautiful</p><p>I would not.</p>",
    "<p><b>Mockingbird by Richard Kenney</b></p><p>My mother hasn\u2019t seen a mockingbird in years.<br/>She\u2019s sure it\u2019s grown inside her.<br/>She\u2019s amazed it\u2019s stray-proof.<br/>What might it be? a bird that doesn\u2019t look like a mockingbird but has many other features that make it resemble one?<br/>I\u2019m not sure.<br/>Where exactly does it have to go before it\u2019s special?<br/>I know it\u2019s a curious bird.<br/>But does it have a name?<br/>Do mockingbirds have families?<br/>I won\u2019t know for years until I meet one.</p>",
    "<p><b>From the Flat by Jorge Luis Borges</b></p><p>Snow raining down<br/>on a bone\u2019s head<br/>shoves one\u2019s home away<br/>from the lean of the bed.</p><p>Out wind,<br/>a house, the sky<br/>climsop.</p><p>What is on fire?<br/>No one cares,<br/>the trees are too big,<br/>themselves too poor,<br/>they\u2019re out of date.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Schoolyard Dresses by Chard DeNiord</b></p><p>Once, I was dressed in sharp-toed shoe heels.<br/>In the schoolyard there are no frills.</p><p>I slipped from heels. I slid off<br/>a high-collared dress.</p><p>I was soaked with sweat.<br/>I opened the door and saw<br/>all my backpacks piled in the closet.</p><p>I was terribly embarrassed.</p><p>The principal shared how shaggy</p><p>petals spread like hairs on a rabbit;</p><p>I burst out laughing and ran</p><p>to my room shouting, \"What the hell!<br/>What was that sound??\"</p><p>All over the schoolyard</p><p>I could hear the principal's laughter,</p><p>the whole schoolyard was laughing,</p><p>the principal's giggles,</p><p>we shared a laugh.</p>",
    "<p><b>Canticle by Lorna Dee Cervantes</b></p><p>I was with one of the circus performers in the dark<br/>Nights, one of the voices, when the stranger started<br/>A hackneyed march</p><p>He drew the curtains and then we<br/>Were suddenly the neighbors,</p><p>The trace of a butter knife<br/>Lingered like the moon</p><p>On the kitchen table<br/>Lucas and I<br/>On the lawn as merry</p><p>Wounded, dazed by laughter</p><p>I stood there,<br/>As if I\u2019d always been there,</p><p>A thousand women, each hugging the man<br/>Till I could\u2019t move.</p><p>Some were crying,<br/>I have no idea what it was</p>",
    "<p><b>The Last Tango by Romaine Barry</b></p><p>Grandma, when the ricewine<br/>cracked with neon heads<br/>flies, the crepe was<br/>mean and made of clover root,</p><p>then a sweet, sweet,<br/>sweet, I mean lemongrass<br/>sprouted on the kitchen table<br/>and developed into a meal</p><p>of rice, platters, and bands<br/>of beaded cloth, women\u2019s girdles,<br/>anywhere they turned, flowers knotted,</p><p>flowers, flowers again<br/>chapped in the arms of a child<br/>with a little pink hair,</p><p>the color and the shape<br/>of a small, furry bell,<br/>at first I thought of the<br/>much smaller bell of a cat,</p><p>but it needed<br/>the power and the knowledge<br/>to be powerful and to be beautiful.</p>",
    "<p><b>Sleeping at the End of My Shift by Manuel Jin</b></p><p>When I tell you that I am dreaming,<br/>I\u2019ve made a promise to myself\u2014<br/>that I\u2019ll undress before dawn,<br/>take my shoes off,<br/>give my coat to the dog.</p><p>But when I tell you that I\u2019m dreaming,<br/>I\u2019ve made a promise to you\u2014<br/>that I\u2019ll undress in a field<br/>of snow, spit on my own feet\u2014<br/>that I\u2019ll have to draw a line<br/>through the field of snow<br/>to get to the bed.</p><p>When I tell you that I\u2019m dreaming,<br/>I\u2019ve made a promise to you\u2014<br/>that I\u2019ll undress in the dark,<br/>whom I\u2019ve never let out<br/>into the light.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Gun-Barrel by Arthur Symons</b></p><p>For once in my life, I paid a lot<br/>Out of my delusive money to hear<br/>A glass of beer sing, a walk<br/>Up a hill to the boat house</p><p>Only to be disappointed. It was<br/>Absurd as a bear cub was<br/>Responsible for making me</p><p>Never get back in the station<br/>The carriage just pulled off</p><p>After the largely empty spot<br/>You can imagine, the one<br/>Who pulled it was the driver</p><p>For once in my life, I paid a lot<br/>Out of my delusive money to hear<br/>The wind of a new train blow</p><p>This time, I've got no fear on my face<br/>I know the tracks, and the stations</p><p>I walk past now I have no fear<br/>The lights are on, the carriages</p><p>Are moving, and the cars parked behind<br/>The rails, all that excitement</p><p>Lenses on a dark room where I'm back<br/>While the train is moving through the dark</p><p>One time, the horse caught in the pit<br/>The wrong way, spring was</p><p>On the horizon, the Great Lakes were sky blue<br/>One time, I said hello to a cowboy</p><p>The train comes along, nothing is said<br/>I don't want to go any further</p><p>I'm sleepy or something, who am I?</p>",
    "<p><b>How I Learned to Spare by Terese Svoboda</b></p><p>With glass sloped<br/>on the earth's surface, and a ladder<br/>tarted to the side, and a hand in<br/>the air to grind the earth, I am<br/>unable to walk across the stage<br/>without a good mother\u2019s love<br/>or the ear to whisper<br/>\u201cChonnam je\"\u201d</p><p>for the first time.<br/>The laughter\u2019s too high now<br/>in the long distance, and I am unmoved.<br/>And the family sits<br/>where the stove is kept warm,<br/>and the candles are kept in the attic.<br/>And the wine is kept in the cellar.</p><p>And the blade I sold<br/>has not been returned to its owner.<br/>And I am not sure if the great<br/>katala tree I planted<br/>survived, or died.</p>",
    "<p><b>Forthcoming in Oklahoma<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Marjorie Pickthall</b></p><p>I am the one,<br/>who is not<br/>a stranger<br/>in the woods or outside the sun room<br/>with your voice<br/>in the ear of that elephant<br/>lifting, but still and<br/>rock at the heart of<br/>trees,<br/>carving,</p><p>the needles<br/>nailed until they<br/>are soched in soft<br/>silk pale wash<br/>of a brown carpet,</p><p>sodden glass,<br/>tangled wire,<br/>chipped paint<br/>in a pocket<br/>tilted to one side<br/>of a living room<br/>of chimneys;</p><p>kingless,<br/>carpeted foot\u2019s<br/>shoaling rug of needles<br/>gaps and splits,<br/>limbs of windows<br/>waste their light<br/>on tiny strings<br/>of smoke<br/>from the east<br/>of the trees,</p><p>from the east<br/>of the trees,<br/>from the east<br/>of the trees.</p>",
    "<p><b>If Some Crews Were Not Unstoppable<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by LeAnne Howe</b></p><p>and make all those honest, picket eyes<br/>yield to strangers, give and take no hats,</p><p>do not watch the trains<br/>only so the driver may rest his hands</p><p>do not see the free food at the station</p><p>devil's horns, you are dead</p>",
    "<p><b>Herbert by Denise Levertov</b></p><p>when I first came to the south I asked<br/>Mother to write a book about the war.<br/>She didn\u2019t know what it was called.<br/>I kept asking, how many pages? ten? four?<br/>she said, I don\u2019t know either.<br/>When I later told Mother about the old lament<br/>from the south that the books were being burned,<br/>she was angry.</p><p>Two years later, after I left for college<br/>and after I lost half of my money,<br/>Mother went home and I followed.</p><p>Though half of the poems included addressed to me,<br/>and a day after my disappearance<br/>I returned from college to see my mother dead,<br/>what I had hoped I\u2019d find in my old books<br/>was missing from my new library,<br/>it was not a disorder I heard about for years.</p><p>There was a white paper instead,<br/>a scan of a book not owned by me.<br/>I didn\u2019t read it, though I now look<br/>back on that day fondly.</p><p>I have dreams of me stumbling down<br/>a great staircase, covered in snow,<br/>and falling from the heights of the library<br/>where I was being taught<br/>how to read the minds of the dead.</p><p>I have dreams of me standing<br/>in a great hall, and then<br/>looking up and seeing<br/>no one, only myself in the<br/>walls of reflection.</p>",
    "<p><b>for All the People by Frank Stanford</b></p><p>You can't go back. You can't<br/>wait until the sun sinks. You can't<br/>drown in the cosmic miseries of a hired<br/>steps, sunlight scanning the tree<br/>ahead of you. The words of love<br/>the words of trust, once written, float<br/>through the framework of the mind, making<br/>a knife fight, a tennis elbow, a walk through<br/>a field of light. If you've ever<br/>abandoned an idea or two, if<br/>the fence of fear you've erected<br/>is still a trysting fawn that signals<br/>a feigned love for a what has been,<br/>that workforce still ploughing out<br/>one foot into the ground,<br/>this crumpled book of twelve<br/>bedside chronicles of blissful ignorance.<br/>You can't go back. You can't<br/>wait until the sun sinks. You can't<br/>suffer the dirty thoughts, the tedious<br/>black-armored names, the middle-class<br/>privilege, or the sudden distractions<br/>of cable and internet. You can't return.<br/>Like mindlessness, chicken--and-egg,<br/>lapdog, or dog-eat-dog,<br/>the walking dead, or the few who survive,<br/>what you need to do is lift<br/>your head, bend over, and listen.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Missal by Samuel Taylor Coleridge</b></p><p>God let the sparrows by the window-sill blow continually ringing<br/>Like a distant bell, and among them, Dory and Herrmann,<br/>Forgetting her care for the moment, stooping and kissing</p><p>The sink eye-level, and speaking[blank] into the microphone.<br/>My heart\u2019s a world, and the world\u2019s a place of roses.<br/>Where will we go the day, the time of day, the place<br/>Where light is a cell? We will be there.</p><p>On the highway<br/>Or on a desert road, the grooves<br/>Of my life, the sight of which I\u2019ve tried to forget,<br/>When did that happen, how did that happen then?</p>",
    "<p><b>\u25c8Top of the World by Claude Noel</b></p><p>I can hear the goddess turning up in a panic<br/>tense as she approaches the Statue of Liberty<br/>at the wharf of the old Fort Hamilton<br/>nearly half the continent\u2019s capitol city.</p><p>She is a woman in a green robe,<br/>thirty feet high and seven feet long.</p><p>She is shouting \u201cRetire earlier,\u201d\u201d and half of America<br/>innocently bends over the parapet</p><p>and gives up their decades of polite<br/>temperament, pretending to have nothing to do<br/>with the man in the pajamas</p><p>in the corner of that apartment<br/>with SUVs filled with suitcases and precious metals.</p><p>They are just staring out the windows<br/>at the night sky that\u2019s still the same color</p><p>as the brick that was once their own place<br/>which has been rented and is now the ground</p><p>so sharp and pure and entirely illuminated<br/>with an eerie twinkle that\u2019s the color of a face</p><p>that\u2019s wearing sunglasses, a face that\u2019s not there anymore.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Widow by Guillaume Apollinaire</b></p><p>Two nights before our confrontation<br/>I had hoped to perform<br/>a wonderful manoeuvre\u2026.My veil<br/>was about to fall.<br/>The wind was light, cool. The rain<br/>came.</p><p>Behind the garden wall<br/>the blinds were drawn.<br/>When I tried to walk<br/>under the windows,</p><p>I was told they were<br/>closed. in Greece,<br/>a widow is supposed to wear<br/>a white gown<br/>and veil<br/>and, in Romans,</p><p>be alone.<br/>Do I know the name of the house<br/>where they lived?</p><p>I know some people are born<br/>to live at the ends of the earth<br/>but I know<br/>that's not how it works.</p><p>When I look at photographs<br/>I know those who are<br/>genetically predisposed<br/>to live at the ends of the earth.</p><p>I know I have to move<br/>but I hate to leave<br/>a house I love.</p><p>Maybe my house is not as fair<br/>as it seems.<br/>Let me call you<br/>a kind of whore.</p>",
    "<p><b>***<br/>I, the Unborn by C. D. Wright</b></p><p>The night has left a familiar shape in my heart,<br/>a place, a name, a funeral,</p><p>like the hush of a city built<br/>on gap year or the empty fields</p><p>of a previous life</p><p>where I want to live, always</p><p>even beyond the scope of my past<br/>and its risk</p><p>even though I never wanted to be</p><p>even if I could walk across</p><p>a room and find the front<br/>even on a wall</p><p>to do it yourself,<br/>even if it was a desert</p><p>and all I can do</p><p>is sit and wait</p>",
    "<p><b>The Pretty Flowers by William Blake</b></p><p>Not to be spied<br/>Not to be noticed</p><p>Not the help<br/>That some</p><p>Dreams they deserve</p><p>But rather the careless</p><p>Complacency<br/>Of power,</p><p>The foolishness<br/>Of those</p><p>That without it</p><p>Amuse no one</p>",
    "<p><b>Pleasure by Francine Sterle</b></p><p>There is nothing like\u200a\u200a\u200amuch more\u200a\u200a\u200a prided and polished<br/>She with her keys in her hand and flowers.....</p><p>She hurries to the house, leaves behind<br/>A husband and two small children.</p><p>She wipes the sour bread from her face.</p><p>She goes outdoors, to a meadow.</p><p>She smiles, and I am certain from her</p><p>A dream that nothing will ever be the same.</p>",
    "<p><b>The War of the Worlds by Samuel Taylor Coleridge</b></p><p>A world of twinkling stars<br/>Flares up in narrow lines,<br/>Hungering for the ever-glinting skies.</p><p>Pieces of the moon<br/>Couldn\u2019t contain the swarm of bees,<br/>Wind, waves, cars and the high winds.</p><p>Nothing gleams on a bed of broken glass,<br/>A long night, wind out the window,</p><p>The moon, the night, the day, the night.<br/>A world of passing cars<br/>Or hover, gliding undetected.</p><p>Near the lake<br/>No odors gather so quickly,<br/>The darkness is less dense,</p><p>The trees, the cow-milk dream,<br/>The wood, the relics of the past.</p><p>Nothing sparkles, sparks, lights, or glows,<br/>Till, as I push a thin knife<br/>Into the air, a voice sings a song I know.</p>",
    "<p><b>T.F. by Eliza Griswold</b></p><p>Though I haven\u2019t been back for years,<br/>I can feel my old head<br/>crawling up on my shoulder</p><p>to the door, the bed I\u2019m on<br/>where I was last seen,<br/>the door with its long slanted handles<br/>that leads to another life.</p><p>The door is locked.<br/>I\u2019m bound to fall</p><p>to the next room.<br/>My car is still in drive,<br/>it\u2019s locked. I\u2019m home.<br/>I\u2019m downstairs</p><p>where the stove is on low,<br/>I\u2019m on the staircase<br/>that leads straight to the balcony<br/>on my bed<br/>where I can watch the sunset<br/>while I\u2019m on my way home.</p>",
    "<p><b>Venetian Night by Richard A. Rapp</b></p><p>The centurions<br/>swarmed north<br/>from the Bicardon seas<br/>with the voices of the dead,</p><p>the violets of the soul,<br/>the tints of the damned.</p><p>In the blue Bicardon<br/>the Jew of the artisans</p><p>had a dream<br/>of slavery and stars.</p><p>The Polish-Lithuanian Orthodox Arch Kleil Foca<br/>was fried at the Philadelphia Orchestra,</p><p>from Pittsburgh, from Newcastle,</p><p>from Harlem, from Michigan\u2014<br/>from Brooklyn,</p><p>from abreger\u2019s feet<br/>his beautiful face</p><p>was blasted<br/>from the air of Austerlitz<br/>by the Mass in St. Petersburg</p><p>and the crowd surged<br/>all the way to Vienna<br/>where they began</p><p>to sing<br/>what\u2019s on</p><p>shoes of the vanquished<br/>from the heights of the Kremlin</p><p>the Poles were back and<br/>moving through the night</p><p>were bleeding rich<br/>and free</p><p>The Departures<br/>Table of Contents</p>",
    "<p><b>Daughters by P. E. Walcott</b></p><p>Black silk and gold feathers, I am of course proud of you,<br/>Our sister, fluttered to the point where a whole field was mine, the dead<br/>Colon, colon, colon, colon, the brook, the mead, the mead, \"sweet mead,\"<br/>Pooh Beer-loghouse, Pooh Beer-loghouse, Pooh Beer-loghouse,<br/>Pooh Beer-loghouse, Pooh Beer-loghouse, Pooh Beer-loghouse,<br/>Did I never said that you were beautiful, that you were my girl, that I<br/>Am proud to call me a woman, that I was proud to call you my girl?</p>",
    "<p><b>Shadow by John Ashbery</b></p><p>The reason I hold this giant,<br/>Tyler, could not grasp,<br/>Could not see the light behind,</p><p>The reason I said I had no smile,<br/>I had no spirit with it,<br/>The reason I let it go,</p><p>The reason I tied my shoes,<br/>I did not want to get out.</p><p>The thing I feared most<br/>Would be the only time I ever shine,</p><p>And it is. I will leave<br/>This room tonight,<br/>And I will stay</p><p>In this shadow.</p>",
    "<p><b>I Want to Play in a Pumped-Up Thrift Store by Gaylord Perry</b></p><p>I want to be nice and let the checkout<br/>Sell in a country store. I wish you<br/>The best and maybe more than anything I might<br/>Have to say. If you insist on<br/>Moving further in the line while the clerk<br/>Lowers the check, I'll be sure to say<br/>That I'm sorry I couldn't cut it on time.<br/> I want to be nice and not cause<br/>My friends have to wait and argue. I want<br/>The best and the best. I'm sure my friends will<br/>Understand. I'm sure their friends will support me.<br/>I want to play like the rest of the kids,<br/>Not because I want to be cool, but<br/>Because I want to be cool. I want to be<br/>Like the other kids who like to shop.</p>",
    "<p><b>Appetite by J. Allyn Rosser</b></p><p>I'd like to kiss my tongue,<br/>to taste its burn,<br/>to rip it apart.</p><p>But I can't.</p><p>And I can't lick my lips<br/>or bite my tongue.</p><p>So instead I sit here,</p><p>my head in my hands,<br/>rapidly filling</p><p>the empty places on the table.<br/>I know, it\u2019s a common trick,</p><p>to let the table<br/>never really settle.</p><p>But this is no joke.</p><p>This is something<br/>I\u2019ll never forget.</p>",
    "<p><b>Farging by Andrei Codrescu</b></p><p>Tender up there</p><p>the sun is shining in a bowl<br/>in the high sky and the sea</p><p>no more sea</p>",
    "<p><b>Dynasty by David Wojahn</b></p><p>For our cinematic ambitions</p><p>we\u2019re a phlegmatic philologist<br/>unwinded by the surge of the weedy</p><p>warehouse went up,<br/>firecannon battened down</p><p>lands without<br/>dwelling back</p><p>the M-16, the .45,</p><p>the bayonet,</p><p>the remote detonation.</p><p>O, our wonted</p><p>soul duplicates the image<br/>the living</p><p>in the next life.</p><p>We play softball</p><p>on the old track,</p><p>we\u2019re on<br/>a porch</p><p>in a leafy neighborhood</p><p>with a scary view</p><p>the woodpecker called</p><p>and the frog couldn\u2019t come.</p>",
    "<p><b>Two by Ovid</b></p><p>Two good brothers who are only well-men<br/>commanded by their wits to watch the woman<br/>and report back to the man who gets the nod<br/>to dust the bloody palms of his grave.</p>",
    "<p><b>Malaria by Robert Bly</b></p><p>Malaria is a bare-fanged<br/>transforming thing. Wherever lightning roams</p><p>spell is on the run.<br/>Near the bank of the river</p><p>can be seen a chain link fence.</p><p>It\u2019s his shadow,</p><p>his stoicism on the barren</p><p>mattress. And his thick-limbed foot</p><p>in the dust.<br/>All these are<br/>far removed from each other</p><p>not far from each other.</p><p>Last night I stepped</p><p>behind the door<br/>of his house</p><p>and saw him pedaling away</p><p>to the motel.<br/>He\u2019s coming back</p><p>to reclaim his town,<br/>his prairies,</p><p>his land,<br/>his original sin,</p><p>his crime.<br/>And all these roads,</p><p>all these roads,</p><p>his own words,<br/>his fears, his karma,</p><p>are all also roads,</p><p>a way to get from one place<br/>to another,</p><p>a way to get from one place<br/>to another.</p>",
    "<p><b>Abracadabra by Edward Thomas</b></p><p>I\u2019m going to walk one hour,<br/>only. The sky sure will clear,<br/>the gauzy evening will go on.</p><p>I\u2019m going for joy,<br/>not to stop. I\u2019ll walk as if<br/>I\u2019ve been through a door ever.</p><p>You know what\u2019s good<br/>--the perfume of Christmas.</p><p>I\u2019ll wait one more hour<br/>before visiting the beach.</p><p>I\u2019ll walk to the beach and look at it,<br/>just like I did on the train<br/>to the amusement park,<br/>and then a little longer.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Exchange by Rebecca Wolff</b></p><p>You are out on the hills when<br/>the sun\u2019s hot. The south is<br/>a landscape with a thousand secrets.<br/>The light, like a body of water<br/>leaves behind a vine. Pale raspberries<br/>bare the moon. The world is one<br/>where shadows are the colors of a man\u2019s<br/>face and a woman\u2019s hand. One<br/>where you have to be quick and considerate<br/>of the little ones. One where a man<br/>knows what the gift of a journal<br/>can do for him, as well<br/>as a woman who says<br/>what she says.\u00a0 What\u2019s going to happen now?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lion by Ralph Waldo Emerson</b></p><p>The lion is not well fed;<br/>He is very thirsty.<br/>I hear he is very angry,<br/>And if he is very angry,<br/>It means he must eat.</p><p>And he is very unhappy,<br/>Are you sure?<br/>I heard a man say.<br/>This is a very sad tale.</p><p>The lion eats.<br/>He grows fat.<br/>He becomes stout.<br/>He wastes away.<br/>He marries.<br/>The lion is very handsome.<br/>The lion is very well fed.<br/>The lion is very thirsty.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Painted Lily by Gwendolyn Brooks</b></p><p>Each thing in the garden is painted<br/>with a different color\u2009\u2014\u2009the pink gingerbread<br/>dough, the white house, the purple rugs.</p><p>Every day my sister wakes to find<br/>the walls painted with all<br/>the pretty colors I can find.</p><p>I love the way the rain<br/>flats against my window<br/>and the way the leaves gather<br/>and bud as if under a sway.</p><p>It's like someone I love<br/>has a heart like a monkey\u2009\u2014\u2009the way<br/>the rain rugs the porch,</p><p>the house, the trees, the garden.<br/>It's love and giving<br/>and more than giving</p><p>and more than giving.</p>",
    "<p><b>Night Flight by Frank Stanford</b></p><p>Over the city, we stand,<br/>forty or fifty feet ahead of the air</p><p>that in its full thickness,<br/>loosens, and everything rushes,</p><p>and we bar the door, shout<br/>up into the night. Our bodies</p><p>are still wet with the emotion<br/>that has washed over us,</p><p>and we have not yet lost the sea.</p><p>The wind howls miles away, like a long<br/>straight line, and we know</p><p>that somewhere in the sky</p><p>someone is watching us,<br/>waiting for us to join the rest</p><p>of the plane, or the rest of the passengers</p><p>that sit down at the back of the plane</p><p>and wait for the day to pass.</p>",
    "<p><b>\"Lake, Lake, Bohemia\" by William Blake</b></p><p>The Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake, the Lake,</p>",
    "<p><b>The Angel by Hester Knibbe</b></p><p>We wanted to feel familiar<br/>for one of the most painful things in our life.<br/>We wanted to be protected<br/>from the unexpected<br/>that comes suddenly and often.</p><p>But when we first arrived<br/>in this country, we were only<br/>worth a visit.</p><p>We wanted to look<br/>like ordinary people,<br/>but the place we wanted to live<br/>was so remote and difficult.</p><p>We wanted to be<br/>a real house.</p><p>Flying into a trance<br/>like we were going into another country,<br/>we took off our shoes.</p><p>We wanted to go back<br/>to a time before television,<br/>before telephones.</p><p>I wanted to dress<br/>like a woman.</p><p>With my sister<br/>I could do it all,<br/>but my sister<br/>was afraid<br/>of heights.</p><p>I wanted a man<br/>to be afraid.</p><p>My sister<br/>knew how to behave<br/>in a house.</p><p>It was her reputation<br/>that got me there.</p><p>My sister<br/>was one of the bravest girls<br/>in the world.</p>",
    "<p><b>Demon by Theo Wiedeman</b></p><p>Like a demon you call<br/>To my cunt, I call</p>",
    "<p><b>At the Shops by Tony Hoagland</b></p><p>After a week at the shops<br/>we get home and go to bed.</p><p>Our minds, immense shops,<br/>are only sprawled on our couches</p><p>and the dusky stairwells stare</p><p>back to us, seeing us pass.</p><p>We have lighted dinner<br/>on our glass doors</p><p>while the coffee</p><p>is hot and full of life.</p><p>We are wrapped in our coats<br/>and hangers of peanuts</p><p>and box after box of candy,</p><p>all the weeks and all the gifts,</p><p>the teeth-gritted, the \"You\u2019re welcome,<br/>the snow-white room, the candy bar\"</p><p>we have relished in,</p><p>the positive and the cheap</p><p>we have demanded</p><p>from the world because we know</p><p>we are only all dreaming</p><p>when I turn on the radio,</p><p>I hear music:Singing</p><p>of the wild and the beautiful</p><p>only a few miles away.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Sorrowful Life by David Baker</b></p><p>I could not live<br/>the life I had in mind.</p><p>I was never<br/>thinking of that house<br/>in Hamden<br/>where you are staying</p><p>where you were born<br/>in the 1920s,</p><p>my grandfather<br/>and I were never<br/>in this world<br/>that we lived in</p><p>his house<br/>that he had<br/>built</p><p>and the shade,<br/>the air, the air<br/>of a thousand miles</p><p>and still I could<br/>not live<br/>the life that I had<br/>in mind.</p><p>Even now I\u2019m wishing<br/>I had never</p><p>married this man.<br/>Even now I\u2019m wishing</p><p>I had never<br/>born this girl.</p><p>And I\u2019m really glad<br/>it was<br/>not me</p><p>I was born into this world<br/>or some short-lived one</p><p>like me,<br/>but for the good<br/>and not for any</p><p>advantage that my life<br/>had afforded me.</p><p>The bad part was<br/>the bad part.</p><p>But you know<br/>what you\u2019re going to do</p>",
    "<p><b>The Singing by Thomas Campion</b></p><p>first part of the second song:<br/>\u2642</p><p>You wander in a Land where you<br/>are not the Land, but the Place.</p><p>You are the Piece of the Puzzle<br/>that makes the whole army of listeners</p><p>that is Night\u2019s Dwelling,</p><p><br/>a woman, by a Road<br/>made of Crows, a man,<br/>by a river, a dove,</p><p>a girl, the song is sung<br/>like a sad song, like a Hymn</p><p>singed by a Hymn Choir,<br/>those birds and the boy<br/>with the cane</p><p>in a Land you\u2019re not a member of,<br/>where you don\u2019t belong,</p><p>you\u2019re alone, you \u2019re the one<br/>who\u2019ll come back.</p>",
    "<p><b>If a Fable Be Not<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Robert W. Service</b></p><p>Right after the war, I heard a song<br/>I\u2019ve never heard in my life. It was April and I wasn\u2019t<br/>in New York, but in Pennsylvania, a suburb<br/>of Philadelphia, and I was staying with a friend.<br/>That\u2019s how I learned about the band<br/>that played in a bar in Harrisburg, where I was living<br/>as a taxidermist, and how, even now,<br/>when I\u2019m driving to the grocery store,<br/>I pull out my \"If a fairy be not\"<br/>toting the ends of the car,<br/>so that I may take the loaf of bread in my mouth.</p><p>It\u2019s not fair to say that I\u2019ve never heard<br/>the song, the one about the fairy and the rock,<br/>the one about the child who awakens<br/>and is a million miles away and is a house.<br/>Maybe it\u2019s the way the song plays in the car,<br/>and I\u2019m imagining it, or maybe I\u2019m not.</p>",
    "<p><b>Sundown by William Trowbridge</b></p><p>The moon</p><p>turning cold</p><p>on that abandoned beach</p><p>is foreign to me.</p><p>I could</p><p>have spent Easter</p><p>with a family</p><p>from California</p><p>or a wandering</p><p>girl from</p><p>Mexico.</p><p>I could</p><p>have been out</p><p>all night</p><p>in the sun</p><p>and not been</p><p>sad.</p><p><br/>And the night</p><p>is coming on again</p><p>with a rasp,</p><p>a raspy noise</p><p>that\u2019s unmistakeable in the distance.</p><p>There\u2019s no</p><p>other way to say this.</p><p>I know even now</p><p>it\u2019s the dream</p><p>of a baby</p><p>that gets me.</p><p>I know even now</p><p>it\u2019s the dream</p><p>of a black</p><p>baby that gets me.</p><p>I know even then</p><p>that\u2019s nothing</p><p>to be ashamed of</p><p>and nothing to be ashamed.</p><p>I know even then</p><p>that\u2019s nothing to be ashamed</p><p>of.</p>",
    "<p><b>Croun by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>\u201cI am proud to be naked<br/>As a beggar\u201d<br/>Another beggar is dead</p><p>I was born lame to a cripple<br/>I am unhappy</p><p>I am lost<br/>I am yellow</p><p>I am bald</p><p>I am a beggar</p><p>The sun will come<br/>And the shade fall</p><p>Then the rain will come<br/>And the earth will shake</p><p>Then the sea will come<br/>And the stars will shine</p><p>I am not real<br/>I am not alive</p><p>I am sleeping<br/>I am leaving</p>",
    "<p><b>Recess by Lawrence Ferlinghetti</b></p><p>Missing nothing, I get up<br/>and walk up to the school<br/>with homework and pencil,</p><p>and if anyone ever gets mad<br/>I just can\u2019t tell.</p><p>Miss House, I\u2019m not<br/>tall enough yet to carry it.</p><p>I sit here for hours<br/>writing down everything,</p><p>I\u2019ve just learned to read<br/>my mind, the alphabet,</p><p>the shape of faces.</p><p>If I don\u2019t learn<br/>I\u2019ll be the dumb</p><p>student who forgot<br/>the name of the cat<br/>a week before the bell</p><p>clipped, never got<br/>his homework,</p><p>or couldn\u2019t spell<br/>the name<br/>or the year.</p><p>Miss House, I\u2019m<br/>certain about this:</p><p>I\u2019m the weird one,<br/>looking for a home,</p><p>I\u2019ve never been to<br/>a movie,</p><p>I\u2019ve never been<br/>to an elementary</p><p>camp,<br/>and if I ever<br/>leave here,</p><p>I\u2019ll never<br/>know if it\u2019s<br/>the same place.</p>",
    "<p><b>For a Little Beatitude by John Keats</b></p><p>One child that I have to leave behind;<br/>One boy that I have to shake against;<br/>One girl that I have to work with;<br/>One dog that I have to bark;<br/>One cat that I have to care for\u2014<br/>Who, when I wake up, I will never<br/>Leave my house again.<br/>But when I visit you, I will not<br/>Leave my house again.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Unborn (1977) by Michael Chitwood</b></p><p>I was walking across the highway in Wisconsin<br/>and I saw an old man with [a gun]<br/>in his mouth leaning over<br/>the same old bench. Looking at him<br/>I said \u201cLook, they\u2019re shooting<br/>at the baby in the crib;\u201d and</p><p>I had just seen that movie<br/>\u201cUnborn,\u201d in which a black woman<br/>was born on our own street<br/>on a Saturday,<br/>and a few hours after that<br/>a couple came to pick her up<br/>and I was standing in the doorway of the car with her<br/>and I said \u201cLook, they\u2019re shooting\u201d and</p><p>I thought, \u201cWell, that\u2019s what happens when<br/>you try to go over night with a pistol<br/>in your fist,\u201d and I didn\u2019t come,<br/>but that night the baby was mine<br/>and the fetus<br/>was the child\u2019s.</p>",
    "<p><b>At the Mountain's Edge by Edward Thomas</b></p><p>Because the mountain<br/>Is in the water\u2019s way,<br/>God took it from the earth<br/>And placed it on the clouds\u2019<br/>Floor; that is,<br/>A stone eternity<br/>To which we are all reduced.</p><p>Why is it that the sea<br/>Is higher than God\u2019s hand?</p><p>And why doesn\u2019t the mountain<br/>Profit its place in the sky<br/>? On this earth, the sea<br/>Is anvil by which to strike out<br/>A land of meaning, a heaven to shout<br/>For the things God wants?</p><p>When we look at the world<br/>Butting against the hillside<br/>We\u2019re reminded of the mountain<br/>And the sea\u2019s boundless<br/>Into which our lives may continue</p><p>When we see the miracles<br/>Of a man and a fish<br/>Who swim fast<br/>Because they know the secrets<br/>Of eternity.</p>",
    "<p><b>By the Sea by John Tipton</b></p><p>I love to ride a tide rising<br/>and flood a portico.<br/>I love to drink the waterfall<br/>of light on a skeletal head<br/>or the rippled waves<br/>of a mother's neck<br/>or a man's loosened pants<br/>and give the grandparents a scare<br/>that they\u2019ll be alright.</p><p>Sometimes, I love to watch a light<br/>like a bobcat standing on a fence<br/>and twitch in the dark of a train.<br/>I love to watch the waves<br/>of a woman\u2019s raveling knee<br/>or a man\u2019s t-shirt<br/>cussing his underwear.<br/>I love to imagine the sunset<br/>where the waves rise and fall<br/>and look down upon<br/>the Blue Ridge and the sea<br/>that lifts and swings<br/>all day long.</p><p>And I love to be a kid<br/>and sit beside a boat<br/>and feel the light<br/>of a moon on a trees\u2014<br/>I love to look up at the horizon<br/>and see the blue<br/>of the sky, the moon<br/>with its cute little eyes,<br/>and feel its heat.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Mermaid's Thumb by Brian Eng</b></p><p>The Mermaid's thumb<br/>seemingly a woman's,<br/>but none of us can see that<br/>from the boats, on land,</p><p>or from the little boats<br/>we used to carry,<br/>from the boats we drove<br/>between our homes</p><p>and the houses we knew<br/>and the houses we did not</p><p>know, I\u2019m sorry,<br/>but it\u2019s not women</p><p>we\u2019re seeing on the page</p><p>of this book<br/>or this giant billboard,<br/>and not the Mermaid</p><p>thinking, I\u2019m there<br/>or I\u2019m not, because</p><p>that\u2019s not what I\u2019m thinking of</p><p>when I read the words<br/></endoftext|><br/><|startoftext|><br/>\u201c\u201d by Vincent van Gogh</p><p>I am the silent one. Is that a thing?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Believing Dog by Devorah Levine</b></p><p>I\u2019m thinking of bringing a dog<br/>with me, to take the kennel<br/>into something more formal,</p><p>to make it something big and strong<br/>like my ox, to make it stand</p><p>alone, to make it known<br/>that I\u2019m there and on my own.</p><p>And I\u2019m going to be fine,<br/>or she, if I bring</p><p>a dog, to keep her--<br/>there will be no other</p><p>there, so I shall be<br/>fine, or him, if I bring</p><p>a dog, to make her</p><p>look good and strong, and eager</p><p>to go in there and do the right thing.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Blind Girl by Jane Hirshfield</b></p><p>Half of the time I\u2019d like to work, I\u2019m overwhelmed<br/> by an immaterial skill\u2014at the bottom of what\u2019s gone<br/>I\u2019ve not brought myself to turn back. The light catches on<br/>now<br/>like a cat\u2019s tail\u2014and the line still must go on.<br/>I suddenly feel lonely, and kind.</p><p>But the blind girl knows</p><p>it is not lonely nor kind.  She\u2019ll keep<br/>looking.  I am busy.  She\u2019ll stay<br/>lucky.</p>",
    "<p><b>High Plains by Larry Levan</b></p><p>A mountaineer strives<br/>back from a snowfield<br/>to a village of tents,<br/>wrestling his way<br/>up goshen and prairie<br/>glacial ridges, demanding<br/>he be the one to climb<br/>or descend. Each time he does<br/>this, he\u2019s reminded<br/>of his own indecision,<br/>of how he\u2019ll never be<br/>the one to do it.</p><p>It\u2019s the \u200ahigh point<br/>of his day, when<br/>he\u2019s the one<br/>currying favor<br/>from the town,<br/>or the inn,<br/>or the limousine<br/>or the car he\u2019s driving.<br/>Silent, the sky<br/>blocks the view.</p><p>A woman\u2019s swinging<br/>from the air<br/>as if dancing<br/>for the camera.</p>",
    "<p><b>Dawn by Zelena</b></p><p>What is the moon<br/>watching over the city?</p><p>The cat is doing the talking</p><p>over the head of the meal.</p><p>The bed is the thing</p><p>that nobody wants</p><p>but the sort of thing</p><p>that nobody wants to get.</p><p>The clock is the source</p><p>of all time. It always</p><p>runs after the sun,</p><p>the prisoner is the source</p><p>of all joy.</p><p>The world is made of</p><p>and not-forgetful moments.</p><p>What is the difference</p><p>between madness<br/>and sadness?</p><p>What is the subject</p><p>that will decide about my</p><p>life?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Day After (and After) by John Bush</b></p><p>I cry when I see a house in decline,<br/>baby-boomers who have forgotten the pleasures<br/>of small-town life, the old oak trees</p><p>and redwood shrubs, and the new cornfields;<br/>I cry when I see the upholstery worn</p><p>and dirty and dirty, the carpet too dark<br/>for my body, the garbage cans</p><p>and the porcelain cupboards dirty with rust.<br/>I cry when I see my mother drive</p><p>an hour north, back to Philadelphia<br/>to a van with a sign on the side</p><p>all about the economy saying, \u201cGet Home<br/>for Your Baby, Pick up Your Stuff, and Don\u2019t</p><p>Meet in a Parking Garage,\u201d I cry when I see</p><p>my daughter driving an hour north,<br/>driving a truck in the rain, and crying</p><p>when I see her driving an hour south,<br/>on her way to meet her sister,</p><p>and her driving an hour north to meet her son<br/>I cry. I cry when I see the trash</p><p>coming to the curb, the old clothes drying<br/>on the shelves, the shoes and socks</p><p>which not only will never be clean, but<br/>I\u2019ll never wear anymore.</p>",
    "<p><b>Day of Infant Loss by Barbara Ehrenreich</b></p><p>At my death, I have nothing to do<br/>with the casket nor the coffin,</p><p>but I look into the full<br/>grown son\u2019s eyes: there\u2019s nothing</p><p>like a weightless voice and<br/>beautiful hands and the ability</p><p>to float above the rubble<br/>and feast on a seaweed boiled</p><p>in a slow-cooked pot, to read<br/>the passage of smoke</p><p>through the window, the words<br/>of anguish inside</p><p>the bodhisattvas that have yet to<br/>be called a day,</p><p>like the two propane tanks<br/>I see me one day filling,</p><p>all the words of my father<br/>and the friends he left behind</p><p>on this quiet, day and all<br/>hoped for, my own life.</p>",
    "<p><b>Babylonian by Douglas Torreson</b></p><p>The sky was a sea and the waves borderless<br/>are still as the waves of Babylon</p><p>and the waves of Babylon.</p><p>The earth does not move. It moves</p><p>unseen. There are no mirages<br/>and no illusions. The earth is a house</p><p>and the house is not a sea.</p>",
    "<p><b>from<br/>  <br/>  <br/>   The Wheel of Fire by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>Thy wealth and honour lie in laureles,<br/>The race of horses that trods,<br/>The moulded joy that lies in thy youth;<br/>But like a slaveholder's fancies<br/>My subservient wealth and honour<br/>Lies with thy blood and love!</p><p>The gift of thy obedience<br/>To this secret will has flow<br/>And set thy way to glory;<br/>Thy wealth and honour lie in laureles</p><p>The race of horses that trods,<br/>The moulded joy that lies in thy youth;<br/>But like a slaveholder's fancies<br/>My subservient wealth and honour<br/>Lies with thy blood and love!</p>",
    "<p><b>Lethargic by Judith Ortiz Cofer</b></p><p>The first time I rode the train,<br/>I sat at a booth,<br/>I drank Dom P\u00e9rignon<br/>in my car,<br/>I ate pancakes<br/>in my car,<br/>I slept in the car,<br/>I brought home<br/>the leg of a friend<br/>that hadn\u2019t been stolen<br/>or burned.</p><p>I think about the color of your hair,<br/>the way you point<br/>a finger in the breeze,<br/>your smile when I walked in,<br/>and the way<br/>you smiled<br/>from the doorway when I left.</p><p>I\u2019ve never had a hungry room,<br/>nor the feeling of being cheated,</p><p>nor was I ever hungry,<br/>I was only hungry<br/>when I\u2019d had a long evening\u2009\u2014<br/>I\u2019ve only ever had<br/>lack of energy,<br/>no stamina,</p><p>and I can\u2019t remember the last time<br/>I sat alone<br/>for an interesting conversation,<br/>or the second time<br/>I\u2019m going home<br/>I think about the way<br/>I walk,<br/>the way I collect<br/>the things I should have bought,<br/>and the way<br/>I put them all in my suitcase,<br/>and sat to think about<br/>the next trip,</p><p>and the way I stayed<br/>goodnight.</p>",
    "<p><b></b></p>",
    "<p><b>The Corporation by Marjorie Pickthall</b></p><p>We are so practical.<br/>We invent greater loves.</p><p>We appoint our own.<br/>We forget to take our own.</p><p>We put our own thoughts<br/>in a new ad,</p><p>We return the favor.<br/>We like to be at the center of something.</p><p>We lie, we steal, we do.<br/>We can handle anything.</p><p>We are stars, not the Moon.<br/>We aren\u2019t stars,</p><p>we are stars, we are stars,</p><p>we are stars, we are stars,<br/>we\u2019re stars.</p>",
    "<p><b>In the Dead of Winter by John W. Chu</b></p><p>In the winter of some dead people's lives<br/>I was coming back to myself</p><p>and this begins to sound like a poem<br/>but I already knew it</p><p>was a poem and in order to know it<br/>one must be born again</p><p>or else they\u2019re just words</p><p>in the sense that they tell us<br/>that somewhere in the darkness</p><p>there was a man who used to live<br/>a long time ago</p><p>or else he was a dog</p><p>or something else entirely</p><p>like a mouse</p><p>or a death mask</p><p>or a flighty bird</p><p>or a bat</p><p>or a bat with a whip</p><p>or a sword </p><p>or a sickle</p><p>or something else entirely<br/>I mean to say</p><p>I do not know</p>",
    "<p><b>Chaudhry said<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Yehuda Amichai</b></p><p>We pressed him with our hands and gave him a taste</p><p>of tortilla, of steak, of chicken. We hung his head.</p><p>We made him sit on the bed</p><p>and watched him watch us watch him</p><p>kiss like a donkey</p><p>and eat like an emaciated duck,</p><p>and then he\u2019d beg for more,</p><p>and we\u2019d take him back.</p><p>We were so proud of him</p><p>we didn\u2019t even have to wait for the</p><p>autumn call. I saw my mother</p><p>open her house to the wind, and it was like</p><p>an armada of airplanes</p><p>was going to the beach, and then</p><p>someone was going to the beach,</p><p>and the wind was like an armada of airplanes</p><p>was coming back to you.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Children by Richard Wilbur</b></p><p>The kids in the back of the truck<br/>or the couple in the back<br/>with their dog<br/>are the dead. There\u2019s nothing to do</p><p>in the cabbage field. The cows<br/>are still eating the cabbage<br/>and it\u2019s not for lack of love.</p><p>No, it\u2019s that my kids are<br/>dead to us. They\u2019re just</p><p>like the ones in the van<br/>in the ditch. They have their<br/>own issues like luggage,</p><p>a stroller, a car seat,<br/>and teachers, whose hands</p><p>aren\u2019t on the table<br/>or the carpet. I have to move</p><p>to read my book and I\u2019ve got<br/>a book to read on my hands.</p><p>The kids are dead. I won\u2019t</p><p>have my own grandson<br/>because he is too young.</p><p>The time has come for me<br/>to go back into the classroom<br/>and sit with students<br/>and talk with them.</p><p>How can I be so stubborn<br/>to the point of being<br/>a hindrance to all of this?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Turning Point in a Story by Kim Addonizio</b></p><p>It was when she thought<br/>she might be alone</p><p>or at least not pretending<br/>to be someone else</p><p>or at least calling it quits</p><p>that she killed herself.</p><p>She was in a bad mood<br/>that day and night</p><p>but planning her escape</p><p>that day and night<br/>with the help of a joke</p><p>from her mother.</p><p>The joke was often<br/>overly sentimental</p><p>or simply terrible</p><p>when she was laughing,<br/>but often was</p><p>or was about to be</p><p>so when her mother said<br/>\u201cYou have to tell<br/>your kids things in the past</p><p>she meant it,<br/>and so that was</p><p>that.</p>",
    "<p><b>Re-reading by Sarah McLane</b></p><p>When I was ten, in the last book<br/>of my mother's collection,<br/>I found myself in a forest</p><p>where a leaf was dangling<br/>from a branch, stuck</p><p>to the blackness of the night,<br/>and I saw myself</p><p>in the hands<br/>of an old man, holding</p><p>a first edition of the Bible<br/>he had just read. I saw</p><p>a black face<br/>next to a man</p><p>who looked like he had spent<br/>his whole life in this country and</p><p>I told myself, \u201cWhat does this teach me?\u201d<br/>I wanted to know how the Bible</p><p>was about to end,<br/>how the black community</p><p>needed to be freed,<br/>what do I do now?</p><p>\u201cWhat do you do now?\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lost Book of the Future by Gabriel Spera</b></p><p>I won\u2019t give the book it holds<br/>until its pages rustle and my eyes close.<br/>I won\u2019t look at the page that\u2019s unfolded.<br/>I won\u2019t lay the thing down in the book<br/>so it will lose its shape. I won\u2019t open it,<br/>wringing it like the thin, fossilized hand<br/>a child made in a drawer. Like how<br/>a child who can\u2019t read may wrap it<br/>around its fingers and read it<br/>but when the book is yours,<br/>all you do is open the book,<br/>read the name on the cover,<br/>and you will be the book.</p>",
    "<p><b>By the Sea by James Ellsworth</b></p><p>On the shore, by the sea,<br/>My dear, where\u2019st thou gone?<br/>The whole world is drowned<br/>For thy sake, for my life.</p><p>A stranger and a stranger<br/>Shall set a strange catch<br/>For thy love; and my heart<br/>Joyfully shall be contented, if I<br/>Shall be trusted for that.</p><p>O, though that be not<br/>Our true story, yet it is<br/>Thou\u2019st done from us;<br/>For thou hast the gift of a sweet<br/>Heart, and of no fear.</p>",
    "<p><b>Are You the One by Peter Campion</b></p><p>I\u2019m searching the house<br/>for my watch, or it\u2019s the splinter<br/>of my father\u2019s watch, found<br/>or lost on the kitchen table,<br/>or the dresser drawer<br/>where it belonged.</p><p>And no, I\u2019m not<br/>adventuring here. I\u2019m<br/>in a public library<br/>in a large, messy room<br/>where the other books<br/>are on the shelves.</p><p>I\u2019ve never been<br/>in public<br/>before. I\u2019ve always<br/>called a cab<br/>or waited<br/>for a friend who was free.</p><p>I\u2019m in love with<br/>this sweater I\u2019ve found<br/>on a shelf<br/>in a corner<br/>but I have to buy<br/>a dozen pairs<br/>to wear tonight.</p>",
    "<p><b>Death is the New Child by Langston Hughes</b></p><p>Death is the new child,</p><p>It runs, it jumps, it is blue and green.</p><p>Death is a kiss, a taste of cinnamon.</p><p>Death is the old man's shoe.</p><p>Death is the rubber.</p><p>Death is the shoe.</p><p>Death is the fungus.</p><p>Death is the lace.</p><p>Death is the crazy love.</p><p>Death is the doll.</p><p>Death is the fat.</p><p>Death is the gun.</p><p>Death is the heart.</p><p>Death is the beautiful one.</p><p>Death is the jewel.</p><p>Death is the fruit.</p><p>Death is the cactus.</p><p>Death is the cocaine.</p><p>Death is the cup of tea.</p><p>Death is the tree.</p><p>Death is the cookie.</p><p>Death is the spoon.</p><p>Death is the bone.</p><p>Death is the brother.</p><p>Death is the coal.</p><p>Death is the dye.</p><p>Death is the casserole.</p><p>Death is the ice cream truck.</p><p>Death is the cookie.</p><p>Death is the banana.</p><p>Death is the strawberry.</p><p>Death is the candle.</p><p>Death is the sword.</p><p>Death is the old man's shoe.</p><p>Death is the child.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cAnd the stranger and I send a kiss\u201d by Robin Ekiss</b></p><p>and the stranger and I send a kiss<br/>I\u2019ve been waiting<br/>to hear your voice</p><p>I\u2019ve had a headache<br/>w/ an empty beer bottle</p><p>I\u2019ve been dreaming<br/>I\u2019ve been playing<br/>a song I\u2019ve been thinking</p><p>I\u2019ve been missing<br/>the will to remain<br/>in bed</p><p>When you\u2019re dead<br/>I\u2019ll bury you next to<br/>a wall</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cOde to my Italian girlfriend\u201d by Alfred, Lord Tennyson</b></p><p>Ode to my Italian girlfriend,<br/>She is a beautiful girl,<br/>The car looked fancy in Italian<br/>So she walked in German<br/>With English accent.</p><p>She was a genius<br/>At putting gum in the cup<br/>To suck the smell of Italian wine.</p><p>She wanted to be a poet<br/>But would not walk in Italian<br/>With English accent,</p><p>She was a genius<br/>At combining parts<br/>To make a diving suit,</p><p>She was a genius<br/>At reading poems in Italian,<br/>The car looked fancy in Italian,</p><p>She was a genius,<br/>And loved to read poems in Italian,<br/>With English accent,</p><p>She was a genius,<br/>And loved to read poems in Italian,<br/>With Italian accent,</p><p>The car looked fancy in Italian,<br/>Translated from the German<br/>She wanted to be a poet,</p><p>The founders of the company<br/>And the talented students<br/>All spoke with Italian accents.</p><p>Don\u2019t be shy,<br/>Admit it\u2019s true,<br/>You\u2019re beautiful,<br/>The car smelled fancy in Italian,</p><p>You\u2019re a genius,<br/>And loved to read poems in Italian,<br/>Translated from the German,</p><p>Don\u2019t be shy,<br/>Admit it\u2019s true,<br/>You\u2019re beautiful,<br/>The car smelled fancy in Italian,</p><p>The founders of the company<br/>And the brilliant students<br/>All spoke with Italian accents.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lighthouse by William Carlos Williams</b></p><p>One woman came to tell the story,<br/>and by way of condolence I\u2019d promised<br/>to go with her. I was tall as a heliotrope,<br/>courted in a skirt of black silk, ornamented<br/>by a jacquard of blistered roses. Her eyes glinted with disgust<br/>or pity; I\u2019d seep into every flower\u2019s breeze<br/>to capture the scent of black and something else,<br/>the heat, the sharpness. I\u2019d find a rose bush,<br/>run my fingers over its petals, see<br/>the scent of what I\u2019d forgotten, saw<br/>the slant blade of grass as hipper<br/>as a car's tires, as my mother\u2019d<br/>wind her guitar strings, and we were on the way home.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Sun by Andrea Cohen</b></p><p>The moon is alive. She comes from the sea,<br/>shows us the future,<br/>and when I raise my eyes<br/>to see the blue in her eyes<br/>I feel her belly<br/>and smile.<br/>I walk with her.</p><p>The moon is alive. She comes from the sea,<br/>she shows us<br/>the future,<br/>and when I raise my eyes<br/>I feel her belly.<br/>I walk with her.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Right Thing by Jane Hirshfield</b></p><p>You can\u2019t see the face in the mirror<br/>but you can\u2019t forget the name.</p><p>It\u2019s the same name we give to clothes<br/>or put down the dishes. The exact same thing</p><p>has happened to us, I was told.</p><p>It\u2019s easier to get lost<br/>than to find a parking spot</p><p>and for those of us with children,<br/>it\u2019s easier to get lost<br/>than to fix our hair.</p><p>Before you know it,<br/>some clown on the bus had</p><p>played you a trick:</p><p>it\u2019s like in W.</p><p>Dear God, I Am Not<br/>Aunt Molly</p><p>the first time you<br/>attempted to kiss me,</p><p>my friend turned around<br/>and I saw</p><p>that you\u2019ve forgotten your hat.</p>",
    "<p><b>Thimble by Susan Gilliam</b></p><p>I\u2019ve come to make a really big mess</p><p>of everything. All that furniture</p><p>has been scattered on the ground. The Koran</p><p>is a jigsaw with multiple pieces missing.</p><p>The front door</p><p>has been kicked in the corridor.</p><p>I\u2019ve made a chicken paratura</p><p>of everything. All that table,</p><p>as well as the books, furniture,</p><p>the coffee table, the bed of cards,</p><p>and even the keys to the locked room.</p><p>All that furniture has been kicked<br/>in the corridor. The Koran</p><p>is a jigsaw with multiple pieces missing.</p><p>The front door</p><p>has been kicked in the corridor</p><p>and stuck on my wall. I cannot get out,</p><p>I cannot get out.</p>",
    "<p><b>Harmony by Bob Hulme</b></p><p>The nation must know what it knows;<br/>It must know from the past<br/>Which ravages the earth among us<br/>With weapons never seen before,<br/>The ways of the mind<br/>Which must not be forgotten,<br/>The power to love richly,<br/>The mind of the great one<br/>Whose only words are love.</p><p>A mighty spirit is assembling<br/>On the plains of Africa,<br/>That inexhaustible force<br/>Must be given to its work,<br/>And the great one,<br/>Who says, \u201cI am my own boss,<br/>I am my own officer,<br/>I am my own soldier,<br/>I\u2019ll do everything by me,<br/>\u201cdoesn\u2019t it\u2019t?\u201d</p><p>It is always more important<br/>That we should love each other<br/>Than it is possible to love,<br/>Especially when it is possible.</p>",
    "<p><b>Rage of the Tiger by Jennifer Zloteno</b></p><p>The one year old asked,How can I not be a tiger?  Na,man, a tiger is not a man.  Na,man, a tiger can kill a tiger.</p><p>We decided it was best to leave the house, go to the nearby woods,<br/>where the tigers often roamed looking for humans.</p><p>We walked over a rocky bridge,<br/>appointed ourselves a corner and sat on a log.</p><p>Suddenly a small tiger made the transition,<br/>reaching up for my shoulder and pulling me</p><p>into the air. We were carried by the wind<br/>across the prairie to a clearing on a fir</p><p>where the animals had gathered.</p><p>Six tigers with their tails and the bronto fleece<br/>were waiting for us.  The one year old<br/>pulled me by the collar</p><p>and I turned my head so there were six<br/>unfurled tigers coming at me.</p>",
    "<p><b>Hill by Cindy Denis</b></p><p>I am a woman with snow<br/>on my stomach<br/>I know how to manage</p><p>I am a woman with snow<br/>to see what is left</p><p>wooden chair</p><p>Skirt on the ground</p><p>skirt on the ground</p><p>cover up</p><p><br/>I am a woman with snow</p><p>I will never</p><p>grow up</p><p>I will never</p><p>grow up</p>",
    "<p><b>Poem by John Ashbery</b></p><p>Is that a bird?<br/>Something like that<br/>or something like that.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Lucky Pie by Wendy Videlock</b></p><p>She loves the pie, but I\u2019m not entirely certain I fell in love<br/>with the pie, or what was the cause for it, or my own<br/>inexhaustible desire to have it, and loved it, till I could not,<br/>for reasons I cannot explain, control myself from loving it, and after<br/>there was a nice big pie, and then I ate it, and I\u2019ve had<br/>another since I have been alive, and I remember the pie, but<br/>not for love of it, or for its innards. It\u2019s hard to be sure you\u2019ve<br/>been through the ringer, because the great weather is so absent<br/>and the sun is so red, and the streets so painted all<br/>white, and the people so distant, and I have no grave,<br/>and I have no shirt and no bed and I am not the greatest.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Autograph by Joyce Sutphen</b></p><p>I never quite understood the autograph,<br/>her voice from the front, a head taller than the bottom of my step,<br/>a hind foot, and a small black shoe,<br/>her smile, to be Bill\u2019s<br/>look like a hard cold shoe<br/>with a hard freezing heel,<br/>her effortless stiffness, the way she<br/>stopped to turn around,<br/>her general grace and civility,<br/>I wanted to give her credit,<br/>just give her a picture,<br/>and ask for a signature,<br/>like everyone else,<br/>and mumble, \"Thank you.\"</p>",
    "<p><b>The Mystery of the Body by Thomas Campion</b></p><p>Grave robbers, the wrong-doers,<br/>those who mocked the living,<br/>have not left my house<br/>nor taken my jewels,<br/>but I know what will happen:<br/>I will go back and forth in the streets of Montreal<br/>with my money,<br/>I will always be where I was born,<br/>a poor, timorous boy,<br/>carried away by the streetcar,<br/>and in a place like this,<br/>I will always be hungry.</p><p>It is not a carelessness\u2014<br/>it is a vanity\u2014<br/>of my body,<br/>I have not what it takes,<br/>to be me\u2014<br/>but tall, black,<br/>and fat,<br/>I will stay where I am born<br/>and then,<br/>I will walk the streets of Montreal<br/>with my money,<br/>carrying clear bags<br/>and my jewels,<br/>and remembering<br/>I was born in Montreal,<br/>and this is my home,<br/>where I will stay<br/>and be rich forever\u2014<br/>and beautiful.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Story I Am Not<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Suzette Petrosino</b></p><p>When I was a child and you were a wall,<br/>I did not know what truck you\u2019re driving.</p><p>I was not afraid and not familiar.</p><p>I heard your footsteps,<br/>and I was hurt.</p><p>I am not the child who cannot run<br/>or who is changed by fear,</p><p>the child who is always<br/>ready to walk into the door<br/>and leave.</p><p>I was not the one who did not know<br/>when to say \"Doesn\u2019t change,\"</p><p>and walk away.</p><p>I was not the one who felt<br/>the need to thank you</p><p>for the food I ate,<br/>and for shelter from the night.</p><p>I was not worried,<br/>nor was I ever<br/>sure about anything</p><p>except that I wanted to help.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Summer by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>In vain we strive to make love,<br/>Wishing to engage in a pure, candid,<br/>True love of each other;<br/>But our lovers, to their utter miss,<br/>Have one foot in the grave.</p><p>What is love?<br/>Love is barren lust,<br/>A cold, bitter, and terrible love.</p><p>Have I not heard that a maiden<br/>Sings sweetest songs if she can?<br/>But my Lord, if I may,<br/>And speak thus thick and fast,<br/>And say also,</p><p>\u201cIf you will to love me\u201d\u2014<br/>My Lord, if I may.</p>",
    "<p><b>Beginnings by Phyllis Wright</b></p><p>When the Earth is young<br/>the blood of the dinosaur<br/>already covers the snow</p><p>and ice which is there<br/>for the taking no longer<br/>the whole thing becomes a place</p><p>to go into and out of<br/>and the birds wait<br/>for the sun to come up</p><p>and it is not the rain that is great<br/>but the sky that changes</p><p>and can be turned around<br/>but the frogs swim away.</p><p>The huge trench on the hill<br/>is not the way to go<br/>but it is the place to go</p><p>where you don\u2019t peel back the snow<br/>and the trench that is still</p><p>not the way to go but the sea<br/>as a whole is an avenue</p><p>that leads to nowhere</p>",
    "<p><b>[Spokeman] by Evelyn C. Baum</b></p><p>He said,<br/>\u201cThis breeze from the west,<br/>a light breeze from the east,</p><p>this breeze from the south,<br/>a breeze from the north,</p><p>this breeze from the east,<br/>a light breeze from the west</p><p>that\u2019s blowing<br/>over there.\u201d</p><p>So, why is that also called</p><p>a breeze that blows over there?</p><p>A helicopter pads by and doesn\u2019t notice<br/>the fallen brick,</p><p>a truck wheels by and doesn\u2019t notice<br/>the broken sandcastle</p><p>you\u2019re building,<br/>but I don\u2019t know which one,<br/>the one that\u2019s been</p><p>kept for later or<br/>the one you sent</p><p>to the one you\u2019ve forgotten.</p>",
    "<p><b>Passion by Joyce Carol Oates</b></p><p>My tree was not a tree<br/>but a slip of foam<br/>at the foot of a hill.</p><p>I loved<br/>the way a man climbed<br/>a high branch<br/>and watched</p><p>the long,<br/>evanescent roots<br/>with a gesture</p><p>of his trunk.<br/>I hated</p><p>the way he<br/>calmly walked<br/>and,</p><p>through a hole in the ground,<br/>saw the first</p><p>leaves falling<br/>from an old oak.</p><p>He was wearing<br/>a thin red coat</p><p>and he was leafing<br/>with his children,</p><p>the children of his children.<br/>\"You never know<br/>just where you'll end up</p><p>when you get here,\"<br/>he said to me,</p><p>and made a gesture<br/>with his trunk.</p>",
    "<p><b>Poet\u2019s Lamps by Alice Moore Dunbar-Nelson</b></p><p>I hear it in her voice<br/>that once\u2019d a man said<br/>\u201cI\u2019m a poet\u201d<br/>but I\u2019m not. I\u2019m just<br/>a reader with a taste for poetry.</p><p>It\u2019s easy to go mad<br/>in a scene like that,<br/>or to be depressed.</p><p>It\u2019s easy to be angry<br/>by chance or<br/>as a result of torture.</p><p>But at night I\u2019m a kind<br/>of flame that rises<br/>dark and cool with a feeling<br/>like I\u2019m not so alone</p><p>and that reads a lot better<br/>than the poem I should have written,<br/>the poem that imagined<br/>her being the one who\u2019d do it,<br/>the poem that would have been true</p><p>if I\u2019d been a real person<br/>like the one she was.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201c\u0639\u0644\u064a \u062a\u0639\u0642\u0644 \u201d by Yehuda Amichai</b></p><p>\u201c\u0639\u0644\u064a \u062a\u0639\u0642\u0644 \u201d<br/>it is a long road<br/>through fields of snow<br/>to the sea</p><p>that glints in the sun<br/>that is a land</p><p>of jesus<br/>where dogs<br/>run amok</p><p>I am a siren<br/>Kittens run amok</p><p>triumphs in front of me<br/>The summer<br/>is a cancer</p><p>It is</p><p>a misfortune<br/>to have dreams of</p><p>burning</p><p>\u201ctriumphs in front of me\u201d</p><p>in the end<br/>I will die</p><p>the sun will lift me<br/>from the plane</p><p>at the end</p><p>I will die<br/>with a smile on my face</p><p>and my name behind me<br/>and my name</p><p>I am the siren</p><p>I am the light</p><p>I am the roar</p>",
    "<p><b>A Girl by Joanne Kyger</b></p><p>How beautiful<br/>by the lake.</p><p>I<br/>It\u2019s not fair to stop<br/>gathering in the front yards<br/>and changing clothes,</p><p>cozy with the smell of<br/>a fine laundry.</p><p><br/>It\u2019s not fair to get<br/>a bit carried away</p><p>with the rush of wet<br/>the sands brushing against<br/>the road or the parked cars\u2019</p><p>dust, but it\u2019s true,<br/>the waves are pounding</p><p>always, and water</p><p>flickers by the windows<br/>of houses, and I<br/>see my future\u2014the</p><p>big fluffy clouds<br/>peeling back the layers of<br/>the understory as a<br/>good luck charm, a way</p><p>to say thank you<br/>for all the rain that</p><p>washes over us<br/>and all the rain that</p><p>never ends.</p>",
    "<p><b>The House of Horrors by Amanda Jernigan</b></p><p>(she-wolf by the lake, she-wolf by the river)<br/>I hid in a whisper<br/>of the catacombs of my mother\u2019s house<br/>where I could not speak.</p><p>The house was one hell of a lot bigger than me.<br/>It was four bedrooms, three baths, a deluxe kitchen,<br/>a four-car garage, a bowling alley, a 100-room Gothic<br/>hotel. It was open to the courtyard, and to the street.</p><p>I had written that I would not come back.<br/>I stood up, never did.</p><p>My mother was not the first woman to leave<br/>and I will not be the last.</p><p>At this moment I am planting a tree.<br/>It\u2019s not because I am scared of trees.<br/>I\u2019m not afraid of trees.</p><p>My mother was not the first woman to leave<br/>and I will not be the last.</p>",
    "<p><b>To the Moon on the Way to Mars by Sir Philip Sidney</b></p><p>Give me the sun,<br/>Give me the moon<br/>And I shall be the moon<br/>And Mars the sun</p>",
    "<p><b>The Ice Cream Truck by David Odum</b></p><p>One day I\u2019m sitting at the Ice Cream Truck<br/>and I say, \u201cWow, that\u2019s a great deal.\u201d<br/>I\u2019ve never had one of these things<br/>but it\u2019s not your fault you couldn\u2019t find one.</p><p>Nothing can wipe this cold off,<br/>though I\u2019ve been to Disney World<br/>and they\u2019re not too bad either.</p><p>I\u2019ve never had one of these things<br/>but then again, nothing can teach<br/>what it does and it\u2019s not your fault you couldn\u2019t find one.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Secret by Minnie Bruce Pratt</b></p><p>It\u2019s a car. It\u2019s a car. It\u2019s a car. It\u2019s a car. It\u2019s a car. It\u2019s a car. It\u2019s the last performance. It\u2019s the last performance. It\u2019s the last performance. It\u2019s the last performance. It\u2019s the last performance.</p><p>It\u2019s a car. It\u2019s a car. It\u2019s the last performance. It\u2019s the last performance. It\u2019s a car. It\u2019s the last performance. It\u2019s the last performance. It\u2019s the last performance. It\u2019s the last performance.</p>",
    "<p><b>The River by Vivian Smith</b></p><p>What rises from the dark and seems green<br/>is a man, hunched over a fish,<br/>and the fish is the man.</p><p>As the river curls and eats through the house<br/>it becomes a room and a song.</p><p>What can be said for the river<br/>that stretches east into west, it is<br/>a song, and what is said<br/>for the river I do not know, it is<br/>a man telling another man</p><p>to the river about the river.<br/>The man starts to swim<br/>but stops, however he may</p><p>and tells him about its journey<br/>and the fish, and the man</p><p>has died. I could not cry<br/>at the sight, but instead held my head<br/>to my chest, sobbing, and said</p><p>I am sorry I did not say something<br/>about the river, I did not say<br/>something about the river.</p><p>There was never even a puddle<br/>for the last fish to disappear into,<br/>the darkness scissoring across my skin,<br/>a river singing in a house that never sleeps.</p>",
    "<p><b>About Hell by Victoria Chang</b></p><p>You were born in hell,<br/>under those rocks.<br/>You\u2019ve been known to my<br/>inner demons, to take my flesh<br/>and turn me into a carafe,<br/>a lily after the fall.<br/>You\u2019re dressed in boots and a hat,<br/>you\u2019re leaping rocks,<br/>and I feel you\u2019re drunk.<br/>You\u2019re as good as I am,<br/>you\u2019re as godly,<br/>and so I am not<br/>sorry to be born in hell.</p>",
    "<p><b>Everyday Life by Gail Mazur</b></p><p>Silence breeds silence, and, so it pains me,<br/>I write from my desk. I'm in my kitchen<br/>watching the news, turning pages<br/>while the television with the remote<br/>plays. The streetlamps are dim,<br/>like the stone hallways, except<br/>it's dark, and the keys aren't</p><p>just for walking: I've been up<br/>for days, and there's no bed.<br/>Even the dishes are under the sink,<br/>like the pantry where the refrigerator<br/>has been kept frozen<br/>forever, if cold. The door<br/>won't open, because I know<br/>it's always closed, and I can hear<br/>the footfallers outside. This is</p><p>morning. It\u2019s dark, and I\u2019m<br/>ending up in the office, and<br/>I feel stupid for leaving<br/>today, but I have to<br/>go home, because there\u2019s no<br/>door in this house, and<br/>what I\u2019m about to do is awful</p><p>on my own.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Tale by Keith Waldrop</b></p><p>We are the beggar cats of the ground.<br/>We dare not ask for bread, but to see<br/>bread twice and be served.</p><p>We are the breath of the dead,<br/>the voice of the living,<br/>the fierce poem of the living.</p><p>We are the voices of the dead<br/>that no one hears. We are the perfect</p><p>cats of the ground.<br/>We dare not ask for bread, but to see<br/>bread twice and be served.</p><p>We are the beggar cats of the ground.<br/>We dare not ask for bread,<br/>but to see<br/>bread twice and be served.</p>",
    "<p><b>Visions by William Whiston</b></p><p>But as for me, who am anointed one,<br/>I have no use for these sirens, nor for the love-love demons<br/>That must have a subject and a time and a place\u2014<br/>No, none, for I am the ideal of the nineteenth-century,<br/>And I have never been one of those, nor the ideal of any,<br/>But rather my name, my honor, my love, the longing<br/>For both these longing, that all the rest of the world may know,<br/>It is I who am far most assured of my own worth,<br/>For I am wholly alone in my self-worth.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Mountains by Kahlil Gibran</b></p><p>I am a mountain.<br/>I am a mountain of water.<br/>I am a pockmarked mountain.</p><p>I am the steep,<br/>difficult climb of a mountain.<br/>I am the view of a mountain<br/>rocked on a rack.</p><p>I am the naked eye<br/>of a mountain.<br/>I am the dead of my former self<br/>sipping rain.</p><p>I am the trail of the mountain.<br/>I am the run-down solitude of a mountain.</p><p>I am the bleak cell of my past self.<br/>I am my own underbrush.<br/>I\u2019m no longer a mountain.</p>",
    "<p><b>Luring by Gail Mazur</b></p><p>I've found something in a drawer\u2019s<br/>darkness that allows me to be special:</p><p>a small black box in a corner of a closet.</p><p>I\u2019ve been meaning to put it in the attic.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Groom by Richard Wilbur</b></p><p>There's always the empty bed,<br/>but which of us has a better one?</p><p>\u201cIf I\u2019m anything,\u201d I puff up my ears,<br/>try to make myself heard in the gutter,</p><p>and make a scene.</p><p>I can\u2019t be the only one who\u2019d like<br/>to escape, to grow up</p><p>and see the end of the world.</p><p>I\u2019ve let it hang out<br/>like a long-legged dog,</p><p>and I don\u2019t know how to get it<br/>out.</p><p>It is vanishing as though it\u2019s a plant<br/>I\u2019ve planted by the house.</p><p>I will wade through the mud<br/>and try, pretending I\u2019m a snail:</p><p>I\u2019ll bury my head in the thigh.</p>",
    "<p><b>Poem by Gwendolyn Brooks</b></p><p>No one will know<br/>what I\u2019ve done to shame<br/>myself in this life.</p><p>I do not know<br/>what it is to be loved</p><p>unripped</p><p>and unharmed</p><p>as the wood was.</p><p>I\u2019ve never seen<br/>a woman all night,</p><p>or slept in a single bed</p><p>as my father did</p><p>and woke to find</p><p>mine empty and caked</p><p>on snow.</p><p>Maybe it\u2019s time<br/>to start chopping</p><p>and moving on</p><p>and no one<br/>will be there</p><p>to hear the knots being made</p><p>of sweeter wine, the wiggles<br/>of butter\u2019s rise, the last notes</p><p>of the piano\u2019s arc</p><p>before it could be heard</p><p>but in this day</p><p>when my daughter makes music</p><p>and sings it,</p><p>and we are sitting</p><p>talking about her,</p><p>it\u2019s easy to look<br/>back and see</p><p>nothing beneath<br/>the light-skinned face</p><p>spreading across the room.</p><p>Oh, she\u2019s grown</p><p>and mature,</p><p>and I know her</p><p>and I know</p><p>what\u2019s in her heart.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Flowers by Charles Hamilton Sorley</b></p><p>In the fields of June<br/>The bull-eye flowers bloom<br/>In summer.</p><p>On the branches<br/>Rich herbs gather<br/>Clusters of petal-white flowers</p><p>In bloom in April<br/>In June.</p><p>The flower\u2019s fragrance<br/>Is like the scent of the air<br/>Passed from the trees</p><p>In the fields of June<br/>The flower\u2019s fragrance</p><p>Bloom in April<br/>In June.</p><p>When the sun goes down,<br/>Blooming red roses<br/>Bloom in the fields of June.</p><p>When the sun goes down,<br/>The bulbs of roses<br/>Flare up in the sun.</p><p>My dear,<br/>Are you lying<br/>Up there,<br/>Blooming red roses?</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cBuild a little house under the bushel train by Harryette Mullen\u201d by Dore Kiesselbach</b></p><p>Build a little house under the bushel train.<br/>We could live here, in its wreckage<br/>where bricks line the asphalt, and the wheels</p><p>are still beating on the engine.<br/>On the many-many ridges of this ridge<br/>we would describe ourselves \u201cboring\u201d.</p><p>A house under the bushel train<br/>would be a good place for a bit of rest,</p><p>for a change of scenery, a sea of grass<br/>to sit in a corner and drink coffee,</p><p>be the fire that never goes out,<br/>a place of many small rooms,</p><p>a thing of wooden beams and a tongue<br/>that moves with the mind.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Decline by David J. Nichols</b></p><p>From a tree<br/>you could have thought I\u2019m dead<br/>let\u2019s call it a decline</p><p>from where I was once<br/>a lush young lady</p><p>a yearning<br/>for life and new beginnings</p><p>a longing for</p><p>\u2013\u2009a moon</p><p>a world you\u2019d never see</p><p>a bird</p><p>a sun</p><p>a wind in my hair</p><p>a taste of spring</p><p>a tear in my eye</p><p>a red tissue</p><p>a bead of fluid</p><p>a bouquet</p><p>I can\u2019t tell you</p><p>who died</p><p>what happened</p><p>what happened</p><p>till I thought</p><p>it\u2019s over</p><p>it\u2019s time to move on</p>",
    "<p><b>Pristine by Amaudy</b></p><p>I looked at my hands and saw<br/>plastic, shiny, lily-white,<br/>edgy, and made-up.<br/>I did not understand this mental illness.<br/>I did not understand this carnal madness.</p><p>I tried to remove the lump<br/>that had formed in my throat,<br/>but I could not and would not.</p><p>The doctor said, \u201cYour lips,<br/>your hands, your eyes\u2014\u201d<br/>I did not understand these mental illnesses.<br/>I was angry at myself.</p><p>I reached for my vagina<br/>and touched my body<br/>with a bare hand,</p><p>but I could not make myself aware<br/>that I had done this.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Voice of the Red Dog by W. S. Merwin</b></p><p>Owls\u2019 voice is not a living thing, but the trophy goes<br/>down to the shore, the wind\u2019s voice, the bush\u2019s<br/>voice, the division of our breath, the bird\u2019s, and the animal\u2009\u2014<br/>it is all a part of a kind of dream, a dream. A where<br/>I found myself in a heap of achy feathers, wet and<br/>already dried, and staring into my own tears.</p><p>It was a pleasure to live that way, to hear my own voice, but<br/>I do not live there. My voice is an aqueous<br/>chicken bone in a Nigerian restaurant, tender as the<br/>beef that was cooked as a trophy. The smell of beer<br/>glues the old broken boots and socks into old shoes and socks<br/>that come back to me in the alley of my house, and<br/>I say to myself, why do I have to live there<br/>with the tug of a soul? A spirit that I did not<br/>know I had, that is not mine, and stands alone on<br/>a brick of forgotten doorsteps and a broken<br/>penmanship. A stranger in the middle of the night<br/>with a painted face that insists I come<br/>to his house, his arm in the way I am<br/>saying, yes, yes, I will.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Bihorn by A. F. Moritz</b></p><p>The snapping leaves are all in the bush.<br/>Wind is a distant voice<br/>in the heart of the night and the window<br/>is open and the water is coming<br/>and anger<br/>is on the porch<br/>and the bell<br/>is ringing<br/>and the moon is coming<br/>and the door is sliding<br/>and the bird is breathing<br/>and the tree is light brown<br/>I am at the gate with you<br/>and the tree is high<br/>and the birds are singing<br/>I am at the gate with you</p>",
    "<p><b>The First Fat Girl by Judy Grahn</b></p><p>I don\u2019t know where my mind is, but I have a feeling I\u2019m wandering.<br/>I\u2019m riding the subway with my suitcase, my shoes<br/>and socks, my unwieldy hair and bags, through the dark.<br/>I\u2019m a princess, not in the sense that someone else<br/>might be a princess\u2014I\u2019m genuinely a princess, the kind of princess<br/>a child would love. I feel everything I see, hear, touch, feel.<br/>I\u2019m walking home with my friends, prepping my laundry,<br/>trying to figure out how to get around, I\u2019m trying to<br/>make myself useful, I\u2019m trying to make my plans.<br/>And I\u2019m at the mercy of the Universe:<br/>something is always going to happen,<br/>it\u2019s just a matter of</p><p>waiting for my destiny to unfold.</p>",
    "<p><b></b></p>",
    "<p><b>Madcap by Nancy Simpson</b></p><p>Darkness gathers<br/>slowly on the pins in the sky.<br/>Food, sleep, a chance to dream<br/>Farewell! Heaven shall not save<br/>The madcap who prays in the dark</p><p>And the madcap who prays in the daylight,<br/>The madcap who prays in the dark and in the daylight,</p><p>The madcap who prays in the dark and in the daylight,</p>",
    "<p><b>A Day of Wheat and Undram<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Rebecca Wolff</b></p><p>in the great middle of a field<br/>where no one always talks</p><p>the outer sky<br/>spacial</p><p>knowing what we know</p><p>we are not aware<br/>we are not aware</p><p>it is not understanding</p><p>not being aware</p><p>it is our silence</p><p>an inner silence<br/>not knowing</p><p>going on</p><p>going on</p>",
    "<p><b>Blue at Night by Walter Clyde Curry</b></p><p>Blue at night the trees<br/>turn and kissed<br/>and blue at daybreak<br/>the moon is blue and quiet</p><p>I am so hungry<br/>I can\u2019t sit down. I am hungry<br/>to live by my own rules.</p><p>I can\u2019t drink my own medicine.<br/>I can\u2019t take a shower alone,<br/>I\u2019m high on mushrooms and caffeine and all</p><p>I drink is water. I\u2019m all<br/>back to black and skinny. My clothes<br/>are loaded with camo and fur.</p><p>I am dead and I will be<br/>as dead.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Little Closer to the Edge by Laura Kasischke</b></p><p>Unlike my brilliant best friend, who's been fighting the good fight<br/>for years, I\u2019ve never had a real boyfriend. I haven\u2019t</p><p>came into this life expecting something else, something<br/>or nothing. I was hoping for an epiphany, the revelation</p><p>of an outer road hidden under a pine tree. My mom said</p><p>she\u2019d never seen a dead body. I understand. I\u2019ve eaten</p><p>chicken fingers, forged my own medicine, and tried</p><p>to bury the hatchet with my mother, but I\u2019ve</p><p>kept it back, and she\u2019d keep it up, the way</p><p>I've always done, the kind of \"I\u2019m still here.\" I\u2019m here</p><p>because I wanted to be, and I\u2019m here still. I</p><p>remember the first time I lived here,</p><p>the first time I drank my share of water</p><p>on a Saturday night. I\u2019m not smoking.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Dream in the Fountain by Kate Greenstreet</b></p><p>We are a narrow circle of light<br/>entering the drunken, cheap pool<br/>and entering the world as a great big ball<br/>grabs me and I, two square feet of me,</p><p>and the whole man, both hands<br/>raised and grasping the ball, the whole body<br/>and the whole useless, worthless, hungry me,</p><p>and the whole earth around me, blocks of me<br/>and I am, beside myself with love<br/>and nothing else. I am the unfinished glass,</p><p>piece of glass in the shape of a window<br/>that looks out into the world and opens<br/>an inner window that has no face,</p><p>a glass that looks out onto the glass<br/>without face or face or face.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Final Victim by Frederic James</b></p><p>The lute catches her head<br/>and the night gambols,</p><p>shrill as a snake's.</p><p>A dark wood is<br/>shivering in the breeze.</p><p>The devil (sadly)<br/>has come down</p><p>to help us sing.</p><p>There is a sign<br/>in a tree<br/>that says,</p><p>\u201cLive!\u201d</p><p>You will die<br/>of grief,</p><p>the old self<br/>will climb<br/>the rails,</p><p>stately,</p><p>eager to please<br/>the crowd,</p><p>but if you<br/>are brave,</p><p>you will escape,</p><p>forever returning<br/>to the same place.</p><p>A flash from the last song<br/>scuttles by</p><p>and you can\u2019t hear it,<br/>the song fades.</p><p>You will die<br/>of grief,</p><p>the old self<br/>will climb<br/>the rails</p><p>and stay<br/>in the dark wood<br/>for eternity.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Book of Shadows by Deborah Paredez</b></p><p>Out of darkness swan song<br/>drawn the ivy\u2019s color.</p><p>The white moth, confident,<br/>was playing with my toes</p><p>and my little books.</p><p>What happens<br/>if we\u2019re smart?</p><p>If we\u2019re smart,<br/>prunes the heart<br/>and leaves the flesh</p><p>behind.</p><p>The heart is the time<br/>when vision is most vivid.</p><p>The heart is the time<br/>when we get most done.</p><p>When we are<br/>at home in our caves</p><p>preparing to welcome the new year,<br/>or when we</p><p>are playing in our own caves,<br/>we play the heart.</p><p>When I shout<br/>from the stairs,</p><p>\"Hurry, Uncle,<br/>we have to hurry,\"</p><p>he leaps from the window<br/>and hooves the door,</p><p>and I see him trot to the stove,<br/>and he\u2019s done it all.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Black Doll in the Garden by Charlotte Mew</b></p><p>The way she walks<br/>as if she\u2019s not moving,<br/>plans to give it up</p><p>and so it goes without saying<br/>that the first and third seasons<br/>are the problem here.</p><p>Uncle Ben says, \u201cCarrots,<br/>you\u2019re lucky I don\u2019t<br/>get the hickory nuts,<br/>my meatball has been missing<br/>the bone.\u201d</p><p>The white-haired Dutch maid<br/>upholds her vegetables in every<br/>airy space, still<br/>holding up the little coffin</p><p>of a kitchen table.<br/>Do I have a question for you?<br/>\u201cWhat goes around comes around,\u201d<br/>she says.</p><p>It\u2019s amazing how soon<br/>the cat\u2019s out, how many times</p><p>I\u2019ve been called a fool,<br/>how many times I\u2019ve been<br/>called a n*****, but can\u2019t<br/>answer any of those questions.</p>",
    "<p><b>Long Distance by David J. McCune</b></p><p>We\u2019ve got the most beautiful woman<br/>in the world and her husband is a saint<br/>but Joe is a slob, an old fool<br/>and his turd keeps on breaking down</p><p>in our kitchen. So we sit around the fire<br/>talking to ourselves<br/>and listening to the weather<br/>and the birds and the music</p><p>of the wind as we walk<br/>and everyone forgets<br/>that there is a giant god<br/>in the picture book<br/>we could have bought<br/>but we ran out of change<br/>and had to start over</p><p>its home away from home<br/>broken down into miniatures<br/>chewing on each other\u2019s hair</p><p>the madcap way we weave our way<br/>to an imaginary moon</p><p>the giant ship we\u2019ve built<br/>stealing sandwiches and handshakes<br/>that never happened</p><p>or was never supposed to happen<br/>but it has and it continues</p>",
    "<p><b>A for the Devil by Vachel Lindsay</b></p><p>All night, I wandered all over the underwater glass.<br/>I watched my mother\u2019s teeth<br/>crunch into each other\u2009\u2014\u2009ragged and slow.</p><p>My father put his arm around my shoulder,<br/>kissed my cheek, and I was in the car.</p>",
    "<p><b>United States of It by Ilya Kaminsky</b></p><p><br/>We are not varied enough.<br/>We need to be reminded that we are not</p><p>different enough. We have the ears,<br/>the eyes, the hands,</p><p>the questions to ask. We will ride with</p><p>the bus stop or the train.<br/>We will stand at the entrance,</p><p>pointing to a man with a ponytail,</p><p>or in the shop window,</p><p>a sweater, a jacket,</p><p>a pair of socks,</p><p>and if we sit alone,</p><p>we will see each other</p><p>and think of all the ways</p><p>we have been ignored,<br/>of all the people we have</p><p>told to shut up about</p><p>and not to say anything about. To</p><p>be careful not to be</p><p>wrong, not to praise or</p><p>burden ourselves with questions.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Postcards from the Hanging Gardens by Wayne Koestenbaum</b></p><p>The first postcards I saw<br/>from the Hanging Gardens came<br/>from the Bronx<br/>and were mostly wet<br/>raccoon-colored and smelling<br/>of cologne and coffee,<br/>with the occasional space<br/>where I could see the dark<br/>of fleshy hair.</p><p>And the second? It was<br/>from Athens, the same field<br/>where I'd once tried to pick<br/>a rose off a tree and missed,<br/>and a half-mile away<br/>from where I'd tried to<br/>spray perfume on flowers<br/>from a distance of twenty feet<br/>and, after a look,<br/>said there was a girl there<br/>who liked flowers,<br/>and that was after<br/>a year of visa trouble<br/>at the airport,<br/>and I believed<br/>her hair and makeup<br/>were fake and fake<br/>and that was a mistake,<br/>because now I'm not<br/>sure if I was in Greece<br/>or if it was Houston<br/>but I'm pretty sure<br/>it was Manhattan,<br/>it was Philadelphia<br/>but maybe Brooklyn<br/>or Queens, or some<br/>other place I was just<br/>certain I was on a train<br/>going somewhere<br/>I wanted to go,<br/>I didn't know what<br/>I was doing there.</p>",
    "<p><b>Adventure of a Cold Theory<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Megan Snyder</b></p><p>I work in the seabed off the coast of Barents<br/>where I can see a train going nowhere fast</p><p>and thought to myself: \u201cIf I come here<br/>and stand on the platform, where does a man</p><p>get up and get to his car, how would I know?\u201d</p><p>The answer is, he doesn\u2019t.</p><p>And so I sit there<br/>holding my silver moon pistol,</p><p>where the sea is quiet,</p><p>and perhaps the wind is blowing<br/>from the north.</p>",
    "<p><b>Daughters by Robert W. Service</b></p><p>My mother's daughters<br/>should have lived at home<br/>and had the fun.</p><p>The too-small sisters had<br/>to prepare for the day<br/>that they, too, would have to go<br/>to work.</p><p>I had a problem<br/>with the way that my mother<br/>asked me<br/>to come too</p><p>and take care of the house<br/>for her.</p><p>The problem<br/>was that</p><p>I didn\u2019t know<br/>what the house<br/>was really</p><p>like and I<br/>was scared</p><p>this being<br/>the first time I\u2019d<br/>been to school</p><p>I had<br/>to go along under<br/>the apple tree</p><p>hearing all day.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Prodigal Son by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>My Master,<br/>With hard heart<br/>I have overcome<br/>The myriad obstacles<br/>Of the dark world,<br/>And have done my best,<br/>Sure, though I fail in some<br/>Or other,<br/>To do my best I go on<br/>The wide road,<br/>While I am a slave.</p><p>I have done my best,<br/>And yet the great task<br/>That great task has done<br/>To me:</p><p>World is not my mistress;<br/>I have done my best,<br/>But what I have done,<br/>For all this,<br/>I will not say;<br/>I will not say;</p><p>I have done my best,<br/>But not my best,<br/>And this is my heart<br/>That will go forward.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Little Glimpse by Mark Waldron</b></p><p>He took me to his house<br/>and had me step on his knee.</p><p>He gave me some shoes.</p><p>He took me to bed where<br/>the air was cool.</p><p>He closed the door.</p><p>The door was open.</p><p>He wore slacks.</p><p>The light came on<br/>glinting in the bedroom.</p><p>I used to love to run</p><p>through the fields, through the ranches<br/>and the prairies.</p><p>He provided me with a good bed.</p><p>He took me to bed for a long</p><p>night.</p><p>I made love with him<br/>like a gentle woman may.</p><p>I put my ear to his back.</p><p>He was in love with me.</p><p>I knew I was there.</p><p>The sky was gray.</p><p>He was on his own.</p><p>I heard the rain<br/>hissing in the house.</p><p>I was thinking</p><p>about how I learned to love</p><p>a dog, how I learned<br/>to love the people in the house.</p><p>I was thinking</p><p>about the little girl<br/>who had difficulty standing<br/>and was eventually carted off on a horse</p><p>that came to the end of the road</p><p>and had no name.</p><p>I was thinking</p><p>about how I learned<br/>to love the wind</p><p>and the telltale bubbles<br/>that rise to meet the fender.</p>",
    "<p><b>Live by George Oppen</b></p><p>The only thing I\u2019ve learned while I\u2019ve been dead is to lie down with my shadow.<br/>I\u2019m sure there\u2019s tension somewhere in the house,<br/>but I\u2019ve never been able to make myself clear,<br/>calibrating the car\u2019s odometer, fingering the wires<br/>of my shower head, deciding which of us will die<br/>next.</p><p>No, there\u2019s a better way:<br/>I\u2019ll pin my life back into a box<br/>and leave it there for the storm to sweep through,<br/>the smoke to linger in the window, the trees<br/>to snap at the slightest breeze, the hair<br/>to fall back into its place at the back of my head<br/>and be swept away.</p>",
    "<p><b>River by W. S. Merwin</b></p><p>The river that we walk into<br/>divides the night into three<br/>circumference of light,</p><p>radio stations, a pile of teeth<br/>distinguishing them, meaningless<br/>walls, a child\u2019s naked back.</p><p>I see you\u2019re moving<br/>in the wake of two horses<br/>bent on moving</p><p>&amp; whistling to each other<br/>in the wake of a train<br/>&amp; whistling to each other</p><p>ahead of the night<br/>two black horses</p><p>broughtailing the van<br/>&amp; singing to each other<br/>in the dark</p><p>dresses in the wake of a horse<br/>pulling the rider<br/>out of the van</p><p>&amp; singing to each other<br/>in the dark</p>",
    "<p><b>Hope<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by CAConrad</b></p><p>I just want to thank you<br/>for the bright lights and the clothes.<br/>For the shoes and clothes for the hit men.<br/>For my husband\u2019s hard work and the men who loved him.</p><p>For your hair and the ties and the lipstick and your smile and your sweetness.<br/>For your antibiotic and the men who died.</p><p>For your hopeful idealism and the men who walked away.</p><p>I will never forget the quality of the sunlight on<br/>your windowsill. I will never forget the soft curls of<br/>the pennies you drop on my head.</p><p>I will never forget the shoes I wear<br/>when I walk down the street. I will not forget<br/>the daddy and mommy I miss. I will not be<br/>sorry for anyone on this earth.</p><p>This is a humbling song.<br/>I am here in this small room<br/>with a book and a TV.</p><p>If you take me back to the beginning<br/>of my life, the beginning of<br/>my love and my marriage,<br/>I\u2019ll be right back with you.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Poem by Mark Twain</b></p><p>A Poem is a lovely thing;<br/>Few can say the better word:<br/>In the Poem, the Word makes clear<br/>The keen and terrible sense;<br/>The Heart is a riveted thing;<br/>Muck, sponge, and tempest are<br/>The three horsemen of the procession;<br/>The Way is a Lamb;<br/>The Courage is a Sheep;<br/>The Sun is a Lion,<br/>The Rain is a Dove,<br/>And the Son is the Lamb.</p><p>A Poem is simply a Word;<br/>A Poem is a lovely thing;<br/>If it be thy heart, then let it grow;<br/>If it be thy heart, then leave it;<br/>For to me is the Glory<br/>Of my terrible Poem, the Word.</p>",
    "<p><b>Strange Erotica<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Gretchen Bowers</b></p><p>I stand<br/>in the hallway,<br/>trying to think<br/>of some way to screw this up.</p><p>As if I could.</p><p>I have a pen<br/>and a book.</p><p>I open the book and begin.</p><p>I try to remember<br/>what it is that makes a man.</p><p>This way<br/>(this way) I am in my own body.</p><p>I am not my own.</p><p>I am a man whom<br/>I am not</p><p>I am not</p><p>My own.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Impala by Rachel Sherwood</b></p><p>This is not a song, it\u2019s not a poem,<br/>but the long stare, pursed lips, the long, porcelain-colored smile<br/>I saw the girl with, long ago, almost eerily,<br/>will always be there.</p><p>The things I see, the friend I make,<br/>the way I share your bed,<br/>have nothing to do with me.<br/>When you\u2019re ready<br/>to go, there\u2019s no need to thank<br/>me.</p><p>They\u2019re only there to protect,<br/>to be a pair of eyes,<br/>to be lips,<br/>to be lips.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Tone by Arthur Sze</b></p><p>In the sea of twilight<br/>the star twitches, the moon<br/>flashes like a question mark.</p><p>You\u2019re awake. If the world<br/>was a clang or a alarm,</p><p>I\u2019ll come to your ear.</p><p>I\u2019m still here.</p><p>Your voice is an inch deep<br/>of a sieve. I\u2019m not</p><p>porcelain, I\u2019m nowhere</p><p>near as good as my sister.</p><p>Oh but I\u2019m not.</p><p>You\u2019re here, I\u2019m here.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Locket by Karen Volkman</b></p><p>In my travels I have come to understand that even the most ardent dreamers must come to terms with the unreliable</p><p>In my travels I have come to understand that even the most ardent dreamers must come to terms with the unreliable</p><p>of waking, discovered, sometimes, to their face,<br/>the commercial, the untended, the curious,</p><p>the rear-end of the city I was in,<br/>and potential intimate \u00a0\u00a0losing oneself,</p><p>I was in the midst of because I am often in the midst of</p><p>how the least of these things is life<br/>and how the most is the other half,</p><p>The way to be a woman in this moment, how to be a woman</p><p>in a world that isn\u2019t saved,</p><p>what it means to be a woman in a world that isn\u2019t</p><p>saved,</p><p>of course, not to be women in a world that isn\u2019t</p><p>saved,</p><p>to be alive, to be alive in a world that isn\u2019t</p><p>saved and to be alive in a world</p><p>saved, though it\u2019s,</p>",
    "<p><b>Family<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Robin Ekiss</b></p><p>There are two ways to get to you<br/>from outer space, by car or by plane.</p><p>You might think this is wishful thinking,</p><p>but I can tell you</p><p>that this is what the future</p><p>looks like: There\u2019s a sky,</p><p>where you\u2019re not</p><p>at all</p><p>and there\u2019s a planet,</p><p>where you\u2019re the sun.</p><p>You might think this is wishful thinking,</p><p>but I can tell you</p><p>that this is what the future</p><p>looks like: There\u2019s a sky,</p><p>where you\u2019re not</p><p>at all.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Way by Joan Hutton</b></p><p>The night wind had drummed<br/>against our door, as if<br/>we had just forced ourselves<br/>from the life we had known.</p><p>We stood at the window<br/>doing what we always do<br/>when there is a party<br/>and we are alone.</p><p>We looked at the ground.<br/>We said,<br/>\u201cThere is no government<br/>in paradise.\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>Ladybird by Robert W. Service</b></p><p>A ladybird up in the sky,<br/>living and happy as a butterfly,<br/>hopped her head in the west,<br/>and there was a ladybird on the way.</p><p>She was walking on the trees,<br/>and in the trees stood the stately house.</p><p>The ladybird was a butterfly,<br/>and so much tall in there<br/>that it looked like a house.</p><p>She was walking on the hills,<br/>and in the hills stood a huge, strong school.</p><p>The ladybird was a butterfly,<br/>and so much tall in there<br/>that it looked like a house.</p><p>She was walking home,<br/>and in the hills stood the country house.</p>",
    "<p><b>Of Two Orchids by William Blake</b></p>",
    "<p><b>I Don't Want to Muck with a Thing by Scott Cairns</b></p><p>I don't want to muck with a thing,<br/>a whited piece of trash. I don't want to muck<br/>with a paper-thin curtain of air,<br/>to step outside<br/>into the morning and walk barefoot</p><p>through the pocked-off courtyard<br/>of a house that wasn't<br/>quite it anymore than I was before.</p><p>I don't want to muck with the house<br/>that\u2019s behind me, broken up<br/>by setbacks and empty walls</p><p>in storage, in the way<br/>it used to be, odd and<br/>wanting to know what\u2019s up ahead,<br/>what\u2019s that punk nicked</p><p>thing up there that\u2019s ugly<br/>and old and and big and<br/>unfinished?</p>",
    "<p><b>A Light by Henry David Thoreau</b></p><p>Flint would have us believe<br/>that we are in the heart of a forest<br/>too bright to be the sky. And the way<br/>I have held my head up there<br/>from the front porch for years<br/>as if a lion on the wall<br/>were attired in flannel<br/>and moving, so graceful,<br/>made of the thin-bodied<br/>I\u2019ve been looking for, though<br/>she, with the hair in her ear,<br/>cannot remember<br/>the name of the dead, I said<br/>to myself. The tree</p><p>the sun was singing<br/>against, we were</p><p>watching from the shadows<br/>the moon and the stars<br/>were there, but<br/>the moon was</p><p>not to be found,<br/>not even near</p><p>the mountains<br/>where the sea<br/>had been a whim<br/>and where waves</p><p>had been placed<br/>to impede navigation.</p>",
    "<p><b>The White Brandy by Fanny Howe</b></p><p>Look, here is a woman<br/>reciting of a vulgar script,<br/>spreading her legs, guessing<br/>what I\u2019m thinking. I\u2019m too old to make<br/>erotic faces at the time, too far from home<br/>to do the things I\u2019m doing today,<br/>so I remain unrecognized.</p><p>Here is a woman<br/>nearly impossible to sit beside<br/>who\u2019s destined to be a statue,</p><p>who\u2019ll never know how lucky she was<br/>and how much she was meant to do<br/>in this life to make it happen,</p><p>how she was there before the revolution<br/>and kept me safe during its height,<br/>staying just long enough to teach me the alphabet,</p><p>how I can remember what it was like<br/>at the time I used to be in this photo,<br/>how I can still feel the warmth of her skin,<br/>how I can still feel her tender body</p><p>and her fiery smile, and the way she\u2019s singing,<br/>it\u2019s as if I\u2019m letting her take me home,<br/>remembering the old days,</p><p>remembering how easy it was<br/>to forget who I used to be,<br/>to look in the mirror,<br/>remembering the books I\u2019ve read,<br/>remembering the things I\u2019ve done<br/>without thinking about myself.</p>",
    "<p><b>1847<br/>  <br/>  <br/>   <br/>    Launch Audio in a New Window by William Blake</b></p><p>Antiquities are coming. They are stranger, and they are cheaper, than we have thought:</p><p>a blanket of feathers<br/>on the flanks of a flying fox,</p><p>or light on a shrub and a windblown snowflake;</p><p>a fitful, and that to one who has come to love</p><p>but never has come to know;</p><p>the eager officials, the bumbling clergy, the odd jokes,</p><p>the general absence of any passion, no end to it,</p><p>the constant fear of getting up, the constant need to stay up</p><p>and remember, to be the one who sleeps in it.</p>",
    "<p><b>Half Brown, Half Brown by William Carlos Williams</b></p><p>Half brown, half brown, I am black,<br/>half brown, half brown, I am black.<br/>There are black buildings<br/>on half brown streets, black cars<br/>driving on brown roads.</p><p>The only black friend,<br/>the only black soul<br/>I know.</p><p>He's white, but he\u2019s not;<br/>he\u2019s white, but he\u2019s not.</p><p>Around my neck,<br/>around my mind,<br/>I can hear myself singing<br/>about black people,<br/>cursey and black.</p><p>It\u2019s been a dream<br/>for me, to have been black,<br/>to feel black, to have been black.</p><p>When I am black, I am proud.<br/>When I am black, I am brave.<br/>I am black, I am brave.</p>",
    "<p><b>This \u2013 A Brief Poem on the Horrible Reason for Being by Robin Ekiss</b></p><p>There is no tears in this poem.</p><p>Therefore it is not sad.</p><p>For the last time I am ready to be sad</p><p>like the last time I was miserable.</p><p>When I was absolutely miserable the first time around</p><p>I pulled the trigger which plunged me into</p><p>a dark place I looked to the inside of my fist</p><p>where I was NOT prepared to be happy.</p><p>I was prepared to be miserable the very way I am going to</p><p>leave this poem behind.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Snail by Robin Ekiss</b></p><p>The snail's a borrowed word.<br/>The snail\u2019s a word borrowed from<br/>a word, from the Latin word for liquid.<br/>The snail\u2019s a word borrowed from<br/>another word, from the Latin word for<br/>foot. The snail\u2019s a word borrowed from<br/>another word, from the Latin word for<br/>mouth. The snail\u2019s a word borrowed from<br/>a word borrowed from another word.<br/>The snail\u2019s a borrowed word.</p><p>I am the snail. I am my own<br/>skeleton, my own skin, my own<br/>flesh, my own egg-laying machine.</p><p>I am the snail. I\u2019ve been<br/>jumped on by a gene. I\u2019ve been</p><p>steaming and crawling and annoyed<br/>like the little fat lady in the squirrel-<br/>holidays picture, scraping the<br/>craw from the sandbox until the mud<br/>is fresh and the carpet is clean.</p><p>I am the snail. I\u2019m back and<br/>still happy. I\u2019m back and<br/>not the little fat lady in the squirrel-<br/>holidays picture. I\u2019m back.</p>",
    "<p><b>The House of the Sunrise by Jorge Luis Borges</b></p><p>The house of the sunrise<br/>Is sacred,<br/>The Madrid sky<br/>The most beautiful sky<br/>In the world,</p><p>The sunset<br/>Is the same too<br/>Astute,</p><p>Still, it is too short<br/>To be a milky way<br/>To live long</p><p>In a world of one day<br/>And eight nights,</p><p>Lying peacefully<br/>In a rectangle<br/>Pushing the yellow road,</p><p>Quietly watching the sea<br/>At night,<br/>I sit at my desk<br/>On a chair<br/>Of my own</p><p>Eat Milagro<br/>I can\u2019t run anymore<br/>I have died so many times</p><p>But I always forget<br/>The time I died<br/>Before my own death,</p><p>And when I make a joke,<br/>The girl at my window<br/>With unusual beauty<br/>Told me once that</p><p>To be honest<br/>I am not convinced<br/>That the sun will come again.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Girl Who The Turtle Banks Against by Kevin Prufer</b></p><p>She is quiet, so quiet<br/>her feet are on the floor,</p><p>she stayed up all night</p>",
    "<p><b>Branches by Jessica Greenbaum</b></p><p>I\u2019ve never been in the woods<br/>but this honeybee hive in my attic strikes me<br/>as more house than field. Lonely and nearly forgotten</p><p>I snarl and thump in the breeze<br/>like the severed head of a bonfire, then go home<br/>and close the door, watch the grid of leaves</p><p>whoops for each other but no one home.<br/>I don\u2019t know where you are, I don\u2019t know<br/>how to get there, I don\u2019t know</p><p>what you\u2019re going to do, if you ever do</p>",
    "<p><b>First of May by Nicole Wilson</b></p><p>You could fight the heat at the May Day Parade<br/>but it\u2019s not your birthday, you\u2019re not even at your best.<br/>You could swear you\u2019re one of the masked fighters<br/>who flashed their paint-on-skin brims and waved<br/>a white flag. You could tell the parade organizers<br/>you were there, that you fought bravely, that you\u2019re<br/>the only one who earned our loyalty. But you<br/>couldn\u2019t name the leader, could only name the leader.<br/>It\u2019s a gag. It\u2019s a guarantee. You\u2019re<br/>the only guy who would wear an upside-down<br/>skirt to the May Day Parade, that\u2019s how it is.<br/>You\u2019re the only guy who would give up his life<br/>to protect the May Day Parade, you\u2019re the only guy<br/>who would call it quits at the end of every single transgression.<br/>You\u2019re the only guy who gave up your life<br/>for the sake of the May Day Parade, and it\u2019s not fair.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Ship's Turret by Kara Walker</b></p><p>What I find most beautiful about what is left of what we have is the tremendous space<br/>in which we have not been. We are a scrub in a wall, and there is a wall<br/>in the middle of the room, the complete absence of which is</p><p>so beautiful, yet also full of things---there are no tarred<br/>curtains on the wall, no doors barred or boarded. The walls</p><p>are always clean and neatly packed, the furniture is always in a cupboard,<br/>like an armadillo, or an iguana. There are no torches</p><p>or hands, the door must always be unlocked, the bed,<br/>the stove, the clothesline, the lefthand, the pegboard--all these things</p><p>are empty of anything, if we have to keep inventing and inventing,<br/>while the walls are picked clean of all the old things that we need to be\u2014</p><p>the lace we weave, the ruffle we thread, the cover of a box of tissues---all these<br/>are things that were, are, or will be, and that must remain</p>",
    "<p><b>The Hand-To-Hand Slayer by David Wojahn</b></p><p>I\u2019ve dropped nearly $25,000<br/>for a body of work that\u2019s done<br/>mostly, although I\u2019ve had sex</p><p>with one or two stabs at it,<br/>and I know it isn\u2019t easy.<br/>I been pimping like mad</p><p>and never finished, I\u2019ve worked<br/>many a job on the old,</p><p>I have no money left over<br/>for rent, and I\u2019ve worked</p><p>for free, and there\u2019s nothing<br/>you can do but wait for</p><p>to arrive to a pda,<br/>and nothing you can do</p><p>is going to get you<br/>to that point where you look</p><p>like a fool, and your tone<br/>is going to sound like a fool,</p><p>and the next thing you know<br/>you\u2019re in a headlock,</p><p>in a barbed-wire room,<br/>a picket line,</p><p>and you\u2019re near a chair<br/>where you\u2019re going to sit<br/>and then you\u2019re off.</p>",
    "<p><b>The White Pine by James Laughlin</b></p><p>I was with a friend one night. Each<br/>night, in the dark, I awake<br/>and gaze upon the stone face<br/>of the pine</p><p>I was with a friend.</p><p>The white face<br/>of the pine</p><p>was empty</p><p>&amp; no body</p><p>could be in sight</p><p>but I could hear my friend</p><p>say</p><p>\u201cthere\u2019s a pine<br/>in the woods\u201d</p><p>He shared the dream</p><p>that the pine</p><p>was in the woods.</p><p>He shared the dream</p><p>with me,</p><p>that the white pine</p><p>was in the woods.</p><p>I want to thank</p><p>James Laughlin</p><p>for this poem</p><p>I\u2019m the one who</p><p>looks for the pine and</p><p>the pine</p><p>is lost.</p><p>Sometimes</p><p>a woman</p><p>who looks for</p><p>ah-knee creek</p><p>has no idea</p><p>what she\u2019s looking</p><p>for.</p>",
    "<p><b>From the Watermound by Robert W. Service</b></p><p>Since I was born in a trailer park,<br/>I\u2019ve had a lot of trouble<br/>finding my place. I had trouble<br/>finding my way home,<br/>or even finding my own.<br/>Inexplicably, I was \"lazy,\"<br/>visually short and ugly,<br/> I couldn\u2019t read or write,<br/>and my classmates teased me.<br/>They\u2019re all gone now,<br/>but the watermound stays,<br/>and the riverbanks still blow.<br/>The sound of it remains<br/>even though we\u2019re moving out.<br/>There\u2019s the finish line,<br/>the finish line is here,<br/>and the finish line is here,<br/>and the end of the race.</p><p>There\u2019s the finish line<br/>even though we\u2019re moving<br/>out. The riverbanks stay,<br/>the river stays,<br/>and the river stays,<br/>and the river stays,<br/>and the river stays,<br/>and the winner\u2019s still<br/>running.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Stoic by William Butler Yeats</b></p><p>Rhetoric alone cannot erode a man's feelings,<br/>But it can cleanse them, and it can make them blind.<br/>It can make them aware of all their own fears,<br/>And realize a great mystery:<br/>That it is not love I despise, but fear that gives<br/>Love its dark side, and its light side.</p><p>I can see from your face that apart from instinct<br/>I love you, and my fire for you<br/>Burns in the rest of my heart.<br/>My love is greater than this, and I will endure<br/>The cruelest of love: That is my life.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Two Houses by Stanley Moss</b></p><p>I remember when I was a boy<br/>You would put your hand.</p><p>He was a boy then<br/>I was a boy</p><p>And I could not<br/>Play with him</p><p>Or my parents,</p><p>They could not<br/>Move him.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Last Call by Brenda Shaughnessy</b></p><p>I was walking in a grassy clearing here<br/>when I was hit by a car<br/>and died. The hospital,<br/>years later, came to the clearing<br/>to do a memorial<br/>but had just come from<br/>the highway. I\u2019m sitting here<br/>whenever I hear the carry-on<br/>comes and goes, my shoes<br/>stuck to my feet,<br/>and the funeral home<br/>I\u2019m often told to go to.</p><p>I have a name for that<br/>--it\u2019s the cushion<br/>after each footfall--<br/>that gives the body<br/>its peace,</p><p>that\u2019s not<br/>a raggedy coat<br/>that can be<br/>dressed up<br/>but the ground<br/>inside your head<br/>still burns.</p><p>I am saying this now<br/>because I recall<br/>the day my brother<br/>was hit by a car<br/>and died<br/>when I was walking<br/>along the other side<br/>of the clearing<br/>when I was hit<br/>by a car.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Chorus by Mona Zafar</b></p><p>Where has the chorus gone?<br/>What has been its destination?<br/>Who sowed confusion among the choristers?<br/>Who dislikes the choristers of the masses?<br/>Who is the hero and who the demon?<br/>Who loves and mocks and who doesn\u2019t?<br/>Whose song, the chaos, and those in the middle<br/>are the ears of the orchestra?<br/>Who is the new guitarist and who will sing the old one?<br/>Who is the new singer and who will sing the old one?<br/>Who is the chorister that has been sown with lilies<br/>and the new one has already been sown with tulips and lights?</p><p>Who will be the new guitarist and who will be the old one?<br/>Who is the new singer and who is the old one?<br/>Who is going to be the chorister that has been sown with lilies<br/>and the old one has already been sown with tulips and lights?</p>",
    "<p><b>The Most Unbearable by Anonymous</b></p><p>Unbearable, unwonted, unforgiving, endless,<br/>A cold, companionship, unending,<br/>The longing to be free, unclasped, unbounded,<br/>The absolute besieged, the unending,<br/>In bloody battles, faced with both air and fire,<br/>The free enemy with full arms, and the unending,<br/>The free enemy with full arms, O despair!</p>",
    "<p><b>A Promise by John Brehm</b></p><p>As a child, I was more<br/>than a certain flower</p><p>I was an old dog</p><p>I had spent all night in</p><p>my luck</p><p>I was a dog</p><p>I had lost my hand</p><p>I walked in a small forest</p><p>for the promise</p><p>to come back</p><p>I went through banks</p><p>for four days</p><p>I did it</p><p>I searched</p><p>for a snake with a great yellow</p><p>foot</p><p>I carried it</p><p>and my love</p><p>to the moon</p><p>I returned</p><p>to see a girl on a train</p><p>wearing a red dress</p><p>I wanted to kiss her</p><p>and she was crying</p><p>I was shaking her</p><p>I said</p><p>I love you<br/>and kissed her</p>",
    "<p><b>Notes on the Theater by Katerina Rossetti</b></p><p>While the Orphic games and the Thanksgiving feast<br/>esquire our attention by their offerings,</p><p>the two-step, the sword fight, the naked</p><p>dead end, the profanity-laced performance</p><p>and the humiliation of our auditors who</p><p>massaged our auditors' books: a troupe</p><p>flexes under a faucet and spits</p><p>out an aroma of coal, the taste</p><p>of lead, the smell of treacle, and</p><p>fleshy tea, and the sight of the audience</p><p>being pushed to the back: a sea of naked</p><p>huskins in the amphitheater, a sea of</p><p>girls and their clothes, faces</p><p>ornaments, champagne glasses,</p><p>and an assembly of old and young</p><p>girls and their girlfriends, in case</p><p>of some eventual catastrophe, dressed</p><p>in sexy stuff and acting in a play.</p><p>The best is over, the best is not</p><p>done: the first act is almost over.</p><p>Let us see if we can keep our</p><p>house in order, in order</p><p>to live, to get to the end of the stage.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Harp by Suzanne McMillan</b></p><p>It was not heavy<br/>but it was not threatening;</p><p>it came off as</p><p>like a spring one</p><p>or like the tail</p><p>of a bat. It was light</p><p>and not one or two<br/>tangles\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0like the harps</p>",
    "<p><b>From the Shadow by David Wojahn</b></p><p>the noon sun<br/>splashed across her skin<br/>and the familiar smells of cabbage and milk<br/>ran through the recesses of her voice.</p><p>the airplanes<br/>kept flying overhead<br/>beneath her eyelids.</p><p>she held her hands over her head<br/>like a piece of macula, repeating<br/>the words of the poem</p><p>but for the sound of it<br/>hurling soundlessly away<br/>and then went back to singing.</p><p>the faces in the wind<br/>gave off a slight smile,<br/>and the ears of the dogs<br/>gave off a little noise<br/>when they came out to bark.</p><p>there was a hollow<br/>in her voice as she sang.</p><p>her hands moved<br/>with the grace and grace<br/>of a beautiful person<br/>and the sound of her singing<br/>was everything<br/>that was not.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Circuit Judge by Liz Waldner</b></p><p>the judge is always the same<br/>I keep wishing<br/>the judge would stop<br/>he\u2019ll never know<br/>I\u2019m a good judge<br/>or else the judge<br/>will decide the case<br/>and be too<br/>late to do anything</p><p>the laws the judge rules<br/>will be cracked<br/>by the time the judge rules<br/>I\u2019ll be like a potato<br/>in the green field</p>",
    "<p><b>La lumi\u00e8re by Heid E. Erdrich</b></p><p>What is it, that you ask</p><p>the wind to blow over your head?</p><p>Forgive me, my love, for asking it.</p><p>The wind\u2019s a horse\u2019s tail.</p><p>You\u2019re gentle, I\u2019ve heard,<br/>or, to use your pun, the wind\u2019s a human</p><p>head.</p><p>While you\u2019re being gentle,<br/>I\u2019ll listen to your back.</p><p>The wind\u2019s a horse\u2019s tail.</p><p>You know what is in my heart.</p><p>What is it, that you know?</p><p>It\u2019s what you\u2019re doing.</p><p>If you knew what it\u2019s like to be a horse,<br/>you would never ask it.</p>",
    "<p><b>Children Are Good by Charlotta Hall</b></p><p>In the dark, it is<br/>first light, then sleep<br/>that counts. I have<br/>no other dream to wake</p><p>to. But I can remember<br/>a time when the moon was<br/>completely round, a time<br/>when I believed<br/>I would find my father.</p><p>Even if I had lived<br/>that time I could<br/>have lived far</p><p>from here, and far<br/>from here, it<br/>would have<br/>been perfectly safe.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Mistake by Jane Hirshfield</b></p><p>New York City is full of mistakes<br/>until a man with a cane<br/>and a fire extinguisher<br/>makes a promise<br/>to himself<br/>and a woman</p><p>to himself<br/>and an upside-down Lincoln<br/>with two wheels<br/>rolls past a station<br/>that wants to run<br/>a stop sign</p><p>to a stop sign<br/>that's upside down<br/>thus I say you need<br/>to have a longer life</p><p>she says<br/>metaphorically<br/>to herself</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cBorn again\u201d by Anonymous</b></p><p>Born again,<br/>born again I am the thief<br/>of love from you.</p><p>I am the thief<br/>of love from you,</p><p>born again.<br/>I am the thief,</p><p>the thief of love.</p>",
    "<p><b>Baby by Michael Robbins</b></p><p>My father always encourages me<br/>to find a square of space</p><p>between my bed and the</p><p>side of the bed, and lay</p><p>there like the sleeping</p><p>dolls I was born to be.</p><p>He said, \u201cYou<br/>\u2019ll be</p><p>a great baby,</p><p>you\u2019ll make a great</p><p>baby.\u201d</p><p>At five, my father</p><p>made me write poems</p><p>in cursive.</p><p>I was taught math</p><p>and the British School</p><p>was the safest place</p><p>for a baby.</p><p>My parents fought</p><p>all night</p><p>over the best crib.</p><p>One night my father</p><p>wrote a poem</p><p>in cursive</p><p>which was considered</p><p>good and sacred</p><p>in English but</p><p>could get lost</p><p>in German.</p><p>The next day my father</p><p>wrote a poem</p><p>in German</p><p>which my mom and dad</p><p>could\u2019t understand.</p><p>They kept telling me</p><p>it was my fault it</p><p>didn\u2019t speak</p><p>as it did,</p><p>it became a</p><p>massive success.</p><p>My mom and dad</p><p>were sitting there</p><p>in the dark</p><p>watching television</p><p>watching the baby.</p><p>They never understood</p><p>that poem.</p><p>The next poem</p><p>was called</p><p>\u201c<br/>\"<br/>Siegfried and Goetz.\"</p><p>My mom and dad</p><p>pushed me</p><p>so hard I</p><p>tried to break</p><p>my tooth.</p><p>They were</p><p>so upset they</p><p>called the dentist</p><p>who took my tooth.</p><p>After the tooth</p><p>they went over</p><p>again the rest</p><p>of the day.</p>",
    "<p><b>Part, Part by Michael Drayton</b></p><p>To it, that is the third time<br/>I have died<br/>I do not know if that is a problem</p><p>\"I am a measure of the madness\"</p><p>Auguste Burnat<br/>Suppose you\u2019re in a small circle<br/>And you\u2019re grey and a mug of oil</p><p>It\u2019s good to be somebody</p><p>And you\u2019re really a handsome man</p><p>And you\u2019re a drama student</p><p>And you\u2019re really hot</p><p>(What, are you drunk or something?)</p>",
    "<p><b>A Habit by Pauli Murray</b></p><p>Who is to say what I shall be<br/>for my next life. When I look back<br/>at the thousand notes I scribbled<br/>on this wall, how far will I have to go?</p><p>Will the distance exceed the time<br/>I spent here? Will it be as long,<br/>as long, as it takes to return<br/>to this apartment, the diarrhea, the stench, the fear?</p><p>Will I have to walk from place to place,<br/>from door to door, picking up<br/>the faintest trace of my last life,</p><p>the way I did before the war?</p><p>These are the fears I must bear,<br/>these are the petty doubts I must speak<br/>against, in haste, with my words.</p><p>Will I be forgiven? Will I be remembered?</p><p>Only the restless heart knows.</p>",
    "<p><b>Eating in the House by Juliet Laird</b></p><p>I took this picture,<br/>two nuns in gleaming flip-flops,</p><p>kissing and taking orders in the kitchen.</p><p>One of them<br/>was carrying out a meditation.</p><p>I did not ask<br/>how, then,</p><p>how?</p><p>Some nuns may have<br/>seen a man</p><p>walking in the kitchen.</p><p>Others may have<br/>seen a woman</p><p>in the kitchen<br/>finding eggs,</p><p>stocking the sink.</p><p>I\u2019ve been told<br/>that, if I had</p><p>a car, I\u2019d drive.</p><p>I\u2019m not sure<br/>what to do now.</p><p>I\u2019ll go back<br/>to eat in the house,</p><p>eat alone,</p><p>steal eggs from the nuns.</p><p>I\u2019ll never be<br/>as good as I used to be.</p><p>That\u2019s the reason I\u2019ve only ever been</p><p>in prison. I\u2019ve turned into a bad guy.</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cThat\u201d by Charles Hamilton Sorley</b></p><p>The fever dream</p><p>That you\u2019re a man</p><p>They did such a wonderful job</p><p>In keeping me alive ten years</p><p>And today is a birthday</p><p>For my wife, and I have to tell you a story</p><p>That should make you laugh</p><p>I was a free man,</p><p>A free child,</p><p>And loved by women</p><p>Until the fever dream</p><p>That you\u2019re a man</p><p>That is painful to my disappointment</p><p>The fever dream that you\u2019re a man</p><p>I\u2019m a free man,</p><p>A free child,</p><p>And loved by women like you and me</p>",
    "<p><b>\u201cWe are still alive\u201d by Fritz Lang</b></p><p>we are still alive</p><p>the last train from T\u200bo Chiap\u200b<br/>chicken soup with rice</p><p>and the line attendant<br/>said \u201cer\u201d</p><p>to restore order</p><p>and when we folded</p><p>the paper in half</p><p>the two long sheets<br/>of cloth</p><p>were gone</p><p>you could see</p><p>the street light<br/>flickering in the gap</p><p>and the windows<br/>touched, like an old man\u2019s</p><p>hands, and the old man</p><p>was moving away once again<br/>and I had to hold</p><p>his hand</p><p>and we were returning</p><p>and as we pulled</p><p>to our parked cars<br/>we bumped into</p><p>a woman<br/>who ran up to us<br/>with a tray</p><p>of food<br/>and said \u201cCiao!\u201d</p>",
    "<p><b>They<br/> <br/> <br/>  <br/>   Launch Audio in a New Window by Eileen Myles</b></p><p>Quaint, yet vivid, they flash<br/>of midwinter and the snowdrops<br/>fall, a tangle-footed tap<br/>of snow against a black wood.<br/>And just out of the way,<br/>a guitar picks up the timpani's<br/>flint-tipped notes, and a woman<br/>in a turquoise, top-hat<br/>and straw hat starts to sing.</p>",
    "<p><b>The Walking Stairs by Louise Erdrich</b></p><p>After the labor party and its numbers were settled, the children, the old, the poor, the injured,<br/>and the hopeless</p><p>the dead, the dying, and the wandering, they marched on<br/>up the stairs,</p><p>and down again,<br/>to the top of the stairs,</p><p>to the bottom:</p><p>the shoe, the bouquet, the dirty dog</p><p>they were carrying,</p><p>the belt of bones<br/>that held the cat in the catsuit</p><p>they were carrying,<br/>he sat on the steps, a coat</p><p>of fur,</p><p>the cage of bones<br/>they had buried him in,</p><p>the random things they had brought<br/>to town</p><p>as they walked,<br/>\"good luck\"</p><p>in the middle of town</p><p>was a standing ovation<br/>for the kids</p><p>and the walking stairs<br/>for the dead and the walking stairs<br/>for the dead</p>",
    "<p><b>Mourning by Andy Weir</b></p><p>And who will clean the grave for me? No one,<br/>and I implore you to leave us not. I shall<br/>[climb] the stairs that lead into the house<br/>and open the door, and kneel before the front door<br/>and say, \u201cIt\u2019s been raining here,\u201d and weep.<br/>I\u2019ll make a bed and I will make myself<br/>[bless]\u2014I will cry and I will be a good girl<br/>[out there on the highway] and I will not take you back,<br/>[and I will not live at any expense] if<br/>you stay.</p>",
    "<p><b>A Little Closer to the Edge by D. Nurkse</b></p><p>Before I was a tree, before I was a stranger<br/>I was a little closer to the edge.</p><p>My father had spent his life on the edge,<br/>and he walked long to the edge,<br/>to the edge of the house.</p><p>He came back, new-cut, he came back<br/>without a shadow of a doubt,<br/>to the same place, on the same day.</p><p>He sat on the porch step, and he<br/>made a little speech for him,<br/>for him, he was one of us.</p><p>Little closer to the edge,<br/>little closer to the edge,</p><p>he\u2019d always said, I\u2019ll be back.</p>",
    "<p><b>''There\u2019s a rockabilly band working at my dad\u201d by Wilmer Mills</b></p><p>There\u2019s a rockabilly band working at my dad\u2009\u2014<br/>up a little hill,<br/>up a mudhill,<br/>waddling up to a chicken shack,<br/>smoking a joint,<br/>singing a little song,<br/>all in the face of the sun</p>",
    "<p><b>Why Shouldn\u2019t We Eat Together by John Donne</b></p><p>Why shouldn\u2019t we have the wits and the gaiety of a matchbox<br/>open on the roadside and somewhere in the twilight</p><p>whenever the sun, the cities, the simple desire<br/>of the world, bursts open to light</p><p>in a big panoply of colors and noises and laughter<br/>in a way that is not the present</p><p>and is not the future and is not the past</p><p>and is not the present but is the future</p><p>that is the shadow that hangs over all</p><p>and all the light that rolls into the</p><p>blackness of our lives</p>",
    "<p><b>Snakes, Toads and Vipers by Cecilia Vicu\u00f1a</b></p><p>This is what happens when you drink too much tequila<br/>or dark chocolate. It's the Mexican Santa Clarita<br/>coming to town last night to do her favz\u2026</p><p>I got home, my cup was half full of whiskey<br/>and hot cocoa, it was a shame to leave<br/>like I did. I had my jacket on and my socks on<br/>and a pair of skinny blue jeans. I tried to walk</p><p>a mile with a skeleton in my shoes<br/>but I couldn't move my feet at all,<br/>I was so hot and sticky and sleepy</p><p>and just plain old boring<br/>I was thinking the time I left<br/>was going to be just like the time I arrived</p><p>I had this alien idea<br/>of making a mountain out of nothing<br/>but the beautiful thing</p><p>I'm back, and I'm going to be<br/>excited to hear the story of my life</p><p>and your story, friend.</p>"
